\pard\nowidctlpar\qc The Other Minister\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs24\par
It was nearing midnight and the Prime Minister was sitting alone in his office, reading a long memo that was slipping through his brain without leaving the slightest trace of meaning be\-hind. He was waiting for a call from the President of a far distant country, and between wondering when the wretched man would telephone, and trying to suppress unpleasant memories of what had been a very long, tiring, and difficult week, there was not much space in his head for anything else. The more he attempted to focus on the print on the page before him, the more clearly the Prime Minister could see the gloating face of one of his political oppo\-nents. This particular opponent had appeared on the news that very day, not only to enumerate all the terrible things that had happened in the last week (as though anyone needed reminding) but also to explain why each and every one of them was the government\rquote s fault.\par
The Prime Minister\rquote s pulse quickened at the very thought of these accusations, for they were neither fair nor true. How on earth\lang3081  \lang1033 was his government supposed to have stopped that bridge collaps\-ing? It was outrageous for anybody to suggest that they were not spending enough on bridges. The bridge was fewer than ten years old, and the best experts were at a loss to explain why it had snapped cleanly in two, sending a dozen cars into the watery depths of the river below. And how dare anyone suggest that it was lack of policemen that had resulted in those two very nasty and well-publicized murders? Or that the government should have somehow foreseen the freak hurricane in the West Country that had caused so much damage to both people and property? And was it \i his\i0  fault that one of his Junior Ministers, Herbert Chorley, had chosen this week to act so peculiarly that he was now going to be spending a lot more time with his family?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A grim mood has gripped the country,\rdblquote  the opponent had con\-cluded, barely concealing his own broad grin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And unfortunately, this was perfectly true. The Prime Minister felt it himself; people really did seem more miserable than usual. Even the weather was dismal; all this chilly mist in the middle of July. \'85 It wasn\rquote t right, it wasn\rquote t normal. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned over the second page of the memo, saw how much longer it went on, and gave it up as a bad job. Stretching his arms above his head he looked around his office mournfully. It was a handsome room, with a fine marble fireplace facing the long sash windows, firmly closed against the unseasonable chill. With a slight shiver, the Prime Minister got up and moved over to the window, looking out at the thin mist that was pressing itself against the glass. It was then, as he stood with his back to the room, that he heard a soft cough behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He froze, nose to nose with his own scared-looking reflection in\lang3081  \lang1033 the dark glass. He knew that cough. He had heard it before. He turned very slowly to face the empty room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hello?\rdblquote  he said, trying to sound braver than he felt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 For a brief moment he allowed himself the impossible hope that nobody would answer him. However, a voice responded at once, a crisp, decisive voice that sounded as though it were reading a pre\-pared statement. It was coming \emdash  as the Prime Minister had known at the first cough \emdash  from the froglike little man wearing a long silver wig who was depicted in a small, dirty oil painting in the far corner of the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote To the Prime Minister of Muggles. Urgent we meet. Kindly re\-spond immediately. Sincerely, Fudge.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The man in the painting looked inquiringly at the Prime Minister.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er,\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister, \ldblquote listen. \'85 It\rquote s not a very good time for me. \'85 I\rquote m waiting for a telephone call, you see \'85 from the President of\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That can be rearranged,\rdblquote  said the portrait at once. The Prime Minister\rquote s heart sank. He had been afraid of that.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But I really was rather hoping to speak \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We shall arrange for the President to forget to call. He will tele\-phone tomorrow night instead,\rdblquote  said the little man. \ldblquote Kindly re\-spond immediately to Mr. Fudge.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85 oh \'85 very well,\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister weakly. \ldblquote Yes, I\rquote ll see Fudge.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He hurried back to his desk, straightening his tie as he went. He had barely resumed his seat, and arranged his face into what he hoped was a relaxed and unfazed expression, when bright green flames burst into life in the empty grate beneath his marble man\-telpiece. He watched, trying not to betray a flicker of surprise or\lang3081  \lang1033 alarm, as a portly man appeared within the flames, spinning as fast as a top. Seconds later, he had climbed out onto a rather fine an\-tique rug, brushing ash from the sleeves of his long pin-striped cloak, a lime-green bowler hat in his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah \'85 Prime Minister,\rdblquote  said Cornelius Fudge, striding forward with his hand outstretched. \ldblquote Good to see you again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister could not honestly return this compliment, so said nothing at all. He was not remotely pleased to see Fudge, whose occasional appearances, apart from being downright alarm\-ing in themselves, generally meant that he was about to hear some very bad news. Furthermore, Fudge was looking distinctly care\-worn. He was thinner, balder, and grayer, and his face had a crum\-pled look. The Prime Minister had seen that kind of look in politicians before, and it never boded well.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How can I help you?\rdblquote  he said, shaking Fudge\rquote s hand very briefly and gesturing toward the hardest of the chairs in front of the desk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Difficult to know where to begin,\rdblquote  muttered Fudge, pulling up the chair, sitting down, and placing his green bowler upon his knees. \ldblquote What a week, what a week \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Had a bad one too, have you?\rdblquote  asked the Prime Minister stiffly, hoping to convey by this that he had quite enough on his plate al\-ready without any extra helpings from Fudge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, of course,\rdblquote  said Fudge, rubbing his eyes wearily and look\-ing morosely at the Prime Minister. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been having the same week you have, Prime Minister. The Brockdale Bridge \'85 the Bones and Vance murders \'85 not to mention the ruckus in the West Country\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You \emdash  er \emdash  your \emdash  I mean to say, some of your people were \emdash  were involved in those \emdash  those things, were they?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge fixed the Prime Minister with a rather stern look. \ldblquote Of course they were,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Surely you\rquote ve realized what\rquote s going on?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85\rdblquote  hesitated the Prime Minister.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was precisely this sort of behavior that made him dislike Fudge\rquote s visits so much. He was, after all, the Prime Minister and did not appreciate being made to feel like an ignorant schoolboy. But of course, it had been like this from his very first meeting with Fudge on his very first evening as Prime Minister. He remembered it as though it were yesterday and knew it would haunt him until his dying day.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had been standing alone in this very office, savoring the tri\-umph that was his after so many years of dreaming and scheming, when he had heard a cough behind him, just like tonight, and turned to find that ugly little portrait talking to him, announcing that the Minister of Magic was about to arrive and introduce himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Naturally, he had thought that the long campaign and the strain of the election had caused him to go mad. He had been utterly ter\-rified to find a portrait talking to him, though this had been noth\-ing to how he felt when a self-proclaimed wizard had bounced out of the fireplace and shaken his hand. He had remained speechless throughout Fudge\rquote s kindly explanation that there were witches and wizards still living in secret all over the world and his reassurances that he was not to bother his head about them as the Ministry of Magic took responsibility for the whole Wizarding community and prevented the non-magical population from getting wind of them. It was, said Fudge, a difficult job that encompassed everything from regulations on responsible use of broomsticks to keeping the dragon population under control (the Prime Minister remem\-bered clutching the desk for support at this point). Fudge had then\lang3081  \lang1033 patted the shoulder of the still-dumbstruck Prime Minister in a fa\-therly sort of way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not to worry,\rdblquote  he had said, \ldblquote it\rquote s odds-on you\rquote ll never see me again. I\rquote ll only bother you if there\rquote s something really serious going on our end, something that\rquote s likely to affect the Muggles \emdash  the non-magical population, I should say. Otherwise, it\rquote s live and let live. And I must say, you\rquote re taking it a lot better than your prede\-cessor. \i He\i0  tried to throw me out the window, thought I was a hoax planned by the opposition.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At this, the Prime Minister had found his voice at last. \ldblquote You\rquote re \emdash  you\rquote re \i not\i0  a hoax, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It had been his last, desperate hope.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Fudge gently. \ldblquote No, I\rquote m afraid I\rquote m not. Look.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he had turned the Prime Minister\rquote s teacup into a gerbil.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But,\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister breathlessly, watching his teacup chewing on the corner of his next speech, \ldblquote but why \emdash  why has no\-body told me \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Minister of Magic only reveals him- or herself to the Mug\-gle Prime Minister of the day,\rdblquote  said Fudge, poking his wand back inside his jacket. \ldblquote We find it the best way to maintain secrecy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But then,\rdblquote  bleated the Prime Minister, \ldblquote why hasn\rquote t a former Prime Minister warned me \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At this, Fudge had actually laughed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dear Prime Minister, are \i you\i0  ever going to tell anybody?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Still chortling, Fudge had thrown some powder into the fireplace, stepped into the emerald flames, and vanished with a whooshing sound. The Prime Minister had stood there, quite motionless, and re\-alized that he would never, as long as he lived, dare mention this en\-counter to a living soul, for who in the wide world would believe him?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The shock had taken a little while to wear off. For a time, he had tried to convince himself that Fudge had indeed been a hallucina\-tion brought on by lack of sleep during his grueling election cam\-paign. In a vain attempt to rid himself of all reminders of this uncomfortable encounter, he had given the gerbil to his delighted niece and instructed his private secretary to take down the portrait of the ugly little man who had announced Fudge\rquote s arrival. To the Prime Minister\rquote s dismay, however, the portrait had proved impossi\-ble to remove. When several carpenters, a builder or two, an art historian, and the Chancellor of the Exchequer had all tried unsuc\-cessfully to prise it from the wall, the Prime Minister had aban\-doned the attempt and simply resolved to hope that the thing remained motionless and silent for the rest of his term in office. Occasionally he could have sworn he saw out of the corner of his eye the occupant of the painting yawning, or else scratching his nose; even, once or twice, simply walking out of his frame and leav\-ing nothing but a stretch of muddy-brown canvas behind. How\-ever, he had trained himself not to look at the picture very much, and always to tell himself firmly that his eyes were playing tricks on him when anything like this happened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then, three years ago, on a night very like tonight, the Prime Minister had been alone in his office when the portrait had once again announced the imminent arrival of Fudge, who had burst out of the fireplace, sopping wet and in a state of considerable panic. Before the Prime Minister could ask why he was dripping all over the Axminster, Fudge had started ranting about a prison the Prime Minister had never heard of, a man named \ldblquote Serious\rdblquote  Black, some\-thing that sounded like \ldblquote Hogwarts,\rdblquote  and a boy called Harry Potter, none of which made the remotest sense to the Prime Minister.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 I\rquote ve just come from Azkaban,\rdblquote  Fudge had panted, tipping a large amount of water out of the rim of his bowler hat into his pocket. \ldblquote Middle of the North Sea, you know, nasty flight\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 the dementors are in uproar\rdblquote  \emdash  he shuddered \emdash  \ldblquote they\rquote ve never had a breakout before. Anyway, I had to come to you, Prime Minister. Black\rquote s a known Muggle killer and may be planning to rejoin You-Know-Who. \'85 But of course, you don\rquote t even know who You-Know-Who is!\rdblquote  He had gazed hopelessly at the Prime Minister for a moment, then said, \ldblquote Well, sit down, sit down, I\rquote d better fill you in. \'85 Have a whiskey \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister rather resented being told to sit down in his own office, let alone offered his own whiskey, but he sat neverthe\-less. Fudge pulled out his wand, conjured two large glasses full of amber liquid out of thin air, pushed one of them into the Prime Minister\rquote s hand, and drew up a chair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge had talked for more than an hour. At one point, he had refused to say a certain name aloud and wrote it instead on a piece of parchment, which he had thrust into the Prime Minister\rquote s whiskey-free hand. When at last Fudge had stood up to leave, the Prime Minister had stood up too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you think that\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  He had squinted down at the name in his left hand. \ldblquote Lord Vol \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named\i0 !\rdblquote  snarled Fudge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry. \'85 You think that He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named is still alive, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Dumbledore says he is,\rdblquote  said Fudge, as he had fastened his pin-striped cloak under his chin, \ldblquote but we\rquote ve never found him. If you ask me, he\rquote s not dangerous unless he\rquote s got support, so it\rquote s Black we ought to be worrying about. You\rquote ll put out that warning,\lang3081  \lang1033 then? Excellent. Well, I hope we don\rquote t see each other again, Prime Minister! Good night.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But they had seen each other again. Less than a year later a harassed-looking Fudge had appeared out of thin air in the cabinet room to inform the Prime Minister that there had been a spot of bother at the Kwidditch (or that was what it had sounded like) World Cup and that several Muggles had been \ldblquote involved,\rdblquote  but that the Prime Minister was not to worry, the fact that You-Know-Who\rquote s Mark had been seen again meant nothing; Fudge was sure it was an isolated incident, and the Muggle Liaison Office was deal\-ing with all memory modifications as they spoke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, and I almost forgot,\rdblquote  Fudge had added. \ldblquote We\rquote re importing three foreign dragons and a sphinx for the Triwizard Tournament, quite routine, but the Department for the Regulation and Control of Magical Creatures tells me that it\rquote s down in the rule book that we have to notify you if we\rquote re bringing highly dangerous creatures into the country.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  what \emdash  \i dragons\i0 ?\rdblquote  spluttered the Prime Minister.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, three,\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote And a sphinx. Well, good day to you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister had hoped beyond hope that dragons and sphinxes would be the worst of it, but no. Less than two years later, Fudge had erupted out of the fire yet again, this time with the news that there had been a mass breakout from Azkaban.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A \i mass\i0  breakout?\rdblquote  repeated the Prime Minister hoarsely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No need to worry, no need to worry!\rdblquote  shouted Fudge, already with one foot in the flames. \ldblquote We\rquote ll have them rounded up in no time \emdash  just thought you ought to know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And before the Prime Minister could shout, \ldblquote Now, wait just one moment!\rdblquote  Fudge had vanished in a shower of green sparks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Whatever the press and the opposition might say, the Prime Min\-ister was not a foolish man. It had not escaped his notice that, de\-spite Fudge\rquote s assurances at their first meeting, they were now seeing rather a lot of each other, nor that Fudge was becoming more flus\-tered with each visit. Little though he liked to think about the Min\-ister of Magic (or, as he always called Fudge in his head, the \i Other \i0 Minister), the Prime Minister could not help but fear that the next time Fudge appeared it would be with graver news still. The sight, therefore, of Fudge stepping out of the fire once more, looking di\-sheveled and fretful and sternly surprised that the Prime Minister did not know exactly why he was there, was about the worst thing that had happened in the course of this extremely gloomy week.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How should I know what\rquote s going on in the \emdash  er \emdash  Wizarding community?\rdblquote  snapped the Prime Minister now. \ldblquote I have a country to run and quite enough concerns at the moment without \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We have the same concerns,\rdblquote  Fudge interrupted. \ldblquote The Brock\-dale Bridge didn\rquote t wear out. That wasn\rquote t really a hurricane. Those murders were not the work of Muggles. And Herbert Chorley\rquote s family would be safer without him. We are currently making arrangements to have him transferred to St. Mungo\rquote s Hospital for Magical Maladies and Injuries. The move should be effected tonight.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you \'85 I\rquote m afraid I \'85 \i What\i0 ?\rdblquote  blustered the Prime Minister.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge took a great, deep breath and said, \ldblquote Prime Minister, I am very sorry to have to tell you that he\rquote s back. He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named is back.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Back? When you say \lquote back\rquote  \'85 he\rquote s alive? I mean \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister groped in his memory for the details of that\lang3081  \lang1033 horrible conversation of three years previously, when Fudge had told him about the wizard who was feared above all others, the wiz\-ard who had committed a thousand terrible crimes before his mys\-terious disappearance fifteen years earlier.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, alive,\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote That is \emdash  I don\rquote t know \emdash  is a man alive if he can\rquote t be killed? I don\rquote t really understand it, and Dumble\-dore won\rquote t explain properly \emdash  but anyway, he\rquote s certainly got a body and is walking and talking and killing, so I suppose, for the purposes of our discussion, yes, he\rquote s alive.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister did not know what to say to this, but a per\-sistent habit of wishing to appear well-informed on any subject that came up made him cast around for any details he could re\-member of their previous conversations.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is Serious Black with \emdash  er \emdash  He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Black? Black?\rdblquote  said Fudge distractedly, turning his bowler rapidly in his fingers. \ldblquote Sirius Black, you mean? Merlin\rquote s beard, no. Black\rquote s dead. Turns out we were \emdash  er \emdash  mistaken about Black. He was innocent after all. And he wasn\rquote t in league with He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named either. I mean,\rdblquote  he added defensively, spin\-ning the bowler hat still faster, \ldblquote all the evidence pointed \emdash  we had more than fifty eyewitnesses \emdash  but anyway, as I say, he\rquote s dead. Murdered, as a matter of fact. On Ministry of Magic premises. There\rquote s going to be an inquiry, actually. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 To his great surprise, the Prime Minister felt a fleeting stab of pity for Fudge at this point. It was, however, eclipsed almost im\-mediately by a glow of smugness at the thought that, deficient though he himself might be in the area of materializing out of fire\-places, there had never been a murder in any of the government de\-partments under \i his\i0  charge. \'85 Not yet, anyway \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 While the Prime Minister surreptitiously touched the wood of his desk, Fudge continued, \ldblquote But Black\rquote s by-the-by now. The point is, we\rquote re at war, Prime Minister, and steps must be taken.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote At war?\rdblquote  repeated the Prime Minister nervously. \ldblquote Surely that\rquote s a little bit of an overstatement?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named has now been joined by those of his followers who broke out of Azkaban in January,\rdblquote  said Fudge, speaking more and more rapidly and twirling his bowler so fast that it was a lime-green blur. \ldblquote Since they have moved into the open, they have been wreaking havoc. The Brockdale Bridge \emdash  he did it, Prime Minister, he threatened a mass Muggle killing unless I stood aside for him and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good grief, so it\rquote s \i your\i0  fault those people were killed and I\rquote m having to answer questions about rusted rigging and corroded ex\-pansion joints and I don\rquote t know what else!\rdblquote  said the Prime Minis\-ter furiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i My\i0  fault!\rdblquote  said Fudge, coloring up. \ldblquote Are you saying you would have caved in to blackmail like that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe not,\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister, standing up and striding about the room, \ldblquote but I would have put all my efforts into catching the blackmailer before he committed any such atrocity!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you really think I wasn\rquote t already making every effort?\rdblquote  de\-manded Fudge heatedly. \ldblquote Every Auror in the Ministry was \emdash  and is \emdash  trying to find him and round up his followers, but we happen to be talking about one of the most powerful wizards of all time, a wizard who has eluded capture for almost three decades!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So I suppose you\rquote re going to tell me he caused the hurricane in the West Country too?\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister, his temper rising with every pace he took. It was infuriating to discover the reason\lang3081  \lang1033 for all these terrible disasters and not to be able to tell the public, almost worse than it being the government\rquote s fault after all.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was no hurricane,\rdblquote  said Fudge miserably.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excuse me!\rdblquote  barked the Prime Minister, now positively stamp\-ing up and down. \ldblquote Trees uprooted, roofs ripped off, lampposts bent, horrible injuries \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was the Death Eaters,\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named\rquote s followers. And \'85 and we suspect giant involvement.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister stopped in his tracks as though he had hit an invisible wall. \ldblquote\i What\i0  involvement?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge grimaced. \ldblquote He used giants last time, when he wanted to go for the grand effect,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote The Office of Misinformation has been working around the clock, we\rquote ve had teams of Obliviators out trying to modify the memories of all the Muggles who saw what really happened, we\rquote ve got most of the Department for the Regulation and Control of Magical Creatures running around Somerset, but we can\rquote t find the giant \emdash  it\rquote s been a disaster.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t say!\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister furiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I won\rquote t deny that morale is pretty low at the Ministry,\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote What with all that, and then losing Amelia Bones.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Losing who?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Amelia Bones. Head of the Department of Magical Law En\-forcement. We think He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named may have murdered her in person, because she was a very gifted witch and \emdash  and all the evidence was that she put up a real fight.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge cleared his throat and, with an effort, it seemed, stopped spinning his bowler hat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But that murder was in the newspapers,\rdblquote  said the Prime Minis\-ter, momentarily diverted from his anger. \ldblquote\i Our\i0  newspapers. Amelia\lang3081  \lang1033 Bones \'85 it just said she was a middle-aged woman who lived alone. It was a \emdash  a nasty killing, wasn\rquote t it? It\rquote s had rather a lot of publicity. The police are baffled, you see.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge sighed. \ldblquote Well, of course they are,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Killed in a room that was locked from the inside, wasn\rquote t she? We, on the other hand, know exactly who did it, not that that gets us any further to\-ward catching him. And then there was Emmeline Vance, maybe you didn\rquote t hear about that one \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes I did!\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister. \ldblquote It happened just around the corner from here, as a matter of fact. The papers had a field day with it, \lquote breakdown of law and order in the Prime Minis\-ter\rquote s backyard \emdash\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And as if all that wasn\rquote t enough,\rdblquote  said Fudge, barely listening to the Prime Minister, \ldblquote we\rquote ve got dementors swarming all over the place, attacking people left, right, and center. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once upon a happier time this sentence would have been unin\-telligible to the Prime Minister, but he was wiser now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought dementors guard the prisoners in Azkaban,\rdblquote  he said cautiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They did,\rdblquote  said Fudge wearily. \ldblquote But not anymore. They\rquote ve deserted the prison and joined He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named. I won\rquote t pretend that wasn\rquote t a blow.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But,\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister, with a sense of dawning horror, \ldblquote didn\rquote t you tell me they\rquote re the creatures that drain hope and happi\-ness out of people?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right. And they\rquote re breeding. That\rquote s what\rquote s causing all this mist.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister sank, weak-kneed, into the nearest chair. The idea of invisible creatures swooping through the towns and\lang3081  \lang1033 countryside, spreading despair and hopelessness in his voters, made him feel quite faint.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now see here, Fudge \emdash  you\rquote ve got to do something! It\rquote s your responsibility as Minister of Magic!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dear Prime Minister, you can\rquote t honestly think I\rquote m still Min\-ister of Magic after all this? I was sacked three days ago! The whole Wizarding community has been screaming for my resignation for a fortnight. I\rquote ve never known them so united in my whole term of office!\rdblquote  said Fudge, with a brave attempt at a smile.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister was momentarily lost for words. Despite his indignation at the position into which he had been placed, he still rather felt for the shrunken-looking man sitting opposite him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m very sorry,\rdblquote  he said finally. \ldblquote If there\rquote s anything I can do?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s very kind of you, Prime Minister, but there is nothing. I was sent here tonight to bring you up to date on recent events and to in\-troduce you to my successor. I rather thought he\rquote d be here by now, but of course, he\rquote s very busy at the moment, with so much going on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge looked around at the portrait of the ugly little man wear\-ing the long curly silver wig, who was digging in his ear with the point of a quill. Catching Fudge\rquote s eye, the portrait said, \ldblquote He\rquote ll be here in a moment, he\rquote s just finishing a letter to Dumbledore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wish him luck,\rdblquote  said Fudge, sounding bitter for the first time. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been writing to Dumbledore twice a day for the past fortnight, but he won\rquote t budge. If he\rquote d just been prepared to persuade the boy, I might still be \'85\lang3081  \lang1033 Well, maybe Scrimgeour will have more success.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge subsided into what was clearly an aggrieved silence, but it was broken almost immediately by the portrait, which suddenly spoke in its crisp, official voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote To the Prime Minister of Muggles. Requesting a meeting.\lang3081  \lang1033 Urgent. Kindly respond immediately. Rufus Scrimgeour, Minister of Magic.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, yes, fine,\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister distractedly, and he barely flinched as the flames in the grate turned emerald green again, rose up, and revealed a second spinning wizard in their heart, disgorging him moments later onto the antique rug.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge got to his feet and, after a moment\rquote s hesitation, the Prime Minister did the same, watching the new arrival straighten up, dust down his long black robes, and look around.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister\rquote s first, foolish thought was that Rufus Scrimgeour looked rather like an old lion. There were streaks of gray in his mane of tawny hair and his bushy eyebrows; he had keen yellowish eyes behind a pair of wire-rimmed spectacles and a certain rangy, loping grace even though he walked with a slight limp. There was an immediate impression of shrewdness and toughness; the Prime Minister thought he understood why the Wizarding community preferred Scrimgeour to Fudge as a leader in these dangerous times.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do you do?\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister politely, holding out his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour grasped it briefly, his eyes scanning the room, then pulled out a wand from under his robes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fudge told you everything?\rdblquote  he asked, striding over to the door and tapping the keyhole with his wand. The Prime Minister heard the lock click.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  yes,\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister. \ldblquote And if you don\rquote t mind, I\rquote d rather that door remained unlocked.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote d rather not be interrupted,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour shortly, \ldblquote or watched,\rdblquote  he added, pointing his wand at the windows, so that the\lang3081  \lang1033 curtains swept across them. \ldblquote Right, well, I\rquote m a busy man, so let\rquote s get down to business. First of all, we need to discuss your security.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Prime Minister drew himself up to his fullest height and replied, \ldblquote I am perfectly happy with the security I\rquote ve already got, thank you very \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, we\rquote re not,\rdblquote  Scrimgeour cut in. \ldblquote It\rquote ll be a poor lookout for the Muggles if their Prime Minister gets put under the Imperius Curse. The new secretary in your outer office \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not getting rid of Kingsley Shacklebolt, if that\rquote s what you\rquote re suggesting!\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister hotly. \ldblquote He\rquote s highly efficient, gets through twice the work the rest of them \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s because he\rquote s a wizard,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, without a flicker of a smile. \ldblquote A highly trained Auror, who has been assigned to you for your protection.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, wait a moment!\rdblquote  declared the Prime Minister. \ldblquote You can\rquote t just put your people into my office, I decide who works for me \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought you were happy with Shacklebolt?\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour coldly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am \emdash  that\rquote s to say, I was \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then there\rquote s no problem, is there?\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85 well, as long as Shacklebolt\rquote s work continues to be \'85 er \'85 excellent,\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister lamely, but Scrimgeour barely seemed to hear him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, about Herbert Chorley, your Junior Minister,\rdblquote  he contin\-ued. \ldblquote The one who has been entertaining the public by imperson\-ating a duck.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What about him?\rdblquote  asked the Prime Minister.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He has clearly reacted to a poorly performed Imperius Curse,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour. \ldblquote It\rquote s addled his brains, but he could still be dangerous.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s only quacking!\rdblquote  said the Prime Minister weakly. \ldblquote Surely a bit of a rest\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 Maybe go easy on the drink \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A team of Healers from St. Mungo\rquote s Hospital for Magical Mal\-adies and Injuries are examining him as we speak. So far he has at\-tempted to strangle three of them,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour. \ldblquote I think it best that we remove him from Muggle society for a while.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85 well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 He\rquote ll be all right, won\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said the Prime Min\-ister anxiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour merely shrugged, already moving back toward the fireplace.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, that\rquote s really all I had to say. I will keep you posted of de\-velopments, Prime Minister \emdash  or, at least, I shall probably be too busy to come personally, in which case I shall send Fudge here. He has consented to stay on in an advisory capacity.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge attempted to smile, but was unsuccessful; he merely looked as though he had a toothache. Scrimgeour was already rum\-maging in his pocket for the mysterious powder that turned the fire green. The Prime Minister gazed hopelessly at the pair of them for a moment, then the words he had fought to suppress all evening burst from him at last.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But for heaven\rquote s sake \emdash  you\rquote re \i wizards\i0 ! You can do \i magic\i0 ! Surely you can sort out \emdash  well \emdash  \i anything\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour turned slowly on the spot and exchanged an incred\-ulous look with Fudge, who really did manage a smile this time as he said kindly, \ldblquote The trouble is, the other side can do magic too, Prime Minister.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And with that, the two wizards stepped one after the other into the bright green fire and vanished.\lang3081\par
