Many miles away the chilly mist that had pressed against the Prime Minister\rquote s windows drifted over a dirty river that wound between overgrown, rubbish-strewn banks. An immense chimney, relic of a disused mill, reared up, shadowy and ominous. There was no sound apart from the whisper of the black water and no sign of life apart from a scrawny fox that had slunk down the bank to nose hopefully at some old fish-and-chip wrap\-pings in the tall grass.\par
But then, with a very faint \i pop,\i0  a slim, hooded figure appeared out of thin air on the edge of the river. The fox froze, wary eyes fixed upon this strange new phenomenon. The figure seemed to take its bearings for a few moments, then set off with light, quick strides, its long cloak rustling over the grass.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a second and louder \i pop,\i0  another hooded figure materi\-alized.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The harsh cry startled the fox, now crouching almost flat in the undergrowth. It leapt from its hiding place and up the bank. There was a flash of green light, a yelp, and the fox fell back to the ground, dead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The second figure turned over the animal with its toe.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just a fox,\rdblquote  said a woman\rquote s voice dismissively from under the hood. \ldblquote I thought perhaps an Auror \emdash  Cissy, wait!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But her quarry, who had paused and looked back at the flash of light, was already scrambling up the bank the fox had just fallen down.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cissy \emdash  Narcissa \emdash  listen to me \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The second woman caught the first and seized her arm, but the other wrenched it away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Go back, Bella!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You must listen to me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve listened already. I\rquote ve made my decision. Leave me alone!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The woman named Narcissa gained the top of the bank, where a line of old railings separated the river from a narrow, cobbled street. The other woman, Bella, followed at once. Side by side they stood looking across the road at the rows and rows of dilapidated brick houses, their windows dull and blind in the darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He lives here?\rdblquote  asked Bella in a voice of contempt. \ldblquote\i Here\i0 ? In this Muggle dunghill? We must be the first of our kind ever to set foot \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Narcissa was not listening; she had slipped through a gap in the rusty railings and was already hurrying across the road.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cissy, \i wait\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Bella followed, her cloak streaming behind, and saw Narcissa darting through an alley between the houses into a second, almost\lang3081  \lang1033 identical street. Some of the streetlamps were broken; the two women were running between patches of light and deep darkness. The pursuer caught up with her prey just as she turned another corner, this time succeeding in catching hold of her arm and swing\-ing her around so that they faced each other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cissy, you must not do this, you can\rquote t trust him \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Dark Lord trusts him, doesn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Dark Lord is \'85 I believe \'85 mistaken,\rdblquote  Bella panted, and her eyes gleamed momentarily under her hood as she looked around to check that they were indeed alone. \ldblquote In any case, we were told not to speak of the plan to anyone. This is a betrayal of the Dark Lord\rquote s \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let go, Bella!\rdblquote  snarled Narcissa, and she drew a wand from be\-neath her cloak, holding it threateningly in the other\rquote s face. Bella merely laughed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cissy, your own sister? You wouldn\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There is nothing I wouldn\rquote t do anymore!\rdblquote  Narcissa breathed, a note of hysteria in her voice, and as she brought down the wand like a knife, there was another flash of light. Bella let go of her sis\-ter\rquote s arm as though burned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Narcissa\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Narcissa had rushed ahead. Rubbing her hand, her pursuer followed again, keeping her distance now, as they moved deeper into the deserted labyrinth of brick houses. At last, Narcissa hur\-ried up a street named Spinner\rquote s End, over which the towering mill chimney seemed to hover like a giant admonitory finger. Her foot\-steps echoed on the cobbles as she passed boarded and broken win\-dows, until she reached the very last house, where a dim light glimmered through the curtains in a downstairs room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She had knocked on the door before Bella, cursing under her breath, had caught up. Together they stood waiting, panting slightly, breathing in the smell of the dirty river that was carried to them on the night breeze. After a few seconds, they heard move\-ment behind the door and it opened a crack. A sliver of a man could be seen looking out at them, a man with long black hair parted in curtains around a sallow face and black eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Narcissa threw back her hood. She was so pale that she seemed to shine in the darkness; the long blonde hair streaming down her back gave her the look of a drowned person.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Narcissa!\rdblquote  said the man, opening the door a little wider, so that the light fell upon her and her sister too. \ldblquote What a pleasant sur\-prise!\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Severus,\rdblquote  she said in a strained whisper. \ldblquote May I speak to you? It\rquote s urgent.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But of course.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stood back to allow her to pass him into the house. Her still-hooded sister followed without invitation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Snape,\rdblquote  she said curtly as she passed him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bellatrix,\rdblquote  he replied, his thin mouth curling into a slightly mocking smile as he closed the door with a snap behind them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They had stepped directly into a tiny sitting room, which had the feeling of a dark, padded cell. The walls were completely cov\-ered in books, most of them bound in old black or brown leather; a threadbare sofa, an old armchair, and a rickety table stood grouped together in a pool of dim light cast by a candle-filled lamp hung from the ceiling. The place had an air of neglect, as though it was not usually inhabited.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape gestured Narcissa to the sofa. She threw off her cloak, cast\lang3081  \lang1033 it aside, and sat down, staring at her white and trembling hands clasped in her lap. Bellatrix lowered her hood more slowly. Dark as her sister was fair, with heavily lidded eyes and a strong jaw, she did not take her gaze from Snape as she moved to stand behind Narcissa.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, what can I do for you?\rdblquote  Snape asked, settling himself in the armchair opposite the two sisters.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We \'85 we are alone, aren\rquote t we?\rdblquote  Narcissa asked quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, of course. Well, Wormtail\rquote s here, but we\rquote re not counting vermin, are we?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pointed his wand at the wall of books behind him and with a bang, a hidden door flew open, revealing a narrow staircase upon which a small man stood frozen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As you have clearly realized, Wormtail, we have guests,\rdblquote  said Snape lazily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The man crept, hunchbacked, down the last few steps and moved into the room. He had small, watery eyes, a pointed nose, and wore an unpleasant simper. His left hand was caressing his right, which looked as though it was encased in a bright silver glove.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Narcissa!\rdblquote  he said, in a squeaky voice. \ldblquote And Bellatrix! How charming \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wormtail will get us drinks, if you\rquote d like them,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote And then he will return to his bedroom.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Wormtail winced as though Snape had thrown something at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am not your servant!\rdblquote  he squeaked, avoiding Snape\rquote s eye.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Really? I was under the impression that the Dark Lord placed you here to assist me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote To assist, yes \emdash  but not to make you drinks and \emdash  and clean your house!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I had no idea, Wormtail, that you were craving more dangerous assignments,\rdblquote  said Snape silkily. \ldblquote This can be easily arranged: I shall speak to the Dark Lord \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can speak to him myself if I want to!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course you can,\rdblquote  said Snape, sneering. \ldblquote But in the mean\-time, bring us drinks. Some of the elf-made wine will do.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Wormtail hesitated for a moment, looking as though he might argue, but then turned and headed through a second hidden door. They heard banging and a clinking of glasses. Within seconds he was back, bearing a dusty bottle and three glasses upon a tray. He dropped these on the rickety table and scurried from their pres\-ence, slamming the book-covered door behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape poured out three glasses of bloodred wine and handed two of them to the sisters. Narcissa murmured a word of thanks, whilst Bellatrix said nothing, but continued to glower at Snape. This did not seem to discompose him; on the contrary, he looked rather amused.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Dark Lord,\rdblquote  he said, raising his glass and draining it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The sisters copied him. Snape refilled their glasses. As Narcissa took her second drink she said in a rush, \ldblquote Severus, I\rquote m sorry to come here like this, but I had to see you. I think you are the only one who can help me \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape held up a hand to stop her, then pointed his wand again at the concealed staircase door. There was a loud bang and a squeal, followed by the sound of Wormtail scurrying back up the stairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My apologies,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote He has lately taken to listening at\lang3081  \lang1033 doors, I don\rquote t know what he means by it. \'85 You were saying, Narcissa?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She took a great, shuddering breath and started again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Severus, I know I ought not to be here, I have been told to say nothing to anyone, but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then you ought to hold your tongue!\rdblquote  snarled Bellatrix. \ldblquote Par\-ticularly in present company!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote Present company\rquote ?\rdblquote  repeated Snape sardonically. \ldblquote And what am I to understand by that, Bellatrix?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That I don\rquote t trust you, Snape, as you very well know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Narcissa let out a noise that might have been a dry sob and cov\-ered her face with her hands. Snape set his glass down upon the table and sat back again, his hands upon the arms of his chair, smil\-ing into Bellatrix\rquote s glowering face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Narcissa, I think we ought to hear what Bellatrix is bursting to say; it will save tedious interruptions. Well, continue, Bellatrix,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote Why is it that you do not trust me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A hundred reasons!\rdblquote  she said loudly, striding out from behind the sofa to slam her glass upon the table. \ldblquote Where to start! Where were you when the Dark Lord fell? Why did you never make any attempt to find him when he vanished? What have you been doing all these years that you\rquote ve lived in Dumbledore\rquote s pocket? Why did you stop the Dark Lord procuring the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone? Why did you not return at once when the Dark Lord was reborn? Where were you a few weeks ago when we battled to retrieve the prophecy for the Dark Lord? And why, Snape, is Harry Potter still alive, when you have had him at your mercy for five years?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She paused, her chest rising and falling rapidly, the color high in\lang3081  \lang1033 her cheeks. Behind her, Narcissa sat motionless, her face still hid\-den in her hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape smiled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Before I answer you \emdash  oh yes, Bellatrix, I am going to answer! You can carry my words back to the others who whisper behind my back, and carry false tales of my treachery to the Dark Lord! Before I answer you, I say, let me ask a question in turn. Do you really think that the Dark Lord has not asked me each and every one of those questions? And do you really think that, had I not been able to give satisfactory answers, I would be sitting here talking to you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She hesitated.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know he believes you, but\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You think he is mistaken? Or that I have somehow hoodwinked him? Fooled the Dark Lord, the greatest wizard, the most accom\-plished Legilimens the world has ever seen?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Bellatrix said nothing, but looked, for the first time, a little dis\-comfited. Snape did not press the point. He picked up his drink again, sipped it, and continued, \ldblquote You ask where I was when the Dark Lord fell. I was where he had ordered me to be, at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry, because he wished me to spy upon Albus Dumbledore. You know, I presume, that it was on the Dark Lord\rquote s orders that I took up the post?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She nodded almost imperceptibly and then opened her mouth, but Snape forestalled her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You ask why I did not attempt to find him when he vanished. For the same reason that Avery, Yaxley, the Carrows, Greyback, Lu\-cius\rdblquote  \emdash  he inclined his head slightly to Narcissa \emdash  \ldblquote and many others did not attempt to find him. I believed him finished. I am not proud of it, I was wrong, but there it is. \'85 If he had not\lang3081  \lang1033 forgiven we who lost faith at that time, he would have very few fol\-lowers left.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote d have me!\rdblquote  said Bellatrix passionately. \ldblquote I, who spent many years in Azkaban for him!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, indeed, most admirable,\rdblquote  said Snape in a bored voice. \ldblquote Of course, you weren\rquote t a lot of use to him in prison, but the gesture was undoubtedly fine \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gesture!\rdblquote  she shrieked; in her fury she looked slightly mad. \ldblquote While I endured the dementors, you remained at Hogwarts, com\-fortably playing Dumbledore\rquote s pet!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not quite,\rdblquote  said Snape calmly. \ldblquote He wouldn\rquote t give me the De\-fense Against the Dark Arts job, you know. Seemed to think it might, ah, bring about a relapse \'85 tempt me into my old ways.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This was your sacrifice for the Dark Lord, not to teach your fa\-vorite subject?\rdblquote  she jeered. \ldblquote Why did you stay there all that time, Snape? Still spying on Dumbledore for a master you believed dead?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hardly,\rdblquote  said Snape, \ldblquote although the Dark Lord is pleased that I never deserted my post: I had sixteen years of information on Dumbledore to give him when he returned, a rather more useful welcome-back present than endless reminiscences of how unpleas\-ant Azkaban is. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
