\lang1033\i Dear Harry,\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i If it is convenient to you, I shall call at number four, Privet Drive this coming Friday at eleven p.m. to escort you to the Burrow, where you have been invited to spend the remainder of your school holidays.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i If you are agreeable, I should also be glad of your assistance in a matter to which I hope to attend on the way to the Burrow. I shall explain this more fully when I see you.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Kindly send your answer by return of this owl. Hoping to see you this Friday,\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i I am, yours most sincerely,\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Albus\lang3081  Dumbledore\par
\lang1033\i0\par
Though he already knew it by heart, Harry had been stealing glances at this missive every few minutes since seven o\rquote clock that evening, when he had first taken up his position beside his bed\-room window, which had a reasonable view of both ends of Privet Drive. He knew it was pointless to keep rereading Dumbledore\rquote s words; Harry had sent back his \ldblquote yes\rdblquote  with the delivering owl, as re\-quested, and all he could do now was wait: Either Dumbledore was going to come, or he was not.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry had not packed. It just seemed too good to be true that he was going to be rescued from the Dursleys after a mere fort\-night of their company. He could not shrug off the feeling that something was going to go wrong \emdash  his reply to Dumbledore\rquote s let\-ter might have gone astray; Dumbledore could be prevented from collecting him; the letter might turn out not to be from Dumble\-dore at all, but a trick or joke or trap. Harry had not been able to face packing and then being let down and having to unpack again. The only gesture he had made to the possibility of a journey was to shut his snowy owl, Hedwig, safely in her cage.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The minute hand on the alarm clock reached the number twelve and, at that precise moment, the streetlamp outside the window went out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry awoke as though the sudden darkness were an alarm. Hastily straightening his glasses and unsticking his cheek from the glass, he pressed his nose against the window instead and squinted down at the pavement. A tall figure in a long, billowing cloak was walking up the garden path.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry jumped up as though he had received an electric shock, knocked over his chair, and started snatching anything and everything within reach from the floor and throwing it into the trunk. Even as he lobbed a set of robes, two spellbooks, and a packet of crisps across the room, the doorbell rang. Downstairs in the living room his Uncle Vernon shouted, \ldblquote Who the blazes is calling at this time of night?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry froze with a brass telescope in one hand and a pair of trainers in the other. He had completely forgotten to warn the Dursleys that Dumbledore might be coming. Feeling both panicky and close to laughter, he clambered over the trunk and wrenched open his bedroom door in time to hear a deep voice say, \ldblquote Good evening. You must be Mr. Dursley. I daresay Harry has told you I would be coming for him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry ran down the stairs two at a time, coming to an abrupt halt several steps from the bottom, as long experience had taught him to remain out of arm\rquote s reach of his uncle whenever possible. There in the doorway stood a tall, thin man with waist-length sil\-ver hair and beard. Half-moon spectacles were perched on his crooked nose, and he was wearing a long black traveling cloak and a pointed hat. Vernon Dursley, whose mustache was quite as bushy as Dumbledore\rquote s, though black, and who was wearing a puce dress\-ing gown, was staring at the visitor as though he could not believe his tiny eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Judging by your look of stunned disbelief, Harry did \i not\i0  warn you that I was coming,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore pleasantly. \ldblquote However, let us assume that you have invited me warmly into your house. It is unwise to linger overlong on doorsteps in these troubled times.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stepped smartly over the threshold and closed the front door behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is a long time since my last visit,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, peering down his crooked nose at Uncle Vernon. \ldblquote I must say, your agapan\-thus are flourishing.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Vernon Dursley said nothing at all. Harry did not doubt that speech would return to him, and soon \emdash  the vein pulsing in his uncle\rquote s temple was reaching danger point \emdash  but something about Dumbledore seemed to have robbed him temporarily of breath. It might have been the blatant wizardishness of his appearance, but it might, too, have been that even Uncle Vernon could sense that here was a man whom it would be very difficult to bully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, good evening Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, looking up at him through his half-moon glasses with a most satisfied expression. \ldblquote Excellent, excellent.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 These words seemed to rouse Uncle Vernon. It was clear that as far as he was concerned, any man who could look at Harry and say \ldblquote excellent\rdblquote  was a man with whom he could never see eye to eye.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t mean to be rude \emdash\rdblquote  he began, in a tone that threatened rudeness in every syllable.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  yet, sadly, accidental rudeness occurs alarmingly often,\rdblquote  Dumbledore finished the sentence gravely. \ldblquote Best to say nothing at all, my dear man. Ah, and this must be Petunia.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The kitchen door had opened, and there stood Harry\rquote s aunt, wearing rubber gloves and a housecoat over her nightdress, clearly halfway through her usual pre-bedtime wipe-down of all the kitchen surfaces. Her rather horsey face registered nothing but shock.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Albus Dumbledore,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, when Uncle Vernon failed to effect an introduction. \ldblquote We have corresponded, of course.\rdblquote  Harry thought this an odd way of reminding Aunt Petunia that he\lang3081  \lang1033 had once sent her an exploding letter, but Aunt Petunia did not challenge the term. \ldblquote And this must be your son, Dudley?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley had that moment peered round the living room door. His large, blond head rising out of the stripy collar of his pajamas looked oddly disembodied, his mouth gaping in astonishment and fear. Dumbledore waited a moment or two, apparently to see whether any of the Dursleys were going to say anything, but as the silence stretched on he smiled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shall we assume that you have invited me into your sitting room?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley scrambled out of the way as Dumbledore passed him. Harry, still clutching the telescope and trainers, jumped the last few stairs and followed Dumbledore, who had settled himself in the armchair nearest the fire and was taking in the surroundings with an expression of benign interest. He looked quite extraordi\-narily out of place.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aren\rquote t \emdash  aren\rquote t we leaving, sir?\rdblquote  Harry asked anxiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, indeed we are, but there are a few matters we need to dis\-cuss first,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote And I would prefer not to do so in the open. We shall trespass upon your aunt and uncle\rquote s hospitality only a little longer.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You will, will you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Vernon Dursley had entered the room, Petunia at his shoulder, and Dudley skulking behind them both.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore simply, \ldblquote I shall.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He drew his wand so rapidly that Harry barely saw it; with a ca\-sual flick, the sofa zoomed forward and knocked the knees out from under all three of the Dursleys so that they collapsed upon it\lang3081  \lang1033 in a heap. Another flick of the wand and the sofa zoomed back to its original position.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We may as well be comfortable,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore pleasantly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As he replaced his wand in his pocket, Harry saw that his hand was blackened and shriveled; it looked as though his flesh had been burned away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir \emdash  what happened to your \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Later, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Please sit down.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry took the remaining armchair, choosing not to look at the Dursleys, who seemed stunned into silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I would assume that you were going to offer me refreshment,\rdblquote  Dumbledore said to Uncle Vernon, \ldblquote but the evidence so far sug\-gests that that would be optimistic to the point of foolishness.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A third twitch of the wand, and a dusty bottle and five glasses appeared in midair. The bottle tipped and poured a generous mea\-sure of honey-colored liquid into each of the glasses, which then floated to each person in the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Madam Rosmerta\rquote s finest oak-matured mead,\rdblquote  said Dumble\-dore, raising his glass to Harry, who caught hold of his own and sipped. He had never tasted anything like it before, but enjoyed it immensely. The Dursleys, after quick, scared looks at one an\-other, tried to ignore their glasses completely, a difficult feat, as they were nudging them gently on the sides of their heads. Harry could not suppress a suspicion that Dumbledore was rather enjoy\-ing himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, turning toward him, \ldblquote a diffi\-culty has arisen which I hope you will be able to solve for us. By \i us,\i0  I mean the Order of the Phoenix. But first of all I must tell you that\lang3081  \lang1033 Sirius\rquote s will was discovered a week ago and that he left you every\-thing he owned.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Over on the sofa, Uncle Vernon\rquote s head turned, but Harry did not look at him, nor could he think of anything to say except, \ldblquote Oh. Right.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is, in the main, fairly straightforward,\rdblquote  Dumbledore went on. \ldblquote You add a reasonable amount of gold to your account at Gringotts, and you inherit all of Sirius\rquote s personal possessions. The slightly problematic part of the legacy \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote His godfather\rquote s dead?\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon loudly from the sofa. Dumbledore and Harry both turned to look at him. The glass of mead was now knocking quite insistently on the side of Vernon\rquote s head; he attempted to beat it away. \ldblquote He\rquote s dead? His godfather?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. He did not ask Harry why he had not confided in the Dursleys. \ldblquote Our problem,\rdblquote  he continued to Harry, as if there had been no interruption, \ldblquote is that Sirius also left you number twelve, Grimmauld Place.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s been left a house?\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon greedily, his small eyes narrowing, but nobody answered him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You can keep using it as headquarters,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I don\rquote t care. You can have it, I don\rquote t really want it.\rdblquote  Harry never wanted to set foot in number twelve, Grimmauld Place again if he could help it. He thought he would be haunted forever by the memory of Sirius prowling its dark musty rooms alone, imprisoned within the place he had wanted so desperately to leave.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That is generous,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote We have, however, va\-cated the building temporarily.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, ignoring the mutterings of Uncle Vernon, who was now being rapped smartly over the head by the persistent glass of mead, \ldblquote Black family tradition decreed that the house was handed down the direct line, to the next male with the name of \lquote Black.\rquote  Sirius was the very last of the line as his younger brother, Regulus, predeceased him and both were childless. While his will makes it perfectly plain that he wants you to have the house, it is nevertheless possible that some spell or enchantment has been set upon the place to ensure that it cannot be owned by anyone other than a pureblood.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A vivid image of the shrieking, spitting portrait of Sirius\rquote s mother that hung in the hall of number twelve, Grimmauld Place flashed into Harry\rquote s mind. \ldblquote I bet there has,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Quite,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote And if such an enchantment exists, then the ownership of the house is most likely to pass to the eldest of Sirius\rquote s living relatives, which would mean his cousin, Bellatrix Lestrange.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Without realizing what he was doing, Harry sprang to his feet; the telescope and trainers in his lap rolled across the floor. Bellatrix Lestrange, Sirius\rquote s killer, inherit his house?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, obviously we would prefer that she didn\rquote t get it either,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore calmly. \ldblquote The situation is fraught with complica\-tions. We do not know whether the enchantments we ourselves have placed upon it, for example, making it Unplottable, will hold now that ownership has passed from Sirius\rquote s hands. It might be that Bellatrix will arrive on the doorstep at any moment. Naturally we had to move out until such time as we have clarified the position.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But how are you going to find out if I\rquote m allowed to own it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fortunately,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote there is a simple test.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He placed his empty glass on a small table beside his chair, but before he could do anything else, Uncle Vernon shouted, \ldblquote\i Will\lang3081  \lang1033 you get these ruddy things off us\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around; all three of the Dursleys were cowering with their arms over their heads as their glasses bounced up and down on their skulls, their contents flying everywhere.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I\rquote m so sorry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore politely, and he raised his wand again. All three glasses vanished. \ldblquote But it would have been better manners to drink it, you know.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It looked as though Uncle Vernon was bursting with any num\-ber of unpleasant retorts, but he merely shrank back into the cush\-ions with Aunt Petunia and Dudley and said nothing, keeping his small piggy eyes on Dumbledore\rquote s wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You see,\rdblquote  Dumbledore said, turning back to Harry and again speaking as though Uncle Vernon had not uttered, \ldblquote if you have in\-deed inherited the house, you have also inherited \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He flicked his wand for a fifth time. There was a loud crack, and a house-elf appeared, with a snout for a nose, giant bat\rquote s ears, and enormous bloodshot eyes, crouching on the Dursleys\rquote  shag carpet and covered in grimy rags. Aunt Petunia let out a hair-raising shriek; nothing this filthy had entered her house in living memory. Dudley drew his large, bare, pink feet off the floor and sat with them raised almost above his head, as though he thought the crea\-ture might run up his pajama trousers, and Uncle Vernon bel\-lowed, \ldblquote What the \i hell\i0  is that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher,\rdblquote  finished Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher won\rquote t, Kreacher won\rquote t, Kreacher won\rquote t!\rdblquote  croaked the house-elf, quite as loudly as Uncle Vernon, stamping his long,\lang3081  \lang1033 gnarled feet and pulling his ears. \ldblquote Kreacher belongs to Miss Bella\-trix, oh yes, Kreacher belongs to the Blacks, Kreacher wants his new mistress, Kreacher won\rquote t go to the Potter brat, Kreacher won\rquote t, won\rquote t, won\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As you can see, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore loudly, over Kreacher\rquote s continued croaks of \ldblquote won\rquote t, won\rquote t, won\rquote t,\rdblquote  \ldblquote Kreacher is showing a certain reluctance to pass into your ownership.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t care,\rdblquote  said Harry again, looking with disgust at the writhing, stamping house-elf. \ldblquote I don\rquote t want him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Won\rquote t, won\rquote t, won\rquote t, won\rquote t\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You would prefer him to pass into the ownership of Bellatrix Lestrange? Bearing in mind that he has lived at the headquarters of the Order of the Phoenix for the past year?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Won\rquote t, won\rquote t, won\rquote t, won\rquote t\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared at Dumbledore. He knew that Kreacher could not be permitted to go and live with Bellatrix Lestrange, but the idea of owning him, of having responsibility for the creature that had be\-trayed Sirius, was repugnant.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Give him an order,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote If he has passed into your ownership, he will have to obey. If not, then we shall have to think of some other means of keeping him from his rightful mis\-tress.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Won\rquote t, won\rquote t, won\rquote t, WON\rquote T\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kreacher\rquote s voice had risen to a scream. Harry could think of nothing to say, except, \ldblquote Kreacher, shut up!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It looked for a moment as though Kreacher was going to choke. He grabbed his throat, his mouth still working furiously, his eyes bulging. After a few seconds of frantic gulping, he threw himself face forward onto the carpet (Aunt Petunia whimpered) and beat\lang3081  \lang1033 the floor with his hands and feet, giving himself over to a violent, but entirely silent, tantrum.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, that simplifies matters,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore cheerfully. \ldblquote It seems that Sirius knew what he was doing. You are the rightful owner of number twelve, Grimmauld Place and of Kreacher.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do I \emdash  do I have to keep him with me?\rdblquote  Harry asked, aghast, as Kreacher thrashed around at his feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not if you don\rquote t want to,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote If I might make a suggestion, you could send him to Hogwarts to work in the kitchen there. In that way, the other house-elves could keep an eye on him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry in relief, \ldblquote yeah, I\rquote ll do that. Er \emdash  Kreacher \emdash  I want you to go to Hogwarts and work in the kitchens there with the other house-elves.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kreacher, who was now lying flat on his back with his arms and legs in the air, gave Harry one upside-down look of deepest loathing and, with another loud crack, vanished.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote There is also the matter of the hip\-pogriff, Buckbeak. Hagrid has been looking after him since Sirius died, but Buckbeak is yours now, so if you would prefer to make different arrangements \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry at once, \ldblquote he can stay with Hagrid. I think Buckbeak would prefer that.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid will be delighted,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, smiling. \ldblquote He was thrilled to see Buckbeak again. Incidentally, we have decided, in the interests of Buckbeak\rquote s safety, to rechristen him \lquote Witherwings\rquote  for the time being, though I doubt that the Ministry would ever guess he is the hippogriff they once sentenced to death. Now, Harry, is your trunk packed?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Erm \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Doubtful that I would turn up?\rdblquote  Dumbledore suggested shrewdly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll just go and \emdash  er \emdash  finish off,\rdblquote  said Harry hastily, hurrying to pick up his fallen telescope and trainers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It took him a little over ten minutes to track down everything he needed; at last he had managed to extract his Invisibility Cloak from under the bed, screwed the top back on his jar of color-change ink, and forced the lid of his trunk shut on his cauldron. Then, heaving his trunk in one hand and holding Hedwig\rquote s cage in the other, he made his way back downstairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was disappointed to discover that Dumbledore was not wait\-ing in the hall, which meant that he had to return to the living room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nobody was talking. Dumbledore was humming quietly, appar\-ently quite at his ease, but the atmosphere was thicker than cold custard, and Harry did not dare look at the Dursleys as he said, \ldblquote Professor \emdash  I\rquote m ready now.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Just one last thing, then.\rdblquote  And he turned to speak to the Dursleys once more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As you will no doubt be aware, Harry comes of age in a year\rquote s time \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia, speaking for the first time since Dum\-bledore\rquote s arrival.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore politely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, he doesn\rquote t. He\rquote s a month younger than Dudley, and Dudders doesn\rquote t turn eighteen until the year after next.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore pleasantly, \ldblquote but in the Wizarding world, we come of age at seventeen.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon muttered, \ldblquote Preposterous,\rdblquote  but Dumbledore ig\-nored him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, as you already know, the wizard called Lord Voldemort has returned to this country. The Wizarding community is cur\-rently in a state of open warfare. Harry, whom Lord Voldemort has already attempted to kill on a number of occasions, is in even greater danger now than the day when I left him upon your doorstep fifteen years ago, with a letter explaining about his par\-ents\rquote  murder and expressing the hope that you would care for him as though he were your own.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore paused, and although his voice remained light and calm, and he gave no obvious sign of anger, Harry felt a kind of chill emanating from him and noticed that the Dursleys drew very slightly closer together.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You did not do as I asked. You have never treated Harry as a son. He has known nothing but neglect and often cruelty at your hands. The best that can be said is that he has at least escaped the appalling damage you have inflicted upon the unfortunate boy sit\-ting between you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Both Aunt Petunia and Uncle Vernon looked around instinc\-tively, as though expecting to see someone other than Dudley squeezed between them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Us \emdash  mistreat Dudders? What d\rquote you \emdash  ?\rdblquote  began Uncle Ver\-non furiously, but Dumbledore raised his finger for silence, a si\-lence which fell as though he had struck Uncle Vernon dumb.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The magic I evoked fifteen years ago means that Harry has pow\-erful protection while he can still call this house \lquote home.\rquote  However miserable he has been here, however unwelcome, however badly treated, you have at least, grudgingly, allowed him houseroom. This\lang3081  \lang1033 magic will cease to operate the moment that Harry turns seventeen; in other words, at the moment he becomes a man. I ask only this: that you allow Harry to return, once more, to this house, before his seventeenth birthday, which will ensure that the protection contin\-ues until that time.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 None of the Dursleys said anything. Dudley was frowning slightly, as though he was still trying to work out when he had ever been mistreated. Uncle Vernon looked as though he had something stuck in his throat; Aunt Petunia, however, was oddly flushed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Harry \'85 time for us to be off,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore at last, standing up and straightening his long black cloak. \ldblquote Until we meet again,\rdblquote  he said to the Dursleys, who looked as though that moment could wait forever as far as they were concerned, and after doffing his hat, he swept from the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bye,\rdblquote  said Harry hastily to the Dursleys, and followed Dum\-bledore, who paused beside Harry\rquote s trunk, upon which Hedwig\rquote s cage was perched.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We do not want to be encumbered by these just now,\rdblquote  he said, pulling out his wand again. \ldblquote I shall send them to the Burrow to await us there. However, I would like you to bring your Invisibility Cloak \'85 just in case.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry extracted his cloak from his trunk with some difficulty, trying not to show Dumbledore the mess within. When he had stuffed it into an inside pocket of his jacket, Dumbledore waved his wand and the trunk, cage, and Hedwig vanished. Dumbledore then waved his wand again, and the front door opened onto cool, misty darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And now, Harry, let us step out into the night and pursue that flighty temptress, adventure.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
