Despite the fact that he had spent every waking moment of\lang3081  \lang1033 the past few days hoping desperately that Dumbledore would indeed come to fetch him, Harry felt distinctly awkward as they set off down Privet Drive together. He had never had a proper conversation with the headmaster outside of Hogwarts before; there was usually a desk between them. The memory of their last face-to-face encounter kept intruding too, and it rather heightened Harry\rquote s sense of embarrassment; he had shouted a lot on that occa\-sion, not to mention done his best to smash several of Dumble\-dore\rquote s most prized possessions.\par
Dumbledore, however, seemed completely relaxed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Keep your wand at the ready, Harry,\rdblquote  he said brightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But I thought I\rquote m not allowed to use magic outside school, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If there is an attack,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote I give you permission to use any counterjinx or curse that might occur to you. However, I do not think you need worry about being attacked tonight.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why not, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are with me,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore simply. \ldblquote This will do, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He came to an abrupt halt at the end of Privet Drive.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You have not, of course, passed your Apparition Test,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I thought you had to be seventeen?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You do,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote So you will need to hold on to my arm very tightly. My left, if you don\rquote t mind \emdash  as you have noticed, my wand arm is a little fragile at the moment.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry gripped Dumbledore\rquote s proffered forearm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very good,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Well, here we go.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt Dumbledore\rquote s arm twist away from him and redou\-bled his grip; the next thing he knew, everything went black; he was being pressed very hard from all directions; he could not breathe, there were iron bands tightening around his chest; his eye\-balls were being forced back into his head; his eardrums were being pushed deeper into his skull and then \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He gulped great lungfuls of cold night air and opened his streaming eyes. He felt as though he had just been forced through a very tight rubber tube. It was a few seconds before he realized that Privet Drive had vanished. He and Dumbledore were now stand\-ing in what appeared to be a deserted village square, in the center of which stood an old war memorial and a few benches. His com\-prehension catching up with his senses, Harry realized that he had just Apparated for the first time in his life.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you all right?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore, looking down at him so\-licitously. \ldblquote The sensation does take some getting used to.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m fine,\rdblquote  said Harry, rubbing his ears, which felt as though\lang3081  \lang1033 they had left Privet Drive rather reluctantly. \ldblquote But I think I might prefer brooms. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore smiled, drew his traveling cloak a little more tightly around his neck, and said, \ldblquote This way.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He set off at a brisk pace, past an empty inn and a few houses. According to a clock on a nearby church, it was almost midnight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So tell me, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Your scar \'85 has it been hurting at all?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry raised a hand unconsciously to his forehead and rubbed the lightning-shaped mark.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote and I\rquote ve been wondering about that. I thought it would be burning all the time now Voldemort\rquote s getting so power\-ful again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He glanced up at Dumbledore and saw that he was wearing a satisfied expression.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I, on the other hand, thought otherwise,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Lord Voldemort has finally realized the dangerous access to his thoughts and feelings you have been enjoying. It appears that he is now employing Occlumency against you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I\rquote m not complaining,\rdblquote  said Harry, who missed neither the disturbing dreams nor the startling flashes of insight into Voldemort\rquote s mind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They turned a corner, passing a telephone box and a bus shelter. Harry looked sideways at Dumbledore again. \ldblquote Professor?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  where exactly are we?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This, Harry, is the charming village of Budleigh Babberton.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And what are we doing here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah yes, of course, I haven\rquote t told you,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Well, I have lost count of the number of times I have said this in recent years, but we are, once again, one member of staff short. We are here to persuade an old colleague of mine to come out of retire\-ment and return to Hogwarts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How can I help with that, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I think we\rquote ll find a use for you,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore vaguely. \ldblquote Left here, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They proceeded up a steep, narrow street lined with houses. All the windows were dark. The odd chill that had lain over Privet Drive for two weeks persisted here too. Thinking of dementors, Harry cast a look over his shoulder and grasped his wand reassur\-ingly in his pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor, why couldn\rquote t we just Apparate directly into your old colleague\rquote s house?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because it would be quite as rude as kicking down the front door,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Courtesy dictates that we offer fellow wizards the opportunity of denying us entry. In any case, most Wizarding dwellings are magically protected from unwanted Ap\-parators. At Hogwarts, for instance \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  you can\rquote t Apparate anywhere inside the buildings or grounds,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote Hermione Granger told me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And she is quite right. We turn left again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The church clock chimed midnight behind them. Harry won\-dered why Dumbledore did not consider it rude to call on his old colleague so late, but now that conversation had been established, he had more pressing questions to ask.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir, I saw in the \i Daily Prophet\i0  that Fudge has been sacked. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Correct,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, now turning up a steep side street.\lang3081  \lang1033\ldblquote He has been replaced, as I am sure you also saw, by Rufus Scrim\-geour, who used to be Head of the Auror office.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is he \'85 Do you think he\rquote s good?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote An interesting question,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote He is able, cer\-tainly. A more decisive and forceful personality than Cornelius.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but I meant \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know what you meant. Rufus is a man of action and, having fought Dark wizards for most of his working life, does not under\-estimate Lord Voldemort.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry waited, but Dumbledore did not say anything about the disagreement with Scrimgeour that the \i Daily Prophet\i0  had reported, and he did not have the nerve to pursue the subject, so he changed it. \ldblquote And \'85 sir \'85 I saw about Madam Bones.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly. \ldblquote A terrible loss. She was a great witch. Just up here, I think \emdash  ouch.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had pointed with his injured hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor, what happened to your \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have no time to explain now,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote It is a thrilling tale, I wish to do it justice.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He smiled at Harry, who understood that he was not being snubbed, and that he had permission to keep asking questions.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir \emdash  I got a Ministry of Magic leaflet by owl, about security measures we should all take against the Death Eaters. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I received one myself,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, still smiling. \ldblquote Did you find it useful?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not really.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I thought not. You have not asked me, for instance, what is my favorite flavor of jam, to check that I am indeed Professor Dumbledore and not an impostor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  Harry began, not entirely sure whether he was be\-ing reprimanded or not.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote For future reference, Harry, it is raspberry\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 although of course, if I were a Death Eater, I would have been sure to research my own jam preferences before impersonating myself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \'85 right,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Well, on that leaflet, it said some\-thing about Inferi. What exactly are they? The leaflet wasn\rquote t very clear.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They are corpses,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore calmly. \ldblquote Dead bodies that have been bewitched to do a Dark wizard\rquote s bidding. Inferi have not been seen for a long time, however, not since Voldemort was last powerful. \'85 He killed enough people to make an army of them, of course. This is the place, Harry, just here. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were nearing a small, neat stone house set in its own gar\-den. Harry was too busy digesting the horrible idea of Inferi to have much attention left for anything else, but as they reached the front gate, Dumbledore stopped dead and Harry walked into him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh dear. Oh dear, dear, dear.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry followed his gaze up the carefully tended front path and felt his heart sink. The front door was hanging off its hinges.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore glanced up and down the street. It seemed quite deserted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wand out and follow me, Harry,\rdblquote  he said quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He opened the gate and walked swiftly and silently up the gar\-den path, Harry at his heels, then pushed the front door very slowly, his wand raised and at the ready.\par
\ldblquote\i Lumos.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore\rquote s wand tip ignited, casting its light up a narrow hallway. To the left, another door stood open. Holding his illumi\-nated wand aloft, Dumbledore walked into the sitting room with Harry right behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A scene of total devastation met their eyes. A grandfather clock lay splintered at their feet, its face cracked, its pendulum lying a lit\-tle farther away like a dropped sword. A piano was on its side, its keys strewn across the floor. The wreckage of a fallen chandelier glittered nearby. Cushions lay deflated, feathers oozing from slashes in their sides; fragments of glass and china lay like powder over everything. Dumbledore raised his wand even higher, so that its light was thrown upon the walls, where something darkly red and glutinous was spattered over the wallpaper. Harry\rquote s small intake of breath made Dumbledore look around.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not pretty, is it?\rdblquote  he said heavily. \ldblquote Yes, something horrible has happened here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore moved carefully into the middle of the room, scru\-tinizing the wreckage at his feet. Harry followed, gazing around, half-scared of what he might see hidden behind the wreck of the pi\-ano or the overturned sofa, but there was no sign of a body.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe there was a fight and \emdash  and they dragged him off, Pro\-fessor?\rdblquote  Harry suggested, trying not to imagine how badly wounded a man would have to be to leave those stains spattered halfway up the walls.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think so,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly, peering behind an overstuffed armchair lying on its side.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You mean he\rquote s \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Still here somewhere? Yes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And without warning, Dumbledore swooped, plunging the tip of his wand into the seat of the overstuffed armchair, which yelled, \ldblquote Ouch!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good evening, Horace,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, straightening up again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s jaw dropped. Where a split second before there had been an armchair, there now crouched an enormously fat, bald, old man who was massaging his lower belly and squinting up at Dumble\-dore with an aggrieved and watery eye.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There was no need to stick the wand in that hard,\rdblquote  he said gruffly, clambering to his feet. \ldblquote It hurt.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wandlight sparkled on his shiny pate, his prominent eyes, his enormous, silver, walruslike mustache, and the highly polished buttons on the maroon velvet jacket he was wearing over a pair of lilac silk pajamas. The top of his head barely reached Dumbledore\rquote s chin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What gave it away?\rdblquote  he grunted as he staggered to his feet, still rubbing his lower belly. He seemed remarkably unabashed for a man who had just been discovered pretending to be an armchair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dear Horace,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, looking amused, \ldblquote if the Death Eaters really had come to call, the Dark Mark would have been set over the house.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wizard clapped a pudgy hand to his vast forehead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Dark Mark,\rdblquote  he muttered. \ldblquote Knew there was something \'85 ah well. Wouldn\rquote t have had time anyway, I\rquote d only just put the finishing touches to my upholstery when you entered the room.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He heaved a great sigh that made the ends of his mustache flutter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Would you like my assistance clearing up?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore politely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please,\rdblquote  said the other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They stood back to back, the tall thin wizard and the short round one, and waved their wands in one identical sweeping motion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The furniture flew back to its original places; ornaments re\-formed in midair, feathers zoomed into their cushions; torn books repaired themselves as they landed upon their shelves; oil lanterns soared onto side tables and reignited; a vast collection of splintered silver picture frames flew glittering across the room and alighted, whole and untarnished, upon a desk; rips, cracks, and holes healed everywhere, and the walls wiped themselves clean.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What kind of blood was that, incidentally?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore loudly over the chiming of the newly unsmashed grandfather clock.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote On the walls? Dragon,\rdblquote  shouted the wizard called Horace, as, with a deafening grinding and tinkling, the chandelier screwed it\-self back into the ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a final \i plunk\i0  from the piano, and silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, dragon,\rdblquote  repeated the wizard conversationally. \ldblquote My last bottle, and prices are sky-high at the moment. Still, it might be reusable.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stumped over to a small crystal bottle standing on top of a sideboard and held it up to the light, examining the thick liquid within.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hmm. Bit dusty.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He set the bottle back on the sideboard and sighed. It was then that his gaze fell upon Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oho,\rdblquote  he said, his large round eyes flying to Harry\rquote s forehead and the lightning-shaped scar it bore. \ldblquote\i Oho\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, moving forward to make the intro\-duction, \ldblquote is Harry Potter. Harry, this is an old friend and colleague of mine, Horace Slughorn.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn turned on Dumbledore, his expression shrewd. \ldblquote So that\rquote s how you thought you\rquote d persuade me, is it? Well, the answer\rquote s no, Albus.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pushed past Harry, his face turned resolutely away with the air of a man trying to resist temptation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I suppose we can have a drink, at least?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore. \ldblquote For old time\rquote s sake?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn hesitated.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right then, one drink,\rdblquote  he said ungraciously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore smiled at Harry and directed him toward a chair not unlike the one that Slughorn had so recently impersonated, which stood right beside the newly burning fire and a brightly glowing oil lamp. Harry took the seat with the distinct impression that Dumbledore, for some reason, wanted to keep him as visible as possible. Certainly when Slughorn, who had been busy with de\-canters and glasses, turned to face the room again, his eyes fell im\-mediately upon Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hmpf,\rdblquote  he said, looking away quickly as though frightened of hurting his eyes. \ldblquote Here \emdash\rdblquote  He gave a drink to Dumbledore, who had sat down without invitation, thrust the tray at Harry, and then sank into the cushions of the repaired sofa and a disgruntled si\-lence. His legs were so short they did not touch the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, how have you been keeping, Horace?\rdblquote  Dumbledore asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not so well,\rdblquote  said Slughorn at once. \ldblquote Weak chest. Wheezy.\lang3081  \lang1033 Rheumatism too. Can\rquote t move like I used to. Well, that\rquote s to be ex\-pected. Old age. Fatigue.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And yet you must have moved fairly quickly to prepare such a welcome for us at such short notice,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote You can\rquote t have had more than three minutes\rquote  warning?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn said, half irritably, half proudly, \ldblquote Two. Didn\rquote t hear my Intruder Charm go off, I was taking a bath. Still,\rdblquote  he added sternly, seeming to pull himself back together again, \ldblquote the fact remains that I\rquote m an old man, Albus. A tired old man who\rquote s earned the right to a quiet life and a few creature comforts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He certainly had those, thought Harry, looking around the room. It was stuffy and cluttered, yet nobody could say it was un\-comfortable; there were soft chairs and footstools, drinks and books, boxes of chocolates and plump cushions. If Harry had not known who lived there, he would have guessed at a rich, fussy old lady.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re not yet as old as I am, Horace,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, maybe you ought to think about retirement yourself,\rdblquote  said Slughorn bluntly. His pale gooseberry eyes had found Dum\-bledore\rquote s injured hand. \ldblquote Reactions not what they were, I see.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re quite right,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore serenely, shaking back his sleeve to reveal the tips of those burned and blackened fingers; the sight of them made the back of Harry\rquote s neck prickle unpleasantly. \ldblquote I am undoubtedly slower than I was. But on the other hand \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He shrugged and spread his hands wide, as though to say that age had its compensations, and Harry noticed a ring on his unin\-jured hand that he had never seen Dumbledore wear before: It was large, rather clumsily made of what looked like gold, and was set\lang3081  \lang1033 with a heavy black stone that had cracked down the middle. Slughorn\rquote s eyes lingered for a moment on the ring too, and Harry saw a tiny frown momentarily crease his wide forehead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, all these precautions against intruders, Horace \'85 are they for the Death Eaters\rquote  benefit, or mine?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What would the Death Eaters want with a poor broken-down old buffer like me?\rdblquote  demanded Slughorn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I imagine that they would want you to turn your considerable talents to coercion, torture, and murder,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Are you really telling me that they haven\rquote t come recruiting yet?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn eyed Dumbledore balefully for a moment, then mut\-tered, \ldblquote I haven\rquote t given them the chance. I\rquote ve been on the move for a year. Never stay in one place more than a week. Move from Mug\-gle house to Muggle house \emdash  the owners of this place are on holi\-day in the Canary Islands \emdash  it\rquote s been very pleasant, I\rquote ll be sorry to leave. It\rquote s quite easy once you know how, one simple Freezing Charm on these absurd burglar alarms they use instead of Sneako\-scopes and make sure the neighbors don\rquote t spot you bringing in the piano.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ingenious,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote But it sounds a rather tiring ex\-istence for a broken-down old buffer in search of a quiet life. Now, if you were to return to Hogwarts \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you\rquote re going to tell me my life would be more peaceful at that pestilential school, you can save your breath, Albus! I might have been in hiding, but some funny rumors have reached me since Do\-lores Umbridge left! If that\rquote s how you treat teachers these days \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Umbridge ran afoul of our centaur herd,\rdblquote  said Dum\-bledore. \ldblquote I think you, Horace, would have known better than to\lang3081  \lang1033 stride into the forest and call a horde of angry centaurs \lquote filthy half-breeds.\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s what she did, did she?\rdblquote  said Slughorn. \ldblquote Idiotic woman. Never liked her.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry chuckled and both Dumbledore and Slughorn looked round at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  Harry said hastily. \ldblquote It\rquote s just \emdash  I didn\rquote t like her either.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore stood up rather suddenly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you leaving?\rdblquote  asked Slughorn at once, looking hopeful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I was wondering whether I might use your bathroom,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Slughorn, clearly disappointed. \ldblquote Second on the left down the hall.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore strode from the room. Once the door had closed behind him, there was silence. After a few moments, Slughorn got to his feet but seemed uncertain what to do with himself. He shot a furtive look at Harry, then crossed to the fire and turned his back on it, warming his wide behind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t think I don\rquote t know why he\rquote s brought you,\rdblquote  he said abruptly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry merely looked at Slughorn. Slughorn\rquote s watery eyes slid over Harry\rquote s scar, this time taking in the rest of his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You look very like your father.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I\rquote ve been told,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Except for your eyes. You\rquote ve got \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My mother\rquote s eyes, yeah.\rdblquote  Harry had heard it so often he found it a bit wearing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hmpf. Yes, well. You shouldn\rquote t have favorites as a teacher, of\lang3081  \lang1033 course, but she was one of mine. Your mother,\rdblquote  Slughorn added, in answer to Harry\rquote s questioning look. \ldblquote Lily Evans. One of the bright\-est I ever taught. Vivacious, you know. Charming girl. I used to tell her she ought to have been in my House. Very cheeky answers I used to get back too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Which was your House?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was Head of Slytherin,\rdblquote  said Slughorn. \ldblquote Oh, now,\rdblquote  he went on quickly, seeing the expression on Harry\rquote s face and wagging a stubby finger at him, \ldblquote don\rquote t go holding that against me! You\rquote ll be Gryffindor like her, I suppose? Yes, it usually goes in families. Not always, though. Ever heard of Sirius Black? You must have done \emdash  been in the papers for the last couple of years \emdash  died a few weeks ago \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was as though an invisible hand had twisted Harry\rquote s intestines and held them tight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, anyway, he was a big pal of your father\rquote s at school. The whole Black family had been in my House, but Sirius ended up in Gryffindor! Shame \emdash  he was a talented boy. I got his brother, Regulus, when he came along, but I\rquote d have liked the set.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He sounded like an enthusiastic collector who had been outbid at auction. Apparently lost in memories, he gazed at the opposite wall, turning idly on the spot to ensure an even heat on his backside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your mother was Muggle-born, of course. Couldn\rquote t believe it when I found out. Thought she must have been pure-blood, she was so good.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote One of my best friends is Muggle-born,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote and she\rquote s the best in our year.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Funny how that sometimes happens, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Slughorn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not really,\rdblquote  said Harry coldly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn looked down at him in surprise. \ldblquote You mustn\rquote t think I\rquote m prejudiced!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote No, no, no! Haven\rquote t I just said your mother was one of my all-time favorite students? And there was Dirk Cresswell in the year after her too \emdash  now Head of the Gob\-lin Liaison Office, of course \emdash  another Muggle-born, a very gifted student, and still gives me excellent inside information on the goings-on at Gringotts!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He bounced up and down a little, smiling in a self-satisfied way, and pointed at the many glittering photograph frames on the dresser, each peopled with tiny moving occupants.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All ex-students, all signed. You\rquote ll notice Barnabas Cuffe, editor of the \i Daily Prophet,\i0  he\rquote s always interested to hear my take on the day\rquote s news. And Ambrosius Flume, of Honeydukes \emdash  a hamper every birthday, and all because I was able to give him an introduc\-tion to Ciceron Harkiss, who gave him his first job! And at the back \emdash  you\rquote ll see her if you just crane your neck \emdash  that\rquote s Gwenog Jones, who of course captains the Holyhead Harpies. \'85 People are always astonished to hear I\rquote m on first-name terms with the Harpies, and free tickets whenever I want them!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This thought seemed to cheer him up enormously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And all these people know where to find you, to send you stuff?\rdblquote  asked Harry, who could not help wondering why the Death Eaters had not yet tracked down Slughorn if hampers of sweets, Quidditch tickets, and visitors craving his advice and opinions could find him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The smile slid from Slughorn\rquote s face as quickly as the blood from his walls.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course not,\rdblquote  he said, looking down at Harry. \ldblquote I have been out of touch with everybody for a year.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
