\lang1033 As they set off down the garden path, Slughorn\rquote s voice floated af\-ter them, \ldblquote I\rquote ll want a pay rise, Dumbledore!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore chuckled. The garden gate swung shut behind them, and they set off back down the hill through the dark and the swirling mist.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well done, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t do anything,\rdblquote  said Harry in surprise.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes you did. You showed Horace exactly how much he stands to gain by returning to Hogwarts. Did you like him?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Er \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry wasn\rquote t sure whether he liked Slughorn or not. He sup\-posed he had been pleasant in his way, but he had also seemed vain and, whatever he said to the contrary, much too surprised that a Muggle-born should make a good witch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Horace,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, relieving Harry of the responsibil\-ity to say any of this, \ldblquote likes his comfort. He also likes the company of the famous, the successful, and the powerful. He enjoys the feel\-ing that he influences these people. He has never wanted to occupy\lang3081  \lang1033 the throne himself; he prefers the backseat \emdash  more room to spread out, you see. He used to handpick favorites at Hogwarts, some\-times for their ambition or their brains, sometimes for their charm or their talent, and he had an uncanny knack for choosing those who would go on to become outstanding in their various fields. Horace formed a kind of club of his favorites with himself at the center, making introductions, forging useful contacts between members, and always reaping some kind of benefit in return, whether a free box of his favorite crystalized pineapple or the chance to recommend the next junior member of the Goblin Liaison Office.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had a sudden and vivid mental image of a great swollen spider, spinning a web around it, twitching a thread here and there to bring its large and juicy flies a little closer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I tell you all this,\rdblquote  Dumbledore continued, \ldblquote not to turn you against Horace \emdash  or, as we must now call him, Professor Slug\-horn \emdash  but to put you on your guard. He will undoubtedly try to collect you, Harry. You would be the jewel of his collection; \lquote the Boy Who Lived\rquote  \'85 or, as they call you these days, \lquote the Chosen\lang3081  \lang1033 One.\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At these words, a chill that had nothing to do with the sur\-rounding mist stole over Harry. He was reminded of words he had heard a few weeks ago, words that had a horrible and particular meaning to him: \i Neither can live while the other survives\i0  \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore had stopped walking, level with the church they had passed earlier.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This will do, Harry. If you will grasp my arm.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Braced this time, Harry was ready for the Apparition, but still found it unpleasant. When the pressure disappeared and he found\lang3081  \lang1033 himself able to breathe again, he was standing in a country lane beside Dumbledore and looking ahead to the crooked silhouette of his second favorite building in the world: the Burrow. In spite of the feeling of dread that had just swept through him, his spirits could not help but lift at the sight of it. Ron was in there \'85 and so was Mrs. Weasley, who could cook better than anyone he knew. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you don\rquote t mind, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, as they passed through the gate, \ldblquote I\rquote d like a few words with you before we part. In private. Perhaps in here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore pointed toward a run-down stone outhouse where the Weasleys kept their broomsticks. A little puzzled, Harry fol\-lowed Dumbledore through the creaking door into a space a little smaller than the average cupboard. Dumbledore illuminated the tip of his wand, so that it glowed like a torch, and smiled down at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I hope you will forgive me for mentioning it, Harry, but I am pleased and a little proud at how well you seem to be coping after everything that happened at the Ministry. Permit me to say that I think Sirius would have been proud of you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry swallowed; his voice seemed to have deserted him. He did not think he could stand to discuss Sirius; it had been painful enough to hear Uncle Vernon say \ldblquote His godfather\rquote s dead?\rdblquote  and even worse to hear Sirius\rquote s name thrown out casually by Slughorn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was cruel,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore softly, \ldblquote that you and Sirius had such a short time together. A brutal ending to what should have been a long and happy relationship.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry nodded, his eyes fixed resolutely on the spider now climb\-ing Dumbledore\rquote s hat. He could tell that Dumbledore understood,\lang3081  \lang1033 that he might even suspect that until his letter arrived, Harry had spent nearly all his time at the Dursleys\rquote  lying on his bed, refusing meals, and staring at the misted window, full of the chill emptiness that he had come to associate with dementors.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s just hard,\rdblquote  Harry said finally, in a low voice, \ldblquote to realize he won\rquote t write to me again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His eyes burned suddenly and he blinked. He felt stupid for ad\-mitting it, but the fact that he had had someone outside Hogwarts who cared what happened to him, almost like a parent, had been one of the best things about discovering his godfather \'85 and now the post owls would never bring him that comfort again. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sirius represented much to you that you had never known before,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore gently. \ldblquote Naturally, the loss is devastat\-ing. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But while I was at the Dursleys\rquote  \'85\rdblquote  interrupted Harry, his voice growing stronger, \ldblquote I realized I can\rquote t shut myself away or \emdash  or crack up. Sirius wouldn\rquote t have wanted that, would he? And anyway, life\rquote s too short. \'85 Look at Madam Bones, look at Emmeline Vance. \'85 It could be me next, couldn\rquote t it? But if it is,\rdblquote  he said fiercely, now looking straight into Dumbledore\rquote s blue eyes gleam\-ing in the wandlight, \ldblquote I\rquote ll make sure I take as many Death Eaters with me as I can, and Voldemort too if I can manage it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Spoken both like your mother and father\rquote s son and Sirius\rquote s true godson!\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, with an approving pat on Harry\rquote s back. \ldblquote I take my hat off to you \emdash  or I would, if I were not afraid of showering you in spiders.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And now, Harry, on a closely related subject\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I gather that you have been taking the \i Daily Prophet\i0  over the last two weeks?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, and his heart beat a little faster.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then you will have seen that there have been not so much leaks as floods concerning your adventure in the Hall of Prophecy?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry again. \ldblquote And now everyone knows that I\rquote m the one \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, they do not,\rdblquote  interrupted Dumbledore. \ldblquote There are only two people in the whole world who know the full contents of the prophecy made about you and Lord Voldemort, and they are both standing in this smelly, spidery broom shed. It is true, however, that many have guessed, correctly, that Voldemort sent his Death Eaters to steal a prophecy, and that the prophecy concerned you.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, I think I am correct in saying that you have not told any\-body that you know what the prophecy said?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A wise decision, on the whole,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Although I think you ought to relax it in favor of your friends, Mr. Ronald Weasley and Miss Hermione Granger. Yes,\rdblquote  he continued, when Harry looked startled, \ldblquote I think they ought to know. You do them a disservice by not confiding something this important to them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t want \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  to worry or frighten them?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, surveying Harry over the top of his half-moon spectacles. \ldblquote Or perhaps, to confess that you yourself are worried and frightened? You need your friends, Harry. As you so rightly said, Sirius would not have wanted you to shut yourself away.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry said nothing, but Dumbledore did not seem to require an answer. He continued, \ldblquote On a different, though related, subject, it is my wish that you take private lessons with me this year.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Private \emdash  with you?\rdblquote  said Harry, surprised out of his preoccu\-pied silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes. I think it is time that I took a greater hand in your educa\-tion.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What will you be teaching me, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, a little of this, a little of that,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore airily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry waited hopefully, but Dumbledore did not elaborate, so he asked something else that had been bothering him slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If I\rquote m having lessons with you, I won\rquote t have to do Occlumency lessons with Snape, will I?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Professor \i0 Snape, Harry \emdash  and no, you will not.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  said Harry in relief, \ldblquote because they were a \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stopped, careful not to say what he really thought.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think the word \lquote fiasco\rquote  would be a good one here,\rdblquote  said Dum\-bledore, nodding.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry laughed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, that means I won\rquote t see much of Professor Snape from now on,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote because he won\rquote t let me carry on Potions unless I get \lquote Outstanding\rquote  in my O.W.L., which I know I haven\rquote t.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t count your owls before they are delivered,\rdblquote  said Dumble\-dore gravely. \ldblquote Which, now I think of it, ought to be some time later today. Now, two more things, Harry, before we part.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Firstly, I wish you to keep your Invisibility Cloak with you at all times from this moment onward. Even within Hogwarts itself. Just in case, you understand me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry nodded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And lastly, while you stay here, the Burrow has been given the\lang3081  \lang1033 highest security the Ministry of Magic can provide. These measures have caused a certain amount of inconvenience to Arthur and Molly \emdash  all their post, for instance, is being searched at the Min\-istry before being sent on. They do not mind in the slightest, for their only concern is your safety. However, it would be poor repay\-ment if you risked your neck while staying with them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I understand,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well, then,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, pushing open the broom shed door and stepping out into the yard. \ldblquote I see a light in the kitchen. Let us not deprive Molly any longer of the chance to de\-plore how thin you are.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
