Harry and Dumbledore approached the back door of the Burrow, which was surrounded by the familiar litter of old Wellington boots and rusty cauldrons; Harry could hear the soft clucking of sleepy chickens coming from a distant shed. Dum\-bledore knocked three times and Harry saw sudden movement be\-hind the kitchen window.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote  said a nervous voice he recognized as Mrs. Weasley\rquote s. \ldblquote Declare yourself!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is I, Dumbledore, bringing Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door opened at once. There stood Mrs. Weasley, short, plump, and wearing an old green dressing gown.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, dear! Gracious, Albus, you gave me a fright, you said not to expect you before morning!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We were lucky,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, ushering Harry over the threshold. \ldblquote Slughorn proved much more persuadable than I had expected. Harry\rquote s doing, of course. Ah, hello, Nymphadora!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around and saw that Mrs. Weasley was not alone, despite the lateness of the hour. A young witch with a pale, heart-shaped face and mousy brown hair was sitting at the table clutch\-ing a large mug between her hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hello, Professor,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Wotcher, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi, Tonks.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry thought she looked drawn, even ill, and there was some\-thing forced in her smile. Certainly her appearance was less color\-ful than usual without her customary shade of bubble-gum-pink hair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote d better be off,\rdblquote  she said quickly, standing up and pulling her cloak around her shoulders. \ldblquote Thanks for the tea and sympathy, Molly.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please don\rquote t leave on my account,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore courte\-ously, \ldblquote I cannot stay, I have urgent matters to discuss with Rufus Scrimgeour.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, I need to get going,\rdblquote  said Tonks, not meeting Dum\-bledore\rquote s eyes. \ldblquote  \rquote Night \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dear, why not come to dinner at the weekend, Remus and Mad-Eye are coming \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, really, Molly \'85 thanks anyway \'85 Good night, every\-one.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Tonks hurried past Dumbledore and Harry into the yard; a few paces beyond the doorstep, she turned on the spot and vanished into thin air. Harry noticed that Mrs. Weasley looked troubled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I shall see you at Hogwarts, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Take care of yourself. Molly, your servant.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He made Mrs. Weasley a bow and followed Tonks, vanishing at precisely the same spot. Mrs. Weasley closed the door on the empty\lang3081  \lang1033 yard and then steered Harry by the shoulders into the full glow of the lantern on the table to examine his appearance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re like Ron,\rdblquote  she sighed, looking him up and down. \ldblquote Both of you look as though you\rquote ve had Stretching Jinxes put on you. I swear Ron\rquote s grown four inches since I last bought him school robes. Are you hungry, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I am,\rdblquote  said Harry, suddenly realizing just how hungry he was.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sit down, dear, I\rquote ll knock something up.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Harry sat down, a furry ginger cat with a squashed face jumped onto his knees and settled there, purring.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So Hermione\rquote s here?\rdblquote  he asked happily as he tickled Crook\-shanks behind the ears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes, she arrived the day before yesterday,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weas\-ley, rapping a large iron pot with her wand. It bounced onto the stove with a loud clang and began to bubble at once. \ldblquote Everyone\rquote s in bed, of course, we didn\rquote t expect you for hours. Here you are \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She tapped the pot again; it rose into the air, flew toward Harry, and tipped over; Mrs. Weasley slid a bowl neatly beneath it just in time to catch the stream of thick, steaming onion soup.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bread, dear?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks, Mrs. Weasley.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She waved her wand over her shoulder; a loaf of bread and a knife soared gracefully onto the table; as the loaf sliced itself and the soup pot dropped back onto the stove, Mrs. Weasley sat down opposite him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you persuaded Horace Slughorn to take the job?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry nodded, his mouth so full of hot soup that he could not speak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He taught Arthur and me,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote He was at Hog\-warts for ages, started around the same time as Dumbledore, I think. Did you like him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His mouth now full of bread, Harry shrugged and gave a non\-committal jerk of the head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know what you mean,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, nodding wisely. \ldblquote Of course he can be charming when he wants to be, but Arthur\rquote s never liked him much. The Ministry\rquote s littered with Slughorn\rquote s old favorites, he was always good at giving leg ups, but he never had much time for Arthur \emdash  didn\rquote t seem to think he was enough of a highflier. Well, that just shows you, even Slughorn makes mistakes. I don\rquote t know whether Ron\rquote s told you in any of his letters \emdash  it\rquote s only just happened \emdash  but Arthur\rquote s been promoted!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It could not have been clearer that Mrs. Weasley had been burst\-ing to say this.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry swallowed a large amount of very hot soup and thought he could feel his throat blistering. \ldblquote That\rquote s great!\rdblquote  he gasped.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are sweet,\rdblquote  beamed Mrs. Weasley, possibly taking his wa\-tering eyes for emotion at the news. \ldblquote Yes, Rufus Scrimgeour has set up several new offices in response to the present situation, and Arthur\rquote s heading the Office for the Detection and Confiscation of Counterfeit Defensive Spells and Protective Objects. It\rquote s a big job, he\rquote s got ten people reporting to him now!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What exactly \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you see, in all the panic about You-Know-Who, odd things have been cropping up for sale everywhere, things that are supposed to guard against You-Know-Who and the Death Eaters. You can imagine the kind of thing \emdash  so-called protective potions that are really gravy with a bit of bubotuber pus added, or instruc\-tions for defensive jinxes that actually make your ears fall off. \'85 Well, in the main the perpetrators are just people like Mundungus Fletcher, who\rquote ve never done an honest day\rquote s work in their lives and are taking advantage of how frightened everybody is, but every now and then something really nasty turns up. The other day Arthur confiscated a box of cursed Sneakoscopes that were almost certainly planted by a Death Eater. So you see, it\rquote s a very important job, and I tell him it\rquote s just silly to miss dealing with spark plugs and toasters and all the rest of that Muggle rubbish.\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley ended her speech with a stern look, as if it had been Harry suggest\-ing that it was natural to miss spark plugs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is Mr. Weasley still at work?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, he is. As a matter of fact, he\rquote s a tiny bit late. \'85 He said he\rquote d be back around midnight. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She turned to look at a large clock that was perched awkwardly on top of a pile of sheets in the washing basket at the end of the table. Harry recognized it at once: It had nine hands, each in\-scribed with the name of a family member, and usually hung on the Weasleys\rquote  sitting room wall, though its current position sug\-gested that Mrs. Weasley had taken to carrying it around the house with her. Every single one of its nine hands was now pointing at \ldblquote mortal peril.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s been like that for a while now,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, in an un\-convincingly casual voice, \ldblquote ever since You-Know-Who came back into the open. I suppose everybody\rquote s in mortal danger now. \'85 I don\rquote t think it can be just our family \'85 but I don\rquote t know anyone else who\rquote s got a clock like this, so I can\rquote t check. Oh!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a sudden exclamation she pointed at the clock\rquote s face. Mr. Weasley\rquote s hand had switched to \ldblquote traveling.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s coming!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And sure enough, a moment later there was a knock on the back door. Mrs. Weasley jumped up and hurried to it; with one hand on the doorknob and her face pressed against the wood she called softly, \ldblquote Arthur, is that you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  came Mr. Weasley\rquote s weary voice. \ldblquote But I would say that even if I were a Death Eater, dear. Ask the question!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, honestly \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Molly!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, all right\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 What is your dearest ambition?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
