Harry spent a lot of the last week of the holidays ponder\-ing the meaning of Malfoy\rquote s behavior in Knockturn Alley. What disturbed him most was the satisfied look on Malfoy\rquote s face as he had left the shop. Nothing that made Malfoy look that happy could be good news. To his slight annoyance, however, nei\-ther Ron nor Hermione seemed quite as curious about Malfoy\rquote s activities as he was; or at least, they seemed to get bored of dis\-cussing it after a few days.\par
\ldblquote Yes, I\rquote ve already agreed it was fishy, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione a lit\-tle impatiently. She was sitting on the windowsill in Fred and George\rquote s room with her feet up on one of the cardboard boxes and had only grudgingly looked up from her new copy of \i Advanced Rune Translation.\i0  \ldblquote But haven\rquote t we agreed there could be a lot of explanations?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe he\rquote s broken his Hand of Glory,\rdblquote  said Ron vaguely, as he\lang3081  \lang1033 attempted to straighten his broomstick\rquote s bent tail twigs. \ldblquote Remem\-ber that shriveled-up arm Malfoy had?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what about when he said, \lquote Don\rquote t forget to keep \i that\i0  one safe\rquote ?\rdblquote  asked Harry for the umpteenth time. \ldblquote That sounded to me like Borgin\rquote s got another one of the broken objects, and Malfoy wants both.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You reckon?\rdblquote  said Ron, now trying to scrape some dirt off his broom handle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I do,\rdblquote  said Harry. When neither Ron nor Hermione an\-swered, he said, \ldblquote Malfoy\rquote s father\rquote s in Azkaban. Don\rquote t you think Malfoy\rquote d like revenge?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron looked up, blinking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Malfoy, revenge? What can he do about it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s my point, I don\rquote t know!\rdblquote  said Harry, frustrated. \ldblquote But he\rquote s up to something and I think we should take it seriously. His father\rquote s a Death Eater and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry broke off, his eyes fixed on the window behind Hermi\-one, his mouth open. A startling thought had just occurred to him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote  said Hermione in an anxious voice. \ldblquote What\rquote s wrong?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your scar\rquote s not hurting again, is it?\rdblquote  asked Ron nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s a Death Eater,\rdblquote  said Harry slowly. \ldblquote He\rquote s replaced his father as a Death Eater!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a silence; then Ron erupted in laughter. \ldblquote\i Malfoy\i0 ? He\rquote s sixteen, Harry! You think You-Know-Who would let \i Malfoy\i0  join?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It seems very unlikely, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione in a repressive sort of voice. \ldblquote What makes you think \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In Madam Malkin\rquote s. She didn\rquote t touch him, but he yelled and jerked his arm away from her when she went to roll up his sleeve. It was his left arm. He\rquote s been branded with the Dark Mark.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Hermione looked at each other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  said Ron, sounding thoroughly unconvinced.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think he just wanted to get out of there, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermi\-one.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He showed Borgin something we couldn\rquote t see,\rdblquote  Harry pressed on stubbornly. \ldblquote Something that seriously scared Borgin. It was the Mark, I know it \emdash  he was showing Borgin who he was dealing with, you saw how seriously Borgin took him!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Hermione exchanged another look.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not sure, Harry. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I still don\rquote t reckon You-Know-Who would let Malfoy join. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Annoyed, but absolutely convinced he was right, Harry snatched up a pile of filthy Quidditch robes and left the room; Mrs. Weasley had been urging them for days not to leave their washing and pack\-ing until the last moment. On the landing he bumped into Ginny, who was returning to her room carrying a pile of freshly laundered clothes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t go in the kitchen just now,\rdblquote  she warned him. \ldblquote There\rquote s a lot of Phlegm around.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll be careful not to slip in it.\rdblquote  Harry smiled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sure enough, when he entered the kitchen it was to find Fleur sitting at the kitchen table, in full flow about plans for her wedding to Bill, while Mrs. Weasley kept watch over a pile of self-peeling sprouts, looking bad-tempered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 Bill and I \rquote ave almost decided on only two bridesmaids, Ginny and Gabrielle will look very sweet togezzer. I am theenking of dressing zem in pale gold \emdash  pink would of course be \rquote orrible with Ginny\rquote s \rquote air \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, Harry!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley loudly, cutting across Fleur\rquote s monologue. \ldblquote Good, I wanted to explain about the security arrange\-ments for the journey to Hogwarts tomorrow. We\rquote ve got Ministry cars again, and there will be Aurors waiting at the station \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is Tonks going to be there?\rdblquote  asked Harry, handing over his Quidditch things.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I don\rquote t think so, she\rquote s been stationed somewhere else from what Arthur said.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She has let \rquote erself go, zat Tonks,\rdblquote  Fleur mused, examining her own stunning reflection in the back of a teaspoon. \ldblquote A big mistake if you ask \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, \i thank\i0  you,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley tartly, cutting across Fleur again. \ldblquote You\rquote d better get on, Harry, I want the trunks ready tonight, if possible, so we don\rquote t have the usual last-minute scramble.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And in fact, their departure the following morning was smoother than usual. The Ministry cars glided up to the front of the Burrow to find them waiting, trunks packed; Hermione\rquote s cat, Crookshanks, safely enclosed in his traveling basket; and Hedwig; Ron\rquote s owl, Pig\-widgeon; and Ginny\rquote s new purple Pygmy Puff, Arnold, in cages.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Au revoir, \rquote Arry,\rdblquote  said Fleur throatily, kissing him good-bye. Ron hurried forward, looking hopeful, but Ginny stuck out her foot and Ron fell, sprawling in the dust at Fleur\rquote s feet. Furious, red-faced, and dirt-spattered, he hurried into the car without saying good-bye.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was no cheerful Hagrid waiting for them at King\rquote s Cross Station. Instead, two grim-faced, bearded Aurors in dark Muggle suits moved forward the moment the cars stopped and, flanking the party, marched them into the station without speaking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Quick, quick, through the barrier,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, who\lang3081  \lang1033 seemed a little flustered by this austere efficiency. \ldblquote Harry had bet\-ter go first, with \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked inquiringly at one of the Aurors, who nodded briefly, seized Harry\rquote s upper arm, and attempted to steer him toward the barrier between platforms nine and ten.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can walk, thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry irritably, jerking his arm out of the Auror\rquote s grip. He pushed his trolley directly at the solid barrier, ignoring his silent companion, and found himself, a second later, standing on platform nine and three-quarters, where the scarlet Hogwarts Express stood belching steam over the crowd.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione and the Weasleys joined him within seconds. With\-out waiting to consult his grim-faced Auror, Harry motioned to Ron and Hermione to follow him up the platform, looking for an empty compartment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We can\rquote t, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking apologetic. \ldblquote Ron and I\rquote ve got to go to the prefects\rquote  carriage first and then patrol the cor\-ridors for a bit.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yeah, I forgot,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote d better get straight on the train, all of you, you\rquote ve only got a few minutes to go,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, consulting her watch. \ldblquote Well, have a lovely term, Ron. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Weasley, can I have a quick word?\rdblquote  said Harry, making up his mind on the spur of the moment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, who looked slightly surprised, but followed Harry out of earshot of the others nevertheless.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had thought it through carefully and come to the conclu\-sion that, if he was to tell anyone, Mr. Weasley was the right per\-son; firstly, because he worked at the Ministry and was therefore in the best position to make further investigations, and secondly,\lang3081  \lang1033 because he thought that there was not too much risk of Mr. Weasley exploding with anger.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He could see Mrs. Weasley and the grim-faced Auror casting the pair of them suspicious looks as they moved away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote When we were in Diagon Alley,\rdblquote  Harry began, but Mr. Weasley forestalled him with a grimace.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Am I about to discover where you, Ron, and Hermione disap\-peared to while you were supposed to be in the back room of Fred and George\rquote s shop?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How did you \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, please. You\rquote re talking to the man who raised Fred and George.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \'85 yeah, all right, we weren\rquote t in the back room.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well, then, let\rquote s hear the worst.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, we followed Draco Malfoy. We used my Invisibility Cloak.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you have any particular reason for doing so, or was it a mere whim?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because I thought Malfoy was up to something,\rdblquote  said Harry, dis\-regarding Mr. Weasley\rquote s look of mingled exasperation and amuse\-ment. \ldblquote He\rquote d given his mother the slip and I wanted to know why.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course you did,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, sounding resigned. \ldblquote Well? Did you find out why?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He went into Borgin and Burkes,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote and started bul\-lying the bloke in there, Borgin, to help him fix something. And he said he wanted Borgin to keep something else for him. He made it sound like it was the same kind of thing that needed fixing. Like they were a pair. And \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry took a deep breath.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s something else. We saw Malfoy jump about a mile when Madam Malkin tried to touch his left arm. I think he\rquote s been branded with the Dark Mark. I think he\rquote s replaced his father as a Death Eater.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley looked taken aback. After a moment he said, \ldblquote Harry, I doubt whether You-Know-Who would allow a sixteen-year-old \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Does anyone really know what You-Know-Who would or wouldn\rquote t do?\rdblquote  asked Harry angrily. \ldblquote Mr. Weasley, I\rquote m sorry, but isn\rquote t it worth investigating? If Malfoy wants something fixing, and he needs to threaten Borgin to get it done, it\rquote s probably something Dark or dangerous, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I doubt it, to be honest, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley slowly. \ldblquote You see, when Lucius Malfoy was arrested, we raided his house. We took away everything that might have been dangerous.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think you missed something,\rdblquote  said Harry stubbornly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, maybe,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, but Harry could tell that Mr. Weasley was humoring him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a whistle behind them; nearly everyone had boarded the train and the doors were closing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote d better hurry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, as Mrs. Weasley cried, \ldblquote Harry, quickly!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He hurried forward and Mr. and Mrs. Weasley helped him load his trunk onto the train.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, dear, you\rquote re coming to us for Christmas, it\rquote s all fixed with Dumbledore, so we\rquote ll see you quite soon,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley through the window, as Harry slammed the door shut behind him and the train began to move. \ldblquote You make sure you look after your\-self and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The train was gathering speed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  be good and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was jogging to keep up now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  stay safe!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry waved until the train had turned a corner and Mr. and Mrs. Weasley were lost to view, then turned to see where the others had got to. He supposed Ron and Hermione were cloistered in the prefects\rquote  carriage, but Ginny was a little way along the corridor, chatting to some friends. He made his way toward her, dragging his trunk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 People stared shamelessly as he approached. They even pressed their faces against the windows of their compartments to get a look at him. He had expected an upswing in the amount of gaping and gawping he would have to endure this term after all the \ldblquote Chosen One\rdblquote  rumors in the \i Daily Prophet,\i0  but he did not enjoy the sensa\-tion of standing in a very bright spotlight. He tapped Ginny on the shoulder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fancy trying to find a compartment?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t, Harry, I said I\rquote d meet Dean,\rdblquote  said Ginny brightly. \ldblquote See you later.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry. He felt a strange twinge of annoyance as she walked away, her long red hair dancing behind her; he had become so used to her presence over the summer that he had almost forgotten that Ginny did not hang around with him, Ron, and Hermione while at school. Then he blinked and looked around: He was surrounded by mesmerized girls.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi, Harry!\rdblquote  said a familiar voice from behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Neville!\rdblquote  said Harry in relief, turning to see a round-faced boy struggling toward him.\lang3081\par
