\lang1033\i Professor\lang3081  H. E. F. Slughorn\par
\lang1033\i0\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s Professor Slughorn?\rdblquote  asked Neville, looking perplexedly at his own invitation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote New teacher,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Well, I suppose we\rquote ll have to go, won\rquote t we?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what does he want me for?\rdblquote  asked Neville nervously, as though he was expecting detention.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No idea,\rdblquote  said Harry, which was not entirely true, though he had no proof yet that his hunch was correct. \ldblquote Listen,\rdblquote  he added, seized by a sudden brain wave, \ldblquote let\rquote s go under the Invisibility Cloak, then we might get a good look at Malfoy on the way, see what he\rquote s up to.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This idea, however, came to nothing: The corridors, which were packed with people on the lookout for the lunch trolley, were im\-possible to negotiate while wearing the cloak. Harry stowed it re\-gretfully back in his bag, reflecting that it would have been nice to wear it just to avoid all the staring, which seemed to have increased in intensity even since he had last walked down the train. Every now and then, students would hurtle out of their compartments to get a better look at him. The exception was Cho Chang, who darted into her compartment when she saw Harry coming. As Harry passed the window, he saw her deep in determined conver\-sation with her friend Marietta, who was wearing a very thick layer of makeup that did not entirely obscure the odd formation of pim\-ples still etched across her face. Smirking slightly, Harry pushed on.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When they reached compartment C, they saw at once that they were not Slughorn\rquote s only invitees, although judging by the enthusiasm of Slughorn\rquote s welcome, Harry was the most warmly anticipated.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, m\rquote boy!\rdblquote  said Slughorn, jumping up at the sight of him so that his great velvet-covered belly seemed to fill all the remain\-ing space in the compartment. His shiny bald head and great sil\-very mustache gleamed as brightly in the sunlight as the golden\lang3081  \lang1033 buttons on his waistcoat. \ldblquote Good to see you, good to see you! And you must be Mr. Longbottom!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville nodded, looking scared. At a gesture from Slughorn, they sat down opposite each other in the only two empty seats, which were nearest the door. Harry glanced around at their fellow guests. He recognized a Slytherin from their year, a tall black boy with high cheekbones and long, slanting eyes; there were also two seventh-year boys Harry did not know and, squashed in the corner beside Slughorn and looking as though she was not entirely sure how she had got there, Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, do you know everyone?\rdblquote  Slughorn asked Harry and Neville. \ldblquote Blaise Zabini is in your year, of course \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Zabini did not make any sign of recognition or greeting, nor did Harry or Neville: Gryffindor and Slytherin students loathed each other on principle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is Cormac McLaggen, perhaps you\rquote ve come across each other \emdash  ? No?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 McLaggen, a large, wiry-haired youth, raised a hand, and Harry and Neville nodded back at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and this is Marcus Belby, I don\rquote t know whether \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Belby, who was thin and nervous-looking, gave a strained smile.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and \i this\i0  charming young lady tells me she knows you!\rdblquote  Slughorn finished.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ginny grimaced at Harry and Neville from behind Slughorn\rquote s back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well now, this is most pleasant,\rdblquote  said Slughorn cozily. \ldblquote A chance to get to know you all a little better. Here, take a napkin. I\rquote ve packed my own lunch; the trolley, as I remember it, is heavy on\lang3081  \lang1033 licorice wands, and a poor old man\rquote s digestive system isn\rquote t quite up to such things. \'85 Pheasant, Belby?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Belby started and accepted what looked like half a cold pheasant.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was just telling young Marcus here that I had the pleasure of teaching his Uncle Damocles,\rdblquote  Slughorn told Harry and Neville, now passing around a basket of rolls. \ldblquote Outstanding wizard, out\-standing, and his Order of Merlin most well-deserved. Do you see much of your uncle, Marcus?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Unfortunately, Belby had just taken a large mouthful of pheas\-ant; in his haste to answer Slughorn he swallowed too fast, turned purple, and began to choke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Anapneo,\i0\rdblquote  said Slughorn calmly, pointing his wand at Belby, whose airway seemed to clear at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 not much of him, no,\rdblquote  gasped Belby, his eyes streaming.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, of course, I daresay he\rquote s busy,\rdblquote  said Slughorn, looking questioningly at Belby. \ldblquote I doubt he invented the Wolfsbane Potion without considerable hard work!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I suppose \'85\rdblquote  said Belby, who seemed afraid to take another bite of pheasant until he was sure that Slughorn had finished with him. \ldblquote Er \'85 he and my dad don\rquote t get on very well, you see, so I don\rquote t really know much about\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His voice tailed away as Slughorn gave him a cold smile and turned to McLaggen instead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, \i you,\i0  Cormac,\rdblquote  said Slughorn, \ldblquote I happen to know you see a lot of your Uncle Tiberius, because he has a rather splendid pic\-ture of the two of you hunting nogtails in, I think, Norfolk?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, yeah, that was fun, that was,\rdblquote  said McLaggen. \ldblquote We went with Bertie Higgs and Rufus Scrimgeour \emdash  this was before he be\-came Minister, obviously \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, you know Bertie and Rufus too?\rdblquote  beamed Slughorn, now offering around a small tray of pies; somehow, Belby was missed out. \ldblquote Now tell me \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was as Harry had suspected. Everyone here seemed to have been invited because they were connected to somebody well-known or influential \emdash  everyone except Ginny. Zabini, who was interrogated after McLaggen, turned out to have a famously beau\-tiful witch for a mother (from what Harry could make out, she had been married seven times, each of her husbands dying mysteri\-ously and leaving her mounds of gold). It was Neville\rquote s turn next: This was a very uncomfortable ten minutes, for Neville\rquote s parents, well-known Aurors, had been tortured into insanity by Bellatrix Lestrange and a couple of Death Eater cronies. At the end of Neville\rquote s interview, Harry had the impression that Slughorn was reserving judgment on Neville, yet to see whether he had any of his parents\rquote  flair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And now,\rdblquote  said Slughorn, shifting massively in his seat with the air of a compere introducing his star act. \ldblquote Harry Potter! \i Where\i0  to begin? I feel I barely scratched the surface when we met over the summer!\rdblquote  He contemplated Harry for a moment as though he was a particularly large and succulent piece of pheasant, then said, \ldblquote  \lquote The Chosen One,\rquote  they\rquote re calling you now!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry said nothing. Belby, McLaggen, and Zabini were all star\-ing at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course,\rdblquote  said Slughorn, watching Harry closely, \ldblquote there have been rumors for years. \'85 I remember when \emdash  well \emdash  after that \i terrible\i0  night \emdash  Lily \emdash  James \emdash  and you survived \emdash  and the word was that you must have powers beyond the ordinary \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Zabini gave a tiny little cough that was clearly supposed to\lang3081  \lang1033 indicate amused skepticism. An angry voice burst out from behind Slughorn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, Zabini, because \i you\rquote re\i0  so talented \'85 at posing. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh dear!\rdblquote  chuckled Slughorn comfortably, looking around at Ginny, who was glaring at Zabini around Slughorn\rquote s great belly. \ldblquote You want to be careful, Blaise! I saw this young lady perform the most marvelous Bat-Bogey Hex as I was passing her carriage! I wouldn\rquote t cross her!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Zabini merely looked contemptuous.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anyway,\rdblquote  said Slughorn, turning back to Harry. \ldblquote\i Such\i0  rumors this summer. Of course, one doesn\rquote t know what to believe, the \i Prophet\i0  has been known to print inaccuracies, make mistakes \emdash  but there seems little doubt, given the number of witnesses, that there was \i quite\i0  a disturbance at the Ministry and that you were there in the thick of it all!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, who could not see any way out of this without flatly lying, nodded but still said nothing. Slughorn beamed at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So modest, so modest, no wonder Dumbledore is so fond \emdash  you \i were\i0  there, then? But the rest of the stories \emdash  so sensational, of course, one doesn\rquote t know quite what to believe \emdash  this fabled prophecy, for instance \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We never heard a prophecy,\rdblquote  said Neville, turning geranium pink as he said it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Ginny staunchly. \ldblquote Neville and I were both there too, and all this \lquote Chosen One\rquote  rubbish is just the \i Prophet\i0  making things up as usual.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You were both there too, were you?\rdblquote  said Slughorn with great interest, looking from Ginny to Neville, but both of them sat clam\-like before his encouraging smile.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes \'85 well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 it is true that the \i Prophet\i0  often exaggerates, of course. \'85\rdblquote  Slughorn said, sounding a little disappointed. \ldblquote I re\-member dear Gwenog telling me (Gwenog Jones, I mean, of course, Captain of the Holyhead Harpies) \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He meandered off into a long-winded reminiscence, but Harry had the distinct impression that Slughorn had not finished with him, and that he had not been convinced by Neville and Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The afternoon wore on with more anecdotes about illustrious wizards Slughorn had taught, all of whom had been delighted to join what he called the \ldblquote Slug Club\rdblquote  at Hogwarts. Harry could not wait to leave, but couldn\rquote t see how to do so politely. Finally the train emerged from yet another long misty stretch into a red sun\-set, and Slughorn looked around, blinking in the twilight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good gracious, it\rquote s getting dark already! I didn\rquote t notice that they\rquote d lit the lamps! You\rquote d better go and change into your robes, all of you. McLaggen, you must drop by and borrow that book on nogtails. Harry, Blaise \emdash  any time you\rquote re passing. Same goes for you, miss,\rdblquote  he twinkled at Ginny. \ldblquote Well, off you go, off you go!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As he pushed past Harry into the darkening corridor, Zabini shot him a filthy look that Harry returned with interest. He, Ginny, and Neville followed Zabini back along the train.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m glad that\rquote s over,\rdblquote  muttered Neville. \ldblquote Strange man, isn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, he is a bit,\rdblquote  said Harry, his eyes on Zabini. \ldblquote How come you ended up in there, Ginny?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He saw me hex Zacharias Smith,\rdblquote  said Ginny. \ldblquote You remember that idiot from Hufflepuff who was in the D.A.? He kept on and on asking about what happened at the Ministry and in the end he annoyed me so much I hexed him \emdash  when Slughorn came in I\lang3081  \lang1033 thought I was going to get detention, but he just thought it was a really good hex and invited me to lunch! Mad, eh?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Better reason for inviting someone than because their mother\rquote s famous,\rdblquote  said Harry, scowling at the back of Zabini\rquote s head, \ldblquote or be\-cause their uncle \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But he broke off. An idea had just occurred to him, a reckless but potentially wonderful idea. \'85 In a minute\rquote s time, Zabini was going to reenter the Slytherin sixth-year compartment and Malfoy would be sitting there, thinking himself unheard by anybody ex\-cept fellow Slytherins. \'85 If Harry could only enter, unseen, be\-hind him, what might he not see or hear? True, there was little of the journey left \emdash  Hogsmeade Station had to be less than half an hour away, judging by the wildness of the scenery flashing by the windows \emdash  but nobody else seemed prepared to take Harry\rquote s sus\-picions seriously, so it was down to him to prove them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll see you two later,\rdblquote  said Harry under his breath, pulling out his Invisibility Cloak and flinging it over himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what\rquote re you \emdash  ?\rdblquote  asked Neville.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Later!\rdblquote  whispered Harry, darting after Zabini as quietly as pos\-sible, though the rattling of the train made such caution almost pointless.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The corridors were almost completely empty now. Nearly every\-one had returned to their carriages to change into their school robes and pack up their possessions. Though he was as close as he could get to Zabini without touching him, Harry was not quick enough to slip into the compartment when Zabini opened the door. Zabini was already sliding it shut when Harry hastily stuck out his foot to prevent it closing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s wrong with this thing?\rdblquote  said Zabini angrily as he smashed the sliding door repeatedly into Harry\rquote s foot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry seized the door and pushed it open, hard; Zabini, still clinging on to the handle, toppled over sideways into Gregory Goyle\rquote s lap, and in the ensuing ruckus, Harry darted into the com\-partment, leapt onto Zabini\rquote s temporarily empty seat, and hoisted himself up into the luggage rack. It was fortunate that Goyle and Zabini were snarling at each other, drawing all eyes onto them, for Harry was quite sure his feet and ankles had been revealed as the cloak had flapped around them; indeed, for one horrible moment he thought he saw Malfoy\rquote s eyes follow his trainer as it whipped up\-ward out of sight. But then Goyle slammed the door shut and flung Zabini off him; Zabini collapsed into his own seat looking ruffled, Vincent Crabbe returned to his comic, and Malfoy, sniggering, lay back down across two seats with his head in Pansy Parkinson\rquote s lap. Harry lay curled uncomfortably under the cloak to ensure that every inch of him remained hidden, and watched Pansy stroke the sleek blond hair off Malfoy\rquote s forehead, smirking as she did so, as though anyone would have loved to have been in her place. The lanterns swinging from the carriage ceiling cast a bright light over the scene: Harry could read every word of Crabbe\rquote s comic directly below him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, Zabini,\rdblquote  said Malfoy, \ldblquote what did Slughorn want?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just trying to make up to well-connected people,\rdblquote  said Zabini, who was still glowering at Goyle. \ldblquote Not that he managed to find many.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This information did not seem to please Malfoy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who else had he invited?\rdblquote  he demanded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote McLaggen from Gryffindor,\rdblquote  said Zabini.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yeah, his uncle\rquote s big in the Ministry,\rdblquote  said Malfoy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  someone else called Belby, from Ravenclaw \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not him, he\rquote s a prat!\rdblquote  said Pansy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and Longbottom, Potter, and that Weasley girl,\rdblquote  finished Zabini.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy sat up very suddenly, knocking Pansy\rquote s hand aside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He invited \i Longbottom\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I assume so, as Longbottom was there,\rdblquote  said Zabini indifferently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s Longbottom got to interest Slughorn?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Zabini shrugged.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Potter, precious Potter, obviously he wanted a look at \lquote\i the Cho\-sen One,\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 sneered Malfoy, \ldblquote but that Weasley girl! What\rquote s so special about \i her\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A lot of boys like her,\rdblquote  said Pansy, watching Malfoy out of the corner of her eyes for his reaction. \ldblquote Even you think she\rquote s good-looking, don\rquote t you, Blaise, and we all know how hard you are to please!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t touch a filthy little blood traitor like her whatever she looked like,\rdblquote  said Zabini coldly, and Pansy looked pleased. Malfoy sank back across her lap and allowed her to resume the stroking of his hair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I pity Slughorn\rquote s taste. Maybe he\rquote s going a bit senile. Shame, my father always said he was a good wizard in his day. My father used to be a bit of a favorite of his. Slughorn probably hasn\rquote t heard I\rquote m on the train, or \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t bank on an invitation,\rdblquote  said Zabini. \ldblquote He asked me about Nott\rquote s father when I first arrived. They used to be old\lang3081  \lang1033 friends, apparently, but when he heard he\rquote d been caught at the Ministry he didn\rquote t look happy, and Nott didn\rquote t get an invitation, did he? I don\rquote t think Slughorn\rquote s interested in Death Eaters.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy looked angry, but forced out a singularly humorless laugh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, who cares what he\rquote s interested in? What is he, when you come down to it? Just some stupid teacher.\rdblquote  Malfoy yawned osten\-tatiously. \ldblquote I mean, I might not even be at Hogwarts next year, what\rquote s it matter to me if some fat old has-been likes me or not?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you mean, you might not be at Hogwarts next year?\rdblquote  said Pansy indignantly, ceasing grooming Malfoy at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you never know,\rdblquote  said Malfoy with the ghost of a smirk. \ldblquote I might have \emdash  er \emdash  moved on to bigger and better things.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Crouched in the luggage rack under his cloak, Harry\rquote s heart be\-gan to race. What would Ron and Hermione say about this? Crabbe and Goyle were gawping at Malfoy; apparently they had had no inkling of any plans to move on to bigger and better things. Even Zabini had allowed a look of curiosity to mar his haughty fea\-tures. Pansy resumed the slow stroking of Malfoy\rquote s hair, looking dumbfounded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you mean \emdash  \i Him\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy shrugged.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mother wants me to complete my education, but personally, I don\rquote t see it as that important these days. I mean, think about it. \'85 When the Dark Lord takes over, is he going to care how many O.W.L.s or N.E.W.T.s anyone\rquote s got? Of course he isn\rquote t. \'85 It\rquote ll be all about the kind of service he received, the level of devotion he was shown.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you think \i you\rquote ll\i0  be able to do something for him?\rdblquote  asked\lang3081  \lang1033 Zabini scathingly. \ldblquote Sixteen years old and not even fully qualified yet?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve just said, haven\rquote t I? Maybe he doesn\rquote t care if I\rquote m qualified. Maybe the job he wants me to do isn\rquote t something that you need to be qualified for,\rdblquote  said Malfoy quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Crabbe and Goyle were both sitting with their mouths open like gargoyles. Pansy was gazing down at Malfoy as though she had never seen anything so awe-inspiring.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can see Hogwarts,\rdblquote  said Malfoy, clearly relishing the effect he had created as he pointed out of the blackened window. \ldblquote We\rquote d bet\-ter get our robes on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was so busy staring at Malfoy, he did not notice Goyle reaching up for his trunk; as he swung it down, it hit Harry hard on the side of the head. He let out an involuntary gasp of pain, and Malfoy looked up at the luggage rack, frowning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was not afraid of Malfoy, but he still did not much like the idea of being discovered hiding under his Invisibility Cloak by a group of unfriendly Slytherins. Eyes still watering and head still throbbing, he drew his wand, careful not to disarrange the cloak, and waited, breath held. To his relief, Malfoy seemed to decide that he had imagined the noise; he pulled on his robes like the others, locked his trunk, and as the train slowed to a jerky crawl, fastened a thick new traveling cloak round his neck.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could see the corridors filling up again and hoped that Hermione and Ron would take his things out onto the platform for him; he was stuck where he was until the compartment had quite emptied. At last, with a final lurch, the train came to a com\-plete halt. Goyle threw the door open and muscled his way out\lang3081  \lang1033 into a crowd of second years, punching them aside; Crabbe and Zabini followed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You go on,\rdblquote  Malfoy told Pansy, who was waiting for him with her hand held out as though hoping he would hold it. \ldblquote I just want to check something.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Pansy left. Now Harry and Malfoy were alone in the compart\-ment. People were filing past, descending onto the dark platform. Malfoy moved over to the compartment door and let down the blinds, so that people in the corridor beyond could not peer in. He then bent down over his trunk and opened it again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry peered down over the edge of the luggage rack, his heart pumping a little faster. What had Malfoy wanted to hide from Pansy? Was he about to see the mysterious broken object it was so important to mend?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Petrificus Totalus\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Without warning, Malfoy pointed his wand at Harry, who was instantly paralyzed. As though in slow motion, he toppled out of the luggage rack and fell, with an agonizing, floor-shaking crash, at Malfoy\rquote s feet, the Invisibility Cloak trapped beneath him, his whole body revealed with his legs still curled absurdly into the cramped kneeling position. He couldn\rquote t move a muscle; he could only gaze up at Malfoy, who smiled broadly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought so,\rdblquote  he said jubilantly. \ldblquote I heard Goyle\rquote s trunk hit you. And I thought I saw something white flash through the air after Zabini came back. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His eyes lingered for a moment upon Harry\rquote s trainers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You didn\rquote t hear anything I care about, Potter. But while I\rquote ve got you here \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he stamped, hard, on Harry\rquote s face. Harry felt his nose break; blood spurted everywhere.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s from my father. Now, let\rquote s see. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy dragged the cloak out from under Harry\rquote s immobilized body and threw it over him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t reckon they\rquote ll find you till the train\rquote s back in London,\rdblquote  he said quietly. \ldblquote See you around, Potter \'85 or not.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And taking care to tread on Harry\rquote s fingers, Malfoy left the compartment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
