Harry could not move a muscle. He lay there beneath the Invisibility Cloak feeling the blood from his nose flow, hot and wet, over his face, listening to the voices and footsteps in the corridor beyond. His immediate thought was that someone, surely, would check the compartments before the train departed again. But at once came the dispiriting realization that even if somebody looked into the compartment, he would be neither seen nor heard. His best hope was that somebody else would walk in and step on him.\par
Harry had never hated Malfoy more than as he lay there, like an absurd turtle on its back, blood dripping sickeningly into his open mouth. What a stupid situation to have landed himself in \'85 and now the last few footsteps were dying away; everyone was shuffling along the dark platform outside; he could hear the scraping of trunks and the loud babble of talk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Hermione would think that he had left the train\lang3081  \lang1033 without them. Once they arrived at Hogwarts and took their places in the Great Hall, looked up and down the Gryffindor table a few times, and finally realized that he was not there, he, no doubt, would be halfway back to London.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He tried to make a sound, even a grunt, but it was impossible. Then he remembered that some wizards, like Dumbledore, could perform spells without speaking, so he tried to summon his wand, which had fallen out of his hand, by saying the words \ldblquote\i Accio Wand\i0 !\rdblquote  over and over again in his head, but nothing happened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He thought he could hear the rustling of the trees that sur\-rounded the lake, and the far-off hoot of an owl, but no hint of a search being made or even (he despised himself slightly for hoping it) panicked voices wondering where Harry Potter had gone. A feeling of hopelessness spread through him as he imagined the con\-voy of thestral-drawn carriages trundling up to the school and the muffled yells of laughter issuing from whichever carriage Malfoy was riding in, where he could be recounting his attack on Harry to Crabbe, Goyle, Zabini, and Pansy Parkinson.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The train lurched, causing Harry to roll over onto his side. Now he was staring at the dusty underside of the seats instead of the ceil\-ing. The floor began to vibrate as the engine roared into life. The Express was leaving and nobody knew he was still on it. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then he felt his Invisibility Cloak fly off him and a voice over\-head said, \ldblquote Wotcher, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a flash of red light and Harry\rquote s body unfroze; he was able to push himself into a more dignified sitting position, hastily wipe the blood off his bruised face with the back of his hand, and raise his head to look up at Tonks, who was holding the Invisibility Cloak she had just pulled away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote d better get out of here, quickly,\rdblquote  she said, as the train win\-dows became obscured with steam and they began to move out of the station. \ldblquote Come on, we\rquote ll jump.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry hurried after her into the corridor. She pulled open the train door and leapt onto the platform, which seemed to be sliding underneath them as the train gathered momentum. He followed her, staggered a little on landing, then straightened up in time to see the gleaming scarlet steam engine pick up speed, round the cor\-ner, and disappear from view.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The cold night air was soothing on his throbbing nose. Tonks was looking at him; he felt angry and embarrassed that he had been discovered in such a ridiculous position. Silently she handed him back the Invisibility Cloak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who did it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Draco Malfoy,\rdblquote  said Harry bitterly. \ldblquote Thanks for \'85 well \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No problem,\rdblquote  said Tonks, without smiling. From what Harry could see in the darkness, she was as mousy-haired and miserable-looking as she had been when he had met her at the Burrow. \ldblquote I can fix your nose if you stand still.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not think much of this idea; he had been intending to visit Madam Pomfrey, the matron, in whom he had a little more confidence when it came to Healing Spells, but it seemed rude to say this, so he stayed stock-still and closed his eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Episkey,\i0\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 said Tonks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s nose felt very hot, and then very cold. He raised a hand and felt it gingerly. It seemed to be mended.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks a lot!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote d better put that cloak back on, and we can walk up to the school,\rdblquote  said Tonks, still unsmiling. As Harry swung the cloak back\lang3081  \lang1033 over himself, she waved her wand; an immense silvery four-legged creature erupted from it and streaked off into the darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Was that a Patronus?\rdblquote  asked Harry, who had seen Dumbledore send messages like this.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I\rquote m sending word to the castle that I\rquote ve got you or they\rquote ll worry. Come on, we\rquote d better not dawdle.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They set off toward the lane that led to the school.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How did you find me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I noticed you hadn\rquote t left the train and I knew you had that cloak. I thought you might be hiding for some reason. When I saw the blinds were drawn down on that compartment I thought I\rquote d check.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what are you doing here, anyway?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m stationed in Hogsmeade now, to give the school extra pro\-tection,\rdblquote  said\lang3081  \lang1033 Tonks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is it just you who\rquote s stationed up here, or \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, Proudfoot, Savage, and Dawlish are here too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dawlish, that Auror Dumbledore attacked last year?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They trudged up the dark, deserted lane, following the freshly made carriage tracks. Harry looked sideways at Tonks under his cloak. Last year she had been inquisitive (to the point of being a lit\-tle annoying at times), she had laughed easily, she had made jokes. Now she seemed older and much more serious and purposeful. Was this all the effect of what had happened at the Ministry? He re\-flected uncomfortably that Hermione would have suggested he say something consoling about Sirius to her, that it hadn\rquote t been her fault at all, but he couldn\rquote t bring himself to do it. He was far from blaming her for Sirius\rquote s death; it was no more her fault than anyone\lang3081  \lang1033 else\rquote s (and much less than his), but he did not like talking about Sirius if he could avoid it. And so they tramped on through the cold night in silence, Tonks\rquote s long cloak whispering on the ground behind them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Having always traveled there by carriage, Harry had never before appreciated just how far Hogwarts was from Hogsmeade Station. With great relief he finally saw the tall pillars on either side of the gates, each topped with a winged boar. He was cold, he was hun\-gry, and he was quite keen to leave this new, gloomy Tonks behind. But when he put out a hand to push open the gates, he found them chained shut.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Alohomora\i0 !\rdblquote  he said confidently, pointing his wand at the pad\-lock, but nothing happened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That won\rquote t work on these,\rdblquote  said Tonks. \ldblquote Dumbledore bewitched them himself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I could climb a wall,\rdblquote  he suggested.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, you couldn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Tonks flatly. \ldblquote Anti-intruder jinxes on all of them. Security\rquote s been tightened a hundredfold this summer.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well then,\rdblquote  said Harry, starting to feel annoyed at her lack of helpfulness, \ldblquote I suppose I\rquote ll just have to sleep out here and wait for morning.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Someone\rquote s coming down for you,\rdblquote  said Tonks. \ldblquote Look.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A lantern was bobbing at the distant foot of the castle. Harry was so pleased to see it he felt he could even endure Filch\rquote s wheezy criticisms of his tardiness and rants about how his timekeeping would improve with the regular application of thumbscrews. It was not until the glowing yellow light was ten feet away from them, and Harry had pulled off his Invisibility Cloak so that he could be\lang3081  \lang1033 seen, that he recognized, with a rush of pure loathing, the uplit hooked nose and long, black, greasy hair of Severus Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, well, well,\rdblquote  sneered Snape, taking out his wand and tap\-ping the padlock once, so that the chains snaked backward and the gates creaked open. \ldblquote Nice of you to turn up, Potter, although you have evidently decided that the wearing of school robes would de\-tract from your appearance.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I couldn\rquote t change, I didn\rquote t have my \emdash\rdblquote  Harry began, but Snape cut across him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There is no need to wait, Nymphadora, Potter is quite \emdash  ah \emdash  safe in my hands.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I meant Hagrid to get the message,\rdblquote  said Tonks, frowning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid was late for the start-of-term feast, just like Potter here, so I took it instead. And incidentally,\rdblquote  said Snape, standing back to allow Harry to pass him, \ldblquote I was interested to see your new Patronus.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He shut the gates in her face with a loud clang and tapped the chains with his wand again, so that they slithered, clinking, back into place.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think you were better off with the old one,\rdblquote  said Snape, the malice in his voice unmistakable. \ldblquote The new one looks weak.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Snape swung the lantern about, Harry saw, fleetingly, a look of shock and anger on Tonks\rquote s face. Then she was covered in dark\-ness once more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good night,\rdblquote  Harry called to her over his shoulder, as he began the walk up to the school with Snape. \ldblquote Thanks for \'85 everything.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote See you, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape did not speak for a minute or so. Harry felt as though his body was generating waves of hatred so powerful that it seemed\lang3081  \lang1033 incredible that Snape could not feel them burning him. He had loathed Snape from their first encounter, but Snape had placed him\-self forever and irrevocably beyond the possibility of Harry\rquote s for\-giveness by his attitude toward Sirius. Whatever Dumbledore said, Harry had had time to think over the summer, and had concluded that Snape\rquote s snide remarks to Sirius about remaining safely hidden while the rest of the Order of the Phoenix were off fighting Volde\-mort had probably been a powerful factor in Sirius rushing off to the Ministry the night that he had died. Harry clung to this notion, because it enabled him to blame Snape, which felt satisfying, and also because he knew that if anyone was not sorry that Sirius was dead, it was the man now striding next to him in the darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fifty points from Gryffindor for lateness, I think,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote And, let me see, another twenty for your Muggle attire. You know, I don\rquote t believe any House has ever been in negative figures this early in the term: We haven\rquote t even started pudding. You might have set a record, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The fury and hatred bubbling inside Harry seemed to blaze white-hot, but he would rather have been immobilized all the way back to London than tell Snape why he was late.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I suppose you wanted to make an entrance, did you?\rdblquote  Snape continued. \ldblquote And with no flying car available you decided that bursting into the Great Hall halfway through the feast ought to create a dramatic effect.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Still Harry remained silent, though he thought his chest might explode. He knew that Snape had come to fetch him for this, for the few minutes when he could needle and torment Harry without anyone else listening.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They reached the castle steps at last and as the great oaken front\lang3081  \lang1033 doors swung open into the vast flagged entrance hall, a burst of talk and laughter and of tinkling plates and glasses greeted them through the doors standing open into the Great Hall. Harry won\-dered whether he could slip his Invisibility Cloak back on, thereby gaining his seat at the long Gryffindor table (which, inconve\-niently, was the farthest from the entrance hall) without being noticed. As though he had read Harry\rquote s mind, however, Snape said, \ldblquote No cloak. You can walk in so that everyone sees you, which is what you wanted, I\rquote m sure.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned on the spot and marched straight through the open doors: anything to get away from Snape. The Great Hall, with its four long House tables and its staff table set at the top of the room, was decorated as usual with floating candles that made the plates below glitter and glow. It was all a shimmering blur to Harry, however, who walked so fast that he was passing the Huf\-flepuff table before people really started to stare, and by the time they were standing up to get a good look at him, he had spotted Ron and Hermione, sped along the benches toward them, and forced his way in between them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where\rquote ve you \emdash  blimey, what\rquote ve you done to your face?\rdblquote  said Ron, goggling at him along with everyone else in the vicinity.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why, what\rquote s wrong with it?\rdblquote  said Harry, grabbing a spoon and squinting at his distorted reflection.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re covered in blood!\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Come here \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She raised her wand, said \ldblquote\i Tergeo\i0 !\rdblquote  and siphoned off the dried blood.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry, feeling his now clean face. \ldblquote How\rquote s my nose looking?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Normal,\rdblquote  said Hermione anxiously. \ldblquote Why shouldn\rquote t it? Harry, what happened? We\rquote ve been terrified!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll tell you later,\rdblquote  said Harry curtly. He was very conscious that Ginny, Neville, Dean, and Seamus were listening in; even Nearly Headless Nick, the Gryffindor ghost, had come floating along the bench to eavesdrop.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But \emdash\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not now, Hermione,\rdblquote  said Harry, in a darkly significant voice. He hoped very much that they would all assume he had been in\-volved in something heroic, preferably involving a couple of Death Eaters and a dementor. Of course, Malfoy would spread the story as far and wide as he could, but there was always a chance it wouldn\rquote t reach too many Gryffindor ears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He reached across Ron for a couple of chicken legs and a hand\-ful of chips, but before he could take them they vanished, to be re\-placed with puddings.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You missed the Sorting, anyway,\rdblquote  said Hermione, as Ron dived for a large chocolate gateau.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hat say anything interesting?\rdblquote  asked Harry, taking a piece of treacle tart.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote More of the same, really \'85 advising us all to unite in the face of our enemies, you know.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore mentioned Voldemort at all?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not yet, but he always saves his proper speech for after the feast, doesn\rquote t he? It can\rquote t be long now.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Snape said Hagrid was late for the feast \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ve seen Snape? How come?\rdblquote  said Ron between frenzied mouthfuls of gateau.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bumped into him,\rdblquote  said Harry evasively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid was only a few minutes late,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Look, he\rquote s waving at you, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked up at the staff table and grinned at Hagrid, who was indeed waving at him. Hagrid had never quite managed to comport himself with the dignity of Professor McGonagall, Head of Gryffindor House, the top of whose head came up to somewhere between Hagrid\rquote s elbow and shoulder as they were sitting side by side, and who was looking disapprovingly at this enthusiastic greet\-ing. Harry was surprised to see the Divination teacher, Professor Trelawney, sitting on Hagrid\rquote s other side; she rarely left her tower room, and he had never seen her at the start-of-term feast before. She looked as odd as ever, glittering with beads and trailing shawls, her eyes magnified to enormous size by her spectacles. Having al\-ways considered her a bit of a fraud, Harry had been shocked to discover at the end of the previous term that it had been she who had made the prediction that caused Lord Voldemort to kill Harry\rquote s parents and attack Harry himself. The knowledge had made him even less eager to find himself in her company, but thankfully, this year he would be dropping Divination. Her great beaconlike eyes swiveled in his direction; he hastily looked away to\-ward the Slytherin table. Draco Malfoy was miming the shattering of a nose to raucous laughter and applause. Harry dropped his gaze to his treacle tart, his insides burning again. What he would not give to fight Malfoy one-on-one \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So what did Professor Slughorn want?\rdblquote  Hermione asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote To know what really happened at the Ministry,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Him and everyone else here,\rdblquote  sniffed Hermione. \ldblquote People were interrogating us about it on the train, weren\rquote t they, Ron?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote All wanting to know if you really are \lquote the Chosen One\rquote  \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There has been much talk on that very subject even amongst the ghosts,\rdblquote  interrupted Nearly Headless Nick, inclining his barely connected head toward Harry so that it wobbled dangerously on its ruff. \ldblquote I am considered something of a Potter authority; it is widely known that we are friendly. I have assured the spirit community that I will not pester you for information, however. \lquote Harry Potter knows that he can confide in me with complete confidence,\rquote  I told them. \lquote I would rather die than betray his trust.\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s not saying much, seeing as you\rquote re already dead,\rdblquote  Ron observed.\lang3081\par
