For the rest of the week\rquote s Potions lessons Harry continued to follow the Half-Blood Prince\rquote s instructions wherever they de\-viated from Libatius Borage\rquote s, with the result that by their fourth lesson Slughorn was raving about Harry\rquote s abilities, saying that he had rarely taught anyone so talented. Neither Ron nor Hermione was delighted by this. Although Harry had offered to share his book with both of them, Ron had more difficulty deciphering the handwriting than Harry did, and could not keep asking Harry to read aloud or it might look suspicious. Hermione, meanwhile, was resolutely plowing on with what she called the \ldblquote official\rdblquote  instruc\-tions, but becoming increasingly bad-tempered as they yielded poorer results than the Prince\rquote s.\par
Harry wondered vaguely who the Half-Blood Prince had been. Although the amount of homework they had been given prevented him from reading the whole of his copy of\lang3081  \lang1033\i Advanced\lang3081  \lang1033 Potion-Making,\i0  he had skimmed through it sufficiently to see that there was barely\lang3081  \lang1033 a page on which the Prince had not made additional notes, not all of them concerned with potion-making. Here and there were direc\-tions for what looked like spells that the Prince had made up himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Or herself,\rdblquote  said Hermione irritably, overhearing Harry point\-ing some of these out to Ron in the common room on Saturday evening. \ldblquote It might have been a girl. I think the handwriting looks more like a girl\rquote s than a boy\rquote s.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Half-Blood \i Prince,\i0  he was called,\rdblquote  Harry said. \ldblquote How many girls have been Princes?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione seemed to have no answer to this. She merely scowled and twitched her essay on \i The Principles of Rematerialization\i0  away from Ron, who was trying to read it upside down.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked at his watch and hurriedly put the old copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making\i0  back into his bag.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s five to eight, I\rquote d better go, I\rquote ll be late for Dumbledore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ooooh!\rdblquote  gasped Hermione, looking up at once. \ldblquote Good luck! We\rquote ll wait up, we want to hear what he teaches you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hope it goes okay,\rdblquote  said Ron, and the pair of them watched Harry leave through the portrait hole.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry proceeded through deserted corridors, though he had to step hastily behind a statue when Professor Trelawney appeared around a corner, muttering to herself as she shuffled a pack of dirty-looking playing cards, reading them as she walked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Two of spades: conflict,\rdblquote  she murmured, as she passed the place where Harry crouched, hidden. \ldblquote Seven of spades: an ill omen. Ten of spades: violence. Knave of spades: a dark young man, possibly troubled, one who dislikes the questioner \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She stopped dead, right on the other side of Harry\rquote s statue.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, that can\rquote t be right,\rdblquote  she said, annoyed, and Harry heard her reshuffling vigorously as she set off again, leaving nothing but a whiff of cooking sherry behind her. Harry waited until he was quite sure she had gone, then hurried off again until he reached the spot in the seventh-floor corridor where a single gargoyle stood against the wall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Acid Pops,\rdblquote  said Harry, and the gargoyle leapt aside; the wall behind it slid apart, and a moving spiral stone staircase was re\-vealed, onto which Harry stepped, so that he was carried in smooth circles up to the door with the brass knocker that led to Dumble\-dore\rquote s office.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry knocked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come in,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good evening, sir,\rdblquote  said Harry, walking into the headmaster\rquote s office.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, good evening, Harry. Sit down,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, smil\-ing. \ldblquote I hope you\rquote ve had an enjoyable first week back at school?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, thanks, sir,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You must have been busy, a detention under your belt already!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er,\rdblquote  began Harry awkwardly, but Dumbledore did not look too stern.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have arranged with Professor Snape that you will do your de\-tention next Saturday instead.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry, who had more pressing matters on his mind than Snape\rquote s detention, and now looked around surreptitiously for some indication of what Dumbledore was planning to do with him this evening. The circular office looked just as it always did; the delicate silver instruments stood on spindle-legged tables, puff\-ing smoke and whirring; portraits of previous headmasters and\lang3081  \lang1033 headmistresses dozed in their frames, and Dumbledore\rquote s magnifi\-cent phoenix, Fawkes, stood on his perch behind the door, watch\-ing Harry with bright interest. It did not even look as though Dumbledore had cleared a space for dueling practice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, in a businesslike voice. \ldblquote You have been wondering, I am sure, what I have planned for you dur\-ing these \emdash  for want of a better word \emdash  lessons?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I have decided that it is time, now that you know what prompted Lord Voldemort to try and kill you fifteen years ago, for you to be given certain information.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a pause.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You said, at the end of last term, you were going to tell me everything,\rdblquote  said Harry. It was hard to keep a note of accusation from his voice. \ldblquote Sir,\rdblquote  he added.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And so I did,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore placidly. \ldblquote I told you everything I know. From this point forth, we shall be leaving the firm founda\-tion of fact and journeying together through the murky marshes of memory into thickets of wildest guesswork. From here on in, Harry, I may be as woefully wrong as Humphrey Belcher, who be\-lieved the time was ripe for a cheese cauldron.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But you think you\rquote re right?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Naturally I do, but as I have already proven to you, I make mis\-takes like the next man. In fact, being \emdash  forgive me \emdash  rather clev\-erer than most men, my mistakes tend to be correspondingly huger.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir,\rdblquote  said Harry tentatively, \ldblquote does what you\rquote re going to tell me have anything to do with the prophecy? Will it help me \'85 survive?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It has a very great deal to do with the prophecy,\rdblquote  said Dumble\-dore, as casually as if Harry had asked him about the next day\rquote s weather, \ldblquote and I certainly hope that it will help you to survive.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore got to his feet and walked around the desk, past Harry, who turned eagerly in his seat to watch Dumbledore bend\-ing over the cabinet beside the door. When Dumbledore straight\-ened up, he was holding a familiar shallow stone basin etched with odd markings around its rim. He placed the Pensieve on the desk in front of Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You look worried.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had indeed been eyeing the Pensieve with some appre\-hension. His previous experiences with the odd device that stored and revealed thoughts and memories, though highly instructive, had also been uncomfortable. The last time he had disturbed its contents, he had seen much more than he would have wished. But Dumbledore was smiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This time, you enter the Pensieve with me \'85 and, even more unusually, with permission.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where are we going, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote For a trip down Bob Ogden\rquote s memory lane,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, pulling from his pocket a crystal bottle containing a swirling silvery-white substance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who was Bob Ogden?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He was employed by the Department of Magical Law Enforce\-ment,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote He died some time ago, but not before I had tracked him down and persuaded him to confide these recol\-lections to me. We are about to accompany him on a visit he made in the course of his duties. If you will stand, Harry \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Dumbledore was having difficulty pulling out the stopper of the crystal bottle: His injured hand seemed stiff and painful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shall \emdash  shall I, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No matter, Harry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore pointed his wand at the bottle and the cork flew out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir \emdash  how did you injure your hand?\rdblquote  Harry asked again, look\-ing at the blackened fingers with a mixture of revulsion and pity.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now is not the moment for that story, Harry. Not yet. We have an appointment with Bob Ogden.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore tipped the silvery contents of the bottle into the Pensieve, where they swirled and shimmered, neither liquid nor gas.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote After you,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, gesturing toward the bowl.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry bent forward, took a deep breath, and plunged his face into the silvery substance. He felt his feet leave the office floor; he was falling, falling through whirling darkness and then, quite sud\-denly, he was blinking in dazzling sunlight. Before his eyes had adjusted, Dumbledore landed beside him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were standing in a country lane bordered by high, tangled hedgerows, beneath a summer sky as bright and blue as a forget-me-not. Some ten feet in front of them stood a short, plump man wearing enormously thick glasses that reduced his eyes to molelike specks. He was reading a wooden signpost that was sticking out of the brambles on the left-hand side of the road. Harry knew this must be Ogden; he was the only person in sight, and he was also wearing the strange assortment of clothes so often chosen by inex\-perienced wizards trying to look like Muggles: in this case, a frock coat and spats over a striped one-piece bathing costume. Before\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry had time to do more than register his bizarre appearance, however, Ogden had set off at a brisk walk down the lane.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore and Harry followed. As they passed the wooden sign, Harry looked up at its two arms. The one pointing back the way they had come read: GREAT HANGLETON, 5 MILES. The arm pointing after Ogden said LITTLE HANGLETON, 1 MILE.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They walked a short way with nothing to see but the hedgerows, the wide blue sky overhead and the swishing, frock-coated figure ahead. Then the lane curved to the left and fell away, sloping steeply down a hillside, so that they had a sudden, unexpected view of a whole valley laid out in front of them. Harry could see a vil\-lage, undoubtedly Little Hangleton, nestled between two steep hills, its church and graveyard clearly visible. Across the valley, set on the opposite hillside, was a handsome manor house surrounded by a wide expanse of velvety green lawn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ogden had broken into a reluctant trot due to the steep down\-ward slope. Dumbledore lengthened his stride, and Harry hurried to keep up. He thought Little Hangleton must be their final desti\-nation and wondered, as he had done on the night they had found Slughorn, why they had to approach it from such a distance. He soon discovered that he was mistaken in thinking that they were going to the village, however. The lane curved to the right and when they rounded the corner, it was to see the very edge of Og\-den\rquote s frock coat vanishing through a gap in the hedge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore and Harry followed him onto a narrow dirt track bordered by higher and wilder hedgerows than those they had left behind. The path was crooked, rocky, and potholed, sloping down\-hill like the last one, and it seemed to be heading for a patch of dark trees a little below them. Sure enough, the track soon opened up\lang3081  \lang1033 at the copse, and Dumbledore and Harry came to a halt behind Ogden, who had stopped and drawn his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Despite the cloudless sky, the old trees ahead cast deep, dark, cool shadows, and it was a few seconds before Harry\rquote s eyes discerned the building half-hidden amongst the tangle of trunks. It seemed to him a very strange location to choose for a house, or else an odd decision to leave the trees growing nearby, blocking all light and the view of the valley below. He wondered whether it was inhabited; its walls were mossy and so many tiles had fallen off the roof that the rafters were visible in places. Nettles grew all around it, their tips reaching the windows, which were tiny and thick with grime. Just as he had concluded that nobody could possibly live there, however, one of the windows was thrown open with a clatter, and a thin trickle of steam or smoke issued from it, as though somebody was cooking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ogden moved forward quietly and, it seemed to Harry, rather cautiously. As the dark shadows of the trees slid over him, he stopped again, staring at the front door, to which somebody had nailed a dead snake.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then there was a rustle and a crack, and a man in rags dropped from the nearest tree, landing on his feet right in front of Ogden, who leapt backward so fast he stood on the tails of his frock coat and stumbled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i You\rquote re not welcome.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The man standing before them had thick hair so matted with dirt it could have been any color. Several of his teeth were missing. His eyes were small and dark and stared in opposite directions. He might have looked comical, but he did not; the effect was frighten\-ing, and Harry could not blame Ogden for backing away several more paces before he spoke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  good morning. I\rquote m from the Ministry of Magic \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i You\rquote re not welcome.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  I\rquote m sorry \emdash  I don\rquote t understand you,\rdblquote  said Ogden nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry thought Ogden was being extremely dim; the stranger was making himself very clear in Harry\rquote s opinion, particularly as he was brandishing a wand in one hand and a short and rather bloody knife in the other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You understand him, I\rquote m sure, Harry?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, of course,\rdblquote  said Harry, slightly nonplussed. \ldblquote Why can\rquote t Ogden \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But as his eyes found the dead snake on the door again, he sud\-denly understood.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s speaking Parseltongue?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very good,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, nodding and smiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The man in rags was now advancing on Ogden, knife in one hand, wand in the other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, look \emdash\rdblquote  Ogden began, but too late: There was a bang, and Ogden was on the ground, clutching his nose, while a nasty yellowish goo squirted from between his fingers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Morfin!\rdblquote  said a loud voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 An elderly man had come hurrying out of the cottage, banging the door behind him so that the dead snake swung pathetically. This man was shorter than the first, and oddly proportioned; his shoulders were very broad and his arms overlong, which, with his bright brown eyes, short scrubby hair, and wrinkled face, gave him the look of a powerful, aged monkey. He came to a halt beside the man with the knife, who was now cackling with laughter at the sight of Ogden on the ground.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ministry, is it?\rdblquote  said the older man, looking down at Ogden.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Correct!\rdblquote  said Ogden angrily, dabbing his face. \ldblquote And you, I take it, are Mr. Gaunt?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote S\rquote right,\rdblquote  said Gaunt. \ldblquote Got you in the face, did he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, he did!\rdblquote  snapped Ogden.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Should\rquote ve made your presence known, shouldn\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Gaunt aggressively. \ldblquote This is private property. Can\rquote t just walk in here and not expect my son to defend himself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Defend himself against what, man?\rdblquote  said Ogden, clambering back to his feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Busybodies. Intruders. Muggles and filth.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ogden pointed his wand at his own nose, which was still issuing large amounts of what looked like yellow pus, and the flow stopped at once. Mr. Gaunt spoke out of the corner of his mouth to Morfin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Get in the house. Don\rquote t argue.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This time, ready for it, Harry recognized Parseltongue; even while he could understand what was being said, he distinguished the weird hissing noise that was all Ogden could hear. Morfin seemed to be on the point of disagreeing, but when his father cast him a threatening look he changed his mind, lumbering away to the cottage with an odd rolling gait and slamming the front door behind him, so that the snake swung sadly again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s your son I\rquote m here to see, Mr. Gaunt,\rdblquote  said Ogden, as he mopped the last of the pus from the front of his coat. \ldblquote That was Morfin, wasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ar, that was Morfin,\rdblquote  said the old man indifferently. \ldblquote Are you pure-blood?\rdblquote  he asked, suddenly aggressive.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s neither here nor there,\rdblquote  said Ogden coldly, and Harry felt his respect for Ogden rise. Apparently Gaunt felt rather\lang3081  \lang1033 differently. He squinted into Ogden\rquote s face and muttered, in what was clearly supposed to be an offensive tone, \ldblquote Now I come to think about it,\lang3081  \lang1033 I\rquote ve seen noses like yours down in the village.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t doubt it, if your son\rquote s been let loose on them,\rdblquote  said Og\-den. \ldblquote Perhaps we could continue this discussion inside?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Inside?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Mr. Gaunt. I\rquote ve already told you. I\rquote m here about Morfin. We sent an owl \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve no use for owls,\rdblquote  said Gaunt. \ldblquote I don\rquote t open letters.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then you can hardly complain that you get no warning of vis\-itors,\rdblquote  said Ogden tartly. \ldblquote I am here following a serious breach of Wizarding law, which occurred here in the early hours of this morning \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, all right, all right!\rdblquote  bellowed Gaunt. \ldblquote Come in the bleeding house, then, and much good it\rquote ll do you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The house seemed to contain three tiny rooms. Two doors led off the main room, which served as kitchen and living room com\-bined. Morfin was sitting in a filthy armchair beside the smoking fire, twisting a live adder between his thick fingers and crooning softly at it in Parseltongue:\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033\i Hissy, hissy, little snakey,\i0\par
\i Slither on the floor,\i0\par
\i You be good to Morfin\i0\par
\i Or he\rquote ll nail you to the door.\lang3081\par
\i0\par
\lang1033 There was a scuffling noise in the corner beside the open win\-dow, and Harry realized that there was somebody else in the room, a girl whose ragged gray dress was the exact color of the dirty stone\lang3081  \lang1033 wall behind her. She was standing beside a steaming pot on a grimy black stove, and was fiddling around with the shelf of squalid-looking pots and pans above it. Her hair was lank and dull and she had a plain, pale, rather heavy face. Her eyes, like her brother\rquote s, stared in opposite directions. She looked a little cleaner than the two men, but Harry thought he had never seen a more defeated-looking person.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote M\rquote daughter, Merope,\rdblquote  said Gaunt grudgingly, as Ogden looked inquiringly toward her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good morning,\rdblquote  said Ogden.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She did not answer, but with a frightened glance at her father turned her back on the room and continued shifting the pots on the shelf behind her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Mr. Gaunt,\rdblquote  said Ogden, \ldblquote to get straight to the point, we have reason to believe that your son, Morfin, performed magic in front of a Muggle late last night.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a deafening clang. Merope had dropped one of the pots.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Pick it up\i0 !\rdblquote  Gaunt bellowed at her. \ldblquote That\rquote s it, grub on the floor like some filthy Muggle, what\rquote s your wand for, you useless sack of muck?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Gaunt, please!\rdblquote  said Ogden in a shocked voice, as Merope, who had already picked up the pot, flushed blotchily scarlet, lost her grip on the pot again, drew her wand shakily from her pocket, pointed it at the pot, and muttered a hasty, inaudible spell that caused the pot to shoot across the floor away from her, hit the op\-posite wall, and crack in two.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Morfin let out a mad cackle of laughter. Gaunt screamed, \ldblquote Mend it, you pointless lump, mend it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Merope stumbled across the room, but before she had time to raise her wand, Ogden had lifted his own and said firmly, \ldblquote\i Reparo.\i0\rdblquote  The pot mended itself instantly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Gaunt looked for a moment as though he was going to shout at Ogden, but seemed to think better of it: Instead, he jeered at his daughter, \ldblquote Lucky the nice man from the Ministry\rquote s here, isn\rquote t it? Perhaps he\rquote ll take you off my hands, perhaps he doesn\rquote t mind dirty Squibs. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Without looking at anybody or thanking Ogden, Merope picked up the pot and returned it, hands trembling, to its shelf. She then stood quite still, her back against the wall between the filthy window and the stove, as though she wished for nothing more than to sink into the stone and vanish.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Gaunt,\rdblquote  Ogden began again, \ldblquote as I\rquote ve said: the reason for my visit \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I heard you the first time!\rdblquote  snapped Gaunt. \ldblquote And so what? Morfin gave a Muggle a bit of what was coming to him \emdash  what about it, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Morfin has broken Wizarding law,\rdblquote  said Ogden sternly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote Morfin has broken Wizarding law.\rquote  \rdblquote  Gaunt imitated Ogden\rquote s voice, making it pompous and singsong. Morfin cackled again. \ldblquote He taught a filthy Muggle a lesson, that\rquote s illegal now, is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Ogden. \ldblquote I\rquote m afraid it is.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pulled from an inside pocket a small scroll of parchment and unrolled it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s that, then, his sentence?\rdblquote  said Gaunt, his voice rising angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is a summons to the Ministry for a hearing \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Summons! \i Summons\i0 ? Who do you think you are, summoning my son anywhere?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m Head of the Magical Law Enforcement Squad,\rdblquote  said Ogden.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you think we\rquote re scum, do you?\rdblquote  screamed Gaunt, advanc\-ing on Ogden now, with a dirty yellow-nailed finger pointing at his chest. \ldblquote Scum who\rquote ll come running when the Ministry tells \rquote em to? Do you know who you\rquote re talking to, you filthy little Mudblood, do you?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was under the impression that I was speaking to Mr. Gaunt,\rdblquote  said Ogden, looking wary, but standing his ground.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right!\rdblquote  roared Gaunt. For a moment, Harry thought Gaunt was making an obscene hand gesture, but then realized that he was showing Ogden the ugly, black-stoned ring he was wearing on his middle finger, waving it before Ogden\rquote s eyes. \ldblquote See this? See this? Know what it is? Know where it came from? Centuries it\rquote s been in our family, that\rquote s how far back we go, and pure-blood all the way! Know how much I\rquote ve been offered for this, with the Peverell coat of arms engraved on the stone?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve really no idea,\rdblquote  said Ogden, blinking as the ring sailed within an inch of his nose, \ldblquote and it\rquote s quite beside the point, Mr. Gaunt. Your son has committed \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a howl of rage, Gaunt ran toward his daughter. For a split second, Harry thought he was going to throttle her as his hand flew to her throat; next moment, he was dragging her toward Ogden by a gold chain around her neck.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote See this?\rdblquote  he bellowed at Ogden, shaking a heavy gold locket at him, while Merope spluttered and gasped for breath.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I see it, I see it!\rdblquote  said Ogden hastily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Slytherin\rquote s\i0 !\rdblquote  yelled Gaunt. \ldblquote Salazar Slytherin\rquote s! We\rquote re his last liv\-ing descendants, what do you say to that, eh?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Gaunt, your daughter!\rdblquote  said Ogden in alarm, but Gaunt had already released Merope; she staggered away from him, back to her corner, massaging her neck and gulping for air.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So!\rdblquote  said Gaunt triumphantly, as though he had just proved a complicated point beyond all possible dispute. \ldblquote Don\rquote t you go talk\-ing to us as if we\rquote re dirt on your shoes! Generations of purebloods, wizards all \emdash  more than \i you\i0  can say, I don\rquote t doubt!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he spat on the floor at Ogden\rquote s feet. Morfin cackled again. Merope, huddled beside the window, her head bowed and her face hidden by her lank hair, said nothing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Gaunt,\rdblquote  said Ogden doggedly, \ldblquote I am afraid that neither your ancestors nor mine have anything to do with the matter in hand. I am here because of Morfin, Morfin and the Muggle he ac\-costed late last night. Our information\rdblquote  \emdash  he glanced down at his scroll of parchment \emdash  \ldblquote is that Morfin performed a jinx or hex on the said Muggle, causing him to erupt in highly painful hives.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Morfin giggled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Be quiet, boy,\i0\rdblquote  snarled Gaunt in Parseltongue, and Morfin fell silent again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And so what if he did, then?\rdblquote  Gaunt said defiantly to Ogden. \ldblquote I expect you\rquote ve wiped the Muggle\rquote s filthy face clean for him, and his memory to boot \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s hardly the point, is it, Mr. Gaunt?\rdblquote  said Ogden. \ldblquote This was an unprovoked attack on a defenseless \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ar, I had you marked out as a Muggle-lover the moment I saw you,\rdblquote  sneered Gaunt, and he spat on the floor again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This discussion is getting us nowhere,\rdblquote  said Ogden firmly. \ldblquote It is\lang3081  \lang1033 clear from your son\rquote s attitude that he feels no remorse for his ac\-tions.\rdblquote  He glanced down at his scroll of parchment again. \ldblquote Morfin will attend a hearing on the fourteenth of September to answer the charges of using magic in front of a Muggle and causing harm and distress to that same Mugg \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ogden broke off. The jingling, clopping sounds of horses and loud, laughing voices were drifting in through the open window. Apparently the winding lane to the village passed very close to the copse where the house stood. Gaunt froze, listening, his eyes wide. Morfin hissed and turned his face toward the sounds, his expres\-sion hungry. Merope raised her head. Her face, Harry saw, was starkly white.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My God, what an eyesore!\rdblquote  rang out a girl\rquote s voice, as clearly au\-dible through the open window as if she had stood in the room be\-side them. \ldblquote Couldn\rquote t your father have that hovel cleared away, Tom?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not ours,\rdblquote  said a young man\rquote s voice. \ldblquote Everything on the other side of the valley belongs to us, but that cottage belongs to an old tramp called Gaunt, and his children. The son\rquote s quite mad, you should hear some of the stories they tell in the village \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
