\lang1033 Hermione pressed her lips together, looking angry and disap\-proving, but was distracted by a third owl landing in front of her carrying that day\rquote s copy of the \i Daily Prophet.\i0  She unfolded it hastily and scanned the front page.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anyone we know dead?\rdblquote  asked Ron in a determinedly casual voice; he posed the same question every time Hermione opened her paper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, but there have been more dementor attacks,\rdblquote  said Hermi\-one. \ldblquote And an arrest.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excellent, who?\rdblquote  said Harry, thinking of Bellatrix Lestrange.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stan Shunpike,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry, startled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i Stanley Shunpike, conductor on the popular Wizarding con\-veyance the Knight Bus, has been arrested on suspicion of Death Eater activity. Mr. Shunpike, 21, was taken into custody late last night after a raid on his Clapham home\lang3081  \lang1033\i0\'85\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stan Shunpike, a Death Eater?\rdblquote  said Harry, remembering the spotty youth he had first met three years before. \ldblquote No way!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He might have been put under the Imperius Curse,\rdblquote  said Ron reasonably. \ldblquote You never can tell.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t look like it,\rdblquote  said Hermione, who was still reading. \ldblquote It says here he was arrested after he was overheard talking about the Death Eaters\rquote  secret plans in a pub.\rdblquote  She looked up with a troubled expression on her face. \ldblquote If he was under the Imperius Curse, he\rquote d hardly stand around gossiping about their plans, would he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It sounds like he was trying to make out he knew more than he did,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t he the one who claimed he was going to be\-come Minister of Magic when he was trying to chat up those veela?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, that\rquote s him,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I dunno what they\rquote re playing at, taking Stan seriously.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They probably want to look as though they\rquote re doing some\-thing,\rdblquote  said Hermione, frowning. \ldblquote People are terrified \emdash  you know\lang3081  \lang1033 the Patil twins\rquote  parents want them to go home? And Eloise Midgen has already been withdrawn. Her father picked her up last night.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What!\rdblquote  said Ron, goggling at Hermione. \ldblquote But Hogwarts is safer than their homes, bound to be! We\rquote ve got Aurors, and all those extra protective spells, and we\rquote ve got Dumbledore!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think we\rquote ve got him all the time,\rdblquote  said Hermione very quietly, glancing toward the staff table over the top of the \i Prophet.\i0  \ldblquote Haven\rquote t you noticed? His seat\rquote s been empty as often as Hagrid\rquote s this past week.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Ron looked up at the staff table. The headmaster\rquote s chair was indeed empty. Now Harry came to think of it, he had not seen Dumbledore since their private lesson a week ago.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think he\rquote s left the school to do something with the Order,\rdblquote  said Hermione in a low voice. \ldblquote I mean \'85 it\rquote s all looking serious, isn\rquote t it?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Ron did not answer, but Harry knew that they were all thinking the same thing. There had been a horrible incident the day before, when Hannah Abbott had been taken out of Herbol\-ogy to be told her mother had been found dead. They had not seen Hannah since.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When they left the Gryffindor table five minutes later to head down to the Quidditch pitch, they passed Lavender Brown and Parvati Patil. Remembering what Hermione had said about the Patil twins\rquote  parents wanting them to leave Hogwarts, Harry was unsurprised to see that the two best friends were whispering to\-gether, looking distressed. What did surprise him was that when Ron drew level with them, Parvati suddenly nudged Lavender, who looked around and gave Ron a wide smile. Ron blinked at her, then returned the smile uncertainly. His walk instantly became some\-thing more like a strut. Harry resisted the temptation to laugh, re\-membering that Ron had refrained from doing so after Malfoy had broken Harry\rquote s nose; Hermione, however, looked cold and distant all the way down to the stadium through the cool, misty drizzle, and departed to find a place in the stands without wishing Ron good luck.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Harry had expected, the trials took most of the morning. Half of Gryffindor House seemed to have turned up, from first years who were nervously clutching a selection of the dreadful old school brooms, to seventh years who towered over the rest, looking coolly intimidating. The latter included a large, wiry-haired boy Harry recognized immediately from the Hogwarts Express.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We met on the train, in old Sluggy\rquote s compartment,\rdblquote  he said confidently, stepping out of the crowd to shake Harry\rquote s hand. \ldblquote Cormac McLaggen, Keeper.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You didn\rquote t try out last year, did you?\rdblquote  asked Harry, taking note of the breadth of McLaggen and thinking that he would probably block all three goal hoops without even moving.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was in the hospital wing when they held the trials,\rdblquote  said McLaggen, with something of a swagger. \ldblquote Ate a pound of doxy eggs for a bet.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Well \'85 if you wait over there \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pointed over to the edge of the pitch, close to where Hermi\-one was sitting. He thought he saw a flicker of annoyance pass over McLaggen\rquote s face and wondered whether McLaggen expected pref\-erential treatment because they were both \ldblquote old Sluggy\rquote s\rdblquote  favorites.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry decided to start with a basic test, asking all applicants for the team to divide into groups of\lang3081  \lang1033 ten and fly once around the pitch. This was a good decision: The first ten was made up of first years\lang3081  \lang1033 and it could not have been plainer that they had hardly ever flown before. Only one boy managed to remain airborne for more than a few seconds, and he was so surprised he promptly crashed into one of the goal posts.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The second group was comprised of\lang3081  \lang1033 ten of the silliest girls Harry had ever encountered, who, when he blew his whistle, merely fell about giggling and clutching one another. Romilda Vane was amongst them. When he told them to leave the pitch, they did so quite cheerfully and went to sit in the stands to heckle everyone else.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The third group had a pileup halfway around the pitch. Most of the fourth group had come without broomsticks. The fifth group were Hufflepuffs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If there\rquote s anyone else here who\rquote s not from Gryffindor,\rdblquote  roared Harry, who was starting to get seriously annoyed, \ldblquote leave now, please!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a pause, then a couple of little Ravenclaws went sprinting off the pitch, snorting with laughter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After two hours, many complaints, and several tantrums, one in\-volving a crashed Comet Two Sixty and several broken teeth, Harry had found himself three Chasers: Katie Bell, returned to the team after an excellent trial; a new find called Demelza Robins, who was particularly good at dodging Bludgers; and Ginny Weasley, who had outflown all the competition and scored seventeen goals to boot. Pleased though he was with his choices, Harry had also shouted himself hoarse at the many complainers and was now en\-during a similar battle with the rejected Beaters.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s my final decision and if you don\rquote t get out of the way for the Keepers I\rquote ll hex you,\rdblquote  he bellowed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neither of his chosen Beaters had the old brilliance of Fred and George, but he was still reasonably pleased with them: Jimmy Peakes, a short but broad-chested third-year boy who had managed to raise a lump the size of an egg on the back of Harry\rquote s head with a ferociously hit Bludger, and Ritchie Coote, who looked weedy but aimed well. They now joined Katie, Demelza, and Ginny in the stands to watch the selection of their last team member.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had deliberately left the trial of the Keepers until last, hoping for an emptier stadium and less pressure on all concerned. Unfortunately, however, all the rejected players and a number of people who had come down to watch after a lengthy breakfast had joined the crowd by now, so that it was larger than ever. As each Keeper flew up to the goal hoops, the crowd roared and jeered in equal measure. Harry glanced over at Ron, who had always had a problem with nerves; Harry had hoped that winning their final match last term might have cured it, but apparently not: Ron was a delicate shade of green.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 None of the first five applicants saved more than two goals apiece. To Harry\rquote s great disappointment, Cormac McLaggen saved four penalties out of five. On the last one, however, he shot off in completely the wrong direction; the crowd laughed and booed and McLaggen returned to the ground grinding his teeth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron looked ready to pass out as he mounted his Cleansweep Eleven. \ldblquote Good luck!\rdblquote  cried a voice from the stands. Harry looked around, expecting to see Hermione, but it was Lavender Brown. He would have quite liked to have hidden his face in his hands, as she did a moment later, but thought that as the Captain he ought to show slightly more grit, and so turned to watch Ron do his trial.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Yet he need not have worried: Ron saved one, two, three, four,\lang3081  \lang1033 five penalties in a row. Delighted, and resisting joining in the cheers of the crowd with difficulty, Harry turned to McLaggen to tell him that, most unfortunately, Ron had beaten him, only to find McLaggen\rquote s red face inches from his own. He stepped back hastily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote His sister didn\rquote t really try,\rdblquote  said McLaggen menacingly. There was a vein pulsing in his temple like the one Harry had often ad\-mired in Uncle Vernon\rquote s. \ldblquote She gave him an easy save.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Rubbish,\rdblquote  said Harry coldly. \ldblquote That was the one he nearly missed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 McLaggen took a step nearer Harry, who stood his ground this time.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Give me another go.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote You\rquote ve had your go. You saved four. Ron saved five. Ron\rquote s Keeper, he won it fair and square. Get out of my way.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He thought for a moment that McLaggen might punch him, but he contented himself with an ugly grimace and stormed away, growling what sounded like threats to thin air.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned around to find his new team beaming at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well done,\rdblquote  he croaked. \ldblquote You flew really well \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You did brilliantly, Ron!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This time it really was Hermione running toward them from the stands; Harry saw Lavender walking off the pitch, arm in arm with Parvati, a rather grumpy expression on her face. Ron looked extremely pleased with himself and even taller than usual as he grinned at the team and at Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After fixing the time of their first full practice for the following Thursday, Harry, Ron, and Hermione bade good-bye to the rest of\lang3081  \lang1033 the team and headed off toward Hagrid\rquote s. A watery sun was trying to break through the clouds now and it had stopped drizzling at last. Harry felt extremely hungry; he hoped there would be some\-thing to eat at Hagrid\rquote s.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought I was going to miss that fourth penalty,\rdblquote  Ron was say\-ing happily. \ldblquote Tricky shot from Demelza, did you see, had a bit of spin on it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, yes, you were magnificent,\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking amused.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was better than that McLaggen anyway,\rdblquote  said Ron in a highly satisfied voice. \ldblquote Did you see him lumbering off in the wrong direc\-tion on his fifth? Looked like he\rquote d been Confunded. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 To Harry\rquote s surprise, Hermione turned a very deep shade of pink at these words. Ron noticed nothing; he was too busy describing each of his other penalties in loving detail.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The great gray hippogriff, Buckbeak, was tethered in front of Hagrid\rquote s cabin. He clicked his razor-sharp beak at their approach and turned his huge head toward them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh dear,\rdblquote  said Hermione nervously. \ldblquote He\rquote s still a bit scary, isn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come off it, you\rquote ve ridden him, haven\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stepped forward and bowed low to the hippogriff without breaking eye contact or blinking. After a few seconds, Buckbeak sank into a bow too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How are you?\rdblquote  Harry asked him in a low voice, moving for\-ward to stroke the feathery head. \ldblquote Missing him? But you\rquote re okay here with Hagrid, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oi!\rdblquote  said a loud voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid had come striding around the corner of his cabin wearing a large flowery apron and carrying a sack of potatoes. His\lang3081  \lang1033 enormous boarhound, Fang, was at his heels; Fang gave a booming bark and bounded forward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Git away from him! He\rquote ll have yer fingers \emdash  oh. It\rquote s yeh lot.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fang was jumping up at Hermione and Ron, attempting to lick their ears. Hagrid stood and looked at them all for a split second, then turned and strode into his cabin, slamming the door behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh dear!\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking stricken.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry about it,\rdblquote  said Harry grimly. He walked over to the door and knocked loudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid! Open up, we want to talk to you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was no sound from within.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you don\rquote t open the door, we\rquote ll blast it open!\rdblquote  Harry said, pulling out his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  said Hermione, sounding shocked. \ldblquote You can\rquote t pos\-sibly \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I can!\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Stand back \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But before he could say anything else, the door flew open again as Harry had known it would, and there stood Hagrid, glowering down at him and looking, despite the flowery apron, positively alarming.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m a teacher!\rdblquote  he roared at Harry. \ldblquote A teacher, Potter! How dare yeh threaten ter break down my door!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, \i sir,\i0\rdblquote  said Harry, emphasizing the last word as he stowed his wand inside his robes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid looked stunned. \ldblquote Since when have yeh called me \lquote sir\rquote ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Since when have you called me \lquote Potter\rquote ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, very clever,\rdblquote  growled Hagrid. \ldblquote Very amusin\rquote . That\rquote s me outsmarted, innit? All righ\rquote , come in then, yeh ungrateful little \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mumbling darkly, he stood back to let them pass. Hermione scurried in after Harry, looking rather frightened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote  said Hagrid grumpily, as Harry, Ron, and Hermione sat down around his enormous wooden table, Fang laying his head im\-mediately upon Harry\rquote s knee and drooling all over his robes. \ldblquote What\rquote s this? Feelin\rquote  sorry for me? Reckon I\rquote m lonely or summat?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry at once. \ldblquote We wanted to see you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve missed you!\rdblquote  said Hermione tremulously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Missed me, have yeh?\rdblquote  snorted Hagrid. \ldblquote Yeah. Righ\rquote .\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stomped around, brewing up tea in his enormous copper kettle, muttering all the while. Finally he slammed down three bucket-sized mugs of mahogany-brown tea in front of them and a plate of his rock cakes. Harry was hungry enough even for Hagrid\rquote s cooking, and took one at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Hermione timidly, when he joined them at the table and started peeling his potatoes with a brutality that sug\-gested that each tuber had done him a great personal wrong, \ldblquote we re\-ally wanted to carry on with Care of Magical Creatures, you know.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid gave another great snort. Harry rather thought some bo\-geys landed on the potatoes, and was inwardly thankful that they were not staying for dinner.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We did!\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote But none of us could fit it into our schedules!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah. Righ\rquote ,\rdblquote  said Hagrid again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a funny squelching sound and they all looked around: Hermione let out a tiny shriek, and Ron leapt out of his seat and hurried around the table away from the large barrel standing in the corner that they had only just noticed. It was full of what looked like foot-long maggots, slimy, white, and writhing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are they, Hagrid?\rdblquote  asked Harry, trying to sound inter\-ested rather than revolted, but putting down his rock cake all the same.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Jus\rquote  giant grubs,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And they grow into \'85 ?\rdblquote  said Ron, looking apprehensive.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They won\rquote  grow inter nuthin\rquote ,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote I got \rquote em ter feed ter Aragog.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And without warning, he burst into tears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid!\rdblquote  cried Hermione, leaping up, hurrying around the table the long way to avoid the barrel of maggots, and putting an arm around his shaking shoulders. \ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s \'85 him \'85\rdblquote  gulped Hagrid, his beetle-black eyes stream\-ing as he mopped his face with his apron. \ldblquote It\rquote s \'85 Aragog. \'85 I think he\rquote s dyin\rquote . \'85 He got ill over the summer an\rquote  he\rquote s not gettin\rquote  better. \'85 I don\rquote  know what I\rquote ll do if he \'85 if he \'85 We\rquote ve bin tergether so long. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione patted Hagrid\rquote s shoulder, looking at a complete loss for anything to say. Harry knew how she felt. He had known Ha\-grid to present a vicious baby dragon with a teddy bear, seen him croon over giant scorpions with suckers and stingers, attempt to reason with his brutal giant of a half-brother, but this was perhaps the most incomprehensible of all his monster fancies: the gigantic talking spider, Aragog, who dwelled deep in the Forbidden Forest and which he and Ron had only narrowly escaped four years previously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is there \emdash  is there anything we can do?\rdblquote  Hermione asked, ig\-noring Ron\rquote s frantic grimaces and head-shakings.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote  think there is, Hermione,\rdblquote  choked Hagrid, attempting\lang3081  \lang1033 to stem the flood of his tears. \ldblquote See, the rest o\rquote  the tribe \'85 Aragog\rquote s family \'85 they\rquote re gettin\rquote  a bit funny now he\rquote s ill\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 bit restive \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I think we saw a bit of that side of them,\rdblquote  said Ron in an undertone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 I don\rquote  reckon it\rquote d be safe fer anyone but me ter go near the colony at the mo\rquote ,\rdblquote  Hagrid finished, blowing his nose hard on his apron and looking up. \ldblquote But thanks fer offerin\rquote , Hermione. \'85 It means a lot. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After that, the atmosphere lightened considerably, for although neither Harry nor Ron had shown any inclination to go and feed giant grubs to a murderous, gargantuan spider, Hagrid seemed to take it for granted that they would have liked to have done and be\-came his usual self once more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ar, I always knew yeh\rquote d find it hard ter squeeze me inter yer timetables,\rdblquote  he said gruffly, pouring them more tea. \ldblquote Even if yeh applied fer Time-Turners \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We couldn\rquote t have done,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote We smashed the en\-tire stock of Ministry Time-Turners when we were there last sum\-mer. It was in the \i Daily Prophet.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ar, well then,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote There\rquote s no way yeh could\rquote ve done it. \'85 I\rquote m sorry I\rquote ve bin \emdash  yeh know \emdash  I\rquote ve jus\rquote  bin worried abou\rquote  Aragog \'85 an\rquote  I did wonder whether, if Professor Grubbly-Plank had bin teachin\rquote  yeh \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At which all three of them stated categorically and untruthfully that Professor Grubbly-Plank, who had substituted for Hagrid a few times, was a dreadful teacher, with the result that by the time Hagrid waved them off the premises at dusk, he looked quite cheerful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m starving,\rdblquote  said Harry, once the door had closed behind them and they were hurrying through the dark and deserted grounds; he had abandoned the rock cake after an ominous crack\-ing noise from one of his back teeth. \ldblquote And I\rquote ve got that detention with Snape tonight, I haven\rquote t got much time for dinner. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As they came into the castle they spotted Cormac McLaggen en\-tering the Great Hall. It took him two attempts to get through the doors; he ricocheted off the frame on the first attempt. Ron merely guffawed gloatingly and strode off into the Hall after him, but Harry caught Hermione\rquote s arm and held her back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Hermione defensively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you ask me,\rdblquote  said Harry quietly, \ldblquote McLaggen looks like he \i was\i0  Confunded this morning. And he was standing right in front of where you were sitting.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione blushed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, all right then, I did it,\rdblquote  she whispered. \ldblquote But you should have heard the way he was talking about Ron and Ginny! Any\-way, he\rquote s got a nasty temper, you saw how he reacted when he didn\rquote t get in \emdash  you wouldn\rquote t have wanted someone like that on the team.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote No, I suppose that\rquote s true. But wasn\rquote t that dis\-honest, Hermione? I mean, you\rquote re a prefect, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, be quiet,\rdblquote  she snapped, as he smirked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you two doing?\rdblquote  demanded Ron, reappearing in the doorway to the Great Hall and looking suspicious.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  said Harry and Hermione together, and they hurried after Ron. The smell of roast beef made Harry\rquote s stomach ache with hunger, but they had barely taken three steps toward the Gryffindor table when Professor Slughorn appeared in front of them, blocking their path.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, Harry, just the man I was hoping to see!\rdblquote  he boomed ge\-nially, twiddling the ends of his walrus mustache and puffing out his enormous belly. \ldblquote I was hoping to catch you before dinner! What do you say to a spot of supper tonight in my rooms instead? We\rquote re having a little party, just a few rising stars, I\rquote ve got McLaggen com\-ing and Zabini, the charming Melinda Bobbin \emdash  I don\rquote t know whether you know her? Her family owns a large chain of apothe\-caries \emdash  and, of course, I hope very much that Miss Granger will favor me by coming too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn made Hermione a little bow as he finished speaking. It was as though Ron was not present; Slughorn did not so much as look at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t come, Professor,\rdblquote  said Harry at once. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got a deten\-tion with Professor Snape.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh dear!\rdblquote  said Slughorn, his face falling comically. \ldblquote Dear, dear, I was counting on you, Harry! Well, now, I\rquote ll just have to have a word with Severus and explain the situation. I\rquote m sure I\rquote ll be able to per\-suade him to postpone your detention. Yes, I\rquote ll see you both later!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He bustled away out of the Hall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s got no chance of persuading Snape,\rdblquote  said Harry, the mo\-ment Slughorn was out of earshot. \ldblquote This detention\rquote s already been postponed once; Snape did it for Dumbledore, but he won\rquote t do it for anyone else.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I wish you could come, I don\rquote t want to go on my own!\rdblquote  said Hermione anxiously; Harry knew that she was thinking about McLaggen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I doubt you\rquote ll be alone, Ginny\rquote ll probably be invited,\rdblquote  snapped Ron, who did not seem to have taken kindly to being ignored by Slughorn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After dinner they made their way back to Gryffindor Tower. The common room was very crowded, as most people had finished din\-ner by now, but they managed to find a free table and sat down; Ron, who had been in a bad mood ever since the encounter with Slughorn, folded his arms and frowned at the ceiling. Hermione reached out for a copy of the \i Evening Prophet,\i0  which somebody had left abandoned on a chair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anything new?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not really \'85\rdblquote  Hermione had opened the newspaper and was scanning the inside pages. \ldblquote Oh, look, your dad\rquote s in here, Ron \emdash  he\rquote s all right!\rdblquote  she added quickly, for Ron had looked around in alarm. \ldblquote It just says he\rquote s been to visit the Malfoys\rquote  house. \lquote\i This sec\-ond search of the Death Eater\rquote s residence does not seem to have yielded any results. Arthur Weasley of the Office for the Detection and Confis\-cation of Counterfeit Defensive Spells and Protective Objects said that his team had been acting upon a confidential tip-off.\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, mine!\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I told him at King\rquote s Cross about Mal\-foy and that thing he was trying to get Borgin to fix! Well, if it\rquote s not at their house, he must have brought whatever it is to Hogwarts with him \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But how can he have done, Harry?\rdblquote  said Hermione, putting down the newspaper with a surprised look. \ldblquote We were all searched when we arrived, weren\rquote t we?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Were you?\rdblquote  said Harry, taken aback. \ldblquote I wasn\rquote t!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh no, of course you weren\rquote t, I forgot you were late. \'85 Well, Filch ran over all of us with Secrecy Sensors when we got into the\lang3081  \lang1033 entrance hall. Any Dark object would have been found, I know for a fact Crabbe had a shrunken head confiscated. So you see, Malfoy can\rquote t have brought in anything dangerous!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Momentarily stymied, Harry watched Ginny Weasley playing with Arnold the Pygmy Puff for a while before seeing a way around this objection.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Someone\rquote s sent it to him by owl, then,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote His mother or someone.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All the owls are being checked too,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Filch told us so when he was jabbing those Secrecy Sensors everywhere he could reach.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Really stumped this time, Harry found nothing else to say. There did not seem to be any way Malfoy could have brought a dangerous or Dark object into the school. He looked hopefully at Ron, who was sitting with his arms folded, staring over at Lavender Brown.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can you think of any way Malfoy \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, drop it, Harry,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Listen, it\rquote s not my fault Slughorn invited Hermione and me to his stupid party, neither of us wanted to go, you know!\rdblquote  said Harry, firing up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, as I\rquote m not invited to any parties,\rdblquote  said Ron, getting to his feet again, \ldblquote I think I\rquote ll go to bed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stomped off toward the door to the boys\rquote  dormitories, leav\-ing Harry and Hermione staring after him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote  said the new Chaser, Demelza Robins, appearing sud\-denly at his shoulder. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got a message for you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote From Professor Slughorn?\rdblquote  asked Harry, sitting up hopefully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No \'85 from Professor Snape,\rdblquote  said Demelza. Harry\rquote s heart\lang3081  \lang1033 sank. \ldblquote He says you\rquote re to come to his office at half past eight tonight to do your detention \emdash  er \emdash  no matter how many party invita\-tions you\rquote ve received. And he wanted you to know you\rquote ll be sorting out rotten flobberworms from good ones, to use in Potions and \emdash  and he says there\rquote s no need to bring protective gloves.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry grimly. \ldblquote Thanks a lot, Demelza.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
