Where was Dumbledore, and what was he doing? Harry caught sight of the headmaster only twice over the next few weeks. He rarely appeared at meals anymore, and Harry was sure Hermione was right in thinking that he was leaving the school for days at a time. Had Dumbledore forgotten the lessons he was supposed to be giving Harry? Dumbledore had said that the lessons were leading to something to do with the prophecy; Harry had felt bolstered, comforted, and now he felt slightly abandoned.\par
Halfway through October came their first trip of the term to Hogsmeade. Harry had wondered whether these trips would still be allowed, given the increasingly tight security measures around the school, but was pleased to know that they were going ahead; it was always good to get out of the castle grounds for a few hours.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry woke early on the morning of the trip, which was proving stormy, and whiled away the time until breakfast by reading his copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making.\i0  He did not usually lie in bed\lang3081  \lang1033 reading his textbooks; that sort of behavior, as Ron rightly said, was indecent in anybody except Hermione, who was simply weird that way. Harry felt, however, that the Half-Blood Prince\rquote s copy of \i Ad\-vanced Potion-Making\i0  hardly qualified as a textbook. The more Harry pored over the book, the more he realized how much was in there, not only the handy hints and shortcuts on potions that were earning him such a glowing reputation with Slughorn, but also the imaginative little jinxes and hexes scribbled in the margins, which Harry was sure, judging by the crossings-out and revisions, that the Prince had invented himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had already attempted a few of the Prince\rquote s self-invented spells. There had been a hex that caused toenails to grow alarm\-ingly fast (he had tried this on Crabbe in the corridor, with very en\-tertaining results); a jinx that glued the tongue to the roof of the mouth (which he had twice used, to general applause, on an un\-suspecting Argus Filch); and, perhaps most useful of all, \i Muffliato,\i0  a spell that filled the ears of anyone nearby with an unidentifiable buzzing, so that lengthy conversations could be held in class with\-out being overheard. The only person who did not find these charms amusing was Hermione, who maintained a rigidly disap\-proving expression throughout and refused to talk at all if Harry had used the \i Muffliato\i0  spell on anyone in the vicinity.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sitting up in bed, Harry turned the book sideways so as to ex\-amine more closely the scribbled instructions for a spell that seemed to have caused the Prince some trouble. There were many crossings-out and alterations, but finally, crammed into a corner of the page, the scribble:\par
\par
\pard\qc\i Levicorpus\lang3081  (nvbl)\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\i0\par
While the wind and sleet pounded relentlessly on the windows, and Neville snored loudly, Harry stared at the letters in brackets. \i Nvbl\lang3081  \lang1033\i0\'85 that had to mean \ldblquote nonverbal.\rdblquote  Harry rather doubted he would be able to bring off this particular spell; he was still having difficulty with nonverbal spells, something Snape had been quick to comment on in every D.A.D.A. class. On the other hand, the Prince had proved a much more effective teacher than Snape so far.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Pointing his wand at nothing in particular, he gave it an upward flick and said \i Levicorpus\i0 ! inside his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aaaaaaaargh!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a flash of light and the room was full of voices: Every\-one had woken up as Ron had let out a yell. Harry sent \i Advanced Potion-Making\i0  flying in panic; Ron was dangling upside down in midair as though an invisible hook had hoisted him up by the ankle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry!\rdblquote  yelled Harry, as Dean and Seamus roared with laughter, and Neville picked himself up from the floor, having fallen out of bed. \ldblquote Hang on \emdash  I\rquote ll let you down \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He groped for the potion book and riffled through it in a panic, trying to find the right page; at last he located it and deciphered one cramped word underneath the spell: Praying that this was the counter-jinx, Harry thought \i Liberacorpus\i0 ! with all his might.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was another flash of light, and Ron fell in a heap onto his mattress.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  repeated Harry weakly, while Dean and Seamus contin\-ued to roar with laughter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tomorrow,\rdblquote  said Ron in a muffled voice, \ldblquote I\rquote d rather you set the alarm clock.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 By the time they had got dressed, padding themselves out with\lang3081  \lang1033 several of Mrs. Weasley\rquote s hand-knitted sweaters and carrying cloaks, scarves, and gloves, Ron\rquote s shock had subsided and he had decided that Harry\rquote s new spell was highly amusing; so amusing, in fact, that he lost no time in regaling Hermione with the story as they sat down for breakfast.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 and then there was another flash of light and I landed on the bed again!\rdblquote  Ron grinned, helping himself to sausages.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione had not cracked a smile during this anecdote, and now turned an expression of wintry disapproval upon Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Was this spell, by any chance, another one from that potion book of yours?\rdblquote  she asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry frowned at her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Always jump to the worst conclusion, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Was it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 yeah, it was, but so what?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you just decided to try out an unknown, handwritten in\-cantation and see what would happen?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why does it matter if it\rquote s handwritten?\rdblquote  said Harry, preferring not to answer the rest of the question.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because it\rquote s probably not Ministry of Magic\lang3081\endash\lang1033 approved,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote And also,\rdblquote  she added, as Harry and Ron rolled their eyes, \ldblquote because I\rquote m starting to think this Prince character was a bit dodgy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Both Harry and Ron shouted her down at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was a laugh!\rdblquote  said Ron, upending a ketchup bottle over his sausages. \ldblquote Just a laugh, Hermione, that\rquote s all!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dangling people upside down by the ankle?\rdblquote  said Hermi\-one. \ldblquote Who puts their time and energy into making up spells like that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fred and George,\rdblquote  said Ron, shrugging, \ldblquote it\rquote s their kind of thing. And, er \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dad,\rdblquote  said Harry. He had only just remembered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Ron and Hermione together.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dad used this spell,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I \emdash  Lupin told me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This last part was not true; in fact, Harry had seen his father use the spell on Snape, but he had never told Ron and Hermione about that particular excursion into the Pensieve. Now, however, a won\-derful possibility occurred to him. Could the Half-Blood Prince possibly be \emdash  ?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe your dad did use it, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote but he\rquote s not the only one. We\rquote ve seen a whole bunch of people use it, in case you\rquote ve forgotten. Dangling people in the air. Making them float along, asleep, helpless.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared at her. With a sinking feeling, he too remembered the behavior of the Death Eaters at the Quidditch World Cup. Ron came to his aid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was different,\rdblquote  he said robustly. \ldblquote They were abusing it. Harry and his dad were just having a laugh. You don\rquote t like the Prince, Hermione,\rdblquote  he added, pointing a sausage at her sternly, \ldblquote because he\rquote s better than you at Potions \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s got nothing to do with that!\rdblquote  said Hermione, her cheeks reddening. \ldblquote I just think it\rquote s very irresponsible to start performing spells when you don\rquote t even know what they\rquote re for, and stop talking about \lquote the Prince\rquote  as if it\rquote s his title, I bet it\rquote s just a stupid nickname, and it doesn\rquote t seem as though he was a very nice person to me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t see where you get that from,\rdblquote  said Harry heatedly. \ldblquote If he\rquote d been a budding Death Eater he wouldn\rquote t have been boasting about being \lquote half-blood,\rquote  would he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Even as he said it, Harry remembered that his father had been pure-blood, but he pushed the thought out of his mind; he would worry about that later. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Death Eaters can\rquote t all be pure-blood, there aren\rquote t enough pure-blood wizards left,\rdblquote  said Hermione stubbornly. \ldblquote I expect most of them are half-bloods pretending to be pure. It\rquote s only Muggle-borns they hate, they\rquote d be quite happy to let you and Ron join up.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There is no way they\rquote d let me be a Death Eater!\rdblquote  said Ron in\-dignantly, a bit of sausage flying off the fork he was now brandish\-ing at Hermione and hitting Ernie Macmillan on the head. \ldblquote My whole family are blood traitors! That\rquote s as bad as Muggle-borns to Death Eaters!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And they\rquote d love to have me,\rdblquote  said Harry sarcastically. \ldblquote We\rquote d be best pals if they didn\rquote t keep trying to do me in.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This made Ron laugh; even Hermione gave a grudging smile, and a distraction arrived in the shape of Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hey, Harry, I\rquote m supposed to give you this.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was a scroll of parchment with Harry\rquote s name written upon it in familiar thin, slanting writing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks, Ginny \'85 It\rquote s Dumbledore\rquote s next lesson!\rdblquote  Harry told Ron and Hermione, pulling open the parchment and quickly read\-ing its contents. \ldblquote Monday evening!\rdblquote  He felt suddenly light and happy. \ldblquote Want to join us in Hogsmeade, Ginny?\rdblquote  he asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m going with Dean \emdash  might see you there,\rdblquote  she replied, wav\-ing at them as she left.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Filch was standing at the oak front doors as usual, checking off the names of people who had permission to go into Hogsmeade. The process took even longer than normal as Filch was triple-checking everybody with his Secrecy Sensor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What does it matter if we\rquote re smuggling Dark stuff OUT?\rdblquote  de\-manded Ron, eyeing the long thin Secrecy Sensor with apprehen\-sion. \ldblquote Surely you ought to be checking what we bring back IN?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His cheek earned him a few extra jabs with the Sensor, and he was still wincing as they stepped out into the wind and sleet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The walk into Hogsmeade was not enjoyable. Harry wrapped his scarf over his lower face; the exposed part soon felt both raw and numb. The road to the village was full of students bent double against the bitter wind. More than once Harry wondered whether they might not have had a better time in the warm common room, and when they finally reached Hogsmeade and saw that Zonko\rquote s Joke Shop had been boarded up, Harry took it as confirmation that this trip was not destined to be fun. Ron pointed, with a thickly gloved hand, toward Honeydukes, which was mercifully open, and Harry and Hermione staggered in his wake into the crowded shop.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank God,\rdblquote  shivered Ron as they were enveloped by warm, toffee-scented air. \ldblquote Let\rquote s stay here all afternoon.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, m\rquote boy!\rdblquote  said a booming voice from behind them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh no,\rdblquote  muttered Harry. The three of them turned to see Pro\-fessor Slughorn, who was wearing an enormous furry hat and an overcoat with matching fur collar, clutching a large bag of crystal\-ized pineapple, and occupying at least a quarter of the shop.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, that\rquote s three of my little suppers you\rquote ve missed now!\rdblquote  said Slughorn, poking him genially in the chest. \ldblquote It won\rquote t do, m\rquote boy, I\rquote m determined to have you! Miss Granger loves them, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione helplessly, \ldblquote they\rquote re really \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So why don\rquote t you come along, Harry?\rdblquote  demanded Slughorn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I\rquote ve had Quidditch practice, Professor,\rdblquote  said Harry, who\lang3081  \lang1033 had indeed been scheduling practices every time Slughorn had sent him a little, violet ribbon-adorned invitation. This strategy meant that Ron was not left out, and they usually had a laugh with Ginny, imagining Hermione shut up with McLaggen and Zabini.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I certainly expect you to win your first match after all this hard work!\rdblquote  said Slughorn. \ldblquote But a little recreation never hurt any\-body. Now, how about Monday night, you can\rquote t possibly want to practice in this weather. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t, Professor, I\rquote ve got \emdash  er \emdash  an appointment with Profes\-sor Dumbledore that evening.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Unlucky again!\rdblquote  cried Slughorn dramatically. \ldblquote Ah, well \'85 you can\rquote t evade me forever, Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And with a regal wave, he waddled out of the shop, taking as lit\-tle notice of Ron as though he had been a display of Cockroach Clusters.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t believe you\rquote ve wriggled out of another one,\rdblquote  said Hermi\-one, shaking her head. \ldblquote They\rquote re not \i that\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 bad, you know. \'85 They\rquote re even quite fun sometimes. \'85\rdblquote  But then she caught sight of Ron\rquote s expression. \ldblquote Oh, look \emdash  they\rquote ve got deluxe sugar quills \emdash  those would last hours!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Glad that Hermione had changed the subject, Harry showed much more interest in the new extra-large sugar quills than he would normally have done, but Ron continued to look moody and merely shrugged when Hermione asked him where he wanted to go next.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s go to the Three Broomsticks,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote It\rquote ll be warm.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They bundled their scarves back over their faces and left the sweetshop. The bitter wind was like knives on their faces after the sugary warmth of Honeydukes. The street was not very busy; no\-body was lingering to chat, just hurrying toward their destinations. The exceptions were two men a little ahead of them, standing just outside the Three Broomsticks. One was very tall and thin; squint\-ing through his rain-washed glasses Harry recognized the barman who worked in the other Hogsmeade pub, the Hog\rquote s Head. As Harry, Ron, and Hermione drew closer, the barman drew his cloak more tightly around his neck and walked away, leaving the shorter man to fumble with something in his arms. They were barely feet from him when Harry realized who the man was.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mundungus!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The squat, bandy-legged man with long, straggly, ginger hair jumped and dropped an ancient suitcase, which burst open, releas\-ing what looked like the entire contents of a junk shop window.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, \rquote ello, \rquote Arry,\rdblquote  said Mundungus Fletcher, with a most un\-convincing stab at airiness. \ldblquote Well, don\rquote t let me keep ya.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he began scrabbling on the ground to retrieve the contents of his suitcase with every appearance of a man eager to be gone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you selling this stuff?\rdblquote  asked Harry, watching Mundungus grab an assortment of grubby-looking objects from the ground.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, well, gotta scrape a living,\rdblquote  said Mundungus. \ldblquote Gimme that!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron had stooped down and picked up something silver.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hang on,\rdblquote  Ron said slowly. \ldblquote This looks familiar \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you!\rdblquote  said Mundungus, snatching the goblet out of Ron\rquote s hand and stuffing it back into the case. \ldblquote Well, I\rquote ll see you all \emdash  OUCH!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had pinned Mundungus against the wall of the pub by the throat. Holding him fast with one hand, he pulled out his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  squealed Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You took that from Sirius\rquote s house,\rdblquote  said Harry, who was almost nose to nose with Mundungus and was breathing in an unpleasant smell of old tobacco and spirits. \ldblquote That had the Black family crest on it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  no \emdash  what \emdash  ?\rdblquote  spluttered Mundungus, who was slowly turning purple.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did you do, go back the night he died and strip the place?\rdblquote  snarled Harry.\par
\ldblquote I \emdash  no \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Give it to me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, you mustn\rquote t!\rdblquote  shrieked Hermione, as Mundungus started to turn blue.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a bang, and Harry felt his hands fly off Mundungus\rquote s throat. Gasping and spluttering, Mundungus seized his fallen case, then \emdash  \i CRACK\i0  \emdash  he Disapparated.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry swore at the top of his voice, spinning on the spot to see where Mundungus had gone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote COME BACK, YOU THIEVING \emdash  !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s no point, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Tonks had appeared out of nowhere, her mousy hair wet with sleet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mundungus will probably be in London by now. There\rquote s no point yelling.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s nicked Sirius\rquote s stuff! Nicked it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but still,\rdblquote  said Tonks, who seemed perfectly untroubled by this piece of information. \ldblquote You should get out of the cold.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She watched them go through the door of the Three Broom\-sticks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The moment he was inside, Harry burst out, \ldblquote\i He was nicking Sirius\rquote s stuff\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know, Harry, but please don\rquote t shout, people are staring,\rdblquote  whis\-pered Hermione. \ldblquote Go and sit down, I\rquote ll get you a drink.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was still fuming when Hermione returned to their table a few minutes later holding three bottles of butterbeer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can\rquote t the Order control Mundungus?\rdblquote  Harry demanded of the other two in a furious whisper. \ldblquote Can\rquote t they at least stop him steal\-ing everything that\rquote s not fixed down when he\rquote s at headquarters?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shh!\rdblquote  said Hermione desperately, looking around to make sure nobody was listening; there were a couple of warlocks sitting close by who were staring at Harry with great interest, and Zabini was lolling against a pillar not far away. \ldblquote Harry, I\rquote d be annoyed too, I know it\rquote s your things he\rquote s stealing \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry gagged on his butterbeer; he had momentarily forgotten that he owned number twelve, Grimmauld Place.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, it\rquote s my stuff!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote No wonder he wasn\rquote t pleased to see me! Well, I\rquote m going to tell Dumbledore what\rquote s going on, he\rquote s the only one who scares Mundungus.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good idea,\rdblquote  whispered Hermione, clearly pleased that Harry was calming down. \ldblquote Ron, what are you staring at?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  said Ron, hastily looking away from the bar, but Harry knew he was trying to catch the eye of the curvy and attractive bar\-maid, Madam Rosmerta, for whom he had long nursed a soft spot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I expect \lquote nothing\rquote s\rquote  in the back getting more firewhisky,\rdblquote  said Hermione waspishly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron ignored this jibe, sipping his drink in what he evidently considered to be a dignified silence. Harry was thinking about Sir\-ius, and how he had hated those silver goblets anyway. Hermione\lang3081  \lang1033 drummed her fingers on the table, her eyes flickering between Ron and the bar. The moment Harry drained the last drops in his bot\-tle she said, \ldblquote Shall we call it a day and go back to school, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The other two nodded; it had not been a fun trip and the weather was getting worse the longer they stayed. Once again they drew their cloaks tightly around them, rearranged their scarves, pulled on their gloves, then followed Katie Bell and a friend out of the pub and back up the High Street. Harry\rquote s thoughts strayed to Ginny as they trudged up the road to Hogwarts through the frozen slush. They had not met up with her, undoubtedly, thought Harry, because she and Dean were cozily closeted in Madam Puddifoot\rquote s Tea Shop, that haunt of happy couples. Scowling, he bowed his head against the swirling sleet and trudged on.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was a little while before Harry became aware that the voices of Katie Bell and her friend, which were being carried back to him on the wind, had become shriller and louder. Harry squinted at their indistinct figures. The two girls were having an argument about something Katie was holding in her hand. \ldblquote It\rquote s nothing to do with you, Leanne!\rdblquote  Harry heard Katie say.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They rounded a corner in the lane, sleet coming thick and fast, blurring Harry\rquote s glasses. Just as he raised a gloved hand to wipe them, Leanne made to grab hold of the package Katie was holding; Katie tugged it back and the package fell to the ground.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At once, Katie rose into the air, not as Ron had done, suspended comically by the ankle, but gracefully, her arms outstretched, as though she was about to fly. Yet there was something wrong, some\-thing eerie. \'85 Her hair was whipped around her by the fierce wind, but her eyes were closed and her face was quite empty of\lang3081  \lang1033 expression. Harry, Ron, Hermione, and Leanne had all halted in their tracks, watching.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then, six feet above the ground, Katie let out a terrible scream. Her eyes flew open but whatever she could see, or whatever she was feeling, was clearly causing her terrible anguish. She screamed and screamed; Leanne started to scream too and seized Katie\rquote s ankles, trying to tug her back to the ground. Harry, Ron, and Hermione rushed forward to help, but even as they grabbed Katie\rquote s legs, she fell on top of them; Harry and Ron managed to catch her but she was writhing so much they could hardly hold her. Instead they low\-ered her to the ground where she thrashed and screamed, appar\-ently unable to recognize any of them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around; the landscape seemed deserted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stay there!\rdblquote  he shouted at the others over the howling wind. \ldblquote I\rquote m going for help!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He began to sprint toward the school; he had never seen anyone behave as Katie had just behaved and could not think what had caused it; he hurtled around a bend in the lane and collided with what seemed to be an enormous bear on its hind legs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid!\rdblquote  he panted, disentangling himself from the hedgerow into which he had fallen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  said Hagrid, who had sleet trapped in his eyebrows and beard, and was wearing his great, shaggy beaverskin coat. \ldblquote Jus\rquote  bin visitin\rquote  Grawp, he\rquote s comin\rquote  on so well yeh wouldn\rquote  \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid, someone\rquote s hurt back there, or cursed, or something \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wha?\rdblquote  said Hagrid, bending lower to hear what Harry was say\-ing over the raging wind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Someone\rquote s been cursed!\rdblquote  bellowed Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cursed? Who\rquote s bin cursed \emdash  not Ron? Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, it\rquote s not them, it\rquote s Katie Bell \emdash  this way \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Together they ran back along the lane. It took them no time to find the little group of people around Katie, who was still writhing and screaming on the ground; Ron, Hermione, and Leanne were all trying to quiet her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get back!\rdblquote  shouted Hagrid. \ldblquote Lemme see her!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Something\rquote s happened to her!\rdblquote  sobbed Leanne. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know what \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid stared at Katie for a second, then without a word, bent down, scooped her into his arms, and ran off toward the castle with her. Within seconds, Katie\rquote s piercing screams had died away and the only sound was the roar of the wind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione hurried over to Katie\rquote s wailing friend and put an arm around her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s Leanne, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The girl nodded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did it just happen all of a sudden, or \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was when that package tore,\rdblquote  sobbed Leanne, pointing at the now sodden brown-paper package on the ground, which had split open to reveal a greenish glitter. Ron bent down, his hand out\-stretched, but Harry seized his arm and pulled him back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Don\rquote t touch it\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He crouched down. An ornate opal necklace was visible, poking out of the paper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve seen that before,\rdblquote  said Harry, staring at the thing. \ldblquote It was on display in Borgin and Burkes ages ago. The label said it was cursed. Katie must have touched it.\rdblquote  He looked up at Leanne, who\lang3081  \lang1033 had started to shake uncontrollably. \ldblquote How did Katie get hold of this?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, that\rquote s why we were arguing. She came back from the bathroom in the Three Broomsticks holding it, said it was a sur\-prise for somebody at Hogwarts and she had to deliver it. She looked all funny when she said it. \'85 Oh no, oh no, I bet she\rquote d been Imperiused and I didn\rquote t realize!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Leanne shook with renewed sobs. Hermione patted her shoulder gently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She didn\rquote t say who\rquote d given it to her, Leanne?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No \'85 she wouldn\rquote t tell me \'85 and I said she was being stupid and not to take it up to school, but she just wouldn\rquote t listen and \'85 and then I tried to grab it from her \'85 and \emdash  and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Leanne let out a wail of despair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote d better get up to school,\rdblquote  said Hermione, her arm still around Leanne. \ldblquote We\rquote ll be able to find out how she is. Come on. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry hesitated for a moment, then pulled his scarf from around his face and, ignoring Ron\rquote s gasp, carefully covered the necklace in it and picked it up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ll need to show this to Madam Pomfrey,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As they followed Hermione and Leanne up the road, Harry was thinking furiously. They had just entered the grounds when he spoke, unable to keep his thoughts to himself any longer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Malfoy knows about this necklace. It was in a case at Borgin and Burkes four years ago, I saw him having a good look at it while I was hiding from him and his dad. \i This\i0  is what he was buying that day when we followed him! He remembered it and he went back for it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  I dunno, Harry,\rdblquote  said Ron hesitantly. \ldblquote Loads of people go\lang3081  \lang1033 to Borgin and Burkes \'85 and didn\rquote t that girl say Katie got it in the girls\rquote  bathroom?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She said she came back from the bathroom with it, she didn\rquote t necessarily get it in the bathroom itself\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote McGonagall!\rdblquote  said Ron warningly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked up. Sure enough, Professor McGonagall was hur\-rying down the stone steps through swirling sleet to meet them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid says you four saw what happened to Katie Bell \emdash  upstairs to my office at once, please! What\rquote s that you\rquote re holding, Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s the thing she touched,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good lord,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, looking alarmed as she took the necklace from Harry. \ldblquote No, no, Filch, they\rquote re with me!\rdblquote  she added hastily, as Filch came shuffling eagerly across the entrance hall holding his Secrecy Sensor aloft. \ldblquote Take this necklace to Profes\-sor Snape at once, but be sure not to touch it, keep it wrapped in the scarf!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and the others followed Professor McGonagall upstairs and into her office. The sleet-spattered windows were rattling in their frames, and the room was chilly despite the fire crackling in the grate. Professor McGonagall closed the door and swept around her desk to face Harry, Ron, Hermione, and the still sobbing Leanne.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote  she said sharply. \ldblquote What happened?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Haltingly, and with many pauses while she attempted to control her crying, Leanne told Professor McGonagall how Katie had gone to the bathroom in the Three Broomsticks and returned holding the unmarked package, how Katie had seemed a little odd, and\lang3081  \lang1033 how they had argued about the advisability of agreeing to deliver unknown objects, the argument culminating in the tussle over the parcel, which tore open. At this point, Leanne was so overcome, there was no getting another word out of her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, not unkindly, \ldblquote go up to the hospital wing, please, Leanne, and get Madam Pomfrey to give you something for shock.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When she had left the room, Professor McGonagall turned back to Harry, Ron, and Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What happened when Katie touched the necklace?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She rose up in the air,\rdblquote  said Harry, before either Ron or Hermi\-one could speak, \ldblquote and then began to scream, and collapsed. Profes\-sor, can I see Professor Dumbledore, please?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The headmaster is away until Monday, Potter,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, looking surprised.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Away?\rdblquote  Harry repeated angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Potter, away!\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall tartly. \ldblquote But any\-thing you have to say about this horrible business can be said to me, I\rquote m sure!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 For a split second, Harry hesitated. Professor McGonagall did not invite confidences; Dumbledore, though in many ways more intimidating, still seemed less likely to scorn a theory, however wild. This was a life-and-death matter, though, and no moment to worry about being laughed at.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think Draco Malfoy gave Katie that necklace, Professor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 On one side of him, Ron rubbed his nose in apparent embar\-rassment; on the other, Hermione shuffled her feet as though quite keen to put a bit of distance between herself and Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That is a very serious accusation, Potter,\rdblquote  said Professor McGon\-agall, after a shocked pause. \ldblquote Do you have any proof?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote but\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  and he told her about following Malfoy to Borgin and Burkes and the conversation they had over\-heard between him and Mr. Borgin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When he had finished speaking, Professor McGonagall looked slightly confused.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Malfoy took something to Borgin and Burkes for repair?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, Professor, he just wanted Borgin to tell him how to mend something, he didn\rquote t have it with him. But that\rquote s not the point, the thing is that he bought something at the same time, and I think it was that necklace \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You saw Malfoy leaving the shop with a similar package?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, Professor, he told Borgin to keep it in the shop for him \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Harry,\rdblquote  Hermione interrupted, \ldblquote Borgin asked him if he wanted to take it with him, and Malfoy said no \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because he didn\rquote t want to touch it, obviously!\rdblquote  said Harry angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What he actually said was, \lquote How would I look carrying that down the street?\rquote  \rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, he would look a bit of a prat carrying a necklace,\rdblquote  inter\-jected Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, Ron,\rdblquote  said Hermione despairingly, \ldblquote it would be all wrapped up, so he wouldn\rquote t have to touch it, and quite easy to hide inside a cloak, so nobody would see it! I think whatever he reserved at Borgin and Burkes was noisy or bulky, something he knew would draw attention to him if he carried it down the street \emdash  and in any case,\rdblquote  she pressed on loudly, before Harry could interrupt, \ldblquote I asked Borgin about the necklace, don\rquote t you remember? When I\lang3081  \lang1033 went in to try and find out what Malfoy had asked him to keep, I saw it there. And Borgin just told me the price, he didn\rquote t say it was already sold or anything \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you were being really obvious, he realized what you were up to within about five seconds, of course he wasn\rquote t going to tell you \emdash  anyway, Malfoy could\rquote ve sent off for it since \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s enough!\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, as Hermione opened her mouth to retort, looking furious. \ldblquote Potter, I appreciate you telling me this, but we cannot point the finger of blame at Mr. Malfoy purely because he visited the shop where this necklace might have been purchased. The same is probably true of hundreds of people \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  that\rquote s what I said \emdash\rdblquote  muttered Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and in any case, we have put stringent security measures in place this year. I do not believe that necklace can possibly have en\-tered this school without our knowledge \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and what is more,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, with an air of awful finality, \ldblquote Mr. Malfoy was not in Hogsmeade today.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry gaped at her, deflating.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do you know, Professor?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because he was doing detention with me. He has now failed to complete his Transfiguration homework twice in a row. So, thank you for telling me your suspicions, Potter,\rdblquote  she said as she marched past them, \ldblquote but I need to go up to the hospital wing now to check on Katie Bell. Good day to you all.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She held open her office door. They had no choice but to file past her without another word.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was angry with the other two for siding with McGonagall;\lang3081  \lang1033 nevertheless, he felt compelled to join in once they started dis\-cussing what had happened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So who do you reckon Katie was supposed to give the necklace to?\rdblquote  asked Ron, as they climbed the stairs to the common room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Goodness only knows,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote But whoever it was has had a narrow escape. No one could have opened that package without touching the necklace.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It could\rquote ve been meant for loads of people,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Dum\-bledore \emdash  the Death Eaters would love to get rid of him, he must be one of their top targets. Or Slughorn \emdash  Dumbledore reckons Voldemort really wanted him and they can\rquote t be pleased that he\rquote s sided with Dumbledore. Or \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Or you,\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking troubled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Couldn\rquote t have been,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote or Katie would\rquote ve just turned around in the lane and given it to me, wouldn\rquote t she? I was behind her all the way out of the Three Broomsticks. It would have made much more sense to deliver the parcel outside Hogwarts, what with Filch searching everyone who goes in and out. I wonder why Mal\-foy told her to take it into the castle?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, Malfoy wasn\rquote t in Hogsmeade!\rdblquote  said Hermione, actually stamping her foot in frustration.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He must have used an accomplice, then,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Crabbe or Goyle \emdash  or, come to think of it, another Death Eater, he\rquote ll have loads better cronies than Crabbe and Goyle now he\rquote s joined up \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Hermione exchanged looks that plainly said \i There\rquote s no point arguing with him.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dilligrout,\rdblquote  said Hermione firmly as they reached the Fat Lady.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The portrait swung open to admit them to the common room. It was quite full and smelled of damp clothing; many people\lang3081  \lang1033 seemed to have returned from Hogsmeade early because of the bad weather. There was no buzz of fear or speculation, however: Clearly, the news of Katie\rquote s fate had not yet spread.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t a very slick attack, really, when you stop and think about it,\rdblquote  said Ron, casually turfing a first year out of one of the good armchairs by the fire so that he could sit down. \ldblquote The curse didn\rquote t even make it into the castle. Not what you\rquote d call foolproof.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re right,\rdblquote  said Hermione, prodding Ron out of the chair with her foot and offering it to the first year again. \ldblquote It wasn\rquote t very well thought-out at all.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But since when has Malfoy been one of the world\rquote s great thinkers?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neither Ron nor Hermione answered him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
