Katie was removed to St. Mungo\rquote s Hospital for Magical Maladies and Injuries the following day, by which time the news that she had been cursed had spread all over the school, though the details were confused and nobody other than Harry, Ron, Hermione, and Leanne seemed to know that Katie herself had not been the intended target.\par
\ldblquote Oh, and Malfoy knows, of course,\rdblquote  said Harry to Ron and Her\-mione, who continued their new policy of feigning deafness when\-ever Harry mentioned his Malfoy-Is-a-Death-Eater theory.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had wondered whether Dumbledore would return from wherever he had been in time for Monday night\rquote s lesson, but hav\-ing had no word to the contrary, he presented himself outside Dumbledore\rquote s office at eight o\rquote clock, knocked, and was told to en\-ter. There sat Dumbledore looking unusually tired; his hand was as black and burned as ever, but he smiled when he gestured to Harry\lang3081  \lang1033 to sit down. The Pensieve was sitting on the desk again, casting sil\-very specks of light over the ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You have had a busy time while I have been away,\rdblquote  Dumble\-dore said. \ldblquote I believe you witnessed Katie\rquote s accident.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, sir. How is she?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Still very unwell, although she was relatively lucky. She appears to have brushed the necklace with the smallest possible amount of skin: There was a tiny hole in her glove. Had she put it on, had she even held it in her ungloved hand, she would have died, perhaps instantly. Luckily Professor Snape was able to do enough to prevent a rapid spread of the curse \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why him?\rdblquote  asked Harry quickly. \ldblquote Why not Madam Pomfrey?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Impertinent,\rdblquote  said a soft voice from one of the portraits on the wall, and Phineas Nigellus Black, Sirius\rquote s great-great-grandfather, raised his head from his arms where he had appeared to be sleeping. \ldblquote I would not have permitted a student to question the way Hog\-warts operated in my day.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, thank you, Phineas,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quellingly. \ldblquote Profes\-sor Snape knows much more about the Dark Arts than Madam Pomfrey, Harry. Anyway, the St. Mungo\rquote s staff are sending me hourly reports, and I am hopeful that Katie will make a full recov\-ery in time.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where were you this weekend, sir?\rdblquote  Harry asked, disregarding a strong feeling that he might be pushing his luck, a feeling appar\-ently shared by Phineas Nigellus, who hissed softly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I would rather not say just now,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote However, I shall tell you in due course.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You will?\rdblquote  said Harry, startled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I expect so,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, withdrawing a fresh bottle of silver memories from inside his robes and uncorking it with a prod of his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir,\rdblquote  said Harry tentatively, \ldblquote I met Mundungus in Hogsmeade.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah yes, I am already aware that Mundungus has been treating your inheritance with light-fingered contempt,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, frowning a little. \ldblquote He has gone to ground since you accosted him outside the Three Broomsticks; I rather think he dreads facing me. However, rest assured that he will not be making away with any more of Sirius\rquote s old possessions.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That mangy old half-blood has been stealing Black heirlooms?\rdblquote  said Phineas Nigellus, incensed; and he stalked out of his frame, undoubtedly to visit his portrait in number twelve, Grimmauld Place.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor,\rdblquote  said Harry, after a short pause, \ldblquote did Professor McGonagall tell you what I told her after Katie got hurt? About Draco Malfoy?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She told me of your suspicions, yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And do you \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I shall take all appropriate measures to investigate anyone who might have had a hand in Katie\rquote s accident,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote But what concerns me now, Harry, is our lesson.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt slightly resentful at this: If their lessons were so very important, why had there been such a long gap between the first and second? However, he said no more about Draco Malfoy, but watched as Dumbledore poured the fresh memories into the Pen\-sieve and began swirling the stone basin once more between his long-fingered hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You will remember, I am sure, that we left the tale of Lord\lang3081  \lang1033 Voldemort\rquote s beginnings at the point where the handsome Muggle, Tom Riddle, had abandoned his witch wife, Merope, and returned to his family home in Little Hangleton. Merope was left alone in London, expecting the baby who would one day become Lord Voldemort.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do you know she was in London, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because of the evidence of one Caractacus Burke,\rdblquote  said Dum\-bledore, \ldblquote who, by an odd coincidence, helped found the very shop whence came the necklace we have just been discussing.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He swilled the contents of the Pensieve as Harry had seen him swill them before, much as a gold prospector sifts for gold. Up out of the swirling, silvery mass rose a little old man revolving slowly in the Pensieve, silver as a ghost but much more solid, with a thatch of hair that completely covered his eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, we acquired it in curious circumstances. It was brought in by a young witch just before Christmas, oh, many years ago now. She said she needed the gold badly, well, that much was obvious. Covered in rags and pretty far along \'85 Going to have a baby, see. She said the locket had been Slytherin\rquote s. Well, we hear that sort of story all the time, \lquote Oh, this was Merlin\rquote s, this was, his favorite teapot,\rquote  but when I looked at it, it had his mark all right, and a few simple spells were enough to tell me the truth. Of course, that made it near enough priceless. She didn\rquote t seem to have any idea how much it was worth. Happy to get ten Galleons for it. Best bar\-gain we ever made!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore gave the Pensieve an extra-vigorous shake and Car\-actacus Burke descended back into the swirling mass of memory from whence he had come.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He only gave her ten Galleons?\rdblquote  said Harry indignantly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Caractacus Burke was not famed for his generosity,\rdblquote  said Dum\-bledore. \ldblquote So we know that, near the end of her pregnancy, Merope was alone in London and in desperate need of gold, desperate enough to sell her one and only valuable possession, the locket that was one of Marvolo\rquote s treasured family heirlooms.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But she could do magic!\rdblquote  said Harry impatiently. \ldblquote She could have got food and everything for herself by magic, couldn\rquote t she?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote perhaps she could. But it is my belief\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  I am guessing again, but I am sure I am right \emdash  that when her husband abandoned her, Merope stopped using magic. I do not think that she wanted to be a witch any longer. Of course, it is also possible that her unrequited love and the attendant despair sapped her of her powers; that can happen. In any case, as you are about to see, Merope refused to raise her wand even to save her own life.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She wouldn\rquote t even stay alive for her son?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore raised his eyebrows. \ldblquote Could you possibly be feeling sorry for Lord Voldemort?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly, \ldblquote but she had a choice, didn\rquote t she, not like my mother \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your mother had a choice too,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore gently. \ldblquote Yes, Merope Riddle chose death in spite of a son who needed her, but do not judge her too harshly, Harry. She was greatly weakened by long suffering and she never had your mother\rquote s courage. And now, if you will stand \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where are we going?\rdblquote  Harry asked, as Dumbledore joined him at the front of the desk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This time,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote we are going to enter \i my\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 memory. I think you will find it both rich in detail and satisfyingly accurate. After you, Harry \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry bent over the Pensieve; his face broke the cool surface of the memory and then he was falling through darkness again. \'85 Seconds later, his feet hit firm ground; he opened his eyes and found that he and Dumbledore were standing in a bustling, old-fashioned London street.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There I am,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore brightly, pointing ahead of them to a tall figure crossing the road in front of a horse-drawn milk cart.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This younger Albus Dumbledore\rquote s long hair and beard were auburn. Having reached their side of the street, he strode off along the pavement, drawing many curious glances due to the flamboy\-antly cut suit of plum velvet that he was wearing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nice suit, sir,\rdblquote  said Harry, before he could stop himself, but Dumbledore merely chuckled as they followed his younger self a short distance, finally passing through a set of iron gates into a bare courtyard that fronted a rather grim, square building surrounded by high railings. He mounted the few steps leading to the front door and knocked once. After a moment or two, the door was opened by a scruffy girl wearing an apron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good afternoon. I have an appointment with a Mrs. Cole, who, I believe, is the matron here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said the bewildered-looking girl, taking in Dumbledore\rquote s eccentric appearance. \ldblquote Um \'85 just a mo\rquote  \'85 MRS. COLE!\rdblquote  she bellowed over her shoulder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry heard a distant voice shouting something in response. The girl turned back to Dumbledore. \ldblquote Come in, she\rquote s on \rquote er way.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore stepped into a hallway tiled in black and white; the whole place was shabby but spotlessly clean. Harry and the older Dumbledore followed. Before the front door had closed behind them, a skinny, harassed-looking woman came scurrying toward them. She had a sharp-featured face that appeared more anxious than unkind, and she was talking over her shoulder to another aproned helper as she walked toward Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 and take the iodine upstairs to Martha, Billy Stubbs has been picking his scabs and Eric Whalley\rquote s oozing all over his sheets \emdash  chicken pox on top of everything else,\rdblquote  she said to no\-body in particular, and then her eyes fell upon Dumbledore and she stopped dead in her tracks, looking as astonished as if a giraffe had just crossed her threshold.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good afternoon,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, holding out his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cole simply gaped.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My name is Albus Dumbledore. I sent you a letter requesting an appointment and you very kindly invited me here today.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cole blinked. Apparently deciding that Dumbledore was not a hallucination, she said feebly, \ldblquote Oh yes. Well \emdash  well then \emdash  you\rquote d better come into my room. Yes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She led Dumbledore into a small room that seemed part sitting room, part office. It was as shabby as the hallway and the furniture was old and mismatched. She invited Dumbledore to sit on a rick\-ety chair and seated herself behind a cluttered desk, eyeing him nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am here, as I told you in my letter, to discuss Tom Riddle and arrangements for his future,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you family?\rdblquote  asked Mrs. Cole.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I am a teacher,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I have come to offer Tom a place at my school.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What school\rquote s this, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is called Hogwarts,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And how come you\rquote re interested in Tom?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We believe he has qualities we are looking for.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You mean he\rquote s won a scholarship? How can he have done? He\rquote s never been entered for one.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, his name has been down for our school since birth \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who registered him? His parents?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was no doubt that Mrs. Cole was an inconveniently sharp woman. Apparently Dumbledore thought so too, for Harry now saw him slip his wand out of the pocket of his velvet suit, at the same time picking up a piece of perfectly blank paper from Mrs. Cole\rquote s desktop.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, waving his wand once as he passed her the piece of paper, \ldblquote I think this will make everything clear.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cole\rquote s eyes slid out of focus and back again as she gazed in\-tently at the blank paper for a moment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That seems perfectly in order,\rdblquote  she said placidly, handing it back. Then her eyes fell upon a bottle of gin and two glasses that had certainly not been present a few seconds before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  may I offer you a glass of gin?\rdblquote  she said in an extra-refined voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you very much,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, beaming.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It soon became clear that Mrs. Cole was no novice when it came to gin drinking. Pouring both of them a generous measure, she drained her own glass in one gulp. Smacking her lips frankly, she\lang3081  \lang1033 smiled at Dumbledore for the first time, and he didn\rquote t hesitate to press his advantage.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was wondering whether you could tell me anything of Tom Riddle\rquote s history? I think he was born here in the orphanage?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Cole, helping herself to more gin. \ldblquote I re\-member it clear as anything, because I\rquote d just started here myself. New Year\rquote s Eve and bitter cold, snowing, you know. Nasty night. And this girl, not much older than I was myself at the time, came staggering up the front steps. Well, she wasn\rquote t the first. We took her in, and she had the baby within the hour. And she was dead in an\-other hour.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cole nodded impressively and took another generous gulp of gin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did she say anything before she died?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore. \ldblquote Anything about the boy\rquote s father, for instance?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, as it happens, she did,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Cole, who seemed to be rather enjoying herself now, with the gin in her hand and an eager audience for her story. \ldblquote I remember she said to me, \lquote I hope he looks like his papa,\rquote  and I won\rquote t lie, she was right to hope it, because she was no beauty \emdash  and then she told me he was to be named Tom, for his father, and Marvolo, for \i her\i0  father \emdash  yes, I know, funny name, isn\rquote t it? We wondered whether she came from a circus \emdash  and she said the boy\rquote s surname was to be Riddle. And she died soon after that without another word.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, we named him just as she\rquote d said, it seemed so important to the poor girl, but no Tom nor Marvolo nor any kind of Riddle ever came looking for him, nor any family at all, so he stayed in the orphanage and he\rquote s been here ever since.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Cole helped herself, almost absentmindedly, to another\lang3081  \lang1033 healthy measure of gin. Two pink spots had appeared high on her cheekbones. Then she said, \ldblquote He\rquote s a funny boy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I thought he might be.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He was a funny baby too. He hardly ever cried, you know. And then, when he got a little older, he was \'85 odd.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Odd in what way?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore gently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, he \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Mrs. Cole pulled up short, and there was nothing blurry or vague about the inquisitorial glance she shot Dumbledore over her gin glass.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s definitely got a place at your school, you say?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Definitely,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And nothing I say can change that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ll be taking him away, whatever?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Whatever,\rdblquote  repeated Dumbledore gravely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She squinted at him as though deciding whether or not to trust him. Apparently she decided she could, because she said in a sud\-den rush, \ldblquote He scares the other children.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You mean he is a bully?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think he must be,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Cole, frowning slightly, \ldblquote but it\rquote s very hard to catch him at it. There have been incidents. \'85 Nasty things\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore did not press her, though Harry could tell that he was interested. She took yet another gulp of gin and her rosy cheeks grew rosier still.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Billy Stubbs\rquote s rabbit\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 well, Tom \i said\i0  he didn\rquote t do it and I don\rquote t see how he could have done, but even so, it didn\rquote t hang itself from the rafters, did it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I shouldn\rquote t think so, no,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But I\rquote m jiggered if I know how he got up there to do it. All I know is he and Billy had argued the day before. And then\rdblquote  \emdash  Mrs. Cole took another swig of gin, slopping a little over her chin this time \emdash  \ldblquote on the summer outing \emdash  we take them out, you know, once a year, to the countryside or to the seaside \emdash  well, Amy Ben\-son and Dennis Bishop were never quite right afterwards, and all we ever got out of them was that they\rquote d gone into a cave with Tom Riddle. He swore they\rquote d just gone exploring, but \i something\i0  hap\-pened in there, I\rquote m sure of it. And, well, there have been a lot of things, funny things. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked around at Dumbledore again, and though her cheeks were flushed, her gaze was steady. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think many people will be sorry to see the back of him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You understand, I\rquote m sure, that we will not be keeping him per\-manently?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote He will have to return here, at the very least, every summer.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, well, that\rquote s better than a whack on the nose with a rusty poker,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Cole with a slight hiccup. She got to her feet, and Harry was impressed to see that she was quite steady, even though two-thirds of the gin was now gone. \ldblquote I suppose you\rquote d like to see him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very much,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, rising too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She led him out of her office and up the stone stairs, calling out instructions and admonitions to helpers and children as she passed. The orphans, Harry saw, were all wearing the same kind of grayish tunic. They looked reasonably well-cared for, but there was no denying that this was a grim place in which to grow up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here we are,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Cole, as they turned off the second\lang3081  \lang1033 landing and stopped outside the first door in a long corridor. She knocked twice and entered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tom? You\rquote ve got a visitor. This is Mr. Dumberton \emdash  sorry, Dunderbore. He\rquote s come to tell you \emdash  well, I\rquote ll let him do it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and the two Dumbledores entered the room, and Mrs. Cole closed the door on them. It was a small bare room with noth\-ing in it except an old wardrobe, a wooden chair,\lang3081  \lang1033 and an iron bed\-stead. A boy was sitting on top of the gray blankets, his legs stretched out in front of him, holding a book.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was no trace of the Gaunts in Tom Riddle\rquote s face. Merope had got her dying wish: He was his handsome father in miniature, tall for eleven years old, dark-haired, and pale. His eyes narrowed slightly as he took in Dumbledore\rquote s eccentric appearance. There was a moment\rquote s silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do you do, Tom?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, walking forward and holding out his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The boy hesitated, then took it, and they shook hands. Dum\-bledore drew up the hard wooden chair beside Riddle, so that the pair of them looked rather like a hospital patient and visitor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am Professor Dumbledore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote Professor\rquote ?\rdblquote  repeated Riddle. He looked wary. \ldblquote Is that like \lquote doctor\rquote ? What are you here for? Did \i she\i0  get you in to have a look at me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was pointing at the door through which Mrs. Cole had just left.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, smiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t believe you,\rdblquote  said Riddle. \ldblquote She wants me looked at, doesn\rquote t she? Tell the truth!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He spoke the last three words with a ringing force that was\lang3081  \lang1033 almost shocking. It was a command, and it sounded as though he had given it many times before. His eyes had widened and he was glaring at Dumbledore, who made no response except to continue smiling pleasantly. After a few seconds Riddle stopped glaring, though he looked, if anything, warier still.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who are you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have told you. My name is Professor Dumbledore and I work at a school called Hogwarts. I have come to offer you a place at my school \emdash  your new school, if you would like to come.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle\rquote s reaction to this was most surprising. He leapt from the bed and backed away from Dumbledore, looking furious.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You can\rquote t kid me! The asylum, that\rquote s where you\rquote re from, isn\rquote t it? \lquote Professor,\rquote  yes, of course \emdash  well, I\rquote m not going, see? That old cat\rquote s the one who should be in the asylum. I never did anything to little Amy Benson or Dennis Bishop, and you can ask them, they\rquote ll tell you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am not from the asylum,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore patiently. \ldblquote I am a teacher and, if you will sit down calmly, I shall tell you about Hog\-warts. Of course, if you would rather not come to the school, no\-body will force you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote d like to see them try,\rdblquote  sneered Riddle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hogwarts,\rdblquote  Dumbledore went on, as though he had not heard Riddle\rquote s last words, \ldblquote is a school for people with special abilities \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not mad!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know that you are not mad. Hogwarts is not a school for mad people. It is a school of magic.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was silence. Riddle had frozen, his face expressionless, but his eyes were flickering back and forth between each of Dumble\-dore\rquote s, as though trying to catch one of them lying.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Magic?\rdblquote  he repeated in a whisper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s \'85 it\rquote s magic, what I can do?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What is it that you can do?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All sorts,\rdblquote  breathed Riddle. A flush of excitement was rising up his neck into his hollow cheeks; he looked fevered. \ldblquote I can make things move without touching them. I can make animals do what I want them to do, without training them. I can make bad things happen to people who annoy me. I can make them hurt if I want to.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His legs were trembling. He stumbled forward and sat down on the bed again, staring at his hands, his head bowed as though in prayer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I knew I was different,\rdblquote  he whispered to his own quivering fin\-gers. \ldblquote I knew I was special. Always, I knew there was something.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you were quite right,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, who was no longer smiling, but watching Riddle intently. \ldblquote You are a wizard.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle lifted his head. His face was transfigured: There was a wild happiness upon it, yet for some reason it did not make him better looking; on the contrary, his finely carved features seemed somehow rougher, his expression almost bestial.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you a wizard too?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I am.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Prove it,\rdblquote  said Riddle at once, in the same commanding tone he had used when he had said, \ldblquote Tell the truth.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore raised his eyebrows. \ldblquote If, as I take it, you are accept\-ing your place at Hogwarts \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course I am!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then you will address me as \lquote Professor\rquote  or \lquote sir.\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle\rquote s expression hardened for the most fleeting moment be\-fore he said, in an unrecognizably polite voice, \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, sir. I meant \emdash  please, Professor, could you show me \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was sure that Dumbledore was going to refuse, that he would tell Riddle there would be plenty of time for practical demonstrations at Hogwarts, that they were currently in a building full of Muggles and must therefore be cautious. To his great sur\-prise, however, Dumbledore drew his wand from an inside pocket of his suit jacket, pointed it at the shabby wardrobe in the corner, and gave the wand a casual flick.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wardrobe burst into flames.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle jumped to his feet; Harry could hardly blame him for howling in shock and rage; all his worldly possessions must be in there. But even as Riddle rounded on Dumbledore, the flames van\-ished, leaving the wardrobe completely undamaged.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle stared from the wardrobe to Dumbledore; then, his ex\-pression greedy, he pointed at the wand. \ldblquote Where can I get one of them?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All in good time,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I think there is some\-thing trying to get out of your wardrobe.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And sure enough, a faint rattling could be heard from inside it. For the first time, Riddle looked frightened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Open the door,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle hesitated, then crossed the room and threw open the wardrobe door. On the topmost shelf, above a rail of threadbare clothes, a small cardboard box was shaking and rattling as though there were several frantic mice trapped inside it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Take it out,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle took down the quaking box. He looked unnerved.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is there anything in that box that you ought not to have?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle threw Dumbledore a long, clear, calculating look. \ldblquote Yes, I suppose so, sir,\rdblquote  he said finally, in an expressionless voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Open it,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle took off the lid and tipped the contents onto his bed without looking at them. Harry, who had expected something much more exciting, saw a mess of small, everyday objects: a yo-yo, a silver thimble, and a tarnished mouth organ among them. Once free of the box, they stopped quivering and lay quite still upon the thin blankets.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You will return them to their owners with your apologies,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore calmly, putting his wand back into his jacket. \ldblquote I shall know whether it has been done. And be warned: Thieving is not tolerated at Hogwarts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle did not look remotely abashed; he was still staring coldly and appraisingly at Dumbledore. At last he said in a colorless voice, \ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote At Hogwarts,\rdblquote  Dumbledore went on, \ldblquote we teach you not only to use magic, but to control it. You have \emdash  inadvertently, I am sure \emdash  been using your powers in a way that is neither taught nor tolerated at our school. You are not the first, nor will you be the last, to allow your magic to run away with you. But you should know that Hog\-warts can expel students, and the Ministry of Magic \emdash  yes, there is a Ministry \emdash  will punish lawbreakers still more severely. All new wizards must accept that, in entering our world, they abide by our laws.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, sir,\rdblquote  said Riddle again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was impossible to tell what he was thinking; his face remained\lang3081  \lang1033 quite blank as he put the little cache of stolen objects back into the cardboard box. When he had finished, he turned to Dumbledore and said baldly, \ldblquote I haven\rquote t got any money.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That is easily remedied,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, drawing a leather money-pouch from his pocket. \ldblquote There is a fund at Hogwarts for those who require assistance to buy books and robes. You might have to buy some of your spellbooks and so on secondhand, but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where do you buy spellbooks?\rdblquote  interrupted Riddle, who had taken the heavy money bag without thanking Dumbledore, and was now examining a fat gold Galleon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In Diagon Alley,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I have your list of books and school equipment with me. I can help you find everything \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re coming with me?\rdblquote  asked Riddle, looking up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Certainly, if you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t need you,\rdblquote  said Riddle. \ldblquote I\rquote m used to doing things for myself, I go round London on my own all the time. How do you get to this Diagon Alley \emdash  sir?\rdblquote  he added, catching Dumbledore\rquote s eye.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry thought that Dumbledore would insist upon accompany\-ing Riddle, but once again he was surprised. Dumbledore handed Riddle the envelope containing his list of equipment, and after telling Riddle exactly how to get to the Leaky Cauldron from the orphanage, he said, \ldblquote You will be able to see it, although Muggles around you \emdash  non-magical people, that is \emdash  will not. Ask for Tom the barman \emdash  easy enough to remember, as he shares your name \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle gave an irritable twitch, as though trying to displace an irksome fly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You dislike the name \lquote Tom\rquote ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There are a lot of Toms,\rdblquote  muttered Riddle. Then, as though he could not suppress the question, as though it burst from him in spite of himself, he asked, \ldblquote Was my father a wizard? He was called Tom Riddle too, they\rquote ve told me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, his voice gentle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My mother can\rquote t have been magic, or she wouldn\rquote t have died,\rdblquote  said Riddle, more to himself than Dumbledore. \ldblquote It must\rquote ve been him. So \emdash  when I\rquote ve got all my stuff\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  when do I come to this Hogwarts?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
