\lang1033 His tone was casual but his eyes moved curiously over Riddle\rquote s face. They stood for a moment, man and boy, staring at each other. Then the handshake was broken; Dumbledore was at the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good-bye, Tom. I shall see you at Hogwarts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think that will do,\rdblquote  said the white-haired Dumbledore at Harry\rquote s side, and seconds later, they were soaring weightlessly through darkness once more, before landing squarely in the present-day office.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sit down,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, landing beside Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry obeyed, his mind still full of what he had just seen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He believed it much quicker than I did \emdash  I mean, when you told him he was a wizard,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t believe Hagrid at first, when he told me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Riddle was perfectly ready to believe that he was \emdash  to use his word \emdash  \lquote special,\rquote  \rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you know \emdash  then?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did I know that I had just met the most dangerous Dark wiz\-ard of all time?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote No, I had no idea that he was to grow up to be what he is. However, I was certainly intrigued by him. I returned to Hogwarts intending to keep an eye upon him, something I should have done in any case, given that he was alone and friendless, but which, already, I felt I ought to do for others\rquote  sake as much as his.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote His powers, as you heard, were surprisingly well-developed for such a young wizard and \emdash  most interestingly and ominously of all \emdash  he had already discovered that he had some measure of con\-trol over them, and begun to use them consciously. And as you saw, they were not the random experiments typical of young wizards: He was already using magic against other people, to frighten, to punish, to control. The little stories of the strangled rabbit and the young boy and girl he lured into a cave were most suggestive. \'85 \lquote\i I can make them hurt if I want to. \'85\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And he was a Parselmouth,\rdblquote  interjected Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, indeed; a rare ability, and one supposedly connected with the Dark Arts, although as we know, there are Parselmouths among the great and the good too. In fact, his ability to speak to serpents did not make me nearly as uneasy as his obvious instincts for cru\-elty, secrecy, and domination.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Time is making fools of us again,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, indicating the dark sky beyond the windows. \ldblquote But before we part, I want to draw your attention to certain features of the scene we have just witnessed, for they have a great bearing on the matters we shall be discussing in future meetings.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Firstly, I hope you noticed Riddle\rquote s reaction when I mentioned that another shared his first name, \lquote Tom\rquote ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry nodded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There he showed his contempt for anything that tied him to other people, anything that made him ordinary. Even then, he wished to be different, separate, notorious. He shed his name, as you know, within a few short years of that conversation and created the mask of\lang3081  \lang1033\lquote Lord Voldemort\rquote  behind which he has been hidden for so long.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I trust that you also noticed that Tom Riddle was already highly self-sufficient, secretive, and, apparently, friendless? He did not want help or companionship on his trip to Diagon Alley. He pre\-ferred to operate alone. The adult Voldemort is the same. You will hear many of his Death Eaters claiming that they are in his confi\-dence, that they alone are close to him, even understand him. They are deluded. Lord Voldemort has never had a friend, nor do I be\-lieve that he has ever wanted one.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And lastly \emdash  I hope you are not too sleepy to pay attention to this, Harry \emdash  the young Tom Riddle liked to collect trophies. You saw the box of stolen articles he had hidden in his room. These were taken from victims of his bullying behavior, souvenirs, if you will, of particularly unpleasant bits of magic. Bear in mind this magpie-like tendency, for this, particularly, will be important later.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And now, it really is time for bed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry got to his feet. As he walked across the room, his eyes fell upon the little table on which Marvolo Gaunt\rquote s ring had rested last time, but the ring was no longer there.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Harry?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, for Harry had come to a halt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The ring\rquote s gone,\rdblquote  said Harry, looking around. \ldblquote But I thought you might have the mouth organ or something.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore beamed at him, peering over the top of his half-moon spectacles.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very astute, Harry, but the mouth organ was only ever a mouth organ.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And on that enigmatic note he waved to Harry, who understood himself to be dismissed.\lang3081\par
