\lang1033 It was not as though he was really surprised, thought Harry, as he wrestled with a thorny vine intent upon throttling him; he had had an inkling that this might happen sooner or later. But he was not sure how he felt about it. \'85 He and Cho were now too em\-barrassed to look at each other, let alone talk to each other; what if Ron and Hermione started going out together, then split up? Could their friendship survive it? Harry remembered the few weeks when they had not been talking to each other in the third year; he had not enjoyed trying to bridge the distance between them. And then, what if they didn\rquote t split up? What if they became like Bill and Fleur, and it became excruciatingly embarrassing to be in their presence, so that he was shut out for good?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gotcha!\rdblquote  yelled Ron, pulling a second pod from the stump just as Hermione managed to burst the first one open, so that the bowl was full of tubers wriggling like pale green worms.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The rest of the lesson passed without further mention of Slughorn\rquote s party. Although Harry watched his two friends more closely over the next few days, Ron and Hermione did not seem any different except that they were a little politer to each other than usual. Harry supposed he would just have to wait to see what\lang3081  \lang1033 happened under the influence of butterbeer in Slughorn\rquote s dimly lit room on the night of the party. In the meantime, however, he had more pressing worries.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Katie Bell was still in St. Mungo\rquote s Hospital with no prospect of leaving, which meant that the promising Gryffindor team Harry had been training so carefully since September was one Chaser short. He kept putting off replacing Katie in the hope that she would return, but their opening match against Slytherin was loom\-ing, and he finally had to accept that she would not be back in time to play.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not think he could stand another full-House tryout. With a sinking feeling that had little to do with Quidditch, he cor\-nered Dean Thomas after Transfiguration one day. Most of the class had already left, although several twittering yellow birds were still zooming around the room, all of Hermione\rquote s creation; nobody else had succeeded in conjuring so much as a feather from thin air.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you still interested in playing Chaser?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wha \emdash  ? Yeah, of course!\rdblquote  said Dean excitedly. Over Dean\rquote s shoulder, Harry saw Seamus Finnigan slamming his books into his bag, looking sour. One of the reasons why Harry would have pre\-ferred not to have to ask Dean to play was that he knew Seamus would not like it. On the other hand, he had to do what was best for the team, and Dean had outflown Seamus at the tryouts.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well then, you\rquote re in,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote There\rquote s a practice tonight, seven o\rquote clock.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Dean. \ldblquote Cheers, Harry! Blimey, I can\rquote t wait to tell Ginny!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He sprinted out of the room, leaving Harry and Seamus alone together, an uncomfortable moment made no easier when a bird\lang3081  \lang1033 dropping landed on Seamus\rquote s head as one of Hermione\rquote s canaries whizzed over them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Seamus was not the only person disgruntled by the choice of Katie\rquote s substitute. There was much muttering in the common room about the fact that Harry had now chosen two of his class\-mates for the team. As Harry had endured much worse mutterings than this in his school career, he was not particularly bothered, but all the same, the pressure was increasing to provide a win in the upcoming match against Slytherin. If Gryffindor won, Harry knew that the whole House would forget that they had criticized him and swear that they had always known it was a great team. If they lost\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 well, Harry thought wryly, he had still endured worse mutterings. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had no reason to regret his choice once he saw Dean fly that evening; he worked well with Ginny and Demelza. The Beat\-ers, Peakes and Coote, were getting better all the time. The only problem was Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had known all along that Ron was an inconsistent player who suffered from nerves and a lack of confidence, and unfortu\-nately, the looming prospect of the opening game of the season seemed to have brought out all his old insecurities. After letting in half a dozen goals, most of them scored by Ginny, his technique became wilder and wilder, until he finally punched an oncoming Demelza Robins in the mouth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was an accident, I\rquote m sorry, Demelza, really sorry!\rdblquote  Ron shouted after her as she zigzagged back to the ground, dripping blood everywhere. \ldblquote I just \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Panicked,\rdblquote  Ginny said angrily, landing next to Demelza and ex\-amining her fat lip. \ldblquote You prat, Ron, look at the state of her!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can fix that,\rdblquote  said Harry, landing beside the two girls, pointing his wand at Demelza\rquote s mouth, and saying \ldblquote\i Episkey.\i0\rdblquote  \ldblquote And Ginny, don\rquote t call Ron a prat, you\rquote re not the Captain of this team \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you seemed too busy to call him a prat and I thought someone should \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry forced himself not to laugh.\lang3081\par
