\lang1033\ldblquote No, I will not!\rdblquote  yelled Ginny, beside herself. \ldblquote I\rquote ve seen you with Phlegm, hoping she\rquote ll kiss you on the cheek every time you see her,\lang3081  \lang1033 it\rquote s pathetic! If you went out and got a bit of snogging done your\-self, you wouldn\rquote t mind so much that everyone else does it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron had pulled out his wand too; Harry stepped swiftly between them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t know what you\rquote re talking about!\rdblquote  Ron roared, trying to get a clear shot at Ginny around Harry, who was now standing in front of her with his arms outstretched. \ldblquote Just because I don\rquote t do it in public \emdash  !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ginny screamed with derisive laughter, trying to push Harry out of the way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Been kissing Pigwidgeon, have you? Or have you got a picture of Auntie Muriel stashed under your pillow?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A streak of orange light flew under Harry\rquote s left arm and missed Ginny by inches; Harry pushed Ron up against the wall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t be stupid \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry\rquote s snogged Cho Chang!\rdblquote  shouted Ginny, who sounded close to tears now. \ldblquote And Hermione snogged Viktor Krum, it\rquote s only you who acts like it\rquote s something disgusting, Ron, and that\rquote s because you\rquote ve got about as much experience as a twelve-year-old!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And with that, she stormed away. Harry quickly let go of Ron; the look on his face was murderous. They both stood there, breath\-ing heavily, until Mrs. Norris, Filch\rquote s cat, appeared around the cor\-ner, which broke the tension.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote C\rquote mon,\rdblquote  said Harry, as the sound of Filch\rquote s shuffling feet reached their ears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They hurried up the stairs and along a seventh-floor corridor. \ldblquote Oi, out of the way!\rdblquote  Ron barked at a small girl who jumped in fright and dropped a bottle of toadspawn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry hardly noticed the sound of shattering glass; he felt dis\-oriented, dizzy; being struck by a lightning bolt must be something like this. \i It\rquote s just because she\rquote s Ron\rquote s sister, \i0 he told himself. \i You just didn\rquote t like seeing her kissing Dean because she\rquote s Ron\rquote s sister. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 But unbidden into his mind came an image of that same de\-serted corridor with himself kissing Ginny instead. \'85 The mon\-ster in his chest purred \'85 but then he saw Ron ripping open the tapestry curtain and drawing his wand on Harry, shouting things like \ldblquote betrayal of trust\rdblquote  \'85 \ldblquote supposed to be my friend\rdblquote  \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you think Hermione did snog Krum?\rdblquote  Ron asked abruptly, as they approached the Fat Lady. Harry gave a guilty start and wrenched his imagination away from a corridor in which no Ron intruded, in which he and Ginny were quite alone \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  he said confusedly. \ldblquote Oh \'85 er \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The honest answer was \ldblquote yes,\rdblquote  but he did not want to give it. However, Ron seemed to gather the worst from the look on Harry\rquote s face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dilligrout,\rdblquote  he said darkly to the Fat Lady, and they climbed through the portrait hole into the common room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neither of them mentioned Ginny or Hermione again; indeed, they barely spoke to each other that evening and got into bed in si\-lence, each absorbed in his own thoughts.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry lay awake for a long time, looking up at the canopy of his four-poster and trying to convince himself that his feelings for Ginny were entirely elder-brotherly. They had lived, had they not, like brother and sister all summer, playing Quidditch, teasing Ron, and having a laugh about Bill and Phlegm? He had known Ginny for years now. \'85 It was natural that he should feel protective \'85 natural that he should want to look out for her \'85 want to rip\lang3081  \lang1033 Dean limb from limb for kissing her \'85 No \'85 he would have to control that particular brotherly feeling. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron gave a great grunting snore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i She\rquote s Ron\rquote s sister,\i0  Harry told himself firmly. \i Ron\rquote s sister. She\rquote s out-of-bounds.\i0  He would not risk his friendship with Ron for anything. He punched his pillow into a more comfortable shape and waited for sleep to come, trying his utmost not to allow his thoughts to stray anywhere near Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry awoke next morning feeling slightly dazed and confused by a series of dreams in which Ron had chased him with a Beater\rquote s bat, but by midday he would have happily exchanged the dream Ron for the real one, who was not only cold-shouldering Ginny and Dean, but also treating a hurt and bewildered Hermione with an icy, sneering indifference. What was more, Ron seemed to have become, overnight, as touchy and ready to lash out as the average Blast-Ended Skrewt. Harry spent the day attempting to keep the peace between Ron and Hermione with no success; finally, Hermi\-one departed for bed in high dudgeon, and Ron stalked off to the boys\rquote  dormitory after swearing angrily at several frightened first years for looking at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 To Harry\rquote s dismay, Ron\rquote s new aggression did not wear off over the next few days. Worse still, it coincided with an even deeper dip in his Keeping skills, which made him still more aggressive, so that during the final Quidditch practice before Saturday\rquote s match, he failed to save every single goal the Chasers aimed at him, but bellowed at everybody so much that he reduced Demelza Robins to tears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You shut up and leave her alone!\rdblquote  shouted Peakes, who was about two-thirds Ron\rquote s height, though admittedly carrying a heavy bat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote ENOUGH!\rdblquote  bellowed Harry, who had seen Ginny glowering in Ron\rquote s direction and, remembering her reputation as an accom\-plished caster of the Bat-Bogey Hex, soared over to intervene be\-fore things got out of hand. \ldblquote Peakes, go and pack up the Bludgers. Demelza, pull yourself together, you played really well today. Ron \'85\rdblquote  he waited until the rest of the team were out of earshot before saying it, \ldblquote you\rquote re my best mate, but carry on treating the rest of them like this and I\rquote m going to kick you off the team.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He really thought for a moment that Ron might hit him, but then something much worse happened: Ron seemed to sag on his broom; all the fight went out of him and he said, \ldblquote I resign. I\rquote m pathetic.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re not pathetic and you\rquote re not resigning!\rdblquote  said Harry fiercely, seizing Ron by the front of his robes. \ldblquote You can save any\-thing when you\rquote re on form, it\rquote s a mental problem you\rquote ve got!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You calling me mental?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, maybe I am!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They glared at each other for a moment, then Ron shook his head wearily. \ldblquote I know you haven\rquote t got any time to find another Keeper, so I\rquote ll play tomorrow, but if we lose, and we will, I\rquote m tak\-ing myself off the team.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nothing Harry said made any difference. He tried boosting Ron\rquote s confidence all through dinner, but Ron was too busy being grumpy and surly with Hermione to notice. Harry persisted in the common room that evening, but his assertion that the whole team would be devastated if Ron left was somewhat undermined by the fact that the rest of the team was sitting in a huddle in a distant corner, clearly muttering about Ron and casting him nasty looks. Finally Harry tried getting angry again in the hope\lang3081  \lang1033 of provoking Ron into a defiant, and hopefully goal-saving, attitude, but this strategy did not appear to work any better than encouragement; Ron went to bed as dejected and hopeless as ever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry lay awake for a very long time in the darkness. He did not want to lose the upcoming match; not only was it his first as Cap\-tain, but he was determined to beat Draco Malfoy at Quidditch even if he could not yet prove his suspicions about him. Yet if Ron played as he had done in the last few practices, their chances of winning were very slim. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 If only there was something he could do to make Ron pull him\-self together \'85 make him play at the top of his form \'85 some\-thing that would ensure that Ron had a really good day. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And the answer came to Harry in one, sudden, glorious stroke of inspiration.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Breakfast was the usual excitable affair next morning; the Slytherins hissed and booed loudly as every member of the Gryffin\-dor team entered the Great Hall. Harry glanced at the ceiling and saw a clear, pale blue sky: a good omen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Gryffindor table, a solid mass of red and gold, cheered as Harry and Ron approached. Harry grinned and waved; Ron gri\-maced weakly and shook his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cheer up, Ron!\rdblquote  called Lavender. \ldblquote I know you\rquote ll be brilliant!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron ignored her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tea?\rdblquote  Harry asked him. \ldblquote Coffee? Pumpkin juice?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anything,\rdblquote  said Ron glumly, taking a moody bite of toast.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A few minutes later Hermione, who had become so tired of Ron\rquote s recent unpleasant behavior that she had not come down to breakfast with them, paused on her way up the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How are you both feeling?\rdblquote  she asked tentatively, her eyes on the back of Ron\rquote s head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine,\rdblquote  said Harry, who was concentrating on handing Ron a glass of pumpkin juice. \ldblquote There you go, Ron. Drink up.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron had just raised the glass to his lips when Hermione spoke sharply.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t drink that, Ron!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Both Harry and Ron looked up at her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione was now staring at Harry as though she could not be\-lieve her eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You just put something in that drink.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excuse me?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You heard me. I saw you. You just tipped something into Ron\rquote s drink. You\rquote ve got the bottle in your hand right now!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know what you\rquote re talking about,\rdblquote  said Harry, stowing the little bottle hastily in his pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron, I warn you, don\rquote t drink it!\rdblquote  Hermione said again, alarmed, but Ron picked up the glass, drained it in one gulp, and said, \ldblquote Stop bossing me around, Hermione.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked scandalized. Bending low so that only Harry could hear her, she hissed, \ldblquote You should be expelled for that. I\rquote d never have believed it of you, Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hark who\rquote s talking,\rdblquote  he whispered back. \ldblquote Confunded anyone lately?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She stormed up the table away from them. Harry watched her go without regret. Hermione had never really understood what a serious business Quidditch was. He then looked around at Ron, who was smacking his lips.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nearly time,\rdblquote  said Harry blithely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The frosty grass crunched underfoot as they strode down to the stadium.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Pretty lucky the weather\rquote s this good, eh?\rdblquote  Harry asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Ron, who was pale and sick-looking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ginny and Demelza were already wearing their Quidditch robes and waiting in the changing room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Conditions look ideal,\rdblquote  said Ginny, ignoring Ron. \ldblquote And guess what? That Slytherin Chaser Vaisey \emdash  he took a Bludger in the head yesterday during their practice, and he\rquote s too sore to play! And even better than that \emdash  Malfoy\rquote s gone off sick too!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i What\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Harry, wheeling around to stare at her. \ldblquote He\rquote s ill? What\rquote s wrong with him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No idea, but it\rquote s great for us,\rdblquote  said Ginny brightly. \ldblquote They\rquote re playing Harper instead; he\rquote s in my year and he\rquote s an idiot.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry smiled back vaguely, but as he pulled on his scarlet robes his mind was far from Quidditch. Malfoy had once before claimed he could not play due to injury, but on that occasion he had made sure the whole match was rescheduled for a time that suited the Slytherins better. Why was he now happy to let a substitute go on? Was he really ill, or was he faking?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fishy, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  he said in an undertone to Ron. \ldblquote Malfoy not playing?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lucky, I call it,\rdblquote  said Ron, looking slightly more animated. \ldblquote And Vaisey off too, he\rquote s their best goal scorer, I didn\rquote t fancy \emdash  hey!\rdblquote  he said suddenly, freezing halfway through pulling on his Keeper\rquote s gloves and staring at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85 you \'85\rdblquote  Ron had dropped his voice, he looked both scared and excited. \ldblquote My drink \'85 my pumpkin juice \'85 you didn\rquote t\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry raised his eyebrows, but said nothing except, \ldblquote We\rquote ll be starting in about five minutes, you\rquote d better get your boots on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They walked out onto the pitch to tumultuous roars and boos. One end of the stadium was solid red and gold; the other, a sea of green and silver. Many Hufflepuffs and Ravenclaws had taken sides too: Amidst all the yelling and clapping Harry could distinctly hear the roar of Luna Lovegood\rquote s famous lion-topped hat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stepped up to Madam Hooch, the referee, who was stand\-ing ready to release the balls from the crate.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Captains shake hands,\rdblquote  she said, and Harry had his hand crushed by the new Slytherin Captain, Urquhart. \ldblquote Mount your brooms. On the whistle \'85 three \'85 two \'85 one \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The whistle sounded, Harry and the others kicked off hard from the frozen ground, and they were away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry soared around the perimeter of the grounds, looking around for the Snitch and keeping one eye on Harper, who was zigzagging far below him. Then a voice that was jarringly different to the usual commentator\rquote s started up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, there they go, and I think we\rquote re all surprised to see the team that Potter\rquote s put together this year. Many thought, given Ronald Weasley\rquote s patchy performance as Keeper last year, that he might be off the team, but of course, a close personal friendship with the Captain does help. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 These words were greeted with jeers and applause from the Slytherin end of the pitch. Harry craned around on his broom to\lang3081  \lang1033 look toward the commentator\rquote s podium. A tall, skinny blond boy with an upturned nose was standing there, talking into the magical megaphone that had once been Lee Jordan\rquote s; Harry recognized Zacharias Smith, a Hufflepuff player whom he heartily disliked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, and here comes Slytherin\rquote s first attempt on goal, it\rquote s Urquhart streaking down the pitch and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s stomach turned over.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  Weasley saves it, well, he\rquote s bound to get lucky sometimes, I suppose. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right, Smith, he is,\rdblquote  muttered Harry, grinning to him\-self, as he dived amongst the Chasers with his eyes searching all around for some hint of the elusive Snitch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With half an hour of the game gone, Gryffindor were leading sixty points to zero, Ron having made some truly spectacular saves, some by the very tips of his gloves, and Ginny having scored four of Gryffindor\rquote s six goals. This effectively stopped Zacharias won\-dering loudly whether the two Weasleys were only there because Harry liked them, and he started on Peakes and Coote instead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course, Coote isn\rquote t really the usual build for a Beater,\rdblquote  said Zacharias loftily, \ldblquote they\rquote ve generally got a bit more muscle \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hit a Bludger at him!\rdblquote  Harry called to Coote as he zoomed past, but Coote, grinning broadly, chose to aim the next Bludger at Harper instead, who was just passing Harry in the opposite direc\-tion. Harry was pleased to hear the dull thunk that meant the Bludger had found its mark.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It seemed as though Gryffindor could do no wrong. Again and again they scored, and again and again, at the other end of the pitch, Ron saved goals with apparent ease. He was actually smiling now, and when the crowd greeted a particularly good save with a\lang3081  \lang1033 rousing chorus of the old favorite \ldblquote Weasley Is Our King,\rdblquote  he pre\-tended to conduct them from on high.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thinks he\rquote s something special today, doesn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said a snide voice, and Harry was nearly knocked off his broom as Harper col\-lided with him hard and deliberately. \ldblquote Your blood-traitor pal\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Madam Hooch\rquote s back was turned, and though Gryffindors be\-low shouted in anger, by the time she looked around, Harper had already sped off. His shoulder aching, Harry raced after him, de\-termined to ram him back. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And I think Harper of Slytherin\rquote s seen the Snitch!\rdblquote  said Zacharias Smith through his megaphone. \ldblquote Yes, he\rquote s certainly seen something Potter hasn\rquote t!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Smith really was an idiot, thought Harry, hadn\rquote t he noticed them collide? But next moment, his stomach seemed to drop out of the sky \emdash  Smith was right and Harry was wrong: Harper had not sped upward at random; he had spotted what Harry had not: The Snitch was speeding along high above them, glinting brightly against the clear blue sky.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry accelerated; the wind was whistling in his ears so that it drowned all sound of Smith\rquote s commentary or the crowd, but Harper was still ahead of him, and Gryffindor was only a hundred points up; if Harper got there first Gryffindor had lost\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 and now Harper was feet from it, his hand outstretched. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oi, Harper!\rdblquote  yelled Harry in desperation. \ldblquote How much did Malfoy pay you to come on instead of him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He did not know what made him say it, but Harper did a dou\-ble-take; he fumbled the Snitch, let it slip through his fingers, and shot right past it. Harry made a great swipe for the tiny, fluttering ball and caught it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote YES!\rdblquote  Harry yelled. Wheeling around, he hurtled back toward the ground, the Snitch held high in his hand. As the crowd realized what had happened, a great shout went up that almost drowned the sound of the whistle that signaled the end of the game.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ginny, where\rquote re you going?\rdblquote  yelled Harry, who had found him\-self trapped in the midst of a mass midair hug with the rest of the team, but Ginny sped right on past them until, with an almighty crash, she collided with the commentator\rquote s podium. As the crowd shrieked and laughed, the Gryffindor team landed beside the wreckage of wood under which Zacharias was feebly stirring; Harry heard Ginny saying blithely to an irate Professor McGona\-gall, \ldblquote Forgot to brake, Professor, sorry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Laughing, Harry broke free of the rest of the team and hugged Ginny, but let go very quickly. Avoiding her gaze, he clapped a cheering Ron on the back instead as, all enmity forgotten, the Gryffindor team left the pitch arm in arm, punching the air and waving to their supporters.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The atmosphere in the changing room was jubilant.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Party up in the common room, Seamus said!\rdblquote  yelled Dean exu\-berantly. \ldblquote C\rquote mon, Ginny, Demelza!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Harry were the last two in the changing room. They were just about to leave when Hermione entered. She was twisting her Gryffindor scarf in her hands and looked upset but determined.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want a word with you, Harry.\rdblquote  She took a deep breath. \ldblquote You shouldn\rquote t have done it. You heard Slughorn, it\rquote s illegal.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you going to do, turn us in?\rdblquote  demanded Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you two talking about?\rdblquote  asked Harry, turning away to hang up his robes so that neither of them would see him grinning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know perfectly well what we\rquote re talking about!\rdblquote  said Hermi\-one shrilly. \ldblquote You spiked Ron\rquote s juice with lucky potion at breakfast! Felix Felicis!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I didn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry, turning back to face them both.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes you did, Harry, and that\rquote s why everything went right, there were Slytherin players missing and Ron saved everything!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t put it in!\rdblquote  said Harry, grinning broadly. He slipped his hand inside his jacket pocket and drew out the tiny bottle that Hermione had seen in his hand that morning. It was full of golden potion and the cork was still tightly sealed with wax. \ldblquote I wanted Ron to think I\rquote d done it, so I faked it when I knew you were look\-ing.\rdblquote  He looked at Ron. \ldblquote You saved everything because you felt lucky. You did it all yourself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pocketed the potion again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There really wasn\rquote t anything in my pumpkin juice?\rdblquote  Ron said, astounded. \ldblquote But the weather\rquote s good \'85 and Vaisey couldn\rquote t play. \'85 I honestly haven\rquote t been given lucky potion?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shook his head. Ron gaped at him for a moment, then rounded on Hermione, imitating her voice. \ldblquote\i You added Felix Felicis to Ron\rquote s juice this morning, that\rquote s why he saved everything\i0 ! See! I can save goals without help, Hermione!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I never said you couldn\rquote t \emdash  Ron, \i you\i0  thought you\rquote d been given it too!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Ron had already strode past her out of the door with his broomstick over his shoulder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er,\rdblquote  said Harry into the sudden silence; he had not expected his plan to backfire like this, \ldblquote shall \'85 shall we go up to the party, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You go!\rdblquote  said Hermione, blinking back tears. \ldblquote I\rquote m \i sick\i0  of Ron at the moment, I don\rquote t know what I\rquote m supposed to have done. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And she stormed out of the changing room too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry walked slowly back up the grounds toward the castle through the crowd, many of whom shouted congratulations at him, but he felt a great sense of letdown; he had been sure that if Ron won the match, he and Hermione would be friends again im\-mediately. He did not see how he could possibly explain to Hermi\-one that what she had done to offend Ron was kiss Viktor Krum, not when the offense had occurred so long ago.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could not see Hermione at the Gryffindor celebration party, which was in full swing when he arrived. Renewed cheers and clapping greeted his appearance, and he was soon surrounded by a mob of people congratulating him. What with trying to shake off the Creevey brothers, who wanted a blow-by-blow match analysis, and the large group of girls that encircled him, laughing at his least amusing comments and batting their eyelids, it was some time before he could try and find Ron. At last, he extricated him\-self from Romilda Vane, who was hinting heavily that she would like to go to Slughorn\rquote s Christmas party with him. As he was duck\-ing toward the drinks table, he walked straight into Ginny, Arnold the Pygmy Puff riding on her shoulder and Crookshanks mewing hopefully at her heels.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Looking for Ron?\rdblquote  she asked, smirking. \ldblquote He\rquote s over there, the filthy hypocrite.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked into the corner she was indicating. There, in full view of the whole room, stood Ron wrapped so closely around Lavender Brown it was hard to tell whose hands were whose.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It looks like he\rquote s eating her face, doesn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Ginny dispas\-sionately. \ldblquote But I suppose he\rquote s got to refine his technique somehow. Good game, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She patted him on the arm; Harry felt a swooping sensation in his stomach, but then she walked off to help herself to more butterbeer. Crookshanks trotted after her, his yellow eyes fixed upon Arnold.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned away from Ron, who did not look like he would be surfacing soon, just as the portrait hole was closing. With a sink\-ing feeling, he thought he saw a mane of bushy brown hair whip\-ping out of sight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He darted forward, sidestepped Romilda Vane again, and pushed open the portrait of the Fat Lady. The corridor outside seemed to be deserted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He found her in the first unlocked classroom he tried. She was sitting on the teacher\rquote s desk, alone except for a small ring of twit\-tering yellow birds circling her head, which she had clearly just conjured out of midair. Harry could not help admiring her spell-work at a time like this.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, hello, Harry,\rdblquote  she said in a brittle voice. \ldblquote I was just prac\-ticing.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 they\rquote re \emdash  er \emdash  really good. \'85\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had no idea what to say to her. He was just wondering whether there was any chance that she had not noticed Ron, that she had merely left the room because the party was a little too rowdy, when she said, in an unnaturally high-pitched voice, \ldblquote Ron seems to be enjoying the celebrations.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \'85 does he?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t pretend you didn\rquote t see him,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote He wasn\rquote t exactly hiding it, was \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door behind them burst open. To Harry\rquote s horror, Ron came in, laughing, pulling Lavender by the hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  he said, drawing up short at the sight of Harry and Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oops!\rdblquote  said Lavender, and she backed out of the room, gig\-gling. The door swung shut behind her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a horrible, swelling, billowing silence. Hermione was staring at Ron, who refused to look at her, but said with an odd mixture of bravado and awkwardness, \ldblquote Hi, Harry! Wondered where you\rquote d got to!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione slid off the desk. The little flock of golden birds con\-tinued to twitter in circles around her head so that she looked like a strange, feathery model of the solar system.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You shouldn\rquote t leave Lavender waiting outside,\rdblquote  she said quietly. \ldblquote She\rquote ll wonder where you\rquote ve gone.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She walked very slowly and erectly toward the door. Harry glanced at Ron, who was looking relieved that nothing worse had happened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Oppugno\i0 !\rdblquote  came a shriek from the doorway.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry spun around to see Hermione pointing her wand at Ron, her expression wild: The little flock of birds was speeding like a hail of fat golden bullets toward Ron, who yelped and covered his face with his hands, but the birds attacked, pecking and clawing at every bit of flesh they could reach.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gerremoffme!\rdblquote  he yelled, but with one last look of vindictive fury, Hermione wrenched open the door and disappeared through it. Harry thought he heard a sob before it slammed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
