\lang1033\ldblquote Look,\rdblquote  sighed Hermione, \ldblquote Secrecy Sensors detect jinxes, curses, and concealment charms, don\rquote t they? They\rquote re used to find Dark Magic and Dark objects. They\rquote d have picked up a powerful curse, like the one on that necklace, within seconds. But something that\rquote s just been put in the wrong bottle wouldn\rquote t register \emdash  and anyway, love potions aren\rquote t Dark or dangerous \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Easy for you to say,\rdblquote  muttered Harry, thinking of Romilda Vane.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  so it would be down to Filch to realize it wasn\rquote t a cough po\-tion, and he\rquote s not a very good wizard, I doubt he can tell one po\-tion from \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione stopped dead; Harry had heard it too. Somebody had moved close behind them among the dark bookshelves. They waited, and a moment later the vulturelike countenance of Madam Pince appeared around the corner, her sunken cheeks, her skin like parchment, and her long hooked nose illuminated unflatteringly by the lamp she was carrying.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The library is now closed,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Mind you return any\-thing you have borrowed to the correct \emdash  \i what have you been do\-ing to that book, you depraved boy\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It isn\rquote t the library\rquote s, it\rquote s mine!\rdblquote  said Harry hastily, snatching his copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making\i0  off the table as she lunged at it with a clawlike hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Despoiled!\rdblquote  she hissed. \ldblquote Desecrated! Befouled!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s just a book that\rquote s been written on!\rdblquote  said Harry, tugging it out of her grip.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked as though she might have a seizure; Hermione, who had hastily packed her things, grabbed Harry by the arm and frog\-marched him away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She\rquote ll ban you from the library if you\rquote re not careful. Why did you have to bring that stupid book?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not my fault she\rquote s barking mad, Hermione. Or d\rquote you think she overheard you being rude about Filch? I\rquote ve always thought there might be something going on between them. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, ha ha \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Enjoying the fact that they could speak normally again, they made their way along the deserted, lamp-lit corridors back to the common room, arguing about whether or not Filch and Madam Pince were secretly in love with each other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Baubles,\rdblquote  said Harry to the Fat Lady, this being the new, festive password.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Same to you,\rdblquote  said the Fat Lady with a roguish grin, and she swung forward to admit them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi, Harry!\rdblquote  said Romilda Vane, the moment he had climbed through the portrait hole. \ldblquote Fancy a gillywater?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione gave him a \ldblquote what-did-I-tell-you?\rdblquote  look over her shoulder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote I don\rquote t like it much.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, take these anyway,\rdblquote  said Romilda, thrusting a box into his hands. \ldblquote Chocolate Cauldrons, they\rquote ve got firewhisky in them. My gran sent them to me, but I don\rquote t like them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \emdash  right \emdash  thanks a lot,\rdblquote  said Harry, who could not think what else to say. \ldblquote Er \emdash  I\rquote m just going over here with \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He hurried off behind Hermione, his voice tailing away feebly.\lang3081\par
