\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, \i Percy\i0 !\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, and she threw herself into his arms.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Rufus Scrimgeour paused in the doorway, leaning on his walk\-ing stick and smiling as he observed this affecting scene.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You must forgive this intrusion,\rdblquote  he said, when Mrs. Weasley looked around at him, beaming and wiping her eyes. \ldblquote Percy and I were in the vicinity \emdash  working, you know \emdash  and he couldn\rquote t re\-sist dropping in and seeing you all.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Percy showed no sign of wanting to greet any of the rest of the family. He stood, poker-straight and awkward-looking, and stared over everybody else\rquote s heads. Mr. Weasley, Fred, and George were all observing him, stony-faced.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please, come in, sit down, Minister!\rdblquote  fluttered Mrs. Weasley, straightening her hat. \ldblquote Have a little purkey, or some tooding. \'85 I mean \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, my dear Molly,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour. Harry guessed that he had checked her name with Percy before they entered the house. \ldblquote I don\rquote t want to intrude, wouldn\rquote t be here at all if Percy hadn\rquote t wanted to see you all so badly. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, Perce!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley tearfully, reaching up to kiss him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 We\rquote ve only looked in for five minutes, so I\rquote ll have a stroll around the yard while you catch up with Percy. No, no, I assure you I don\rquote t want to butt in! Well, if anybody cared to show me your charming garden \'85 Ah, that young man\rquote s finished, why doesn\rquote t he take a stroll with me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The atmosphere around the table changed perceptibly. Every\-body looked from Scrimgeour to Harry. Nobody seemed to find Scrimgeour s pretense that he did not know Harry\rquote s name convinc\-ing, or find it natural that he should be chosen to accompany the Minister around the garden when Ginny, Fleur, and George also had clean plates.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, all right,\rdblquote  said Harry into the silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was not fooled; for all Scrimgeour\rquote s talk that they had just been in the area, that Percy wanted to look up his family, this must be the real reason that they had come, so that Scrimgeour could speak to Harry alone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s fine,\rdblquote  he said quietly, as he passed Lupin, who had half risen from his chair. \ldblquote Fine,\rdblquote  he added, as Mr. Weasley opened his mouth to speak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wonderful!\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, standing back to let Harry pass\lang3081  \lang1033 through the door ahead of him. \ldblquote We\rquote ll just take a turn around the garden, and Percy and I\rquote ll be off. Carry on, everyone!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry walked across the yard toward the Weasleys\rquote  overgrown, snow-covered garden, Scrimgeour limping slightly at his side. He had, Harry knew, been Head of the Auror office; he looked tough and battle-scarred, very different from portly Fudge in his bowler hat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Charming,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, stopping at the garden fence and looking out over the snowy lawn and the indistinguishable plants. \ldblquote Charming.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry said nothing. He could tell that Scrimgeour was watching him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve wanted to meet you for a very long time,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, after a few moments. \ldblquote Did you know that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry truthfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes, for a very long time. But Dumbledore has been very protective of you,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour. \ldblquote Natural, of course, natural, after what you\rquote ve been through. \'85 Especially what happened at the Ministry \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He waited for Harry to say something, but Harry did not oblige, so he went on, \ldblquote I have been hoping for an occasion to talk to you ever since I gained office, but Dumbledore has \emdash  most under\-standably, as I say \emdash  prevented this.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Still, Harry said nothing, waiting.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The rumors that have flown around!\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour. \ldblquote Well, of course, we both know how these stories get distorted \'85 all these whispers of a prophecy \'85 of you being \lquote the Chosen One\rquote\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were getting near it now, Harry thought, the reason Scrim\-geour was here.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 I assume that Dumbledore has discussed these matters with you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry deliberated, wondering whether he ought to lie or not. He looked at the little gnome prints all around the flowerbeds, and the scuffed-up patch that marked the spot where Fred had caught the gnome now wearing the tutu at the top of the Christmas tree. Finally, he decided on the truth \'85 or a bit of it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, we\rquote ve discussed it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Have you, have you \'85\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour. Harry could see, out of the corner of his eye, Scrimgeour squinting at him, so he pre\-tended to be very interested in a gnome that had just poked its head out from underneath a frozen rhododendron. \ldblquote And what has Dumbledore told you, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry, but that\rquote s between us,\rdblquote  said Harry. He kept his voice as pleasant as he could, and Scrimgeour\rquote s tone, too, was light and friendly as he said, \ldblquote Oh, of course, if it\rquote s a question of confidences, I wouldn\rquote t want you to divulge \'85 no, no \'85 and in any case, does it really matter whether you are \lquote the Chosen One\rquote  or not?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had to mull that one over for a few seconds before re\-sponding. \ldblquote I don\rquote t really know what you mean, Minister.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, of course, to \i you\i0  it will matter enormously,\rdblquote  said Scrim\-geour with a laugh. \ldblquote But to the Wizarding community at large \'85 it\rquote s all perception, isn\rquote t it? It\rquote s what people believe that\rquote s important.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry said nothing. He thought he saw, dimly, where they were heading, but he was not going to help Scrimgeour get there. The gnome under the rhododendron was now digging for worms at its roots, and Harry kept his eyes fixed upon it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote People believe you \i are\i0  \lquote the Chosen One,\rquote  you see,\rdblquote  said Scrim\-geour. \ldblquote They think you quite the hero \emdash  which, of course, you\lang3081  \lang1033 are, Harry, chosen or not! How many times have you faced He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named now? Well, anyway,\rdblquote  he pressed on, without waiting for a reply, \ldblquote the point is, you are a symbol of hope for many, Harry. The idea that there is somebody out there who might be able, who might even be \i destined,\i0  to destroy He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named \emdash  well, naturally, it gives people a lift. And I can\rquote t help but feel that, once you realize this, you might consider it, well, almost a duty, to stand alongside the Ministry, and give everyone a boost.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The gnome had just managed to get hold of a worm. It was now tugging very hard on it, trying to get it out of the frozen ground. Harry was silent so long that Scrimgeour said, looking from Harry to the gnome, \ldblquote Funny little chaps, aren\rquote t they? But what say you, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t exactly understand what you want,\rdblquote  said Harry slowly. \ldblquote  \lquote Stand alongside the Ministry\rquote  \'85 What does that mean?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, well, nothing at all onerous, I assure you,\rdblquote  said Scrim\-geour. \ldblquote If you were to be seen popping in and out of the Ministry from time to time, for instance, that would give the right impres\-sion. And of course, while you were there, you would have ample opportunity to speak to Gawain Robards, my successor as Head of the Auror office. Dolores Umbridge has told me that you cherish an ambition to become an Auror. Well, that could be arranged very easily. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt anger bubbling in the pit of his stomach: So Dolores Umbridge was still at the Ministry, was she?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So basically,\rdblquote  he said, as though he just wanted to clarify a few points, \ldblquote you\rquote d like to give the impression that I\rquote m working for the Ministry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It would give everyone a lift to think you were more involved, Harry,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, sounding relieved that Harry had cot\-toned on so quickly. \ldblquote  \lquote The Chosen One,\rquote  you know\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 It\rquote s all about giving people hope, the feeling that exciting things are hap\-pening. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But if I keep running in and out of the Ministry,\rdblquote  said Harry, still endeavoring to keep his voice friendly, \ldblquote won\rquote t that seem as though I approve of what the Ministry\rquote s up to?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, frowning slightly, \ldblquote well, yes, that\rquote s partly why we\rquote d like \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I don\rquote t think that\rquote ll work,\rdblquote  said Harry pleasantly. \ldblquote You see, I don\rquote t like some of the things the Ministry\rquote s doing. Locking up Stan Shunpike, for instance.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour did not speak for a moment but his expression hard\-ened instantly. \ldblquote I would not expect you to understand,\rdblquote  he said, and he was not as successful at keeping anger out of his voice as Harry had been. \ldblquote These are dangerous times, and certain measures need to be taken. You are sixteen years old \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore\rquote s a lot older than sixteen, and he doesn\rquote t think Stan should be in Azkaban either,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote You\rquote re making Stan a scapegoat, just like you want to make me a mascot.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They looked at each other, long and hard. Finally Scrimgeour said, with no pretense at warmth, \ldblquote I see. You prefer \emdash  like your hero, Dumbledore \emdash  to disassociate yourself from the Ministry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t want to be used,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Some would say it\rquote s your duty to be used by the Ministry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, and others might say it\rquote s your duty to check that people really are Death Eaters before you chuck them in prison,\rdblquote  said Harry, his temper rising now. \ldblquote You\rquote re doing what Barty Crouch\lang3081  \lang1033 did. You never get it right, you people, do you? Either we\rquote ve got Fudge, pretending everything\rquote s lovely while people get murdered right under his nose, or we\rquote ve got you, chucking the wrong people into jail and trying to pretend you\rquote ve got \lquote the Chosen One\rquote  work\-ing for you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you\rquote re not \lquote the Chosen One\rquote ?\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought you said it didn\rquote t matter either way?\rdblquote  said Harry, with a bitter laugh. \ldblquote Not to you anyway.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I shouldn\rquote t have said that,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour quickly. \ldblquote It was tactless \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, it was honest,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote One of the only honest things you\rquote ve said to me. You don\rquote t care whether I live or die, but you do care that I help you convince everyone you\rquote re winning the war against Voldemort. I haven\rquote t forgotten, Minister. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He raised his right fist. There, shining white on the back of his cold hand, were the scars which Dolores Umbridge had forced him to carve into his own flesh: \i I must not tell lies.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t remember you rushing to my defense when I was trying to tell everyone Voldemort was back. The Ministry wasn\rquote t so keen to be pals last year.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They stood in silence as icy as the ground beneath their feet. The gnome had finally managed to extricate his worm and was now sucking on it happily, leaning against the bottommost branches of the rhododendron bush.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What is Dumbledore up to?\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour brusquely. \ldblquote Where does he go when he is absent from Hogwarts?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No idea,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you wouldn\rquote t tell me if you knew,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, \ldblquote would you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I wouldn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, then, I shall have to see whether I can\rquote t find out by other means.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You can try,\rdblquote  said Harry indifferently. \ldblquote But you seem cleverer than Fudge, so I\rquote d have thought you\rquote d have learned from his mis\-takes. He tried interfering at Hogwarts. You might have noticed he\rquote s not Minister anymore, but Dumbledore\rquote s still headmaster. I\rquote d leave Dumbledore alone, if I were you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a long pause.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, it is clear to me that he has done a very good job on you,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, his eyes cold and hard behind his wire-rimmed glasses. \ldblquote Dumbledore\rquote s man through and through, aren\rquote t you, Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I am,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Glad we straightened that out.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And turning his back on the Minister of Magic, he strode back toward the house.\lang3081\par
