Late in the afternoon, a few days after New Year, Harry, Ron, and Ginny lined up beside the kitchen fire to return to Hog\-warts. The Ministry had arranged this one-off connection to the Floo Network to return students quickly and safely to the school. Only Mrs. Weasley was there to say good-bye, as Mr. Weasley, Fred, George, Bill, and Fleur were all at work. Mrs. Weasley dis\-solved into tears at the moment of parting. Admittedly, it took very little to set her off lately; she had been crying on and off ever since Percy had stormed from the house on Christmas Day with his glasses splattered with mashed parsnip (for which Fred, George, and Ginny all claimed credit).\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t cry, Mum,\rdblquote  said Ginny, patting her on the back as Mrs. Weasley sobbed into her shoulder. \ldblquote It\rquote s okay. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, don\rquote t worry about us,\rdblquote  said Ron, permitting his mother to plant a very wet kiss on his cheek, \ldblquote or about Percy. He\rquote s such a prat, it\rquote s not really a loss, is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley sobbed harder than ever as she enfolded Harry in her arms.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Promise me you\rquote ll look after yourself. \'85 Stay out of trou\-ble. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I always do, Mrs. Weasley,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I like a quiet life, you know me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She gave a watery chuckle and stood back. \ldblquote Be good, then, all of you. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stepped into the emerald fire and shouted \ldblquote Hogwarts!\rdblquote  He had one last fleeting view of the Weasleys\rquote  kitchen and Mrs. Weasley\rquote s tearful face before the flames engulfed him; spinning very fast, he caught blurred glimpses of other Wizarding rooms, which were whipped out of sight before he could get a proper look; then he was slowing down, finally stopping squarely in the fireplace in Professor McGonagall\rquote s office. She barely glanced up from her work as he clambered out over the grate.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Evening, Potter. Try not to get too much ash on the carpet.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, Professor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry straightened his glasses and flattened his hair as Ron came spinning into view. When Ginny had arrived, all three of them trooped out of McGonagall\rquote s office and off toward Gryffindor Tower. Harry glanced out of the corridor windows as they passed; the sun was already sinking over grounds carpeted in deeper snow than had lain over the Burrow garden. In the distance, he could see Hagrid feeding Buckbeak in front of his cabin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Baubles,\rdblquote  said Ron confidently, when they reached the Fat Lady, who was looking rather paler than usual and winced at his loud voice.\lang3081\par
