\lang1033 Dumbledore listened to Harry\rquote s story with an impassive face. When Harry had finished he did not speak for a few moments, then said, \ldblquote Thank you for telling me this, Harry, but I suggest that you put it out of your mind. I do not think that it is of great importance.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not of great importance?\rdblquote  repeated Harry incredulously. \ldblquote Pro\-fessor, did you understand \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Harry, blessed as I am with extraordinary brainpower, I\lang3081  \lang1033 understood everything you told me,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, a little sharply. \ldblquote I think you might even consider the possibility that I un\-derstood more than you did. Again, I am glad that you have con\-fided in me, but let me reassure you that you have not told me anything that causes me disquiet.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sat in seething silence, glaring at Dumbledore. What was going on? Did this mean that Dumbledore had indeed ordered Snape to find out what Malfoy was doing, in which case he had already heard everything Harry had just told him from Snape? Or was he really worried by what he had heard, but pretending not to be?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, sir,\rdblquote  said Harry, in what he hoped was a polite, calm voice, \ldblquote you definitely still trust \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have been tolerant enough to answer that question already,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, but he did not sound very tolerant anymore. \ldblquote My answer has not changed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I should think not,\rdblquote  said a snide voice; Phineas Nigellus was ev\-idently only pretending to be asleep. Dumbledore ignored him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And now, Harry, I must insist that we press on. I have more im\-portant things to discuss with you this evening.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sat there feeling mutinous. How would it be if he refused to permit the change of subject, if he insisted upon arguing the case against Malfoy? As though he had read Harry\rquote s mind, Dumbledore shook his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, Harry, how often this happens, even between the best of friends! Each of us believes that what he has to say is much more important than anything the other might have to contribute!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think what you\rquote ve got to say is unimportant, sir,\rdblquote  said Harry stiffly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you are quite right, because it is not,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore briskly. \ldblquote I have two more memories to show you this evening, both obtained with enormous difficulty, and the second of them is, I think, the most important I have collected.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not say anything to this; he still felt angry at the re\-ception his confidences had received, but could not see what was to be gained by arguing further.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, in a ringing voice, \ldblquote we meet this eve\-ning to continue the tale of Tom Riddle, whom we left last lesson poised on the threshold of his years at Hogwarts. You will remem\-ber how excited he was to hear that he was a wizard, that he refused my company on a trip to Diagon Alley, and that I, in turn, warned him against continued thievery when he arrived at school.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, the start of the school year arrived and with it came Tom Riddle, a quiet boy in his secondhand robes, who lined up with the other first years to be sorted. He was placed in Slytherin House al\-most the moment that the Sorting Hat touched his head,\rdblquote  contin\-ued Dumbledore, waving his blackened hand toward the shelf over his head where the Sorting Hat sat, ancient and unmoving. \ldblquote How soon Riddle learned that the famous founder of the House could talk to snakes, I do not know \emdash  perhaps that very evening. The knowledge can only have excited him and increased his sense of self-importance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote However, if he was frightening or impressing fellow Slytherins with displays of Parseltongue in their common room, no hint of it reached the staff. He showed no sign of outward arrogance or ag\-gression at all. As an unusually talented and very good-looking or\-phan, he naturally drew attention and sympathy from the staff almost from the moment of his arrival. He seemed polite, quiet,\lang3081  \lang1033 and thirsty for knowledge. Nearly all were most favorably im\-pressed by him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Didn\rquote t you tell them, sir, what he\rquote d been like when you met him at the orphanage?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I did not. Though he had shown no hint of remorse, it was possible that he felt sorry for how he had behaved before and was resolved to turn over a fresh leaf. I chose to give him that chance.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore paused and looked inquiringly at Harry, who had opened his mouth to speak. Here, again, was Dumbledore\rquote s ten\-dency to trust people in spite of overwhelming evidence that they did not deserve it! But then Harry remembered something. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But you didn\rquote t \i really\i0  trust him, sir, did you? He told me \'85 the Riddle who came out of that diary said, \lquote Dumbledore never seemed to like me as much as the other teachers did.\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let us say that I did not take it for granted that he was trust\-worthy,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I had, as I have already indicated, re\-solved to keep a close eye upon him, and so I did. I cannot pretend that I gleaned a great deal from my observations at first. He was very guarded with me; he felt, I am sure, that in the thrill of dis\-covering his true identity he had told me a little too much. He was careful never to reveal as much again, but he could not take back what he had let slip in his excitement, nor what Mrs. Cole had con\-fided in me. However, he had the sense never to try and charm me as he charmed so many of my colleagues.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As he moved up the school, he gathered about him a group of dedicated friends; I call them that, for want of a better term, although as I have already indicated, Riddle undoubtedly felt no affection for any of them. This group had a kind of dark glamour within the castle. They were a motley collection; a mixture of the\lang3081  \lang1033 weak seeking protection, the ambitious seeking some shared glory, and the thuggish gravitating toward a leader who could show them more refined forms of cruelty. In other words, they were the fore\-runners of the Death Eaters, and indeed some of them became the first Death Eaters after leaving Hogwarts.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Rigidly controlled by Riddle, they were never detected in open wrongdoing, although their seven years at Hogwarts were marked by a number of nasty incidents to which they were never satisfac\-torily linked, the most serious of which was, of course, the opening of the Chamber of Secrets, which resulted in the death of a girl. As you know, Hagrid was wrongly accused of that crime.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have not been able to find many memories of Riddle at Hog\-warts,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, placing his withered hand on the Pen\-sieve. \ldblquote Few who knew him then are prepared to talk about him; they are too terrified. What I know, I found out after he had left Hogwarts, after much painstaking effort, after tracing those few who could be tricked into speaking, after searching old records and questioning Muggle and wizard witnesses alike.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Those whom I could persuade to talk told me that Riddle was obsessed with his parentage. This is understandable, of course; he had grown up in an orphanage and naturally wished to know how he came to be there. It seems that he searched in vain for some trace of Tom Riddle senior on the shields in the trophy room, on the lists of prefects in the old school records, even in the books of Wiz\-arding history. Finally he was forced to accept that his father had never set foot in Hogwarts. I believe that it was then that he dropped the name forever, assumed the identity of Lord Volde\-mort, and began his investigations into his previously despised\lang3081  \lang1033 mother\rquote s family \emdash  the woman whom, you will remember, he had thought could not be a witch if she had succumbed to the shame\-ful human weakness of death.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All he had to go upon was the single name \lquote Marvolo,\rquote  which he knew from those who ran the orphanage had been his mother\rquote s fa\-ther\rquote s name. Finally, after painstaking research through old books of Wizarding families, he discovered the existence of Slytherin\rquote s surviving line. In the summer of his sixteenth year, he left the or\-phanage to which he returned annually and set off to find his Gaunt relatives. And now, Harry, if you will stand \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore rose, and Harry saw that he was again holding a small crystal bottle filled with swirling, pearly memory.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was very lucky to collect this,\rdblquote  he said, as he poured the gleaming mass into the Pensieve. \ldblquote As you will understand when we have experienced it. Shall we?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stepped up to the stone basin and bowed obediently until his face sank through the surface of the memory; he felt the famil\-iar sensation of falling through nothingness and then landed upon a dirty stone floor in almost total darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It took him several seconds to recognize the place, by which time Dumbledore had landed beside him. The Gaunts\rquote  house was now more indescribably filthy than anywhere Harry had ever seen. The ceiling was thick with cobwebs, the floor coated in grime; moldy and rotting food lay upon the table amidst a mass of crusted pots. The only light came from a single guttering candle placed at the feet of a man with hair and beard so overgrown Harry could see neither eyes nor mouth. He was slumped in an armchair by the fire, and Harry wondered for a moment whether he was dead. But\lang3081  \lang1033 then there came a loud knock on the door and the man jerked awake, raising a wand in his right hand and a short knife in his left.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door creaked open. There on the threshold, holding an old-fashioned lamp, stood a boy Harry recognized at once: tall, pale, dark-haired, and handsome \emdash  the teenage Voldemort.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Voldemort\rquote s eyes moved slowly around the hovel and then found the man in the armchair. For a few seconds they looked at each other, then the man staggered upright, the many empty bottles at his feet clattering and tinkling across the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote YOU!\rdblquote  he bellowed. \ldblquote YOU!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he hurtled drunkenly at Riddle, wand and knife held aloft.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Stop.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle spoke in Parseltongue. The man skidded into the table, sending moldy pots crashing to the floor. He stared at Riddle. There was a long silence while they contemplated each other. The man broke it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i You speak it\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Yes, I speak it,\i0\rdblquote  said Riddle. He moved forward into the room, allowing the door to swing shut behind him. Harry could not help but feel a resentful admiration for Voldemort\rquote s complete lack of fear. His face merely expressed disgust and, perhaps, disappoint\-ment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Where is Marvolo\i0 ?\rdblquote  he asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Dead,\i0\rdblquote  said the other. \ldblquote\i Died\lang3081  \lang1033 years ago, didn\rquote t he\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle frowned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Who are you, then\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i I\rquote m Morfin, ain\rquote t I\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Marvolo\rquote s son\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote\i Course I am, then\i0  \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Morfin pushed the hair out of his dirty face, the better to see Riddle, and Harry saw that he wore Marvolo\rquote s black-stoned ring on his right hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i I thought you was that Muggle,\i0\rdblquote  whispered Morfin. \ldblquote\i You look mighty like that Muggle.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i What Muggle\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Riddle sharply.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i That Muggle what my sister took a fancy to, that Muggle what lives in the big house over the way,\i0\rdblquote  said Morfin, and he spat unexpectedly upon the floor between them. \ldblquote\i You look right like him. Riddle. But he\rquote s older now, in \rquote e? He\rquote s older\rquote n you, now I think on it. \'85\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Morfin looked slightly dazed and swayed a little, still clutching the edge of the table for support. \ldblquote\i He come back, see,\i0\rdblquote  he added stupidly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Voldemort was gazing at Morfin as though appraising his possi\-bilities. Now he moved a little closer and said, \ldblquote\i Riddle came back\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Ar, he left her, and serve her right, marrying filth\i0 !\rdblquote  said Morfin, spitting on the floor again. \ldblquote\i Robbed us, mind, before she ran off! Where\rquote s the locket, eh, where\rquote s Slytherin\rquote s locket\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Voldemort did not answer. Morfin was working himself into a rage again; he brandished his knife and shouted, \ldblquote\i Dishonored us, she did, that little slut! And who\rquote re you, coming here and asking ques\-tions about all that? It\rquote s over, innit. \'85 It\rquote s over. \'85\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked away, staggering slightly, and Voldemort moved for\-ward. As he did so, an unnatural darkness fell, extinguishing Volde\-mort\rquote s lamp and Morfin\rquote s candle, extinguishing everything. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore\rquote s fingers closed tightly around Harry\rquote s arm and\lang3081  \lang1033 they were soaring back into the present again. The soft golden light in Dumbledore\rquote s office seemed to dazzle Harry\rquote s eyes after that im\-penetrable darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is that all?\rdblquote  said Harry at once. \ldblquote Why did it go dark, what hap\-pened?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because Morfin could not remember anything from that point onward,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, gesturing Harry back into his seat. \ldblquote When he awoke next morning, he was lying on the floor, quite alone. Marvolo\rquote s ring had gone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Meanwhile, in the village of Little Hangleton, a maid was run\-ning along the High Street, screaming that there were three bodies lying in the drawing room of the big house: Tom Riddle Senior and his mother and father.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Muggle authorities were perplexed. As far as I am aware, they do not know to this day how the Riddles died, for the \i Avada Kedavra\i0  curse does not usually leave any sign of damage. \'85 The exception sits before me,\rdblquote  Dumbledore added, with a nod to Harry\rquote s scar. \ldblquote The Ministry, on the other hand, knew at once that this was a wizard\rquote s murder. They also knew that a convicted Muggle-hater lived across the valley from the Riddle house, a Muggle-hater who had already been imprisoned once for attacking one of the murdered people.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So the Ministry called upon Morfin. They did not need to question him, to use Veritaserum or Legilimency. He admitted to the murder on the spot, giving details only the murderer could know. He was proud, he said, to have killed the Muggles, had been awaiting his chance all these years. He handed over his wand, which was proved at once to have been used to kill the Riddles. And he permitted himself to be led off to Azkaban without a fight.\lang3081  \lang1033 All that disturbed him was the fact that his father\rquote s ring had disap\-peared. \lquote He\rquote ll kill me for losing it,\rquote  he told his captors over and over again. \lquote He\rquote ll kill me for losing his ring.\rquote  And that, apparently, was all he ever said again. He lived out the remainder of his life in Azka\-ban, lamenting the loss of Marvolo\rquote s last heirloom, and is buried beside the prison, alongside the other poor souls who have expired within its walls.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So Voldemort stole Morfin\rquote s wand and used it?\rdblquote  said Harry, sit\-ting up straight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote We have no memories to show us this, but I think we can be fairly sure what happened. Voldemort Stupefied his uncle, took his wand, and proceeded across the valley to \lquote the big house over the way\rquote  There he murdered the Muggle man who had abandoned his witch mother, and, for good measure, his Muggle grandparents, thus obliterating the last of the unworthy Riddle line and revenging himself upon the father who never wanted him. Then he returned to the Gaunt hovel, per\-formed the complex bit of magic that would implant a false mem\-ory in his uncle\rquote s mind, laid Morfin\rquote s wand beside its unconscious owner, pocketed the ancient ring he wore, and departed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And Morfin never realized he hadn\rquote t done it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Never,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote He gave, as I say, a full and boastful confession.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But he had this real memory in him all the time!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but it took a great deal of skilled Legilimency to coax it out of him,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote and why should anybody delve further into Morfin\rquote s mind when he had already confessed to the crime? However, I was able to secure a visit to Morfin in the last weeks of his life, by which time I was attempting to discover as much as I\lang3081  \lang1033 could about Voldemort\rquote s past. I extracted this memory with diffi\-culty. When I saw what it contained, I attempted to use it to secure Morfin\rquote s release from Azkaban. Before the Ministry reached their decision, however, Morfin had died.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But how come the Ministry didn\rquote t realize that Voldemort had done all that to Morfin?\rdblquote  Harry asked angrily. \ldblquote He was underage at the time, wasn\rquote t he? I thought they could detect underage magic!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are quite right \emdash  they can detect magic, but not the per\-petrator: You will remember that you were blamed by the Ministry for the Hover Charm that was, in fact, cast by \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dobby,\rdblquote  growled Harry; this injustice still rankled. \ldblquote So if you\rquote re underage and you do magic inside an adult witch or wizard\rquote s house, the Ministry won\rquote t know?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They will certainly be unable to tell who performed the magic,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, smiling slightly at the look of great indignation on Harry\rquote s face. \ldblquote They rely on witch and wizard parents to enforce their offspring\rquote s obedience while within their walls.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, that\rquote s rubbish,\rdblquote  snapped Harry. \ldblquote Look what happened here, look what happened to Morfin!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I agree,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Whatever Morfin was, he did not deserve to die as he did, blamed for murders he had not commit\-ted. But it is getting late, and I want you to see this other memory before we part. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore took from an inside pocket another crystal phial and Harry fell silent at once, remembering that Dumbledore had said it was the most important one he had collected. Harry noticed that the contents proved difficult to empty into the Pensieve, as though they had congealed slightly; did memories go bad?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This will not take long,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, when he had finally\lang3081  \lang1033 emptied the phial. \ldblquote We shall be back before you know it. Once more into the Pensieve, then \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And Harry fell again through the silver surface, landing this time right in front of a man he recognized at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was a much younger Horace Slughorn. Harry was so used to him bald that he found the sight of Slughorn with thick, shiny, straw-colored hair quite disconcerting; it looked as though he had had his head thatched, though there was already a shiny Galleon-sized bald patch on his crown. His mustache, less massive than it was these days, was gingery-blond. He was not quite as rotund as the Slughorn Harry knew, though the golden buttons on his richly embroidered waistcoat were taking a fair amount of strain. His lit\-tle feet resting upon a velvet pouffe, he was sitting well back in a comfortable winged armchair, one hand grasping a small glass of wine, the other searching through a box of crystalized pineapple.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around as Dumbledore appeared beside him and saw that they were standing in Slughorn\rquote s office. Half a dozen boys were sitting around Slughorn, all on harder or lower seats than his, and all in their mid-teens. Harry recognized Voldemort at once. His was the most handsome face and he looked the most relaxed of all the boys. His right hand lay negligently upon the arm of his chair; with a jolt, Harry saw that he was wearing Marvolo\rquote s gold-and-black ring; he had already killed his father.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir, is it true that Professor Merrythought is retiring?\rdblquote  he asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tom, Tom, if I knew I couldn\rquote t tell you,\rdblquote  said Slughorn, wag\-ging a reproving, sugar-covered finger at Riddle, though ruining the effect slightly by winking. \ldblquote I must say, I\rquote d like to know where you get your information, boy, more knowledgeable than half the staff, you are.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Riddle smiled; the other boys laughed and cast him admiring looks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What with your uncanny ability to know things you shouldn\rquote t, and your careful flattery of the people who matter \emdash  thank you for the pineapple, by the way, you\rquote re quite right, it is my favorite \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As several of the boys tittered, something very odd happened. The whole room was suddenly filled with a thick white fog, so that Harry could see nothing but the face of Dumbledore, who was standing beside him. Then Slughorn\rquote s voice rang out through the mist, unnaturally loudly, \ldblquote\i You\rquote ll\lang3081  \lang1033 go wrong, boy, mark my words.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The fog cleared as suddenly as it had appeared and yet nobody made any allusion to it, nor did anybody look as though anything unusual had just happened. Bewildered, Harry looked around as a small golden clock standing upon Slughorn\rquote s desk chimed eleven o\rquote clock.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good gracious, is it that time already?\rdblquote  said Slughorn. \ldblquote You\rquote d better get going, boys, or we\rquote ll all be in trouble. Lestrange, I want your essay by tomorrow or it\rquote s detention. Same goes for you, Avery.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn pulled himself out of his armchair and carried his empty glass over to his desk as the boys filed out. Voldemort, how\-ever, stayed behind. Harry could tell he had dawdled deliberately, wanting to be last in the room with Slughorn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look sharp, Tom,\rdblquote  said Slughorn, turning around and finding him still present. \ldblquote You don\rquote t want to be caught out of bed out of hours, and you a prefect\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir, I wanted to ask you something.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ask away, then, m\rquote boy, ask away. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir, I wondered what you know about\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 about Horcruxes?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And it happened all over again: The dense fog filled the room\lang3081  \lang1033 so that Harry could not see Slughorn or Voldemort at all; only Dumbledore, smiling serenely beside him. Then Slughorn\rquote s voice boomed out again, just as it had done before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i I don\rquote t know anything about Horcruxes and I wouldn\rquote t tell you if I did! Now get out of here at once and don\rquote t let me catch you mentioning them again\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, that\rquote s that,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore placidly beside Harry. \ldblquote Time to go.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And Harry\rquote s feet left the floor to fall, seconds later, back onto the rug in front of Dumbledore\rquote s desk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s all there is?\rdblquote  said Harry blankly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore had said that this was the most important memory of all, but he could not see what was so significant about it. Ad\-mittedly the fog, and the fact that nobody seemed to have noticed it, was odd, but other than that nothing seemed to have happened except that Voldemort had asked a question and failed to get an answer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As you might have noticed,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, reseating him\-self behind his desk, \ldblquote that memory has been tampered with.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tampered with?\rdblquote  repeated Harry, sitting back down too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Certainly,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Professor Slughorn has meddled with his own recollections.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But why would he do that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because, I think, he is ashamed of what he remembers,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote He has tried to rework the memory to show himself in a better light, obliterating those parts which he does not wish me to see. It is, as you will have noticed, very crudely done, and that is all to the good, for it shows that the true memory is still there be\-neath the alterations.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And so, for the first time, I am giving you homework, Harry. It will be your job to persuade Professor Slughorn to divulge the real memory, which will undoubtedly be our most crucial piece of in\-formation of all.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But surely, sir,\rdblquote  he said, keeping his voice as respectful as pos\-sible, \ldblquote you don\rquote t need me \emdash  you could use Legilimency\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 or Veritaserum. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Slughorn is an extremely able wizard who will be ex\-pecting both,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote He is much more accomplished at Occlumency than poor Morfin Gaunt, and I would be aston\-ished if he has not carried an antidote to Veritaserum with him ever since I coerced him into giving me this travesty of a recollection.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I think it would be foolish to attempt to wrest the truth from Professor Slughorn by force, and might do much more harm than good; I do not wish him to leave Hogwarts. However, he has his weaknesses like the rest of us, and I believe that you are the one person who might be able to penetrate his defenses. It is most im\-portant that we secure the true memory, Harry. \'85 How impor\-tant, we will only know when we have seen the real thing. So, good luck \'85 and good night.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A little taken aback by the abrupt dismissal, Harry got to his feet quickly. \ldblquote Good night, sir.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As he closed the study door behind him, he distinctly heard Phineas Nigellus say, \ldblquote I can\rquote t see why the boy should be able to do it better than you, Dumbledore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t expect you to, Phineas,\rdblquote  replied Dumbledore, and Fawkes gave another low, musical cry.\lang3081\par
