The next day Harry confided in both Ron and Hermione the task that Dumbledore had set him, though separately, for Hermione still refused to remain in Ron\rquote s presence longer than it took to give him a contemptuous look.\par
Ron thought that Harry was unlikely to have any trouble with Slughorn at all.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He loves you,\rdblquote  he said over breakfast, waving an airy forkful of fried egg. \ldblquote Won\rquote t refuse you anything, will he? Not his little Potions Prince. Just hang back after class this afternoon and ask him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione, however, took a gloomier view. \ldblquote He must be deter\-mined to hide what really happened if Dumbledore couldn\rquote t get it out of him,\rdblquote  she said in a low voice, as they stood in the deserted, snowy courtyard at break. \ldblquote Horcruxes \'85 \i Horcruxes\i0  \'85 I\rquote ve never even heard of them. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You haven\rquote t?\rdblquote  Harry was disappointed; he had hoped that\lang3081  \lang1033 Hermione might have been able to give him a clue as to what Hor\-cruxes were.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They must be really advanced Dark Magic, or why would Voldemort have wanted to know about them? I think it\rquote s going to be difficult to get the information, Harry, you\rquote ll have to be very careful about how you approach Slughorn, think out a strat\-egy. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron reckons I should just hang back after Potions this after\-noon. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, well, if \i Won-Won\i0  thinks that, you\rquote d better do it,\rdblquote  she said, flaring up at once. \ldblquote After all, when has \i Won-Won\rquote s\i0  judgment ever been faulty?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione, can\rquote t you \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i No\i0 !\rdblquote  she said angrily, and stormed away, leaving Harry alone and ankle-deep in snow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Potions lessons were uncomfortable enough these days, seeing as Harry, Ron, and Hermione had to share a desk. Today, Hermione moved her cauldron around the table so that she was close to Ernie, and ignored both Harry and Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote ve\lang3081  \lang1033\i you\i0  done?\rdblquote  Ron muttered to Harry, looking at Hermi\-one\rquote s haughty profile.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But before Harry could answer, Slughorn was calling for silence from the front of the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Settle down, settle down, please! Quickly, now, lots of work to get through this afternoon! Golpalott\rquote s Third Law \'85 who can tell me \emdash  ? But Miss Granger can, of course!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione recited at top speed: \ldblquote Golpalott\rquote s-Third-Law-states-that-the-antidote-for-a-blended-poison-will-be-equal-to-more-than-the-sum-of-the-antidotes-for-each-of-the-separate-components.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Precisely!\rdblquote  beamed Slughorn. \ldblquote Ten points for Gryffindor! Now, if we accept Golpalott\rquote s Third Law as true \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was going to have to take Slughorn\rquote s word for it that Gol\-palott\rquote s Third Law was true, because he had not understood any of it. Nobody apart from Hermione seemed to be following what Slughorn said next either.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 which means, of course, that assuming we have achieved correct identification of the potion\rquote s ingredients by Scarpin\rquote s Revel\-aspell, our primary aim is not the relatively simple one of selecting antidotes to those ingredients in and of themselves, but to find that added component that will, by an almost alchemical process, trans\-form these disparate elements \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron was sitting beside Harry with his mouth half open, doo\-dling absently on his new copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making.\i0  Ron kept forgetting that he could no longer rely on Hermione to help him out of trouble when he failed to grasp what was going on.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 and so,\rdblquote  finished Slughorn, \ldblquote I want each of you to come and take one of these phials from my desk. You are to create an an\-tidote for the poison within it before the end of the lesson. Good luck, and don\rquote t forget your protective gloves!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione had left her stool and was halfway toward Slughorn\rquote s desk before the rest of the class had realized it was time to move, and by the time Harry, Ron, and Ernie returned to the table, she had already tipped the contents of her phial into her cauldron and was kindling a fire underneath it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s a shame that the Prince won\rquote t be able to help you much with this, Harry,\rdblquote  she said brightly as she straightened up. \ldblquote You have to understand the principles involved this time. No shortcuts or cheats!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Annoyed, Harry uncorked the poison he had taken from Slug\-horn\rquote s desk, which was a garish shade of pink, tipped it into his cauldron, and lit a fire underneath it. He did not have the faintest idea what he was supposed to do next. He glanced around at Ron, who was now standing there looking rather gormless, having copied everything Harry had done.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You sure the Prince hasn\rquote t got any tips?\rdblquote  Ron muttered to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry pulled out his trusty copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making\i0  and turned to the chapter on antidotes. There was Golpalott\rquote s Third Law, stated word for word as Hermione had recited it, but not a single illuminating note in the Prince\rquote s hand to explain what it meant. Apparently the Prince, like Hermione, had had no diffi\-culty understanding it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  said Harry gloomily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione was now waving her wand enthusiastically over her cauldron. Unfortunately, they could not copy the spell she was do\-ing because she was now so good at nonverbal incantations that she did not need to say the words aloud. Ernie Macmillan, however, was muttering, \ldblquote\i Specialis Revelio\i0 !\rdblquote  over his cauldron, which sounded impressive, so Harry and Ron hastened to imitate him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It took Harry only five minutes to realize that his reputation as the best potion-maker in the class was crashing around his ears. Slughorn had peered hopefully into his cauldron on his first circuit of the dungeon, preparing to exclaim in delight as he usually did, and instead had withdrawn his head hastily, coughing, as the smell of bad eggs overwhelmed him. Hermione\rquote s expression could not have been any smugger; she had loathed being outperformed in every Potions class. She was now decanting the mysteriously sepa\-rated ingredients of her poison into ten different crystal phials. More to avoid watching this irritating sight than anything else, Harry bent over the Half-Blood Prince\rquote s book and turned a few pages with unnecessary force.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And there it was, scrawled right across a long list of antidotes:\par
\lang3081\par
\pard\qc\lang1033\i Just\lang3081  shove a bezoar down their throats\lang1033 .\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\i0\par
Harry stared at these words for a moment. Hadn\rquote t he once, long ago, heard of bezoars? Hadn\rquote t Snape mentioned them in their first-ever Potions lesson? \ldblquote\i A stone taken from the stomach of a goat, which will protect from most poisons.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was not an answer to the Golpalott problem, and had Snape still been their teacher, Harry would not have dared do it, but this was a moment for desperate measures. He hastened toward the store cupboard and rummaged within it, pushing aside unicorn horns and tangles of dried herbs until he found, at the very back, a small cardboard box on which had been scribbled the word\lang3081  \lang1033 bezoars.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He opened the box just as Slughorn called, \ldblquote Two minutes left, everyone!\rdblquote  Inside were half a dozen shriveled brown objects, look\-ing more like dried-up kidneys than real stones. Harry seized one, put the box back in the cupboard, and hurried back to his cauldron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Time\rquote s \'85 UP!\rdblquote  called Slughorn genially. \ldblquote Well, let\rquote s see how you\rquote ve done! Blaise \'85 what have you got for me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slowly, Slughorn moved around the room, examining the vari\-ous antidotes. Nobody had finished the task, although Hermione was trying to cram a few more ingredients into her bottle before\lang3081  \lang1033 Slughorn reached her. Ron had given up completely, and was merely trying to avoid breathing in the putrid fumes issuing from his cauldron. Harry stood there waiting, the bezoar clutched in a slightly sweaty hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn reached their table last. He sniffed Ernie\rquote s potion and passed on to Ron\rquote s with a grimace. He did not linger over Ron\rquote s cauldron, but backed away swiftly, retching slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you, Harry,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote What have you got to show me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry held out his hand, the bezoar sitting on his palm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn looked down at it for a full ten seconds. Harry won\-dered, for a moment, whether he was going to shout at him. Then he threw back his head and roared with laughter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ve got nerve, boy!\rdblquote  he boomed, taking the bezoar and hold\-ing it up so that the class could see it. \ldblquote Oh, you\rquote re like your mother. \'85 Well, I can\rquote t fault you. \'85 A bezoar would certainly act as an antidote to all these potions!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione, who was sweaty-faced and had soot on her nose, looked livid. Her half-finished antidote, comprising fifty-two in\-gredients, including a chunk of her own hair, bubbled sluggishly behind Slughorn, who had eyes for nobody but Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you thought of a bezoar all by yourself, did you, Harry?\rdblquote  she asked through gritted teeth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s the individual spirit a real potion-maker needs!\rdblquote  said Slughorn happily, before Harry could reply. \ldblquote Just like his mother, she had the same intuitive grasp of potion-making, it\rquote s undoubt\-edly from Lily he gets it. \'85 Yes, Harry, yes, if you\rquote ve got a bezoar to hand, of course that would do the trick\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 although as they don\rquote t work on everything, and are pretty rare, it\rquote s still worth know\-ing how to mix antidotes. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The only person in the room looking angrier than Hermione was Malfoy, who, Harry was pleased to see, had spilled something that looked like cat-sick over himself. Before either of them could express their fury that Harry had come top of the class by not do\-ing any work, however, the bell rang.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Time to pack up!\rdblquote  said Slughorn. \ldblquote And an extra ten points to Gryffindor for sheer cheek!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Still chuckling, he waddled back to his desk at the front of the dungeon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry dawdled behind, taking an inordinate amount of time to do up his bag. Neither Ron nor Hermione wished him luck as they left; both looked rather annoyed. At last Harry and Slughorn were the only two left in the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come on, now, Harry, you\rquote ll be late for your next lesson,\rdblquote  said Slughorn affably, snapping the gold clasps shut on his dragon-skin briefcase.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir,\rdblquote  said Harry, reminding himself irresistibly of Voldemort, \ldblquote I wanted to ask you something.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ask away, then, my dear boy, ask away. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir, I wondered what you know about\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 about Horcruxes?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Slughorn froze. His round face seemed to sink in upon itself. He licked his lips and said hoarsely, \ldblquote What did you say?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I asked whether you know anything about Horcruxes, sir. You see \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore put you up to this,\rdblquote  whispered Slughorn. His voice had changed completely. It was not genial anymore, but shocked, terrified. He fumbled in his breast pocket and pulled out a handkerchief, mopping his sweating brow. \ldblquote Dumbledore\rquote s shown you that \emdash  that memory. Well? Hasn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, deciding on the spot that it was best not to lie.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, of course,\rdblquote  said Slughorn quietly, still dabbing at his white face. \ldblquote Of course \'85 well, if you\rquote ve seen that memory, Harry, you\rquote ll know that I don\rquote t know anything \emdash  \i anything\i0\rdblquote  \emdash  he repeated the word forcefully \emdash  \ldblquote about Horcruxes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He seized his dragon-skin briefcase, stuffed his handkerchief back into his pocket, and marched to the dungeon door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir,\rdblquote  said Harry desperately, \ldblquote I just thought there might be a bit more to the memory \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you?\rdblquote  said Slughorn. \ldblquote Then you were wrong, weren\rquote t you? WRONG!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He bellowed the last word and, before Harry could say another word, slammed the dungeon door behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neither Ron nor Hermione was at all sympathetic when Harry told them of this disastrous interview. Hermione was still seething at the way Harry had triumphed without doing the work properly. Ron was resentful that Harry hadn\rquote t slipped him a bezoar too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It would\rquote ve just looked stupid if we\rquote d both done it!\rdblquote  said Harry irritably. \ldblquote Look, I had to try and soften him up so I could ask him about Voldemort, didn\rquote t I? Oh, will you \i get a grip\i0 !\rdblquote  he added in ex\-asperation, as Ron winced at the sound of the name.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Infuriated by his failure and by Ron\rquote s and Hermione\rquote s attitudes, Harry brooded for the next few days over what to do next about Slughorn. He decided that, for the time being, he would let Slug\-horn think that he had forgotten all about Horcruxes; it was surely best to lull him into a false sense of security before returning to the attack.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When Harry did not question Slughorn again, the Potions master reverted to his usual affectionate treatment of him, and\lang3081  \lang1033 appeared to have put the matter from his mind. Harry awaited an invitation to one of his little evening parties, determined to accept this time, even if he had to reschedule Quidditch practice. Unfor\-tunately, however, no such invitation arrived. Harry checked with Hermione and Ginny: Neither of them had received an invitation and nor, as far as they knew, had anybody else. Harry could not help wondering whether this meant that Slughorn was not quite as forgetful as he appeared, simply determined to give Harry no addi\-tional opportunities to question him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Meanwhile, the Hogwarts library had failed Hermione for the first time in living memory. She was so shocked, she even forgot that she was annoyed at Harry for his trick with the bezoar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I haven\rquote t found one single explanation of what Horcruxes do!\rdblquote  she told him. \ldblquote Not a single one! I\rquote ve been right through the re\-stricted section and even in the most \i horrible\i0  books, where they tell you how to brew the most \i gruesome\i0  potions \emdash  nothing! All I could find was this, in the introduction to \i Magick Moste Evile\i0  \emdash  listen \emdash  \lquote Of the Horcrux, wickedest of magical inventions, we shall not speak nor give direction. \'85\rquote  I mean, why mention it then?\rdblquote  she said impatiently, slamming the old book shut; it let out a ghostly wail. \ldblquote Oh, shut up,\rdblquote  she snapped, stuffing it back into her bag.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The snow melted around the school as February arrived, to be replaced by cold, dreary wetness. Purplish-gray clouds hung low over the castle and a constant fall of chilly rain made the lawns slip\-pery and muddy. The upshot of this was that the sixth years\rquote  first Apparition lesson, which was scheduled for a Saturday morning so that no normal lessons would be missed, took place in the Great Hall instead of in the grounds.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When Harry and Hermione arrived in the Hall (Ron had come\lang3081  \lang1033 down with Lavender), they found that the tables had disappeared. Rain lashed against the high windows and the enchanted ceiling swirled darkly above them as they assembled in front of Professors McGonagall, Snape, Flitwick, and Sprout \emdash  the Heads of Houses \emdash  and a small wizard whom Harry took to be the Apparition in\-structor from the Ministry. He was oddly colorless, with transpar\-ent eyelashes, wispy hair, and an insubstantial air, as though a single gust of wind might blow him away. Harry wondered whether con\-stant disappearances and reappearances had somehow diminished his substance, or whether this frail build was ideal for anyone wish\-ing to vanish.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good morning,\rdblquote  said the Ministry wizard, when all the stu\-dents had arrived and the Heads of Houses had called for quiet. \ldblquote My name is Wilkie Twycross and I shall be your Ministry Appari\-tion instructor for the next twelve weeks. I hope to be able to prepare you for your Apparition Tests in this time \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Malfoy, be quiet and pay attention!\rdblquote  barked Professor McGon\-agall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Everybody looked around. Malfoy had flushed a dull pink; he looked furious as he stepped away from Crabbe, with whom he ap\-peared to have been having a whispered argument. Harry glanced quickly at Snape, who also looked annoyed, though Harry strongly suspected that this was less because of Malfoy\rquote s rudeness than the fact that McGonagall had reprimanded one of his House.\lang3081\par
