\lang1033 The news that Ron had been poisoned spread quickly next day, but it did not cause the sensation that Katie\rquote s attack had done. Peo\-ple seemed to think that it might have been an accident, given that he had been in the Potions master\rquote s room at the time, and that as\lang3081  \lang1033 he had been given an antidote immediately there was no real harm done. In fact, the Gryffindors were generally much more interested in the upcoming Quidditch match against Hufflepuff, for many of them wanted to see Zacharias Smith, who played Chaser on the Hufflepuff team, punished soundly for his commentary during the opening match against Slytherin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, however, had never been less interested in Quidditch; he was rapidly becoming obsessed with Draco Malfoy. Still checking the Marauder\rquote s Map whenever he got a chance, he sometimes made detours to wherever Malfoy happened to be, but had not yet detected him doing anything out of the ordinary. And still there were those inexplicable times when Malfoy simply vanished from the map. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry did not get a lot of time to consider the problem, what with Quidditch practice, homework, and the fact that he was now being dogged wherever he went by Cormac McLaggen and Lavender Brown.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He could not decide which of them was more annoying. McLaggen kept up a constant stream of hints that he would make a better permanent Keeper for the team than Ron, and that now that Harry was seeing him play regularly he would surely come around to this way of thinking too; he was also keen to criticize the other players and provide Harry with detailed training schemes, so that more than once Harry was forced to remind him who was Captain.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Meanwhile, Lavender kept sidling up to Harry to discuss Ron, which Harry found almost more wearing than McLaggen\rquote s Quid\-ditch lectures. At first, Lavender had been very annoyed that nobody had thought to tell her that Ron was in the hospital\lang3081  \lang1033 wing \emdash  \ldblquote I mean, I \i am\i0  his girlfriend!\rdblquote  \emdash  but unfortunately she had now decided to forgive Harry this lapse of memory and was keen to have lots of in-depth chats with him about Ron\rquote s feelings, a most uncomfortable experience that Harry would have happily forgone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look, why don\rquote t you talk to Ron about all this?\rdblquote  Harry asked, after a particularly long interrogation from Lavender that took in everything from precisely what Ron had said about her new dress robes to whether or not Harry thought that Ron considered his re\-lationship with Lavender to be \ldblquote serious.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I would, but he\rquote s always asleep when I go and see him!\rdblquote  said Lavender fretfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is he?\rdblquote  said Harry, surprised, for he had found Ron perfectly alert every time he had been up to the hospital wing, both highly interested in the news of Dumbledore and Snape\rquote s row and keen to abuse McLaggen as much as possible.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is Hermione Granger still visiting him?\rdblquote  Lavender demanded suddenly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I think so. Well, they\rquote re friends, aren\rquote t they?\rdblquote  said Harry uncomfortably.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Friends, don\rquote t make me laugh,\rdblquote  said Lavender scornfully. \ldblquote She didn\rquote t talk to him for weeks after he started going out with me! But I suppose she wants to make up with him now he\rquote s all \i inter\-esting. \'85\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Would you call getting poisoned being interesting?\rdblquote  asked Harry. \ldblquote Anyway \emdash  sorry, got to go \emdash  there\rquote s McLaggen coming for a talk about Quidditch,\rdblquote  said Harry hurriedly, and he dashed sideways through a door pretending to be solid wall and sprinted\lang3081  \lang1033 down the shortcut that would take him off to Potions where, thankfully, neither Lavender nor McLaggen could follow him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 On the morning of the Quidditch match against Hufflepuff, Harry dropped in on the hospital wing before heading down to the pitch. Ron was very agitated; Madam Pomfrey would not let him go down to watch the match, feeling it would overexcite him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So how\rquote s McLaggen shaping up?\rdblquote  he asked Harry nervously, ap\-parently forgetting that he had already asked the same question twice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve told you,\rdblquote  said Harry patiently, \ldblquote he could be world-class and I wouldn\rquote t want to keep him. He keeps trying to tell everyone what to do, he thinks he could play every position better than the rest of us. I can\rquote t wait to be shot of him. And speaking of getting shot of people,\rdblquote  Harry added, getting to his feet and picking up his Firebolt, \ldblquote will you stop pretending to be asleep when Lavender comes to see you? She\rquote s driving me mad as well.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Ron, looking sheepish. \ldblquote Yeah. All right.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you don\rquote t want to go out with her anymore, just tell her,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 it\rquote s not that easy, is it?\rdblquote  said Ron. He paused. \ldblquote Hermione going to look in before the match?\rdblquote  he added casually.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, she\rquote s already gone down to the pitch with Ginny.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Ron, looking rather glum. \ldblquote Right. Well, good luck. Hope you hammer McLag \emdash  I mean, Smith.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll try,\rdblquote  said Harry, shouldering his broom. \ldblquote See you after the match.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He hurried down through the deserted corridors; the whole school was outside, either already seated in the stadium or heading\lang3081  \lang1033 down toward it. He was looking out of the windows he passed, try\-ing to gauge how much wind they were facing, when a noise ahead made him glance up and he saw Malfoy walking toward him, ac\-companied by two girls, both of whom looked sulky and resentful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy stopped short at the sight of Harry, then gave a short, humorless laugh and continued walking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where\rquote re you going?\rdblquote  Harry demanded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I\rquote m really going to tell you, because it\rquote s your business, Potter,\rdblquote  sneered Malfoy. \ldblquote You\rquote d better hurry up, they\rquote ll be waiting for \lquote the Chosen Captain\rquote  \emdash  \lquote the Boy Who Scored\rquote  \emdash  whatever they call you these days.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 One of the girls gave an unwilling giggle. Harry stared at her. She blushed. Malfoy pushed past Harry and she and her friend fol\-lowed at a trot, turning the corner and vanishing from view.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stood rooted on the spot and watched them disappear. This was infuriating; he was already cutting it fine to get to the match on time and yet there was Malfoy, skulking off while the rest of the school was absent: Harry\rquote s best chance yet of discovering what Malfoy was up to. The silent seconds trickled past, and Harry remained where he was, frozen, gazing at the place where Malfoy had vanished. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where have you been?\rdblquote  demanded Ginny, as Harry sprinted into the changing rooms. The whole team was changed and ready; Coote and Peakes, the Beaters, were both hitting their clubs ner\-vously against their legs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I met Malfoy,\rdblquote  Harry told her quietly, as he pulled his scarlet robes over his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So I wanted to know how come he\rquote s up at the castle with a cou\-ple of girlfriends while everyone else is down here. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Does it matter right now?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I\rquote m not likely to find out, am I?\rdblquote  said Harry, seizing his Firebolt and pushing his glasses straight. \ldblquote Come on then!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And without another word, he marched out onto the pitch to deafening cheers and boos.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was little wind; the clouds were patchy; every now and then there were dazzling flashes of bright sunlight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tricky conditions!\rdblquote  McLaggen said bracingly to the team. \ldblquote Coote, Peakes, you\rquote ll want to fly out of the sun, so they don\rquote t see you coming \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m the Captain, McLaggen, shut up giving them instructions,\rdblquote  said Harry angrily. \ldblquote Just get up by the goal posts!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once McLaggen had marched off, Harry turned to Coote and Peakes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Make sure you \i do\i0  fly out of the sun,\rdblquote  he told them grudgingly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He shook hands with the Hufflepuff Captain, and then, on Madam Hooch\rquote s whistle, kicked off and rose into the air, higher than the rest of his team, streaking around the pitch in search of the Snitch. If he could catch it good and early, there might be a chance he could get back up to the castle, seize the Marauder\rquote s Map, and find out what Malfoy was doing. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And that\rquote s Smith of Hufflepuff with the Quaffle,\rdblquote  said a dreamy voice, echoing over the grounds. \ldblquote He did the commentary last time, of course, and Ginny Weasley flew into him, I think proba\-bly on purpose, it looked like it. Smith was being quite rude about Gryffindor, I expect he regrets that now he\rquote s playing them \emdash  oh,\lang3081  \lang1033 look, he\rquote s lost the Quaffle, Ginny took it from him, I do like her, she\rquote s very nice. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared down at the commentator\rquote s podium. Surely no\-body in their right mind would have let Luna Lovegood commen\-tate? But even from above there was no mistaking that long, dirty-blonde hair, nor the necklace of butterbeer corks. \'85 Beside Luna, Professor McGonagall was looking slightly uncomfortable, as though she was indeed having second thoughts about this appointment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 but now that big Hufflepuff player\rquote s got the Quaffle from her, I can\rquote t remember his name, it\rquote s something like Bibble \emdash  no, Buggins \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s Cadwallader!\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall loudly from be\-side Luna. The crowd laughed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared around for the Snitch; there was no sign of it. Mo\-ments later, Cadwallader scored. McLaggen had been shouting criticism at Ginny for allowing the Quaffle out of her possession, with the result that he had not noticed the large red ball soaring past his right ear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote McLaggen, will you pay attention to what you\rquote re supposed to be doing and leave everyone else alone!\rdblquote  bellowed Harry, wheeling around to face his Keeper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re not setting a great example!\rdblquote  McLaggen shouted back, red-faced and furious.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And Harry Potter\rquote s now having an argument with his Keeper,\rdblquote  said Luna serenely, while both Hufflepuffs and Slytherins below in the crowd cheered and jeered. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think that\rquote ll help him find the Snitch, but maybe it\rquote s a clever ruse. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Swearing angrily, Harry spun round and set off around the pitch again, scanning the skies for some sign of the tiny, winged golden ball.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ginny and Demelza scored a goal apiece, giving the red-and-gold-clad supporters below something to cheer about. Then Cad\-wallader scored again, making things level, but Luna did not seem to have noticed; she appeared singularly uninterested in such mun\-dane things as the score, and kept attempting to draw the crowd\rquote s attention to such things as interestingly shaped clouds and the pos\-sibility that Zacharias Smith, who had so far failed to maintain possession of the Quaffle for longer than a minute, was suffering from something called \ldblquote Loser\rquote s Lurgy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Seventy-forty to Hufflepuff!\rdblquote  barked Professor McGonagall into Luna\rquote s megaphone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is it, already?\rdblquote  said Luna vaguely. \ldblquote Oh, look! The Gryffindor Keeper\rquote s got hold of one of the Beater\rquote s bats.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry spun around in midair. Sure enough, McLaggen, for rea\-sons best known to himself, had pulled Peakes\rquote s bat from him and appeared to be demonstrating how to hit a Bludger toward an on\-coming Cadwallader.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Will you give him back his bat and get back to the goal posts\i0 !\rdblquote  roared Harry, pelting toward McLaggen just as McLaggen took a ferocious swipe at the Bludger and mishit it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A blinding, sickening pain \'85 a flash of light\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 distant screams\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 and the sensation of falling down a long tunnel\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And the next thing Harry knew, he was lying in a remarkably warm and comfortable bed and looking up at a lamp that was throwing a circle of golden light onto a shadowy ceiling. He raised\lang3081  \lang1033 his head awkwardly. There on his left was a familiar-looking, freckly, red-haired person.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nice of you to drop in,\rdblquote  said Ron, grinning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry blinked and looked around. Of course: He was in the hos\-pital wing. The sky outside was indigo streaked with crimson. The match must have finished hours ago \'85 as had any hope of cor\-nering Malfoy. Harry\rquote s head felt strangely heavy; he raised a hand and felt a stiff turban of bandages.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What happened?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cracked skull,\rdblquote  said Madam Pomfrey, bustling up and pushing him back against his pillows. \ldblquote Nothing to worry about, I mended it at once, but I\rquote m keeping you in overnight. You shouldn\rquote t over\-exert yourself for a few hours.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t want to stay here overnight,\rdblquote  said Harry angrily, sitting up and throwing back his covers. \ldblquote I want to find McLaggen and kill him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid that would come under the heading of \lquote overexer\-tion,\rquote  \rdblquote  said Madam Pomfrey, pushing him firmly back onto the bed and raising her wand in a threatening manner. \ldblquote You will stay here until I discharge you, Potter, or I shall call the headmaster.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She bustled back into her office, and Harry sank back into his pillows, fuming.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you know how much we lost by?\rdblquote  he asked Ron through clenched teeth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, yeah I do,\rdblquote  said Ron apologetically. \ldblquote Final score was three hundred and twenty to sixty.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Brilliant,\rdblquote  said Harry savagely. \ldblquote Really brilliant! When I get hold of McLaggen \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t want to get hold of him, he\rquote s the size of a troll,\rdblquote  said\lang3081  \lang1033 Ron reasonably. \ldblquote Personally, I think there\rquote s a lot to be said for hex\-ing him with that toenail thing of the Prince\rquote s. Anyway, the rest of the team might\rquote ve dealt with him before you get out of here, they\rquote re not happy. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a note of badly suppressed glee in Ron\rquote s voice; Harry could tell he was nothing short of thrilled that McLaggen had messed up so badly. Harry lay there, staring up at the patch of light on the ceiling, his recently mended skull not hurting, precisely, but feeling slightly tender underneath all the bandaging.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I could hear the match commentary from here,\rdblquote  said Ron, his voice now shaking with laughter. \ldblquote I hope Luna always commen\-tates from now on. \'85 \i Loser\rquote s Lurgy\i0  \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry was still too angry to see much humor in the situa\-tion, and after a while Ron\rquote s snorts subsided.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ginny came in to visit while you were unconscious,\rdblquote  he said, after a long pause, and Harry\rquote s imagination zoomed into overdrive, rapidly constructing a scene in which Ginny, weeping over his life\-less form, confessed her feelings of deep attraction to him while Ron gave them his blessing. \'85\lang3081  \lang1033\ldblquote She reckons you only just arrived on time for the match. How come? You left here early enough.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \'85\rdblquote  said Harry, as the scene in his mind\rquote s eye imploded. \ldblquote Yeah \'85 well, I saw Malfoy sneaking off with a couple of girls who didn\rquote t look like they wanted to be with him, and that\rquote s the sec\-ond time he\rquote s made sure he isn\rquote t down on the Quidditch pitch with the rest of the school; he skipped the last match too, remember?\rdblquote  Harry sighed. \ldblquote Wish I\rquote d followed him now, the match was such a fiasco. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t be stupid,\rdblquote  said Ron sharply. \ldblquote You couldn\rquote t have missed a Quidditch match just to follow Malfoy, you\rquote re the Captain!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want to know what he\rquote s up to,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote And don\rquote t tell me it\rquote s all in my head, not after what I overheard between him and Snape \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I never said it was all in your head,\rdblquote  said Ron, hoisting himself up on an elbow in turn and frowning at Harry, \ldblquote but there\rquote s no rule saying only one person at a time can be plotting anything in this place! You\rquote re getting a bit obsessed with Malfoy, Harry. I mean, thinking about missing a match just to follow him \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want to catch him at it!\rdblquote  said Harry in frustration. \ldblquote I mean, where\rquote s he going when he disappears off the map?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I dunno \'85 Hogsmeade?\rdblquote  suggested Ron, yawning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve never seen him going along any of the secret passageways on the map. I thought they were being watched now anyway?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well then, I dunno,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Silence fell between them. Harry stared up at the circle of lamp\-light above him, thinking. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 If only he had Rufus Scrimgeour\rquote s power, he would have been able to set a tail upon Malfoy, but unfortunately Harry did not have an office full of Aurors at his command. \'85 He thought fleet\-ingly of trying to set something up with the D.A., but there again was the problem that people would be missed from lessons; most of them, after all, still had full schedules. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a low, rumbling snore from Ron\rquote s bed. After a while Madam Pomfrey came out of her office, this time wearing a thick dressing gown. It was easiest to feign sleep; Harry rolled over onto his side and listened to all the curtains closing themselves as she waved her wand. The lamps dimmed, and she returned to her office; he heard the door click behind her and knew that she was off to bed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This was, Harry reflected in the darkness, the third time that he had been brought to the hospital wing because of a Quidditch in\-jury. Last time he had fallen off his broom due to the presence of dementors around the pitch, and the time before that, all the bones had been removed from his arm by the incurably inept Professor Lockhart. \'85 That had been his most painful injury by far \'85 he remembered the agony of regrowing an armful of bones in one night, a discomfort not eased by the arrival of an unexpected visi\-tor in the middle of the \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sat bolt upright, his heart pounding, his bandage turban askew. He had the solution at last: There \i was\i0  a way to have Malfoy followed \emdash  how could he have forgotten, why hadn\rquote t he thought of it before?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But the question was, how to call him? What did you do?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Quietly, tentatively, Harry spoke into the darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a very loud \i crack,\i0  and the sounds of scuffling and squeaks filled the silent room. Ron awoke with a yelp.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s going \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry pointed his wand hastily at the door of Madam Pomfrey\rquote s office and muttered, \ldblquote\i Muffliato\i0 !\rdblquote  so that she would not come run\-ning. Then he scrambled to the end of his bed for a better look at what was going on.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Two house-elves were rolling around on the floor in the middle of the dormitory, one wearing a shrunken maroon jumper and sev\-eral woolly hats, the other, a filthy old rag strung over his hips like a loincloth. Then there was another loud bang, and Peeves the Pol\-tergeist appeared in midair above the wrestling elves.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was watching that, Potty!\rdblquote  he told Harry indignantly, point\-ing at the fight below, before letting out a loud cackle. \ldblquote Look at the ickle creatures squabbling, bitey bitey, punchy punchy \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher will not insult Harry Potter in front of Dobby, no he won\rquote t, or Dobby will shut Kreacher\rquote s mouth for him!\rdblquote  cried Dobby in a high-pitched voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  kicky, scratchy!\rdblquote  cried Peeves happily, now pelting bits of chalk at the elves to enrage them further. \ldblquote Tweaky, pokey!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher will say what he likes about his master, oh yes, and what a master he is, filthy friend of Mudbloods, oh, what would poor Kreacher\rquote s mistress say \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Exactly what Kreacher\rquote s mistress would have said they did not find out, for at that moment Dobby sank his knobbly little fist into Kreacher\rquote s mouth and knocked out half of his teeth. Harry and Ron both leapt out of their beds and wrenched the two elves apart, though they continued to try and kick and punch each other, egged on by Peeves, who swooped around the lamp squealing, \ldblquote Stick your fingers up his nosey, draw his cork and pull his earsies \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry aimed his wand at Peeves and said, \ldblquote\i Langlock\i0 !\rdblquote  Peeves clutched at his throat, gulped, then swooped from the room mak\-ing obscene gestures but unable to speak, owing to the fact that his tongue had just glued itself to the roof of his mouth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nice one,\rdblquote  said Ron appreciatively, lifting Dobby into the air so that his flailing limbs no longer made contact with Kreacher. \ldblquote That was another Prince hex, wasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, twisting Kreacher\rquote s wizened arm into a half nelson. \ldblquote Right \emdash  I\rquote m forbidding you to fight each other! Well,\lang3081  \lang1033 Kreacher, you\rquote re forbidden to fight Dobby. Dobby, I know I\rquote m not allowed to give you orders \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dobby is a free house-elf and he can obey anyone he likes and Dobby will do whatever Harry Potter wants him to do!\rdblquote  said Dobby, tears now streaming down his shriveled little face onto his jumper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay then,\rdblquote  said Harry, and he and Ron both released the elves, who fell to the floor but did not continue fighting.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Master called me?\rdblquote  croaked Kreacher, sinking into a bow even as he gave Harry a look that plainly wished him a painful death.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I did,\rdblquote  said Harry, glancing toward Madam Pomfrey\rquote s of\-fice door to check that the \i Muffliato\i0  spell was still working; there was no sign that she had heard any of the commotion. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got a job for you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher will do whatever Master wants,\rdblquote  said Kreacher, sink\-ing so low that his lips almost touched his gnarled toes, \ldblquote because Kreacher has no choice, but Kreacher is ashamed to have such a master, yes \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dobby will do it, Harry Potter!\rdblquote  squeaked Dobby, his tennis-ball-sized eyes still swimming in tears. \ldblquote Dobby would be honored to help Harry Potter!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come to think of it, it would be good to have both of you,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Okay then \'85 I want you to tail Draco Malfoy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ignoring the look of mingled surprise and exasperation on Ron\rquote s face, Harry went on, \ldblquote I want to know where he\rquote s going, who he\rquote s meeting, and what he\rquote s doing. I want you to follow him around the clock.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Harry Potter!\rdblquote  said Dobby at once, his great eyes shining\lang3081  \lang1033 with excitement. \ldblquote And if Dobby does it wrong, Dobby will throw himself off the topmost tower, Harry Potter!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There won\rquote t be any need for that,\rdblquote  said Harry hastily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Master wants me to follow the youngest of the Malfoys?\rdblquote  croaked Kreacher. \ldblquote Master wants me to spy upon the pure-blood great-nephew of my old mistress?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s the one,\rdblquote  said Harry, foreseeing a great danger and de\-termining to prevent it immediately. \ldblquote And you\rquote re forbidden to tip him off, Kreacher, or to show him what you\rquote re up to, or to talk to him at all, or to write him messages or \'85 or to contact him in any way. Got it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He thought he could see Kreacher struggling to see a loophole in the instructions he had just been given and waited. After a moment or two, and to Harry\rquote s great satisfaction, Kreacher bowed deeply again and said, with bitter resentment, \ldblquote Master thinks of every\-thing, and Kreacher must obey him even though Kreacher would much rather be the servant of the Malfoy boy, oh yes. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s settled, then,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I\rquote ll want regular reports, but make sure I\rquote m not surrounded by people when you turn up. Ron and Hermione are okay. And don\rquote t tell anyone what you\rquote re doing. Just stick to Malfoy like a couple of wart plasters.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
