Harry and Ron left the hospital wing first thing on Mon\-day morning, restored to full health by the ministra\-tions of Madam Pomfrey and now able to enjoy the benefits of having been knocked out and poisoned, the best of which was that Hermione was friends with Ron again. Hermione even escorted them down to breakfast, bringing with her the news that Ginny had argued with Dean. The drowsing creature in Harry\rquote s chest sud\-denly raised its head, sniffing the air hopefully.\par
\ldblquote What did they row about?\rdblquote  he asked, trying to sound casual as they turned onto a seventh-floor corridor that was deserted but for a very small girl who had been examining a tapestry of trolls in tu\-tus. She looked terrified at the sight of the approaching sixth years and dropped the heavy brass scales she was carrying.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s all right!\rdblquote  said Hermione kindly, hurrying forward to help her. \ldblquote Here \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She tapped the broken scales with her wand and said, \ldblquote\i Reparo.\i0\rdblquote  The girl did not say thank you, but remained rooted to the spot as they passed and watched them out of sight; Ron glanced back at her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I swear they\rquote re getting smaller,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Never mind her,\rdblquote  said Harry, a little impatiently. \ldblquote What did Ginny and Dean row about, Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, Dean was laughing about McLaggen hitting that Bludger at you,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It must\rquote ve looked funny,\rdblquote  said Ron reasonably.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It didn\rquote t look funny at all!\rdblquote  said Hermione hotly. \ldblquote It looked ter\-rible and if Coote and Peakes hadn\rquote t caught Harry he could have been very badly hurt!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, well, there was no need for Ginny and Dean to split up over it,\rdblquote  said Harry, still trying to sound casual. \ldblquote Or are they still together?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, they are \emdash  but why are you so interested?\rdblquote  asked Hermi\-one, giving Harry a sharp look.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I just don\rquote t want my Quidditch team messed up again!\rdblquote  he said hastily, but Hermione continued to look suspicious, and he was most relieved when a voice behind them called, \ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  giving him an excuse to turn his back on her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, hi, Luna.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I went to the hospital wing to find you,\rdblquote  said Luna, rummag\-ing in her bag. \ldblquote But they said you\rquote d left. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She thrust what appeared to be a green onion, a large spotted toadstool, and a considerable amount of what looked like cat litter into Ron\rquote s hands, finally pulling out a rather grubby scroll of parch\-ment that she handed to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 I\rquote ve been told to give you this.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was a small roll of parchment, which Harry recognized at once as another invitation to a lesson with Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tonight,\rdblquote  he told Ron and Hermione, once he had unrolled it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nice commentary last match!\rdblquote  said Ron to Luna as she took back the green onion, the toadstool, and the cat litter. Luna smiled vaguely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re making fun of me, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Everyone says I was dreadful.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I\rquote m serious!\rdblquote  said Ron earnestly. \ldblquote I can\rquote t remember enjoy\-ing commentary more! What is this, by the way?\rdblquote  he added, hold\-ing the onionlike object up to eye level.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, it\rquote s a Gurdyroot,\rdblquote  she said, stuffing the cat litter and the toadstool back into her bag. \ldblquote You can keep it if you like, I\rquote ve got a few of them. They\rquote re really excellent for warding off Gulping Plimpies.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And she walked away, leaving Ron chortling, still clutching the Gurdyroot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know, she\rquote s grown on me, Luna,\rdblquote  he said, as they set off again for the Great Hall. \ldblquote I know she\rquote s insane, but it\rquote s in a good \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stopped talking very suddenly. Lavender Brown was stand\-ing at the foot of the marble staircase looking thunderous.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi,\rdblquote  said Ron nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote C\rquote mon,\rdblquote  Harry muttered to Hermione, and they sped past, though not before they had heard Lavender say, \ldblquote Why didn\rquote t you tell me you were getting out today? And why was \i she\i0  with you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron looked both sulky and annoyed when he appeared at break\-fast half an hour later, and though he sat with Lavender, Harry did not see them exchange a word all the time they were together. Her\-mione was acting as though she was quite oblivious to all of this,\lang3081  \lang1033 but once or twice Harry saw an inexplicable smirk cross her face. All that day she seemed to be in a particularly good mood, and that evening in the common room she even consented to look over (in other words, finish writing) Harry\rquote s Herbology essay, something she had been resolutely refusing to do up to this point, because she had known that Harry would then let Ron copy his work.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks a lot, Hermione,\rdblquote  said Harry, giving her a hasty pat on the back as he checked his watch and saw that it was nearly eight o\rquote clock. \ldblquote Listen, I\rquote ve got to hurry or I\rquote ll be late for Dumble\-dore. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She did not answer, but merely crossed out a few of his feebler sentences in a weary sort of way. Grinning, Harry hurried out through the portrait hole and off to the headmaster\rquote s office. The gargoyle leapt aside at the mention of toffee \'e9clairs, and Harry took the spiral staircase two steps at a time, knocking on the door just as a clock within chimed eight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Enter,\rdblquote  called Dumbledore, but as Harry put out a hand to push the door, it was wrenched open from inside. There stood Pro\-fessor Trelawney.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aha!\rdblquote  she cried, pointing dramatically at Harry as she blinked at him through her magnifying spectacles. \ldblquote So this is the reason I am to be thrown unceremoniously from your office, Dumbledore!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dear Sybill,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore in a slightly exasperated voice, \ldblquote there is no question of throwing you unceremoniously from anywhere, but Harry does have an appointment, and I really don\rquote t think there is any more to be said \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well,\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney, in a deeply wounded voice. \ldblquote If you will not banish the usurping nag, so be it. \'85\lang3081  \lang1033 Perhaps I shall find a school where my talents are better appreci\-ated. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She pushed past Harry and disappeared down the spiral stair\-case; they heard her stumble halfway down, and Harry guessed that she had tripped over one of her trailing shawls.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please close the door and sit down, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, sounding rather tired.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry obeyed, noticing as he took his usual seat in front of Dumbledore\rquote s desk that the Pensieve lay between them once more, as did two more tiny crystal bottles full of swirling memory.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Trelawney still isn\rquote t happy Firenze is teaching, then?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote Divination is turning out to be much more trouble than I could have foreseen, never having studied the subject myself. I cannot ask Firenze to return to the forest, where he is now an outcast, nor can I ask Sybill Trelawney to leave. Be\-tween ourselves, she has no idea of the danger she would be in out\-side the castle. She does not know \emdash  and I think it would be unwise to enlighten her \emdash  that she made the prophecy about you and Voldemort, you see.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore heaved a deep sigh, then said, \ldblquote But never mind my staffing problems. We have much more important matters to dis\-cuss. Firstly \emdash  have you managed the task I set you at the end of our previous lesson?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Harry, brought up short. What with Apparition lessons and Quidditch and Ron being poisoned and getting his skull cracked and his determination to find out what Draco Malfoy was up to, Harry had almost forgotten about the memory Dumbledore\lang3081  \lang1033 had asked him to extract from Professor Slughorn. \ldblquote Well, I asked Professor Slughorn about it at the end of Potions, sir, but, er, he wouldn\rquote t give it to me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a little silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I see,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore eventually, peering at Harry over the top of his half-moon spectacles and giving Harry the usual sensa\-tion that he was being X-rayed. \ldblquote And you feel that you have exerted your very best efforts in this matter, do you? That you have exer\-cised all of your considerable ingenuity? That you have left no depth of cunning unplumbed in your quest to retrieve the memory?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  Harry stalled, at a loss for what to say next. His single at\-tempt to get hold of the memory suddenly seemed embarrassingly feeble. \ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 the day Ron swallowed love potion by mistake I took him to Professor Slughorn. I thought maybe if I got Professor Slughorn in a good enough mood \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And did that work?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, no, sir, because Ron got poisoned \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  which, naturally, made you forget all about trying to retrieve the memory; I would have expected nothing else, while your best friend was in danger. Once it became clear that Mr. Weasley was going to make a full recovery, however, I would have hoped that you returned to the task I set you. I thought I made it clear to you how very important that memory is. Indeed, I did my best to im\-press upon you that it is the most crucial memory of all and that we will be wasting our time without it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A hot, prickly feeling of shame spread from the top of Harry\rquote s head all the way down his body. Dumbledore had not raised his voice, he did not even sound angry, but Harry would have preferred him to yell; this cold disappointment was worse than anything.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir,\rdblquote  he said, a little desperately, \ldblquote it isn\rquote t that I wasn\rquote t bothered or anything, I\rquote ve just had other \emdash  other things \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Other things on your mind,\rdblquote  Dumbledore finished the sen\-tence for him. \ldblquote I see.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Silence fell between them again, the most uncomfortable silence Harry had ever experienced with Dumbledore; it seemed to go on and on, punctuated only by the little grunting snores of the por\-trait of Armando Dippet over Dumbledore\rquote s head. Harry felt strangely diminished, as though he had shrunk a little since he had entered the room. When he could stand it no longer he said, \ldblquote Pro\-fessor Dumbledore, I\rquote m really sorry. I should have done more. \'85 I should have realized you wouldn\rquote t have asked me to do it if it wasn\rquote t really important.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you for saying that, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly. \ldblquote May I hope, then, that you will give this matter higher priority from now on? There will be little point in our meeting after tonight unless we have that memory.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll do it, sir, I\rquote ll get it from him,\rdblquote  he said earnestly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then we shall say no more about it just now,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore more kindly, \ldblquote but continue with our story where we left off. You re\-member where that was?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, sir,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote Voldemort killed his father and his grandparents and made it look as though his Uncle Morfin did it. Then he went back to Hogwarts and he asked \'85 he asked Pro\-fessor Slughorn about Horcruxes,\rdblquote  he mumbled shamefacedly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very good,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Now, you will remember, I hope, that I told you at the very outset of these meetings of ours that we would be entering the realms of guesswork and speculation?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thus far, as I hope you agree, I have shown you reasonably firm sources of fact for my deductions as to what Voldemort did until the age of seventeen?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry nodded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But now, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote now things become murkier and stranger. If it was difficult to find evidence about the boy Riddle, it has been almost impossible to find anyone prepared to reminisce about the man Voldemort. In fact, I doubt whether there is a soul alive, apart from himself, who could give us a full ac\-count of his life since he left Hogwarts. However, I have two last memories that I would like to share with you.\rdblquote  Dumbledore indi\-cated the two little crystal bottles gleaming beside the Pensieve. \ldblquote I shall then be glad of your opinion as to whether the conclusions I have drawn from them seem likely.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The idea that Dumbledore valued his opinion this highly made Harry feel even more deeply ashamed that he had failed in the task of retrieving the Horcrux memory, and he shifted guiltily in his seat as Dumbledore raised the first of the two bottles to the light and examined it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I hope you are not tired of diving into other people\rquote s memories, for they are curious recollections, these two,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote This first one came from a very old house-elf by the name of Hokey. Before we see what Hokey witnessed, I must quickly recount how Lord Voldemort left Hogwarts.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He reached the seventh year of his schooling with, as you might have expected, top grades in every examination he had taken. All around him, his classmates were deciding which jobs they were to pursue once they had left Hogwarts. Nearly everybody expected spectacular things from Tom Riddle, prefect, Head Boy, winner of\lang3081  \lang1033 the Award for Special Services to the School. I know that several teachers, Professor Slughorn amongst them, suggested that he join the Ministry of Magic, offered to set up appointments, put him in touch with useful contacts. He refused all offers. The next thing the staff knew, Voldemort was working at Borgin and Burkes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote At Borgin and Burkes?\rdblquote  Harry repeated, stunned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote At Borgin and Burkes,\rdblquote  repeated Dumbledore calmly. \ldblquote I think you will see what attractions the place held for him when we have entered Hokey\rquote s memory. But this was not Voldemort\rquote s first choice of job. Hardly anyone knew of it at the time \emdash  I was one of the few in whom the then headmaster confided \emdash  but Voldemort first approached Professor Dippet and asked whether he could remain at Hogwarts as a teacher.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He wanted to stay here? Why?\rdblquote  asked Harry, more amazed still.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I believe he had several reasons, though he confided none of them to Professor Dippet,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Firstly, and very importantly, Voldemort was, I believe, more attached to this school than he has ever been to a person. Hogwarts was where he had been happiest; the first and only place he had felt at home.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt slightly uncomfortable at these words, for this was ex\-actly how he felt about Hogwarts too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Secondly, the castle is a stronghold of ancient magic. Undoubt\-edly Voldemort had penetrated many more of its secrets than most of the students who pass through the place, but he may have felt that there were still mysteries to unravel, stores of magic to tap.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And thirdly, as a teacher, he would have had great power and in\-fluence over young witches and wizards. Perhaps he had gained the idea from Professor Slughorn, the teacher with whom he was on best terms, who had demonstrated how influential a role a teacher\lang3081  \lang1033 can play. I do not imagine for an instant that Voldemort envisaged spending the rest of his life at Hogwarts, but I do think that he saw it as a useful recruiting ground, and a place where he might begin to build himself an army.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But he didn\rquote t get the job, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, he did not. Professor Dippet told him that he was too young at eighteen, but invited him to reapply in a few years, if he still wished to teach.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How did you feel about that, sir?\rdblquote  asked Harry hesitantly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Deeply uneasy,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I had advised Armando against the appointment \emdash  I did not give the reasons I have given you, for Professor Dippet was very fond of Voldemort and con\-vinced of his honesty. But I did not want Lord Voldemort back at this school, and especially not in a position of power.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Which job did he want, sir? What subject did he want to teach?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Somehow, Harry knew the answer even before Dumbledore gave it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Defense Against the Dark Arts. It was being taught at the time by an old Professor by the name of Galatea Merrythought, who had been at Hogwarts for nearly fifty years.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So Voldemort went off to Borgin and Burkes, and all the staff who had admired him said what a waste it was, a brilliant young wizard like that, working in a shop. However, Voldemort was no mere assistant. Polite and handsome and clever, he was soon given particular jobs of the type that only exist in a place like Borgin and Burkes, which specializes, as you know, Harry, in objects with un\-usual and powerful properties. Voldemort was sent to persuade\lang3081  \lang1033 people to part with their treasures for sale by the partners, and he was, by all accounts, unusually gifted at doing this.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll bet he was,\rdblquote  said Harry, unable to contain himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, quite,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, with a faint smile. \ldblquote And now it is time to hear from Hokey the house-elf, who worked for a very old, very rich witch by the name of Hepzibah Smith.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore tapped a bottle with his wand, the cork flew out, and he tipped the swirling memory into the Pensieve, saying as he did so, \ldblquote After you, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry got to his feet and bent once more over the rippling silver contents of the stone basin until his face touched them. He tum\-bled through dark nothingness and landed in a sitting room in front of an immensely fat old lady wearing an elaborate ginger wig and a brilliant pink set of robes that flowed all around her, giving her the look of a melting iced cake. She was looking into a small jeweled mirror and dabbing rouge onto her already scarlet cheeks with a large powder puff, while the tiniest and oldest house-elf Harry had ever seen laced her fleshy feet into tight satin slippers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hurry up, Hokey!\rdblquote  said Hepzibah imperiously. \ldblquote He said he\rquote d come at four, it\rquote s only a couple of minutes to and he\rquote s never been late yet!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She tucked away her powder puff as the house-elf straightened up. The top of the elf\rquote s head barely reached the seat of Hepzibah\rquote s chair, and her papery skin hung off her frame just like the crisp linen sheet she wore draped like a toga.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do I look?\rdblquote  said Hepzibah, turning her head to admire the various angles of her face in the mirror.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lovely, madam,\rdblquote  squeaked Hokey.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could only assume that it was down in Hokey\rquote s contract that she must lie through her teeth when asked this question, be\-cause Hepzibah Smith looked a long way from lovely in his opinion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A tinkling doorbell rang and both mistress and elf jumped.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Quick, quick, he\rquote s here, Hokey!\rdblquote  cried Hepzibah and the elf scurried out of the room, which was so crammed with objects that it was difficult to see how anybody could navigate their way across it without knocking over at least a dozen things: There were cabi\-nets full of little lacquered boxes, cases full of gold-embossed books, shelves of orbs and celestial globes, and many flourishing potted plants in brass containers. In fact, the room looked like a cross between a magical antique shop and a conservatory.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The house-elf returned within minutes, followed by a tall young man Harry had no difficulty whatsoever in recognizing as Volde\-mort. He was plainly dressed in a black suit; his hair was a little longer than it had been at school and his cheeks were hollowed, but all of this suited him; he looked more handsome than ever. He picked his way through the cramped room with an air that showed he had visited many times before and bowed low over Hepzibah\rquote s fat little hand, brushing it with his lips.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I brought you flowers,\rdblquote  he said quietly, producing a bunch of roses from nowhere.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You naughty boy, you shouldn\rquote t have!\rdblquote  squealed old Hepzibah, though Harry noticed that she had an empty vase standing ready on the nearest little table. \ldblquote You do spoil this old lady, Tom. \'85 Sit down, sit down. \'85 Where\rquote s Hokey? Ah \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The house-elf had come dashing back into the room carrying a tray of little cakes, which she set at her mistress\rquote s elbow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Help yourself, Tom,\rdblquote  said Hepzibah, \ldblquote I know how you love my cakes. Now, how are you? You look pale. They overwork you at that shop, I\rquote ve said it a hundred times. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Voldemort smiled mechanically and Hepzibah simpered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, what\rquote s your excuse for visiting this time?\rdblquote  she asked, bat\-ting her lashes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Burke would like to make an improved offer for the gob\-lin-made armor,\rdblquote  said Voldemort. \ldblquote Five hundred Galleons, he feels it is a more than fair \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, now, not so fast, or I\rquote ll think you\rquote re only here for my trin\-kets!\rdblquote  pouted Hepzibah.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am ordered here because of them,\rdblquote  said Voldemort quietly. \ldblquote I am only a poor assistant, madam, who must do as he is told. Mr. Burke wishes me to inquire \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, Mr. Burke, phooey!\rdblquote  said Hepzibah, waving a little hand. \ldblquote I\rquote ve something to show you that I\rquote ve never shown Mr. Burke! Can you keep a secret, Tom? Will you promise you won\rquote t tell Mr. Burke I\rquote ve got it? He\rquote d never let me rest if he knew I\rquote d shown it to you, and I\rquote m not selling, not to Burke, not to anyone! But you, Tom, you\rquote ll appreciate it for its history, not how many Galleons you can get for it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote d be glad to see anything Miss Hepzibah shows me,\rdblquote  said Voldemort quietly, and Hepzibah gave another girlish giggle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I had Hokey bring it out for me. \'85 Hokey, where are you? I want to show Mr. Riddle our \i finest\i0  treasure. \'85 In fact, bring both, while you\rquote re at it. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here, madam,\rdblquote  squeaked the house-elf, and Harry saw two leather boxes, one on top of the other, moving across the room as if of their own volition, though he knew the tiny elf was holding\lang3081  \lang1033 them over her head as she wended her way between tables, pouffes, and footstools.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now,\rdblquote  said Hepzibah happily, taking the boxes from the elf, laying them in her lap, and preparing to open the topmost one, \ldblquote I think you\rquote ll like this, Tom. \'85 Oh, if my family knew I was show\-ing you. \'85 They can\rquote t wait to get their hands on this!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She opened the lid. Harry edged forward a little to get a better view and saw what looked like a small golden cup with two finely wrought handles.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wonder whether you know what it is, Tom? Pick it up, have a good look!\rdblquote  whispered Hepzibah, and Voldemort stretched out a long-fingered hand and lifted the cup by one handle out of its snug silken wrappings. Harry thought he saw a red gleam in his dark eyes. His greedy expression was curiously mirrored on Hepzibah\rquote s face, except that her tiny eyes were fixed upon Voldemort\rquote s hand\-some features.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A badger,\rdblquote  murmured Voldemort, examining the engraving upon the cup. \ldblquote Then this was \'85 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Helga Hufflepuff\rquote s, as you very well know, you clever boy!\rdblquote  said Hepzibah, leaning forward with a loud creaking of corsets and ac\-tually pinching his hollow cheek. \ldblquote Didn\rquote t I tell you I was distantly descended? This has been handed down in the family for years and years. Lovely, isn\rquote t it? And all sorts of powers it\rquote s supposed to pos\-sess too, but I haven\rquote t tested them thoroughly, I just keep it nice and safe in here. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She hooked the cup back off Voldemort\rquote s long forefinger and re\-stored it gently to its box, too intent upon settling it carefully back into position to notice the shadow that crossed Voldemort\rquote s face as the cup was taken away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now then,\rdblquote  said Hepzibah happily, \ldblquote where\rquote s Hokey? Oh yes, there you are \emdash  take that away now, Hokey.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The elf obediently took the boxed cup, and Hepzibah turned her attention to the much flatter box in her lap.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think you\rquote ll like this even more, Tom,\rdblquote  she whispered. \ldblquote Lean in a little, dear boy, so you can see. \'85 Of course, Burke knows I\rquote ve got this one, I bought it from him, and I daresay he\rquote d love to get it back when I\rquote m gone. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
