\lang1033 Snape returned ten minutes later. He stepped into the bathroom and closed the door behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Go,\rdblquote  he said to Myrtle, and she swooped back into her toilet at once, leaving a ringing silence behind her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t mean it to happen,\rdblquote  said Harry at once. His voice echoed in the cold, watery space. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t know what that spell did.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Snape ignored this. \ldblquote Apparently I underestimated you, Pot\-ter,\rdblquote  he said quietly. \ldblquote Who would have thought you knew such Dark Magic? Who taught you that spell?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  read about it somewhere.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was \emdash  a library book,\rdblquote  Harry invented wildly. \ldblquote I can\rquote t re\-member what it was call \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Liar,\rdblquote  said Snape. Harry\rquote s throat went dry. He knew what Snape was going to do and he had never been able to prevent it. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The bathroom seemed to shimmer before his eyes; he struggled to block out all thought, but try as he might, the Half-Blood Prince\rquote s copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making\i0  swam hazily to the fore\-front of his mind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then he was staring at Snape again, in the midst of this wrecked, soaked bathroom. He stared into Snape\rquote s black eyes, hop\-ing against hope that Snape had not seen what he feared, but \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bring me your schoolbag,\rdblquote  said Snape softly, \ldblquote and all of your schoolbooks. \i All\i0  of them. Bring them to me here. Now!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was no point arguing. Harry turned at once and splashed\lang3081  \lang1033 out of the bathroom. Once in the corridor, he broke into a run to\-ward Gryffindor Tower. Most people were walking the other way; they gaped at him, drenched in water and blood, but he answered none of the questions fired at him as he ran past.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He felt stunned; it was as though a beloved pet had turned sud\-denly savage; what had the Prince been thinking to copy such a spell into his book? And what would happen when Snape saw it? Would he tell Slughorn \emdash  Harry\rquote s stomach churned \emdash  how Harry had been achieving such good results in Potions all year? Would he confiscate or destroy the book that had taught Harry so much \'85 the book that had become a kind of guide and friend? Harry could not let it happen. \'85 He could not\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where\rquote ve you \emdash  ? Why are you soaking \emdash  ? Is that \i blood\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron was standing at the top of the stairs, looking bewildered at the sight of Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I need your book,\rdblquote  Harry panted. \ldblquote Your Potions book. Quick \'85 give it to me \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what about the Half-Blood \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll explain later!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron pulled his copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making\i0  out of his bag and handed it over; Harry sprinted off past him and back to the common room. Here, he seized his schoolbag, ignoring the amazed looks of several people who had already finished their dinner, threw himself back out of the portrait hole, and hurtled off along the seventh-floor corridor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He skidded to a halt beside the tapestry of dancing trolls, closed his eyes, and began to walk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i I need a place to hide my book. \'85 I need a place to hide my book. \'85 I need a place to hide my book. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 Three times he walked up and down in front of the stretch of blank wall. When he opened his eyes, there it was at last: the door to the Room of Requirement. Harry wrenched it open, flung him\-self inside, and slammed it shut.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He gasped. Despite his haste, his panic, his fear of what awaited him back in the bathroom, he could not help but be overawed by what he was looking at. He was standing in a room the size of a large cathedral, whose high windows were sending shafts of light down upon what looked like a city with towering walls, built of what Harry knew must be objects hidden by generations of Hog\-warts inhabitants. There were alleyways and roads bordered by tee\-tering piles of broken and damaged furniture, stowed away, perhaps, to hide the evidence of mishandled magic, or else hidden by castle-proud house-elves. There were thousands and thousands of books, no doubt banned or graffitied or stolen. There were winged catapults and Fanged Frisbees, some still with enough life in them to hover halfheartedly over the mountains of other forbidden items; there were chipped bottles of congealed potions, hats, jewels, cloaks; there were what looked like dragon eggshells, corked bottles whose contents still shimmered evilly, several rusting swords, and a heavy, bloodstained axe.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry hurried forward into one of the many alleyways between all this hidden treasure. He turned right past an enormous stuffed troll, ran on a short way, took a left at the broken Vanishing Cabi\-net in which Montague had got lost the previous year, finally paus\-ing beside a large cupboard that seemed to have had acid thrown at its blistered surface. He opened one of the cupboard\rquote s creaking doors: It had already been used as a hiding place for something in a cage that had long since died; its skeleton had five legs. He stuffed\lang3081  \lang1033 the Half-Blood Prince\rquote s book behind the cage and slammed the door. He paused for a moment, his heart thumping horribly, gaz\-ing around at all the clutter. \'85 Would he be able to find this spot again amidst all this junk? Seizing the chipped bust of an ugly old warlock from on top of a nearby crate, he stood it on top of the cupboard where the book was now hidden, perched a dusty old wig and a tarnished tiara on the statue\rquote s head to make it more distinc\-tive, then sprinted back through the alleyways of hidden junk as fast as he could go, back to the door, back out onto the corridor, where he slammed the door behind him, and it turned at once back into stone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry ran flat-out toward the bathroom on the floor below, cramming Ron\rquote s copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making\i0  into his bag as he did so. A minute later, he was back in front of Snape, who held out his hand wordlessly for Harry\rquote s schoolbag. Harry handed it over, panting, a searing pain in his chest, and waited.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 One by one, Snape extracted Harry\rquote s books and examined them. Finally, the only book left was the Potions book, which he looked at very carefully before speaking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is your copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making,\i0  is it, Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, still breathing hard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re quite sure of that, are you, Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, with a touch more defiance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is the copy of \i Advanced Potion-Making\i0  that you purchased from Flourish and Blotts?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry firmly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then why,\rdblquote  asked Snape, \ldblquote does it have the name \lquote Roonil Waz\-lib\rquote  written inside the front cover?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s heart missed a beat. \ldblquote That\rquote s my nickname,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your nickname,\rdblquote  repeated Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 that\rquote s what my friends call me,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I understand what a nickname is,\rdblquote  said Snape. The cold, black eyes were boring once more into Harry\rquote s; he tried not to look into them. \i Close your mind. \'85\i0  \i Close your mind. \'85\i0  But he had never learned how to do it properly. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you know what I think, Potter?\rdblquote  said Snape, very quietly. \ldblquote I think that you are a liar and a cheat and that you deserve detention with me every Saturday until the end of term. What do you think, Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  I don\rquote t agree, sir,\rdblquote  said Harry, still refusing to look into Snape\rquote s eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, we shall see how you feel after your detentions,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote Ten o\rquote clock Saturday morning, Potter. My office.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But sir \'85\rdblquote  said Harry, looking up desperately. \ldblquote Quidditch \'85 the last match of the \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ten o\rquote clock,\rdblquote  whispered Snape, with a smile that showed his yellow teeth. \ldblquote Poor Gryffindor\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 fourth place this year, I fear\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he left the bathroom without another word, leaving Harry to stare into the cracked mirror, feeling sicker, he was sure, than Ron had ever felt in his life.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I won\rquote t say \lquote I told you so,\rquote  \rdblquote  said Hermione, an hour later in the common room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Leave it, Hermione,\rdblquote  said Ron angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had never made it to dinner; he had no appetite at all. He had just finished telling Ron, Hermione, and Ginny what had hap\-pened, not that there seemed to have been much need. The news had traveled very fast: Apparently Moaning Myrtle had taken it\lang3081  \lang1033 upon herself to pop up in every bathroom in the castle to tell the story; Malfoy had already been visited in the hospital wing by Pansy Parkinson, who had lost no time in vilifying Harry far and wide, and Snape had told the staff precisely what had happened. Harry had already been called out of the common room to endure fifteen highly unpleasant minutes in the company of Professor McGonagall, who had told him he was lucky not to have been ex\-pelled and that she supported wholeheartedly Snape\rquote s punishment of detention every Saturday until the end of term.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I told you there was something wrong with that Prince person,\rdblquote  Hermione said, evidently unable to stop herself. \ldblquote And I was right, wasn\rquote t I?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I don\rquote t think you were,\rdblquote  said Harry stubbornly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was having a bad enough time without Hermione lecturing him; the looks on the Gryffindor team\rquote s faces when he had told them he would not be able to play on Saturday had been the worst punishment of all. He could feel Ginny\rquote s eyes on him now but did not meet them; he did not want to see disappointment or anger there. He had just told her that she would be playing Seeker on Sat\-urday and that Dean would be rejoining the team as Chaser in her place. Perhaps, if they won, Ginny and Dean would make up dur\-ing the post-match euphoria. \'85 The thought went through Harry like an icy knife. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote how can you still stick up for that book when that spell \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
