The fact that Harry Potter was going out with Ginny Weasley seemed to interest a great number of people, most of them girls, yet Harry found himself newly and happily impervi\-ous to gossip over the next few weeks. After all, it made a very nice change to be talked about because of something that was making him happier than he could remember being for a very long time, rather than because he had been involved in horrific scenes of Dark Magic.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote d think people had better things to gossip about,\rdblquote  said Ginny, as she sat on the common room floor, leaning against Harry\rquote s legs and reading the \i Daily Prophet.\i0  \ldblquote Three dementor at\-tacks in a week, and all Romilda Vane does is ask me if it\rquote s true you\rquote ve got a hippogriff tattooed across your chest.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Hermione both roared with laughter. Harry ignored them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did you tell her?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I told her it\rquote s a Hungarian Horntail,\rdblquote  said Ginny, turning a page of the newspaper idly. \ldblquote Much more macho.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry, grinning. \ldblquote And what did you tell her Ron\rquote s got?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A Pygmy Puff, but I didn\rquote t say where.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron scowled as Hermione rolled around laughing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Watch it,\rdblquote  he said, pointing warningly at Harry and Ginny. \ldblquote Just because I\rquote ve given my permission doesn\rquote t mean I can\rquote t with\-draw it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\i Your\lang3081  \lang1033 permission,\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\i  \lang1033\i0 scoffed Ginny. \ldblquote Since when did you give me permission to do anything? Anyway, you said yourself you\rquote d rather it was Harry than Michael or Dean.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I would,\rdblquote  said Ron grudgingly. \ldblquote And just as long as you don\rquote t start snogging each other in public \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You filthy hypocrite! What about you and Lavender, thrashing around like a pair of eels all over the place?\rdblquote  demanded Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Ron\rquote s tolerance was not to be tested much as they moved into June, for Harry and Ginny\rquote s time together was becoming in\-creasingly restricted. Ginny\rquote s O.W.L.s were approaching and she was therefore forced to study for hours into the night. On one such evening, when Ginny had retired to the library, and Harry was sit\-ting beside the window in the common room, supposedly finishing his Herbology homework but in reality reliving a particularly happy hour he had spent down by the lake with Ginny at lunch\-time, Hermione dropped into the seat between him and Ron with an unpleasantly purposeful look on her face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want to talk to you, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What about?\rdblquote  said Harry suspiciously. Only the previous day,\lang3081  \lang1033 Hermione had told him off for distracting Ginny when she ought to be working hard for her examinations.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The so-called Half-Blood Prince.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, not again,\rdblquote  he groaned. \ldblquote Will you please drop it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had not dared to return to the Room of Requirement to re\-trieve his book, and his performance in Potions was suffering ac\-cordingly (though Slughorn, who approved of Ginny, had jocularly attributed this to Harry being lovesick). But Harry was sure that Snape had not yet given up hope of laying hands on the Prince\rquote s book, and was determined to leave it where it was while Snape re\-mained on the lookout.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not dropping it,\rdblquote  said Hermione firmly, \ldblquote until you\rquote ve heard me out. Now, I\rquote ve been trying to find out a bit about who might make a hobby of inventing Dark spells \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He didn\rquote t make a hobby of it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He, he \emdash  who says it\rquote s a he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve been through this,\rdblquote  said Harry crossly. \ldblquote\i Prince,\i0  Hermi\-one, \i Prince\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right!\rdblquote  said Hermione, red patches blazing in her cheeks as she pulled a very old piece of newsprint out of her pocket and slammed it down on the table in front of Harry. \ldblquote Look at that! Look at the picture!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry picked up the crumbling piece of paper and stared at the moving photograph, yellowed with age; Ron leaned over for a look too. The picture showed a skinny girl of around fifteen. She was not pretty; she looked simultaneously cross and sullen, with heavy brows and a long, pallid face. Underneath the photograph was the caption: EILEEN PRINCE, CAPTAIN OF THE HOGWARTS GOBSTONES TEAM.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So?\rdblquote  said Harry, scanning the short news item to which the pic\-ture belonged; it was a rather dull story about interschool compe\-titions.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Her name was Eileen Prince. \i Prince,\i0  Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They looked at each other, and Harry realized what Hermione was trying to say. He burst out laughing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No way.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You think \i she\i0  was the Half-Blood \'85 ? Oh, come on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, why not? Harry, there aren\rquote t any real princes in the Wiz\-arding world! It\rquote s either a nickname, a made-up title somebody\rquote s given themselves, or it could be their actual name, couldn\rquote t it? No, listen! If, say, her father was a wizard whose surname was Prince, and her mother was a Muggle, then that would make her a \lquote half-blood Prince\rquote !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, very ingenious, Hermione \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But it would! Maybe she was proud of being half a Prince!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Listen, Hermione, I can tell it\rquote s not a girl. I can just tell.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The truth is that you don\rquote t think a girl would have been clever enough,\rdblquote  said Hermione angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How can I have hung round with you for five years and not think girls are clever?\rdblquote  said Harry, stung by this. \ldblquote It\rquote s the way he writes, I just know the Prince was a bloke, I can tell. This girl hasn\rquote t got anything to do with it. Where did you get this anyway?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The library,\rdblquote  said Hermione predictably. \ldblquote There\rquote s a whole col\-lection of old \i Prophets\i0  up there. Well, I\rquote m going to find out more about Eileen Prince if I can.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Enjoy yourself,\rdblquote  said Harry irritably.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I will,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote And the first place I\rquote ll look,\rdblquote  she shot\lang3081  \lang1033 at him, as she reached the portrait hole, \ldblquote is records of old Potions awards!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry scowled after her for a moment, then continued his con\-templation of the darkening sky.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She\rquote s just never got over you outperforming her in Potions,\rdblquote  said Ron, returning to his copy of \i A Thousand Magical Herbs and Fungi.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t think I\rquote m mad, wanting that book back, do you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Course not,\rdblquote  said Ron robustly. \ldblquote He was a genius, the Prince. Anyway \'85 without his bezoar tip \'85\rdblquote  He drew his finger signifi\-cantly across his own throat. \ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t be here to discuss it, would I? I mean, I\rquote m not saying that spell you used on Malfoy was great \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nor am I,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But he healed all right, didn\rquote t he? Back on his feet in no time.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry; this was perfectly true, although his con\-science squirmed slightly all the same. \ldblquote Thanks to Snape \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You still got detention with Snape this Saturday?\rdblquote  Ron con\-tinued.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, and the Saturday after that, and the Saturday after that,\rdblquote  sighed Harry. \ldblquote And he\rquote s hinting now that if I don\rquote t get all the boxes done by the end of term, we\rquote ll carry on next year.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was finding these detentions particularly irksome because they cut into the already limited time he could have been spending with Ginny. Indeed, he had frequently wondered lately whether Snape did not know this, for he was keeping Harry later and later every time, while making pointed asides about Harry having to miss the good weather and the varied opportunities it offered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was shaken from these bitter reflections by the appearance\lang3081  \lang1033 at his side of Jimmy Peakes, who was holding out a scroll of parchment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks, Jimmy \'85 Hey, it\rquote s from Dumbledore!\rdblquote  said Harry excitedly, unrolling the parchment and scanning it. \ldblquote He wants me to go to his office as quick as I can!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They stared at each other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Blimey,\rdblquote  whispered Ron. \ldblquote You don\rquote t reckon\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 he hasn\rquote t found \'85 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Better go and see, hadn\rquote t I?\rdblquote  said Harry, jumping to his feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He hurried out of the common room and along the seventh floor as fast as he could, passing nobody but Peeves, who swooped past in the opposite direction, throwing bits of chalk at Harry in a routine sort of way and cackling loudly as he dodged Harry\rquote s de\-fensive jinx. Once Peeves had vanished, there was silence in the corridors; with only fifteen minutes left until curfew, most people had already returned to their common rooms.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then Harry heard a scream and a crash. He stopped in his tracks, listening.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How \emdash  \i dare\i0  \emdash  you \emdash  aaaaargh!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The noise was coming from a corridor nearby; Harry sprinted toward it, his wand at the ready, hurtled around another corner, and saw Professor Trelawney sprawled upon the floor, her head covered in one of her many shawls, several sherry bottles lying be\-side her, one broken.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry hurried forward and helped Professor Trelawney to her feet. Some of her glittering beads had become entangled with her glasses. She hiccuped loudly, patted her hair, and pulled herself up on Harry\rquote s helping arm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What happened, Professor?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You may well ask!\rdblquote  she said shrilly. \ldblquote I was strolling along, brood\-ing upon certain dark portents I happen to have glimpsed \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry was not paying much attention. He had just noticed where they were standing: There on the right was the tapestry of dancing trolls, and on the left, that smoothly impenetrable stretch of stone wall that concealed \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor, were you trying to get into the Room of Require\-ment?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 omens I have been vouchsafed \emdash  what?\rdblquote  She looked sud\-denly shifty.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Room of Requirement,\rdblquote  repeated Harry. \ldblquote Were you trying to get in there?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  well \emdash  I didn\rquote t know students knew about \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not all of them do,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote But what happened? You screamed. \'85 It sounded as though you were hurt. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  well,\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney, drawing her shawls around her defensively and staring down at him with her vastly magnified eyes. \ldblquote I wished to \emdash  ah \emdash  deposit certain \emdash  um \emdash  personal items in the room. \'85\rdblquote  And she muttered something about \ldblquote nasty accusa\-tions.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry, glancing down at the sherry bottles. \ldblquote But you couldn\rquote t get in and hide them?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He found this very odd; the room had opened for him, after all, when he had wanted to hide the Half-Blood Prince\rquote s book.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I got in all right,\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney, glaring at the wall. \ldblquote But there was somebody already in there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Somebody in \emdash  ? Who?\rdblquote  demanded Harry. \ldblquote Who was in there?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have no idea,\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney, looking slightly taken aback at the urgency in Harry\rquote s voice. \ldblquote I walked into the room and I heard a voice, which has never happened before in all my years of hiding \emdash  of using the room, I mean.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A voice? Saying what?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know that it was saying anything,\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney. \ldblquote It was \'85 whooping.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Whooping\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gleefully,\rdblquote  she said, nodding.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared at her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Was it male or female?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I would hazard a guess at male,\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And it sounded happy?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
