\lang1033\ldblquote I am afraid,\rdblquote  she went on, \ldblquote that the nag \emdash  I\rquote m sorry, the cen\-taur \emdash  knows nothing of cartomancy. I asked him \emdash  one Seer to another \emdash  had he not, too, sensed the distant vibrations of com\-ing catastrophe? But he seemed to find me almost comical. Yes, comical!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Her voice rose rather hysterically, and Harry caught a powerful whiff of sherry even though the bottles had been left behind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Perhaps the horse has heard people say that I have not inherited my great-great-grandmother\rquote s gift. Those rumors have been bandied about by the jealous for years. You know what I say to such people, Harry? Would Dumbledore have let me teach at this great school, put so much trust in me all these years, had I not proved myself to him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry mumbled something indistinct.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I well remember my first interview with Dumbledore,\rdblquote  went on Professor Trelawney, in throaty tones. \ldblquote He was deeply im\-pressed, of course, deeply impressed. \'85 I was staying at the Hog\rquote s Head, which I do not advise, incidentally \emdash  bedbugs, dear boy \emdash  but funds were low. Dumbledore did me the courtesy of calling upon me in my room. He questioned me. \'85 I must confess that, at first, I thought he seemed ill-disposed toward Divination \'85 and I remember I was starting to feel a little odd, I had not eaten much that day \'85 but then \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And now Harry was paying attention properly for the first time,\lang3081  \lang1033 for he knew what had happened then: Professor Trelawney had made the prophecy that had altered the course of his whole life, the prophecy about him and Voldemort.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 but then we were rudely interrupted by Severus Snape!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, there was a commotion outside the door and it flew open, and there was that rather uncouth barman standing with Snape, who was waffling about having come the wrong way up the stairs, although I\rquote m afraid that I myself rather thought he had been ap\-prehended eavesdropping on my interview with Dumbledore \emdash  you see, he himself was seeking a job at the time, and no doubt hoped to pick up tips! Well, after that, you know, Dumbledore seemed much more disposed to give me a job, and I could not help thinking, Harry, that it was because he appreciated the stark con\-trast between my own unassuming manners and quiet talent, com\-pared to the pushing, thrusting young man who was prepared to listen at keyholes \emdash  Harry, dear?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked back over her shoulder, having only just realized that Harry was no longer with her; he had stopped walking and they were now ten feet from each other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote  she repeated uncertainly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Perhaps his face was white to make her look so concerned and frightened. Harry was standing stock-still as waves of shock crashed over him, wave after wave, obliterating everything except the information that had been kept from him for so long. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was Snape who had overheard the prophecy. It was Snape who had carried the news of the prophecy to Voldemort. Snape and Peter Pettigrew together had sent Voldemort hunting after Lily and James and their son. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nothing else mattered to Harry just now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney again. \ldblquote Harry \emdash  I thought we were going to see the headmaster together?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You stay here,\rdblquote  said Harry through numb lips.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But dear \'85 I was going to tell him how I was assaulted in the Room of\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You stay here!\rdblquote  Harry repeated angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked alarmed as he ran past her, around the corner into Dumbledore\rquote s corridor, where the lone gargoyle stood sentry. Harry shouted the password at the gargoyle and ran up the moving spiral staircase three steps at a time. He did not knock upon Dum\-bledore\rquote s door, he hammered; and the calm voice answered, \ldblquote En\-ter\rdblquote  after Harry had already flung himself into the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fawkes the phoenix looked around, his bright black eyes gleam\-ing with reflected gold from the sunset beyond the windows. Dumbledore was standing at the window looking out at the grounds, a long, black traveling cloak in his arms.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Harry, I promised that you could come with me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 For a moment or two, Harry did not understand; the conversa\-tion with Trelawney had driven everything else out of his head and his brain seemed to be moving very slowly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come \'85 with you \'85 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Only if you wish it, of course.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If I \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then Harry remembered why he had been eager to come to Dumbledore\rquote s office in the first place. \ldblquote You\rquote ve found one? You\rquote ve found a Horcrux?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I believe so.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Rage and resentment fought shock and excitement: For several moments, Harry could not speak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is natural to be afraid,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not scared!\rdblquote  said Harry at once, and it was perfectly true; fear was one emotion he was not feeling at all. \ldblquote Which Horcrux is it? Where is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am not sure which it is \emdash  though I think we can rule out the snake \emdash  but I believe it to be hidden in a cave on the coast many miles from here, a cave I have been trying to locate for a very long time: the cave in which Tom Riddle once terrorized two children from his orphanage on their annual trip; you remember?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote How is it protected?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I do not know; I have suspicions that may be entirely wrong.\rdblquote  Dumbledore hesitated, then said, \ldblquote Harry, I promised you that you could come with me, and I stand by that promise, but it would be very wrong of me not to warn you that this will be exceedingly dangerous.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m coming,\rdblquote  said Harry, almost before Dumbledore had fin\-ished speaking. Boiling with anger at Snape, his desire to do some\-thing desperate and risky had increased tenfold in the last few minutes. This seemed to show on Harry\rquote s face, for Dumbledore moved away from the window and looked more closely at Harry, a slight crease between his silver eyebrows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What has happened to you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  lied Harry promptly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What has upset you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not upset.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, you were never a good Occlumens \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The word was the spark that ignited Harry\rquote s fury.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Snape!\rdblquote  he said, very loudly, and Fawkes gave a soft squawk be\-hind them. \ldblquote Snape\rquote s what\rquote s happened! He told Voldemort about the prophecy, it was \i him,\i0  he listened outside the door, Trelawney told me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore\rquote s expression did not change, but Harry thought his face whitened under the bloody tinge cast by the setting sun. For a long moment, Dumbledore said nothing. \ldblquote When did you find out about this?\rdblquote  he asked at last.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just now!\rdblquote  said Harry, who was refraining from yelling with enormous difficulty. And then, suddenly, he could not stop him\-self. \ldblquote AND YOU LET HIM TEACH HERE AND HE TOLD VOLDEMORT TO GO AFTER MY MUM AND DAD!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Breathing hard as though he was fighting, Harry turned away from Dumbledore, who still had not moved a muscle, and paced up and down the study, rubbing his knuckles in his hand and exer\-cising every last bit of restraint to prevent himself knocking things over. He wanted to rage and storm at Dumbledore, but he also wanted to go with him to try and destroy the Horcrux; he wanted to tell him that he was a foolish old man for trusting Snape, but he was terrified that Dumbledore would not take him along unless he mastered his anger. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly. \ldblquote Please listen to me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was as difficult to stop his relentless pacing as to refrain from shouting. Harry paused, biting his lip, and looked into Dumble\-dore\rquote s lined face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Snape made a terrible \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t tell me it was a mistake, sir, he was listening at the door!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please let me finish.\rdblquote  Dumbledore waited until Harry had\lang3081  \lang1033 nodded curtly, then went on. \ldblquote Professor Snape made a terrible mis\-take. He was still in Lord Voldemort\rquote s employ on the night he heard the first half of Professor Trelawney\rquote s prophecy. Naturally, he hastened to tell his master what he had heard, for it concerned his master most deeply. But he did not know \emdash  he had no possible way of know\-ing \emdash  which boy Voldemort would hunt from then onward, or that the parents he would destroy in his murderous quest were people that Professor Snape knew, that they were your mother and father \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry let out a yell of mirthless laughter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He hated my dad like he hated Sirius! Haven\rquote t you noticed, Professor, how the people Snape hates tend to end up dead?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You have no idea of the remorse Professor Snape felt when he realized how Lord Voldemort had interpreted the prophecy, Harry. I believe it to be the greatest regret of his life and the reason that he returned \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But \i he\rquote s\i0  a very good Occlumens, isn\rquote t he, sir?\rdblquote  said Harry, whose voice was shaking with the effort of keeping it steady. \ldblquote And isn\rquote t Voldemort convinced that Snape\rquote s on his side, even now? Professor \'85 how can you be \i sure\i0  Snape\rquote s on our side?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore did not speak for a moment; he looked as though he was trying to make up his mind about something. At last he said, \ldblquote I am sure. I trust Severus Snape completely.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry breathed deeply for a few moments in an effort to steady himself. It did not work.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I don\rquote t!\rdblquote  he said, as loudly as before. \ldblquote He\rquote s up to some\-thing with Draco Malfoy right now, right under your nose, and you still \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We have discussed this, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, and now he sounded stern again. \ldblquote I have told you my views.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re leaving the school tonight, and I\rquote ll bet you haven\rquote t even considered that Snape and Malfoy might decide to \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote To what?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore, his eyebrows raised. \ldblquote What is it that you suspect them of doing, precisely?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85 they\rquote re up to something!\rdblquote  said Harry, and his hands curled into fists as he said it. \ldblquote Professor Trelawney was just in the Room of Requirement, trying to hide her sherry bottles, and she heard Mal\-foy whooping, celebrating! He\rquote s trying to mend something danger\-ous in there and if you ask me, he\rquote s fixed it at last and you\rquote re about to just walk out of school without \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Enough,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. He said it quite calmly, and yet Harry fell silent at once; he knew that he had finally crossed some invisible line. \ldblquote Do you think that I have once left the school un\-protected during my absences this year? I have not. Tonight, when I leave, there will again be additional protection in place. Please do not suggest that I do not take the safety of my students seriously, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote  mumbled Harry, a little abashed, but Dumbledore cut across him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I do not wish to discuss the matter any further.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry bit back his retort, scared that he had gone too far, that he had ruined his chance of accompanying Dumbledore, but Dum\-bledore went on, \ldblquote Do you wish to come with me tonight?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well, then: Listen.\rdblquote  Dumbledore drew himself up to his full height. \ldblquote I take you with me on one condition: that you obey any command I might give you at once, and without question.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Be sure to understand me, Harry. I mean that you must follow\lang3081  \lang1033 even such orders as \lquote run,\rquote  \lquote hide,\rquote  or \lquote go back.\rquote  Do I have your word?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  yes, of course.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If I tell you to hide, you will do so?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If I tell you to flee, you will obey?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If I tell you to leave me and save yourself, you will do as I tell you?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They looked at each other for a moment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very good. Then I wish you to go and fetch your Invisibility Cloak and meet me in the entrance hall in five minutes\rquote  time.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore turned back to look out of the fiery window; the sun was now a ruby red glare along the horizon. Harry walked quickly from the office and down the spiral staircase. His mind was oddly clear all of a sudden. He knew what to do.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Hermione were sitting together in the common room when he came back. \ldblquote What does he want?\rdblquote  Hermione said at once. \ldblquote Harry, are you okay?\rdblquote  she added anxiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m fine,\rdblquote  said Harry shortly, racing past them. He dashed up the stairs and into his dormitory, where he flung open his trunk and pulled out the Marauder\rquote s Map and a pair of balled-up socks. Then he sped back down the stairs and into the common room, skidding to a halt where Ron and Hermione sat, looking stunned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve got to be quick,\rdblquote  Harry panted. \ldblquote Dumbledore thinks I\rquote m getting my Invisibility Cloak. Listen. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Quickly he told them where he was going and why. He did not pause either for Hermione\rquote s gasps of horror or for Ron\rquote s hasty ques\-tions; they could work out the finer details for themselves later.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 so you see what this means?\rdblquote  Harry finished at a gallop. \ldblquote Dumbledore won\rquote t be here tonight, so Malfoy\rquote s going to have an\-other clear shot at whatever he\rquote s up to. \i No, listen to me\i0 !\rdblquote  he hissed angrily, as both Ron and Hermione showed every sign of interrupt\-ing. \ldblquote I know it was Malfoy celebrating in the Room of Require\-ment. Here \emdash\rdblquote  He shoved the Marauder\rquote s Map into Hermione\rquote s hands. \ldblquote You\rquote ve got to watch him and you\rquote ve got to watch Snape too. Use anyone else who you can rustle up from the D.A., Hermione, those contact Galleons will still work, right? Dumbledore says he\rquote s put extra protection in the school, but if Snape\rquote s involved, he\rquote ll know what Dumbledore\rquote s protection is, and how to avoid it \emdash  but he won\rquote t be expecting you lot to be on the watch, will he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry \emdash\rdblquote  began Hermione, her eyes huge with fear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I haven\rquote t got time to argue,\rdblquote  said Harry curtly. \ldblquote Take this as well \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He thrust the socks into Ron\rquote s hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Er \emdash  why do I need socks?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You need what\rquote s wrapped in them, it\rquote s the Felix Felicis. Share it between yourselves and Ginny too. Say good-bye to her for me. I\rquote d better go, Dumbledore\rquote s waiting \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  said Hermione, as Ron unwrapped the tiny little bottle of golden potion, looking awestruck. \ldblquote We don\rquote t want it, you take it, who knows what you\rquote re going to be facing?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll be fine, I\rquote ll be with Dumbledore,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I want to know you lot are okay. \'85 Don\rquote t look like that, Hermione, I\rquote ll see you later. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he was off, hurrying back through the portrait hole and to\-ward the entrance hall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore was waiting beside the oaken front doors. He turned as Harry came skidding out onto the topmost stone step, panting hard, a searing stitch in his side.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I would like you to wear your cloak, please,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, and he waited until Harry had thrown it on before saying, \ldblquote Very good. Shall we go?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore set off at once down the stone steps, his own trav\-eling cloak barely stirring in the still summer air. Harry hurried alongside him under the Invisibility Cloak, still panting and sweat\-ing rather a lot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what will people think when they see you leaving, Profes\-sor?\rdblquote  Harry asked, his mind on Malfoy and Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That I am off into Hogsmeade for a drink,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore lightly. \ldblquote I sometimes offer Rosmerta my custom, or else visit the Hog\rquote s Head \'85 or I appear to. It is as good a way as any of dis\-guising one\rquote s true destination.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They made their way down the drive in the gathering twilight. The air was full of the smells of warm grass, lake water, and wood smoke from Hagrid\rquote s cabin. It was difficult to believe that they were heading for anything dangerous or frightening.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor,\rdblquote  said Harry quietly, as the gates at the bottom of the drive came into view, \ldblquote will we be Apparating?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote You can Apparate now, I believe?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote but I haven\rquote t got a license.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He felt it best to be honest; what if he spoiled everything by turning up a hundred miles from where he was supposed to go?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No matter,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote I can assist you again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They turned out of the gates into the twilit, deserted lane to Hogsmeade. Darkness descended fast as they walked, and by the time they reached the High Street night was falling in earnest. Lights twinkled from windows over shops and as they neared the Three Broomsticks they heard raucous shouting.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and stay out!\rdblquote  shouted Madam Rosmerta, forcibly ejecting a grubby-looking wizard. \ldblquote Oh, hello, Albus \'85 You\rquote re out late \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good evening, Rosmerta, good evening \'85 forgive me, I\rquote m off to the Hog\rquote s Head. \'85 No offense, but I feel like a quieter atmo\-sphere tonight. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A minute later they turned the corner into the side street where the Hog\rquote s Head\rquote s sign creaked a little, though there was no breeze. In contrast to the Three Broomsticks, the pub appeared to be com\-pletely empty.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It will not be necessary for us to enter,\rdblquote  muttered Dumbledore, glancing around. \ldblquote As long as nobody sees us go \'85 now place your hand upon my arm, Harry. There is no need to grip too hard, I am merely guiding you. On the count of three \'85 One \'85 two \'85 three \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned. At once, there was that horrible sensation that he was being squeezed through a thick rubber tube; he could not draw breath, every part of him was being compressed almost past en\-durance and then, just when he thought he must suffocate, the in\-visible bands seemed to burst open, and he was standing in cool darkness, breathing in lungfuls of fresh, salty air.\lang3081\par
