\lang1033\ldblquote\i Blood\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I said it was crude,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, who sounded disdainful, even disappointed, as though Voldemort had fallen short of the standards Dumbledore expected. \ldblquote The idea, as I am sure you will have gathered, is that your enemy must weaken him- or herself to enter. Once again, Lord Voldemort fails to grasp that there are much more terrible things than physical injury.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, but still, if you can avoid it\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  said Harry, who had ex\-perienced enough pain not to be keen for more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sometimes, however, it is unavoidable,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, shaking back the sleeve of his robes and exposing the forearm of his injured hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor!\rdblquote  protested Harry, hurrying forward as Dumbledore raised his knife. \ldblquote I\rquote ll do it, I\rquote m \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He did not know what he was going to say \emdash  younger, fitter?\lang3081  \lang1033 But Dumbledore merely smiled. There was a flash of silver, and a spurt of scarlet; the rock face was peppered with dark, glistening drops.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are very kind, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, now passing the tip of his wand over the deep cut he had made in his own arm, so that it healed instantly, just as Snape had healed Malfoy\rquote s wounds. \ldblquote But your blood is worth more than mine. Ah, that seems to have done the trick, doesn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The blazing silver outline of an arch had appeared in the wall once more, and this time it did not fade away: The blood-spattered rock within it simply vanished, leaving an opening into what seemed total darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote After me, I think,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, and he walked through the archway with Harry on his heels, lighting his own wand hastily as he went.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 An eerie sight met their eyes: They were standing on the edge of a great black lake, so vast that Harry could not make out the dis\-tant banks, in a cavern so high that the ceiling too was out of sight. A misty greenish light shone far away in what looked like the mid\-dle of the lake; it was reflected in the completely still water below. The greenish glow and the light from the two wands were the only things that broke the otherwise velvety blackness, though their rays did not penetrate as far as Harry would have expected. The dark\-ness was somehow denser than normal darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let us walk,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly. \ldblquote Be very careful not to step into the water. Stay close to me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He set off around the edge of the lake, and Harry followed close behind him. Their footsteps made echoing, slapping sounds on the narrow rim of rock that surrounded the water. On and on they\lang3081  \lang1033 walked, but the view did not vary: on one side of them, the rough cavern wall, on the other, the boundless expanse of smooth, glassy blackness, in the very middle of which was that mysterious greenish glow. Harry found the place and the silence oppressive, unnerving.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor?\rdblquote  he said finally. \ldblquote Do you think the Horcrux is here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Yes, I\rquote m sure it is. The question is, how do we get to it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We couldn\rquote t\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 we couldn\rquote t just try a Summoning Charm?\rdblquote  Harry said, sure that it was a stupid suggestion. But he was much keener than he was prepared to admit on getting out of this place as soon as possible.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Certainly we could,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, stopping so suddenly that Harry almost walked into him. \ldblquote Why don\rquote t you do it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Me? Oh \'85 okay \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had not expected this, but cleared his throat and said loudly, wand aloft, \ldblquote\i Accio Horcrux\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a noise like an explosion, something very large and pale erupted out of the dark water some twenty feet away; before Harry could see what it was, it had vanished again with a crashing splash that made great, deep ripples on the mirrored surface. Harry leapt backward in shock and hit the wall; his heart was still thundering as he turned to Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What was that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Something, I think, that is ready to respond should we attempt to seize the Horcrux.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked back at the water. The surface of the lake was once more shining black glass: The ripples had vanished unnaturally fast; Harry\rquote s heart, however, was still pounding.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you think that would happen, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought \i something\i0  would happen if we made an obvious at\-tempt to get our hands on the Horcrux. That was a very good idea, Harry; much the simplest way of finding out what we are facing.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But we don\rquote t know what the thing was,\rdblquote  said Harry, looking at the sinisterly smooth water.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What the things \i are,\i0  you mean,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I doubt very much that there is only one of them. Shall we walk on?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you think we\rquote re going to have to go into the lake?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Into it? Only if we are very unfortunate.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t think the Horcrux is at the bottom?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh no \'85 I think the Horcrux is in the \i middle.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And Dumbledore pointed toward the misty green light in the center of the lake.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So we\rquote re going to have to cross the lake to get to it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I think so.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not say anything. His thoughts were all of water mon\-sters, of giant serpents, of demons, kelpies, and sprites. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aha,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, and he stopped again; this time, Harry really did walk into him; for a moment he toppled on the edge of the dark water, and Dumbledore\rquote s uninjured hand closed tightly around his upper arm, pulling him back. \ldblquote So sorry, Harry, I should have given warning. Stand back against the wall, please; I think I have found the place.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had no idea what Dumbledore meant; this patch of dark bank was exactly like every other bit as far as he could tell, but Dumbledore seemed to have detected something special about it. This time he was running his hand, not over the rocky wall, but\lang3081  \lang1033 through the thin air, as though expecting to find and grip some\-thing invisible.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oho,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore happily, seconds later. His hand had closed in midair upon something Harry could not see. Dumble\-dore moved closer to the water; Harry watched nervously as the tips of Dumbledore\rquote s buckled shoes found the utmost edge of the rock rim. Keeping his hand clenched in midair, Dumbledore raised his wand with the other and tapped his fist with the point.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Immediately a thick coppery green chain appeared out of thin air, extending from the depths of the water into Dumbledore\rquote s clenched hand. Dumbledore tapped the chain, which began to slide through his fist like a snake, coiling itself on the ground with a clinking sound that echoed noisily off the rocky walls, pulling something from the depths of the black water. Harry gasped as the ghostly prow of a tiny boat broke the surface, glowing as green as the chain, and floated, with barely a ripple, toward the place on the bank where Harry and Dumbledore stood.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How did you know that was there?\rdblquote  Harry asked in astonish\-ment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Magic always leaves traces,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, as the boat hit the bank with a gentle bump, \ldblquote sometimes very distinctive traces. I taught Tom Riddle. I know his style.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is \'85 is this boat safe?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes, I think so. Voldemort needed to create a means to cross the lake without attracting the wrath of those creatures he had placed within it in case he ever wanted to visit or remove his Horcrux.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So the things in the water won\rquote t do anything to us if we cross in Voldemort\rquote s boat?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think we must resign ourselves to the fact that they will, at some point, realize we are not Lord Voldemort. Thus far, however, we have done well. They have allowed us to raise the boat.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But why have they let us?\rdblquote  asked Harry, who could not shake off the vision of tentacles rising out of the dark water the moment they were out of sight of the bank.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Voldemort would have been reasonably confident that none but a very great wizard would have been able to find the boat,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I think he would have been prepared to risk what was, to his mind, the most unlikely possibility that somebody else would find it, knowing that he had set other obstacles ahead that only he would be able to penetrate. We shall see whether he is right.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked down into the boat. It really was very small.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t look like it was built for two people. Will it hold both of us? Will we be too heavy together?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore chuckled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Voldemort will not have cared about the weight, but about the amount of magical power that crossed his lake. I rather think an enchantment will have been placed upon this boat so that only one wizard at a time will be able to sail in it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But then \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I do not think you will count, Harry: You are underage and un\-qualified. Voldemort would never have expected a sixteen-year-old to reach this place: I think it unlikely that your powers will register compared to mine.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 These words did nothing to raise Harry\rquote s morale; perhaps Dumbledore knew it, for he added, \ldblquote Voldemort\rquote s mistake, Harry, Voldemort\rquote s mistake \'85 Age is foolish and forgetful when it\lang3081  \lang1033 underestimates youth. \'85 Now, you first this time, and be careful not to touch the water.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore stood aside and Harry climbed carefully into the boat. Dumbledore stepped in too, coiling the chain onto the floor. They were crammed in together; Harry could not comfortably sit, but crouched, his knees jutting over the edge of the boat, which be\-gan to move at once. There was no sound other than the silken rus\-tle of the boat\rquote s prow cleaving the water; it moved without their help, as though an invisible rope was pulling it onward toward the light in the center. Soon they could no longer see the walls of the cavern; they might have been at sea except that there were no waves.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked down and saw the reflected gold of his wandlight sparkling and glittering on the black water as they passed. The boat was carving deep ripples upon the glassy surface, grooves in the dark mirror. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then Harry saw it, marble white, floating inches below the surface.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor!\rdblquote  he said, and his startled voice echoed loudly over the silent water.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think I saw a hand in the water \emdash  a human hand!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I am sure you did,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore calmly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared down into the water, looking for the vanished hand, and a sick feeling rose in his throat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So that thing that jumped out of the water \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry had his answer before Dumbledore could reply; the wandlight had slid over a fresh patch of water and showed him, this time, a dead man lying faceup inches beneath the surface, his open\lang3081  \lang1033 eyes misted as though with cobwebs, his hair and his robes swirling around him like smoke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There are bodies in here!\rdblquote  said Harry, and his voice sounded much higher than usual and most unlike his own.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore placidly, \ldblquote but we do not need to worry about them at the moment.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote At the moment?\rdblquote  Harry repeated, tearing his gaze from the wa\-ter to look at Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not while they are merely drifting peacefully below us,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote There is nothing to be feared from a body, Harry, any more than there is anything to be feared from the darkness. Lord Voldemort, who of course secretly fears both, disagrees. But once again he reveals his own lack of wisdom. It is the unknown we fear when we look upon death and darkness, nothing more.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry said nothing; he did not want to argue, but he found the idea that there were bodies floating around them and beneath them horrible and, what was more, he did not believe that they were not dangerous.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But one of them jumped,\rdblquote  he said, trying to make his voice as level and calm as Dumbledore\rquote s. \ldblquote When I tried to Summon the Horcrux, a body leapt out of the lake.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I am sure that once we take the Horcrux, we shall find them less peaceable. However, like many creatures that dwell in cold and darkness, they fear light and warmth, which we shall therefore call to our aid should the need arise. Fire, Harry,\rdblquote  Dumbledore added with a smile, in response to Harry\rquote s bewildered expression.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \'85 right\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. He turned his head to look at the greenish glow toward which the boat was still inexorably\lang3081  \lang1033 sailing. He could not pretend now that he was not scared. The great black lake, teeming with the dead \'85 It seemed hours and hours ago that he had met Professor Trelawney, that he had given Ron and Hermione Felix Felicis. \'85 He suddenly wished he had said a better good-bye to them \'85 and he hadn\rquote t seen Ginny at all. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nearly there,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore cheerfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sure enough, the greenish light seemed to be growing larger at last, and within minutes, the boat had come to a halt, bumping gently into something that Harry could not see at first, but when he raised his illuminated wand he saw that they had reached a small island of smooth rock in the center of the lake.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Careful not to touch the water,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore again as Harry climbed out of the boat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The island was no larger than Dumbledore\rquote s office, an expanse of flat dark stone on which stood nothing but the source of that greenish light, which looked much brighter when viewed close to. Harry squinted at it; at first, he thought it was a lamp of some kind, but then he saw that the light was coming from a stone basin rather like the Pensieve, which was set on top of a pedestal.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore approached the basin and Harry followed. Side by side, they looked down into it. The basin was full of an emerald liq\-uid emitting that phosphorescent glow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote  asked Harry quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am not sure,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Something more worrisome than blood and bodies, however.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore pushed back the sleeve of his robe over his black\-ened hand, and stretched out the tips of his burned fingers toward the surface of the potion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir, no, don\rquote t touch \emdash  !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I cannot touch,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, smiling faintly. \ldblquote See? I can\-not approach any nearer than this. You try.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Staring, Harry put his hand into the basin and attempted to touch the potion. He met an invisible barrier that prevented him coming within an inch of it. No matter how hard he pushed, his fingers encountered nothing but what seemed to be solid and in\-flexible air.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Out of the way, please, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. He raised his wand and made complicated movements over the surface of the potion, murmuring soundlessly. Nothing happened, except per\-haps that the potion glowed a little brighter. Harry remained silent while Dumbledore worked, but after a while Dumbledore with\-drew his wand, and Harry felt it was safe to talk again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You think the Horcrux is in there, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes.\rdblquote  Dumbledore peered more closely into the basin. Harry saw his face reflected, upside down, in the smooth surface of the green potion. \ldblquote But how to reach it? This potion cannot be pen\-etrated by hand, Vanished, parted, scooped up, or siphoned away, nor can it be Transfigured, Charmed, or otherwise made to change its nature.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Almost absentmindedly, Dumbledore raised his wand again, twirled it once in midair, and then caught the crystal goblet that he had conjured out of nowhere.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can only conclude that this potion is supposed to be drunk.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote No!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I think so: Only by drinking it can I empty the basin and see what lies in its depths.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what if\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  what if it kills you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I doubt that it would work like that,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore\lang3081  \lang1033 easily. \ldblquote Lord Voldemort would not want to kill the person who reached this island.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry couldn\rquote t believe it. Was this more of Dumbledore\rquote s insane determination to see good in everyone?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir,\rdblquote  said Harry, trying to keep his voice reasonable, \ldblquote sir, this is \i Voldemort\i0  we\rquote re \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, Harry; I should have said, he would not want to \i im\-mediately\i0  kill the person who reached this island,\rdblquote  Dumbledore corrected himself. \ldblquote He would want to keep them alive long enough to find out how they managed to penetrate so far through his de\-fenses and, most importantly of all, why they were so intent upon emptying the basin. Do not forget that Lord Voldemort believes that he alone knows about his Horcruxes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry made to speak again, but this time Dumbledore raised his hand for silence, frowning slightly at the emerald liquid, evidently thinking hard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Undoubtedly,\rdblquote  he said, finally, \ldblquote this potion must act in a way that will prevent me taking the Horcrux. It might paralyze me, cause me to forget what I am here for, create so much pain I am dis\-tracted, or render me incapable in some other way. This being the case, Harry, it will be your job to make sure I keep drinking, even if you have to tip the potion into my protesting mouth. You understand?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Their eyes met over the basin, each pale face lit with that strange, green light. Harry did not speak. Was this why he had been invited along \emdash  so that he could force-feed Dumbledore a potion that might cause him unendurable pain?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You remember,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote the condition on which I brought you with me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry hesitated, looking into the blue eyes that had turned green in the reflected light of the basin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what if \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You swore, did you not, to follow any command I gave you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I warned you, did I not, that there might be danger?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, then,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, shaking back his sleeves once more and raising the empty goblet, \ldblquote you have my orders.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why can\rquote t I drink the potion instead?\rdblquote  asked Harry desperately.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because I am much older, much cleverer, and much less valuable,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Once and for all, Harry, do I have your word that you will do all in your power to make me keep drinking?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Couldn\rquote t \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do I have it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Your word, Harry.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  all right, but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Before Harry could make any further protest, Dumbledore low\-ered the crystal goblet into the potion. For a split second, Harry hoped that he would not be able to touch the potion with the gob\-let, but the crystal sank into the surface as nothing else had; when the glass was full to the brim, Dumbledore lifted it to his mouth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your good health, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he drained the goblet. Harry watched, terrified, his hands gripping the rim of the basin so hard that his fingertips were numb.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor?\rdblquote  he said anxiously, as Dumbledore lowered the empty glass. \ldblquote How do you feel?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore shook his head, his eyes closed. Harry wondered whether he was in pain. Dumbledore plunged the glass blindly back into the basin, refilled it, and drank once more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In silence, Dumbledore drank three gobletsful of the potion. Then, halfway through the fourth goblet, he staggered and fell for\-ward against the basin. His eyes were still closed, his breathing heavy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Dumbledore?\rdblquote  said Harry, his voice strained. \ldblquote Can you hear me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
