\lang1033\ldblquote And Dumbledore \'85\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Minerva, is it true \'85 Is he really \'85 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Professor McGonagall nodded, Harry felt Ginny move beside him and looked at her. Her slightly narrowed eyes were fixed upon Fleur, who was gazing down at Bill with a frozen expression on her face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore gone,\rdblquote  whispered Mr. Weasley, but Mrs. Weasley had eyes only for her eldest son; she began to sob, tears falling onto Bill\rquote s mutilated face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course, it doesn\rquote t matter how he looks. \'85 It\rquote s not r-really important\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 but he was a very handsome little b-boy \'85 always very handsome \'85 and he was g-going to be married!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And what do you mean by zat?\rdblquote  said Fleur suddenly and loudly. \ldblquote What do you mean, \lquote\rquote e was \i going\i0  to be married?\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley raised her tear-stained face, looking startled. \ldblquote Well \emdash\lang3081  \lang1033 only that\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You theenk Bill will not wish to marry me anymore?\rdblquote  demanded Fleur. \ldblquote You theenk, because of these bites, he will not love me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, that\rquote s not what I \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because \rquote e will!\rdblquote  said Fleur, drawing herself up to her full height and throwing back her long mane of silver hair. \ldblquote It would take more zan a werewolf to stop Bill loving me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, yes, I\rquote m sure,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, \ldblquote but I thought per\-haps \emdash  given how \emdash  how he \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You thought I would not weesh to marry him? Or per\rquote aps, you hoped?\rdblquote  said Fleur, her nostrils flaring. \ldblquote What do I care how he looks? I am good-looking enough for both of us, I theenk! All these scars show is zat my husband is brave! And I shall do zat!\rdblquote  she added fiercely, pushing Mrs. Weasley aside and snatching the oint\-ment from her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley fell back against her husband and watched Fleur mopping up Bill\rquote s wounds with a most curious expression upon her face. Nobody said anything; Harry did not dare move. Like every\-body else, he was waiting for the explosion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Our Great-Auntie Muriel,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley after a long pause, \ldblquote has a very beautiful tiara \emdash  goblin-made \emdash  which I am sure I could persuade her to lend you for the wedding. She is very fond of Bill, you know, and it would look lovely with your hair.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  said Fleur stiffly. \ldblquote I am sure zat will be lovely.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then, Harry did not quite see how it happened, both women were crying and hugging each other. Completely bewil\-dered, wondering whether the world had gone mad, he turned around: Ron looked as stunned as he felt and Ginny and Hermione were exchanging startled looks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You see!\rdblquote  said a strained voice. Tonks was glaring at Lupin. \ldblquote She still wants to marry him, even though he\rquote s been bitten! She doesn\rquote t care!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s different,\rdblquote  said Lupin, barely moving his lips and looking\lang3081  \lang1033 suddenly tense. \ldblquote Bill will not be a full werewolf. The cases are com\-pletely \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But I don\rquote t care either, I don\rquote t care!\rdblquote  said Tonks, seizing the front of Lupin\rquote s robes and shaking them. \ldblquote I\rquote ve told you a million times. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And the meaning of Tonks\rquote s Patronus and her mouse-colored hair, and the reason she had come running to find Dumbledore when she had heard a rumor someone had been attacked by Grey\-back, all suddenly became clear to Harry; it had not been Sirius that Tonks had fallen in love with after all.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And I\rquote ve told\lang3081  \lang1033\i you\i0  a million times,\rdblquote  said Lupin, refusing to meet her eyes, staring at the floor, \ldblquote that I am too old for you, too poor \'85 too dangerous. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve said all along you\rquote re taking a ridiculous line on this, Re\-mus,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley over Fleur\rquote s shoulder as she patted her on the back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am not being ridiculous,\rdblquote  said Lupin steadily. \ldblquote Tonks deserves somebody young and whole.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But she wants you,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, with a small smile. \ldblquote And after all, Remus, young and whole men do not necessarily remain so.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He gestured sadly at his son, lying between them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 not the moment to discuss it,\rdblquote  said Lupin, avoiding everybody\rquote s eyes as he looked around distractedly. \ldblquote Dumbledore is dead. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore would have been happier than anybody to think that there was a little more love in the world,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall curtly, just as the hospital doors opened again and Hagrid walked in.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The little of his face that was not obscured by hair or beard was soaking and swollen; he was shaking with tears, a vast, spotted handkerchief in his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve \'85 I\rquote ve done it, Professor,\rdblquote  he choked. \ldblquote M-moved him. Professor Sprout\rquote s got the kids back in bed. Professor Flitwick\rquote s lyin\rquote  down, but he says he\rquote ll be all righ\rquote  in a jiffy, an\rquote  Professor Slughorn says the Ministry\rquote s bin informed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you, Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, standing up at once and turning to look at the group around Bill\rquote s bed. \ldblquote I shall have to see the Ministry when they get here. Hagrid, please tell the Heads of Houses \emdash  Slughorn can represent Slytherin \emdash  that I want to see them in my office forthwith. I would like you to join us too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Hagrid nodded, turned, and shuffled out of the room again, she looked down at Harry. \ldblquote Before I meet them I would like a quick word with you, Harry. If you\rquote ll come with me. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stood up, murmured \ldblquote See you in a bit\rdblquote  to Ron, Hermi\-one, and Ginny, and followed Professor McGonagall back down the ward. The corridors outside were deserted and the only sound was the distant phoenix song. It was several minutes before Harry became aware that they were not heading for Professor McGona\-gall\rquote s office, but for Dumbledore\rquote s, and another few seconds before he realized that of course, she had been deputy headmistress. \'85 Apparently she was now headmistress \'85 so the room behind the gargoyle was now hers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In silence they ascended the moving spiral staircase and entered the circular office. He did not know what he had expected: that the room would be draped in black, perhaps, or even that Dumble\-dore\rquote s body might be lying there. In fact, it looked almost exactly as\lang3081  \lang1033 it had done when he and Dumbledore had left it mere hours previ\-ously: the silver instruments whirring and puffing on their spindle-legged tables, Gryffindor\rquote s sword in its glass case gleaming in the moonlight, the Sorting Hat on a shelf behind the desk. But Fawkes\rquote s perch stood empty, he was still crying his lament to the grounds. And a new portrait had joined the ranks of the dead head\-masters and headmistresses of Hogwarts: Dumbledore was slum\-bering in a golden frame over the desk, his half-moon spectacles perched upon his crooked nose, looking peaceful and untroubled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After glancing once at this portrait, Professor McGonagall made an odd movement as though steeling herself, then rounded the desk to look at Harry, her face taut and lined.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote I would like to know what you and Professor Dumbledore were doing this evening when you left the school.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t tell you that, Professor,\rdblquote  said Harry. He had expected the question and had his answer ready. It had been here, in this very room, that Dumbledore had told him that he was to confide the contents of their lessons to nobody but Ron and Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, it might be important,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote very, but he didn\rquote t want me to tell anyone.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor McGonagall glared at him. \ldblquote Potter\rdblquote  \emdash  Harry regis\-tered the renewed use of his surname \emdash  \ldblquote in the light of Professor Dumbledore\rquote s death, I think you must see that the situation has changed somewhat \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think so,\rdblquote  said Harry, shrugging. \ldblquote Professor Dumble\-dore never told me to stop following his orders if he died.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s one thing you should know before the Ministry gets\lang3081  \lang1033 here, though. Madam Rosmerta\rquote s under the Imperius Curse, she was helping Malfoy and the Death Eaters, that\rquote s how the necklace and the poisoned mead \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Rosmerta?\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall incredulously, but be\-fore she could go on, there was a knock on the door behind them and Professors Sprout, Flitwick, and Slughorn traipsed into the room, followed by Hagrid, who was still weeping copiously, his huge frame trembling with grief.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Snape!\rdblquote  ejaculated Slughorn, who looked the most shaken, pale and sweating. \ldblquote Snape! I taught him! I thought I knew him!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But before any of them could respond to this, a sharp voice spoke from high on the wall: A sallow-faced wizard with a short black fringe had just walked back into his empty canvas.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Minerva, the Minister will be here within seconds, he has just Disapparated from the Ministry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you, Everard,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, and she turned quickly to her teachers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want to talk about what happens to Hogwarts before he gets here,\rdblquote  she said quickly. \ldblquote Personally, I am not convinced that the school should reopen next year. The death of the headmaster at the hands of one of our colleagues is a terrible stain upon Hogwarts\rquote s history. It is horrible.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am sure Dumbledore would have wanted the school to re\-main open,\rdblquote  said Professor Sprout. \ldblquote I feel that if a single pupil wants to come, then the school ought to remain open for that pupil.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
