All lessons were suspended, all examinations postponed. Some students were hurried away from Hogwarts by their parents over the next couple of days \emdash  the Patil twins were gone before breakfast on the morning following Dumbledore\rquote s death, and Zacharias Smith was escorted from the castle by his haughty-looking father. Seamus Finnigan, on the other hand, re\-fused point-blank to accompany his mother home; they had a shouting match in the entrance hall that was resolved when she agreed that he could remain behind for the funeral. She had diffi\-culty in finding a bed in Hogsmeade, Seamus told Harry and Ron, for wizards and witches were pouring into the village, preparing to pay their last respects to Dumbledore.\par
Some excitement was caused among the younger students, who had never seen it before, when a powder-blue carriage the size of a house, pulled by a dozen giant winged palominos, came soaring out of the sky in the late afternoon before the funeral and landed on the\lang3081  \lang1033 edge of the forest. Harry watched from a window as a gigantic and handsome olive-skinned, black-haired woman descended the car\-riage steps and threw herself into the waiting Hagrid\rquote s arms. Mean\-while a delegation of Ministry officials, including the Minister of Magic himself, was being accommodated within the castle. Harry was diligently avoiding contact with any of them; he was sure that, sooner or later, he would be asked again to account for Dumble\-dore\rquote s last excursion from Hogwarts.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, Hermione, and Ginny were spending all of their time together. The beautiful weather seemed to mock them; Harry could imagine how it would have been if Dumbledore had not died, and they had had this time together at the very end of the year, Ginny\rquote s examinations finished, the pressure of homework lifted \'85 and hour by hour, he put off saying the thing that he knew he must say, doing what he knew was right to do, because it was too hard to forgo his best source of comfort.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They visited the hospital wing twice a day: Neville had been dis\-charged, but Bill remained under Madam Pomfrey\rquote s care. His scars were as bad as ever \emdash  in truth, he now bore a distinct resemblance to Mad-Eye Moody, though thankfully with both eyes and legs \emdash  but in personality he seemed just the same as ever. All that ap\-peared to have changed was that he now had a great liking for very rare steaks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 so eet ees lucky \rquote e is marrying me,\rdblquote  said Fleur happily, plumping up Bill\rquote s pillows, \ldblquote because ze British overcook their meat, I \rquote ave always said this.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I suppose I\rquote m just going to have to accept that he really is going to marry her,\rdblquote  sighed Ginny later that evening, as she, Harry, Ron,\lang3081  \lang1033 and Hermione sat beside the open window of the Gryffindor com\-mon room, looking out over the twilit grounds.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She\rquote s not that bad,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Ugly, though,\rdblquote  he added hastily, as Ginny raised her eyebrows, and she let out a reluctant\lang3081  \lang1033 giggle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I suppose if Mum can stand it, I can.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anyone else we know died?\rdblquote  Ron asked Hermione, who was pe\-rusing the \i Evening Prophet.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 Hermione winced at the forced toughness in his voice. \ldblquote No,\rdblquote  she said reprovingly, folding up the newspaper. \ldblquote They\rquote re still look\-ing for Snape but no sign \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course there isn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry, who became angry every time this subject cropped up. \ldblquote They won\rquote t find Snape till they find Voldemort, and seeing as they\rquote ve never managed to do that in all this time \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m going to go to bed,\rdblquote  yawned Ginny. \ldblquote I haven\rquote t been sleep\-ing that well since \'85 well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I could do with some sleep.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She kissed Harry (Ron looked away pointedly), waved at the other two, and departed for the girls\rquote  dormitories. The moment the door had closed behind her, Hermione leaned forward toward Harry with a most Hermione-ish look on her face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I found something out this morning, in the library.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote R.A.B.?\rdblquote  said Harry, sitting up straight.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He did not feel the way he had so often felt before, excited, curi\-ous, burning to get to the bottom of a mystery; he simply knew that the task of discovering the truth about the real Horcrux had to be completed before he could move a little farther along the dark and winding path stretching ahead of him, the path that he and\lang3081  \lang1033 Dumbledore had set out upon together, and which he now knew he would have to journey alone. There might still be as many as four Horcruxes out there somewhere, and each would need to be found and eliminated before there was even a possibility that Volde\-mort could be killed. He kept reciting their names to himself, as though by listing them he could bring them within reach: \i the locket \i0\'85\i  the cup\i0  \'85 \i the snake\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85 \i something of\lang3081  \lang1033 Gryffindor\rquote s or Ravenclaw\rquote s \i0\'85 \i the locket\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85 \i the cup\i0  \'85 \i the snake\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85 \i something of Gryffindor\rquote s or Ravenclaw\rquote s\i0  \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This mantra seemed to pulse through Harry\rquote s mind as he fell asleep at night, and his dreams were thick with cups, lockets, and mysterious objects that he could not quite reach, though Dumble\-dore helpfully offered Harry a rope ladder that turned to snakes the moment he began to climb. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had shown Hermione the note inside the locket the morning after Dumbledore\rquote s death, and although she had not immediately recognized the initials as belonging to some obscure wizard about whom she had been reading, she had since been rushing off to the library a little more often than was strictly necessary for somebody who had no homework to do.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  she said sadly, \ldblquote I\rquote ve been trying, Harry, but I haven\rquote t found anything. \'85 There are a couple of reasonably well-known wizards with those initials \emdash  Rosalind Antigone Bungs \'85 Rupert \lquote Axebanger\rquote  Brookstanton \'85 but they don\rquote t seem to fit at all. Judging by that note, the person who stole the Horcrux knew Voldemort, and I can\rquote t find a shred of evidence that Bungs or Axe\-banger ever had anything to do with him. \'85 No, actually, it\rquote s about\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 well, Snape.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked nervous even saying the name again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What about him?\rdblquote  asked Harry heavily, slumping back in his chair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s just that I was sort of right about the Half-Blood Prince business,\rdblquote  she said tentatively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you have to rub it in, Hermione? How d\rquote you think I feel about that now?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No \emdash  no \emdash  Harry, I didn\rquote t mean that!\rdblquote  she said hastily, look\-ing around to check that they were not being overheard. \ldblquote It\rquote s just that I was right about Eileen Prince once owning the book. You see \'85 she was Snape\rquote s mother!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought she wasn\rquote t much of a looker,\rdblquote  said Ron. Hermione ig\-nored him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was going through the rest of the old \i Prophets \i0 and there was a tiny announcement about Eileen Prince marrying a man called Tobias Snape, and then later an announcement saying that she\rquote d given birth to a \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  murderer,\rdblquote  spat Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well \'85 yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote So \'85 I was sort of right. Snape must have been proud of being \lquote half a Prince,\rquote  you see? Tobias Snape was a Muggle from what it said in the \i Prophet.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, that fits,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote He\rquote d play up the pure-blood side so he could get in with Lucius Malfoy and the rest of them. \'85 He\rquote s just like Voldemort. Pure-blood mother, Muggle father \'85 ashamed of his parentage, trying to make himself feared using the Dark Arts, gave himself an impressive new name \emdash  \i Lord\i0  Volde\-mort \emdash  the Half-Blood \i Prince\i0  \emdash  how could Dumbledore have missed \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He broke off, looking out the window. He could not stop him\-self dwelling upon Dumbledore\rquote s inexcusable trust in Snape \'85\lang3081  \lang1033 but as Hermione had just inadvertently reminded him, he, Harry, had been taken in just the same. \'85 In spite of the increasing nas\-tiness of those scribbled spells, he had refused to believe ill of the boy who had been so clever, who had helped him so much. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Helped him \i0\'85 it was an almost unendurable thought now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I still don\rquote t get why he didn\rquote t turn you in for using that book,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote He must\rquote ve known where you were getting it all from.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He knew,\rdblquote  said Harry bitterly. \ldblquote He knew when I used Sectum\-sempra. He didn\rquote t really need Legilimency. \'85 He might even have known before then, with Slughorn talking about how brilliant I was at Potions. \'85 Shouldn\rquote t have left his old book in the bottom of that cupboard, should he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But why didn\rquote t he turn you in?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think he wanted to associate himself with that book,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think Dumbledore would have liked it very much if he\rquote d known. And even if Snape pretended it hadn\rquote t been his, Slughorn would have recognized his writing at once. Anyway, the book was left in Snape\rquote s old classroom, and I\rquote ll bet Dumbledore knew his mother was called \lquote Prince.\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I should\rquote ve shown the book to Dumbledore,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote All that time he was showing me how Voldemort was evil even when he was at school, and I had proof Snape was too \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote Evil\rquote  is a strong word,\rdblquote  said Hermione quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You were the one who kept telling me the book was dan\-gerous!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m trying to say, Harry, that you\rquote re putting too much blame on yourself. I thought the Prince seemed to have a nasty sense of hu\-mor, but I would never have guessed he was a potential killer. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote None of us could\rquote ve guessed Snape would \'85 you know,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Silence fell between them, each of them lost in their own thoughts, but Harry was sure that they, like him, were thinking about the following morning, when Dumbledore\rquote s body would be laid to rest. He had never attended a funeral before; there had been no body to bury when Sirius had died. He did not know what to ex\-pect and was a little worried about what he might see, about how he would feel. He wondered whether Dumbledore\rquote s death would be more real to him once it was over. Though he had moments when the horrible fact of it threatened to overwhelm him, there were blank stretches of numbness where, despite the fact that nobody was talking about anything else in the whole castle, he still found it difficult to believe that Dumbledore had really gone. Admittedly he had not, as he had with Sirius, looked desperately for some kind of loophole, some way that Dumbledore would come back. \'85 He felt in his pocket for the cold chain of the fake Horcrux, which he now carried with him everywhere, not as a talisman, but as a re\-minder of what it had cost and what remained still to do.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry rose early to pack the next day; the Hogwarts Express would be leaving an hour after the funeral. Downstairs, he found the mood in the Great Hall subdued. Everybody was wearing their dress robes and no one seemed very hungry. Professor McGonagall had left the thronelike chair in the middle of the staff table empty. Hagrid\rquote s chair was deserted too; Harry thought that perhaps he had not been able to face breakfast, but Snape\rquote s place had been uncere\-moniously filled by Rufus Scrimgeour. Harry avoided his yellowish eyes as they scanned the Hall; Harry had the uncomfortable feeling\lang3081  \lang1033 that Scrimgeour was looking for him. Among Scrimgeour\rquote s en\-tourage Harry spotted the red hair and horn-rimmed glasses of Percy Weasley. Ron gave no sign that he was aware of Percy, apart from stabbing pieces of kipper with unwonted venom.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Over at the Slytherin table Crabbe and Goyle were muttering together. Hulking boys though they were, they looked oddly lonely without the tall, pale figure of Malfoy between them, bossing them around. Harry had not spared Malfoy much thought. His animos\-ity was all for Snape, but he had not forgotten the fear in Malfoy\rquote s voice on that tower top, nor the fact that he had lowered his wand before the other Death Eaters arrived. Harry did not believe that Malfoy would have killed Dumbledore. He despised Malfoy still for his infatuation with the Dark Arts, but now the tiniest drop of pity mingled with his dislike. Where, Harry wondered, was Malfoy now, and what was Voldemort making him do under threat of killing him and his parents?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s thoughts were interrupted by a nudge in the ribs from Ginny. Professor McGonagall had risen to her feet, and the mourn\-ful hum in the Hall died away at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is nearly time,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Please follow your Heads of Houses out into the grounds. Gryffindors, after me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They filed out from behind their benches in near silence. Harry glimpsed Slughorn at the head of the Slytherin column, wearing magnificent, long, emerald green robes embroidered with silver. He had never seen Professor Sprout, Head of the Hufflepuffs, look\-ing so clean; there was not a single patch on her hat, and when they reached the entrance hall, they found Madam Pince standing be\-side Filch, she in a thick black veil that fell to her knees, he in an ancient black suit and tie reeking of mothballs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were heading, as Harry saw when he stepped out onto the stone steps from the front doors, toward the lake. The warmth of the sun caressed his face as they followed Professor McGonagall in silence to the place where hundreds of chairs had been set out in rows. An aisle ran down the center of them: There was a marble table standing at the front, all chairs facing it. It was the most beau\-tiful summer\rquote s day.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 An extraordinary assortment of people had already settled into half of the chairs; shabby and smart, old and young. Most Harry did not recognize, but a few he did, including members of the Or\-der of the Phoenix: Kingsley Shacklebolt; Mad-Eye Moody; Tonks, her hair miraculously returned to vividest pink; Remus Lupin, with whom she seemed to be holding hands; Mr. and Mrs. Weasley; Bill supported by Fleur and followed by Fred and George, who were wearing jackets of black dragon skin. Then there was Madame Maxime, who took up two and a half chairs on her own; Tom, the landlord of the Leaky Cauldron in London; Arabella Figg, Harry\rquote s Squib neighbor; the hairy bass player from the Wiz\-arding group the Weird Sisters; Ernie Prang, driver of the Knight Bus; Madam Malkin, of the robe shop in Diagon Alley; and some people whom Harry merely knew by sight, such as the barman of the Hog\rquote s Head and the witch who pushed the trolley on the Hog\-warts Express. The castle ghosts were there too, barely visible in the bright sunlight, discernible only when they moved, shimmering in\-substantially on the gleaming air.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, Hermione, and Ginny filed into seats at the end of a row beside the lake. People were whispering to each other; it sounded like a breeze in the grass, but the birdsong was louder by far. The crowd continued to swell; with a great rush of affection\lang3081  \lang1033 for both of them, Harry saw Neville being helped into a seat by Luna. Neville and Luna alone of the D.A. had responded to Her\-mione\rquote s summons the night that Dumbledore had died, and Harry knew why: They were the ones who had missed the D.A. most\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 probably the ones who had checked their coins regularly in the hope that there would be another meeting.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Cornelius Fudge walked past toward the front rows, his expres\-sion miserable, twirling his green bowler hat as usual; Harry next recognized Rita Skeeter, who, he was infuriated to see, had a note\-book clutched in her red-taloned hand, and then, with a worse jolt of fury, Dolores Umbridge, an unconvincing expression of grief upon her toadlike face, a black velvet bow set atop her iron-colored curls. At the sight of the centaur Firenze, who was standing like a sentinel near the water\rquote s edge, she gave a start and scurried hastily into a seat a good distance away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The staff was seated at last. Harry could see Scrimgeour looking grave and dignified in the front row with Professor McGonagall. He wondered whether Scrimgeour or any of these important peo\-ple were really sorry that Dumbledore was dead. But then he heard music, strange, otherworldly music, and he forgot his dislike of the Ministry in looking around for the source of it. He was not the only one: Many heads were turning, searching, a little alarmed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In there,\rdblquote  whispered Ginny in Harry\rquote s ear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he saw them in the clear green sunlit water, inches below the surface, reminding him horribly of the Inferi: a chorus of mer\-people singing in a strange language he did not understand, their pallid faces rippling, their purplish hair flowing all around them. The music made the hair on Harry\rquote s neck stand up, and yet it was not unpleasant. It spoke very clearly of loss and of despair. As he\lang3081  \lang1033 looked down into the wild faces of the singers, he had the feeling that they, at least, were sorry for Dumbledore\rquote s passing. Then Ginny nudged him again and he looked around.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid was walking slowly up the aisle between the chairs. He was crying quite silently, his face gleaming with tears, and in his arms, wrapped in purple velvet spangled with golden stars, was what Harry knew to be Dumbledore\rquote s body. A sharp pain rose in Harry\rquote s throat at this sight: For a moment, the strange music and the knowledge that Dumbledore\rquote s body was so close seemed to take all warmth from the day. Ron looked white and shocked. Tears were falling thick and fast into both Ginny\rquote s and Hermione\rquote s laps.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They could not see clearly what was happening at the front. Ha\-grid seemed to have placed the body carefully upon the table. Now he retreated down the aisle, blowing his nose with loud trumpeting noises that drew scandalized looks from some, including, Harry saw, Dolores Umbridge \'85 but Harry knew that Dumbledore would not have cared. He tried to make a friendly gesture to Ha\-grid as he passed, but Hagrid\rquote s eyes were so swollen it was a wonder he could see where he was going. Harry glanced at the back row to which Hagrid was heading and realized what was guiding him, for there, dressed in a jacket and trousers each the size of a small mar\-quee, was the giant Grawp, his great ugly boulderlike head bowed, docile, almost human. Hagrid sat down next to his half-brother, and Grawp patted Hagrid hard on the head, so that his chair legs sank into the ground. Harry had a wonderful momentary urge to laugh. But then the music stopped, and he turned to face the front again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A little tufty-haired man in plain black robes had got to his feet and stood now in front of Dumbledore\rquote s body. Harry could not\lang3081  \lang1033 hear what he was saying. Odd words floated back to them over the hundreds of heads. \ldblquote Nobility of spirit\rdblquote  \'85 \ldblquote intellectual contribu\-tion\rdblquote  \'85 \ldblquote greatness of heart\rdblquote  \'85 It did not mean very much. It had little to do with Dumbledore as Harry had known him. He sud\-denly remembered Dumbledore\rquote s idea of a few words, \ldblquote nitwit,\rdblquote  \ldblquote oddment,\rdblquote  \ldblquote blubber,\rdblquote  and \ldblquote tweak,\rdblquote  and again had to suppress a grin. \'85 What was the matter with him?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a soft splashing noise to his left and he saw that the merpeople had broken the surface to listen too. He remembered Dumbledore crouching at the water\rquote s edge two years ago, very close to where Harry now sat, and conversing in Mermish with the Mer\-chieftainess. Harry wondered where Dumbledore had learned Mermish. There was so much he had never asked him, so much he should have said. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then, without warning, it swept over him, the dreadful truth, more completely and undeniably than it had until now. Dumbledore was dead, gone. \'85 He clutched the cold locket in his hand so tightly that it hurt, but he could not prevent hot tears spilling from his eyes: He looked away from Ginny and the others and stared out over the lake, toward the forest, as the little man in black droned on. \'85 There was movement among the trees. The centaurs had come to pay their respects too. They did not move into the open but Harry saw them standing quite still, half hidden in shadow, watching the wizards, their bows hanging at their sides. And Harry remembered his first nightmarish trip into the forest, the first time he had ever encountered the thing that was then Voldemort, and how he had faced him, and how he and Dumble\-dore had discussed fighting a losing battle not long thereafter. It\lang3081  \lang1033 was important, Dumbledore said, to fight, and fight again, and keep fighting, for only then could evil be kept at bay, though never quite eradicated. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And Harry saw very clearly as he sat there under the hot sun how people who cared about him had stood in front of him one by one, his mother, his father, his godfather, and finally Dumbledore, all determined to protect him; but now that was over. He could not let anybody else stand between him and Voldemort; he must abandon forever the illusion he ought to have lost at the age of one, that the shelter of a parent\rquote s arms meant that nothing could hurt him. There was no waking from his nightmare, no comforting whisper in the dark that he was safe really, that it was all in his imagination; the last and greatest of his protectors had died, and he was more alone than he had ever been before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The little man in black had stopped speaking at last and re\-sumed his seat. Harry waited for somebody else to get to their feet; he expected speeches, probably from the Minister, but nobody moved.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then several people screamed. Bright, white flames had erupted around Dumbledore\rquote s body and the table upon which it lay: Higher and higher they rose, obscuring the body. White smoke spiraled into the air and made strange shapes: Harry thought, for one heart-stopping moment, that he saw a phoenix fly joyfully into the blue, but next second the fire had vanished. In its place was a white marble tomb, encasing Dumbledore\rquote s body and the table on which he had rested.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were a few more cries of shock as a shower of arrows soared through the air, but they fell far short of the crowd. It was,\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry knew, the centaurs\rquote  tribute: He saw them turn tail and dis\-appear back into the cool trees. Likewise, the merpeople sank slowly back into the green water and were lost from view.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked at Ginny, Ron, and Hermione: Ron\rquote s face was screwed up as though the sunlight were blinding him. Hermione\rquote s face was glazed with tears, but Ginny was no longer crying. She met Harry\rquote s gaze with the same hard, blazing look that he had seen when she had hugged him after winning the Quidditch Cup in his absence, and he knew that at that moment they understood each other perfectly, and that when he told her what he was going to do now, she would not say, \ldblquote Be careful,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote Don\rquote t do it,\rdblquote  but accept his decision, because she would not have expected anything less of him. And so he steeled himself to say what he had known he must say ever since Dumbledore had died.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ginny, listen \'85\rdblquote  he said very quietly, as the buzz of conversa\-tion grew louder around them and people began to get to their feet, \ldblquote I can\rquote t be involved with you anymore. We\rquote ve got to stop seeing each other. We can\rquote t be together.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She said, with an oddly twisted smile, \ldblquote It\rquote s for some stupid, no\-ble reason, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s been like \'85 like something out of someone else\rquote s life, these last few weeks with you,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote But I can\rquote t\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 we can\rquote t\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I\rquote ve got things to do alone now.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She did not cry, she simply looked at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Voldemort uses people his enemies are close to. He\rquote s already used you as bait once, and that was just because you\rquote re my best friend\rquote s sister. Think how much danger you\rquote ll be in if we keep this up. He\rquote ll know, he\rquote ll find out. He\rquote ll try and get to me through you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What if I don\rquote t care?\rdblquote  said Ginny fiercely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I care,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote How do you think I\rquote d feel if this was your funeral\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 and it was my fault. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She looked away from him, over the lake.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I never really gave up on you,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Not really. I always hoped. \'85 Hermione told me to get on with life, maybe go out with some other people, relax a bit around you, because I never used to be able to talk if you were in the room, remember? And she thought you might take a bit more notice if I was a bit more \emdash  myself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Smart girl, that Hermione,\rdblquote  said Harry, trying to smile. \ldblquote I just wish I\rquote d asked you sooner. We could\rquote ve had ages \'85 months \'85 years maybe. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But you\rquote ve been too busy saving the Wizarding world,\rdblquote  said Ginny, half laughing. \ldblquote Well \'85 I can\rquote t say I\rquote m surprised. I knew this would happen in the end. I knew you wouldn\rquote t be happy un\-less you were hunting Voldemort. Maybe that\rquote s why I like you so much.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could not bear to hear these things, nor did he think his resolution would hold if he remained sitting beside her. Ron, he saw, was now holding Hermione and stroking her hair while she sobbed into his shoulder, tears dripping from the end of his own long nose. With a miserable gesture, Harry got up, turned his back on Ginny and on Dumbledore\rquote s tomb, and walked away around the lake. Moving felt much more bearable than sitting still, just as setting out as soon as possible to track down the Horcruxes and kill Voldemort would feel better than waiting to do it. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned. Rufus Scrimgeour was limping rapidly toward him around the bank, leaning on his walking stick.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve been hoping to have a word \'85 do you mind if I walk a lit\-tle way with you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry indifferently, and set off again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, this was a dreadful tragedy,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour quietly. \ldblquote I cannot tell you how appalled I was to hear of it. Dumbledore was a very great wizard. We had our disagreements, as you know, but no one knows better than I \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you want?\rdblquote  asked Harry flatly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour looked annoyed, but as before, hastily modified his expression to one of sorrowful understanding.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are, of course, devastated,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I know that you were very close to Dumbledore. I think you may have been his favorite pupil ever. The bond between the two of you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you want?\rdblquote  Harry repeated, coming to a halt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour stopped too, leaned on his stick, and stared at Harry, his expression shrewd now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The word is that you were with him when he left the school the night that he died.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Whose word?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Somebody Stupefied a Death Eater on top of the tower after Dumbledore died. There were also two broomsticks up there. The Ministry can add two and two, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Glad to hear it,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Well, where I went with Dum\-bledore and what we did is my business. He didn\rquote t want people to know.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Such loyalty is admirable, of course,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, who seemed to be restraining his irritation with difficulty, \ldblquote but Dum\-bledore is gone, Harry. He\rquote s gone.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He will only be gone from the school when none here are loyal to him,\rdblquote  said Harry, smiling in spite of himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dear boy \'85 even Dumbledore cannot return from the \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am not saying he can. You wouldn\rquote t understand. But I\rquote ve got nothing to tell you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour hesitated, then said, in what was evidently supposed to be a tone of delicacy, \ldblquote The Ministry can offer you all sorts of protection, you know, Harry. I would be delighted to place a cou\-ple of my Aurors at your service \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry laughed. \ldblquote Voldemort wants to kill me himself, and Aurors won\rquote t stop him. So thanks for the offer, but no thanks.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  said Scrimgeour, his voice cold now, \ldblquote the request I made of you at Christmas \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What request? Oh yeah \'85 the one where I tell the world what a great job you\rquote re doing in exchange for \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  for raising everyone\rquote s morale!\rdblquote  snapped Scrimgeour.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry considered him for a moment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Released Stan Shunpike yet?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour turned a nasty purple color highly reminiscent of Uncle Vernon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I see you are \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore\rquote s man through and through,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote That\rquote s right.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scrimgeour glared at him for another moment, then turned and limped away without another word. Harry could see Percy and the rest of the Ministry delegation waiting for him, casting nervous glances at the sobbing Hagrid and Grawp, who were still in their seats. Ron and Hermione were hurrying toward Harry, passing\lang3081  \lang1033 Scrimgeour going in the opposite direction. Harry turned and walked slowly on, waiting for them to catch up, which they finally did in the shade of a beech tree under which they had sat in hap\-pier times.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did Scrimgeour want?\rdblquote  Hermione whispered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Same as he wanted at Christmas,\rdblquote  shrugged Harry. \ldblquote Wanted me to give him inside information on Dumbledore and be the Ministry\rquote s new poster boy.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron seemed to struggle with himself for a moment, then he said loudly to Hermione, \ldblquote Look, let me go back and hit Percy!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
